<SLUG> BC-NJ-COURT-VERNIERO-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATT: N.C.)  
 WHITMAN PICKS ATTORNEY GENERAL FOR N.J. STATE SUPREME COURT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Moving swiftly to strengthen her imprint on New
Jersey's highest court, Gov. Christie Whitman Friday nominated
Attorney General Peter G. Verniero, her longtime political ally, to
fill an unexpected vacancy on the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Justice Stewart G. Pollock announced that he would
leave the bench in September, Whitman announced the selection of
Verniero, a loyal confidant who has previously served as her chief
of staff, general counsel and campaign lawyer. To replace Verniero,
she nominated her chief counsel, John Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Both nominations require confirmation by the Legislature, but
neither is expected to face much opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In his two years as Whitman's appointed attorney general,
Verniero has aggressively championed her agenda, including
protecting the sex offender notification statute known as Megan's
Law, and persuading the U. S. Supreme Court that New Jersey was the
rightful owner of part of Ellis Island.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero, 39, was the object of considerable skepticism when he
joined the Whitman administration in 1994, because many Trenton
insiders questioned his relative youth and limited courtroom
experience. But even his former political adversaries acknowledge
that he has been an effective advocate for the governor's causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came here with a lot to learn, and he's learned it,'' said
Harold Hodes, a lobbyist. ``As chief counsel, chief of staff,
attorney general _ three very different jobs _ he's done them all
well. So there's no reason to believe he won't also learn to become
an excellent state Supreme Court Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   But some state legislators complained that Whitman was
nominating a political figure rather than a practicing judge, even
though New Jersey governors of both parties have made similar
appointments in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's most recent appointee to the court, Chief Justice
Deborah Poritz, also served as attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts also said the nomination, Whitman's third
opportunity to select a member of the seven-judge bench, signaled
an attempt to rein in a court with a history of judicial activism.
</P>
<P>
   Two more justices, Alan B. Handler and Daniel J. O'Hern, will
reach the mandatory retirement age of 70 before the governor's term
expires in 2001, and some legal scholars voiced concern that she
would leave office with a far more conservative bench than the one
she inherited.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great danger that this court's tradition will be
undermined,'' said Frank Askin, a professor of law at Rutgers
University. ``Peter Verniero has never demonstrated the qualities
that have distinguished the New Jersey state Supreme Court, namely
a passionate and intellectual commitment to the rights of the
powerless, the poor, or the rights of the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman dismissed suggestions that she was creating a court with
a more restrictive view of its own powers and insisted she would
continue the practice of choosing judicial nominees based on their
qualifications, rather than their ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never sat down and run through a list of litmus test
issues,'' she said. ``There is no conscious effort to make the
court more conservative or liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature will vote on the nomination by June, and,
because both houses are controlled by Republicans, Verniero is
expected to win approval easily.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Appearing at a news conference in the governor's office,
Verniero said he was gratified to be nominated, but he politely
deflected most questions about his beliefs regarding the powers of
the court.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing a case before the court last year, Verniero reminded
the justices that they did not have the power to create law, but he
would not say whether he would take a more expansive view of
judicial powers once he is on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courts often have to interpret statutes, and my only approach
will be to come to each case with an open mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero was born in Montclair and graduated from Drew
University in 1981 and Duke University Law School in 1984. His
involvement in Republican politics dates back to his high school
days, when he wrote a letter to the editor of The New York Times in
1976, arguing that the Republican Party was still alive and well,
despite the Watergate scandal and the re-election defeat of
President Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Richard Zimmer noticed the letter and recruited young
Verniero to work on his campaign. In the decade that followed,
Verniero went on to run the campaigns of several Republican
legislators and rose to the position of executive director of New
Jersey's Republican State Committee. In 1984, he served as a law
clerk to Justice Robert L. Clifford of the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming attorney general, Verniero has assiduously
avoided political events, declining to attend fund-raisers,
inaugural balls or other social engagements that might raise the
appearance of a partisan favoritism or conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Verniero was named the governor's chief of staff
in 1995, Hodes sent him two gifts, a bottle of vanilla flavoring
and a box of Ivory Snow, playful references to Verniero's fierce
loyalty to Whitman and his spotless reputation. Verniero refused to
accept them, saying it would be improper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's squeaky clean,'' Hodes said. ``He's so clean he only
wears white shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   But some New Jersey residents criticize Verniero's response to
lingering allegations that some state troopers routinely pick out
black motorists for tickets and arrests, an illegal practice known
as racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   As attorney general, Verniero has allowed his staff to represent
the troopers in their attempt to appeal a 1996 ruling by a
Gloucester County judge who found that troopers stopped motorists
on the New Jersey Turnpike solely because of their race.
</P>
</TEXT>
