<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN MAKES PLAY FOR HISPANICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Sen. John McCain made a bold pitch for Latino votes
in California on Friday, vowing to end the ``politics of division''
and campaign for the vote of every American, ``no matter where you
came from.''
</P>
<P>
   The move was a slap at the state party's right wing, and it sent
a clear message that McCain will fight Texas Gov. George W. Bush
for the political center of the GOP field.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the names of Abraham Lincoln and Theodore Roosevelt as
well as Ronald Reagan, McCain told the delegates that he
understands Latino issues, and will aggressively court their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won re-election last November with the support of 55 percent
of Hispanic voters in Arizona,'' McCain said. ``I am proud of that.
But I am not satisfied with that number. I want all their votes.
Their support is my honor. They believe in me, and I believe in
them. I want their help to build a better country.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's remarks came in a speech Friday night to the California
Republican Convention, where delegates are still reeling from a
political whipping in November that was attributed in part to the
dramatic flight of Hispanic voters from the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was McCain's first significant political address in a
state that is rich in delegates to the GOP nominating convention
next year and boasts an early primary election on March 7, 2000.
The opportunity to make a mark in California also attracted
candidates Dan Quayle of Arizona, Lamar Alexander, Gary Bauer,
Steve Forbes, Alan Keyes and Bob Smith.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech came just days after California Gov. Pete Wilson
announced he would not run for president. Wilson was resented by
many Hispanics for pushing anti-immigration measures and proposals
that would eliminate bilingual education. Wilson pulled out less
than a month after 25 members of the California Assembly wrote an
open letter urging Bush to enter the race.
</P>
<P>
   The California GOP is facing an identity crisis, as moderates
are making a strong push to wrest control of the party hierarchy
from conservatives. Many feel the party's conservative emphasis on
abortion, homosexuality and immigration is driving away too many
voters who would ordinarily vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP has lost 11 percent of its statewide registration
since 1992. And while Democratic registration is also down
slightly, that party carried the last two presidential elections in
the state and dominated the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Latino voter registration is increasing dramatically in
California and other Sun Belt states, including Arizona and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   McCain argued that the Republican message would appeal strongly
to Latino voters if divisive issues are avoided.
</P>
<P>
   There is strong support in the Hispanic community for many
conservative issues, he said, from school vouchers and the
anti-abortion movement to national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the party that best rewards hard work,'' McCain
declared. ``We are the party that supports small businesses. We are
the party that wants to make parochial education more affordable
for more Americans. We are the party of smaller government. These
are the central principles of the Republican message, but they are
too often drowned out by the politics of division. We're a better
country than that. And we're a better party than that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain closed the speech by telling the story of Roy Benavidez,
the son of a Texas sharecropper, once taunted as a ``dumb
Mexican,'' who grew up to be a decorated Green Beret in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer to live in a bigger place. I prefer to live in a
growing America, as proud of its variety as it is of the ideals
that unite us,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, both McCain and Vice President Al Gore received
awards for their support of bilingual education from the mainstream
Latino organization, the League of United Latin American Citizens,
and he has won more than 50 percent of the Hispanic vote in Arizona
in his past two elections. That puts McCain in a competitive
position for the increasingly important Hispanic vote in California
and helps him defuse what is widely seen as a Bush advantage.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, McCain is also scheduled to receive an award in
Washington from the National Council of La Raza, an organization
that was founded in 1968 and has evolved into a major Latino think
tank and pressure group.
</P>
<P>
   In his campaigns for governor, Bush, who is expected to form an
exploratory committee for president next month, has stressed that
the GOP be inclusive. He aggressively pursued Hispanic voters,
closing some of his television commercials speaking lines in fluent
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledged Bush and another unannounced candidate,
Elizabeth Dole, in his speech. He promised not to attack Bush, Dole
or any other GOP candidate with negative ads. He said that Bush,
Dole, John Kasich and Quayle were his friends before the campaign,
and that he hopes they will be friends when the campaign is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not engage in personal attacks and the politics of
division. I will not stoop to negative campaigning against fellow
Republicans. I will not run negative attack advertising. I give you
my word on it,'' McCain said. ``Scorched earth Republican primaries
will lead directly to an Al Gore presidency.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
