<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIANS WAITING TO HEAR BUSH, DOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The name Bush or Dole has appeared on every GOP
presidential ticket since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   As the state holds its Republican party convention this weekend
in Sacramento, many California Republicans are reluctant to endorse
anyone else until George W. Bush and Elizabeth Dole decide whether
to get in the race.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizonans John McCain and Dan Quayle are here anyway,
joining a slew of other contenders who are trying to get a jump in
the Golden State, the nation's largest electoral prize.
</P>
<P>
   Both McCain and Quayle won prime-time slots to address the
delegates, and each will use the time to begin the process of
building campaign networks to compete in California's potentially
decisive March 7, 2000, primary.
</P>
<P>
   But in California, both men are toiling in the long shadows of
Bush and Dole, who aren't even attending the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that everything is on hold until the first tier _
meaning Bush and Dole _ decide where they are going to go and what
they are going to do. Even those right-wing Republicans that you
generally hear from haven't been very vocal,'' says Sherry Bebitch
Jeffe, a senior associate at the School of Politics and Economics
at Claremont Graduate School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's meaningless. Everything is fluid, and everything is
waiting on Bush and, to a lesser extent, Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   California Republicans are still reeling from the 1998
elections, in which Democrats swept statewide offices, winning back
the governor's mansion. The party hasn't won Ronald Reagan's home
state in a presidential election since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of discontent in the party came last month, when 25
members of the California Assembly wrote an open letter to Bush,
urging him to run for president. The move in part torpedoed a
presidential bid by former Gov. Pete Wilson, who announced earlier
this week that he will not run.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that leaves an opening not only for Bush and
Dole but for McCain and Quayle as well. Most candidates are making
a push in California this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, no candidates showed up for the state party meetings.
That was largely because the primary was held in June _ long after
the race was decided. The early date makes it the prize of the
campaign in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   McCain in particular has been very candid about wanting to do
well in California. He's made the state a top priority, and has
been popping up all over the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst who appears frequently on
California radio and television stations, said McCain staffers
called her after she applied for media credentials for the
convention this week. They told her McCain would be available for
one-on-one interviews.
</P>
<P>
   And she saw him at a Christmas party in Orange County at the
home of a politico who helped put Reagan in the governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him by accident a couple of times, and I think it's
quite interesting,'' she said. ``He's really aggressive. . . . His
people are taking it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The main thing McCain needs to do is meet people and begin to
explain his positions on issues, Bebitch Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain has a lot of name recognition work to do out here. He
might be attractive to the base because of this war-hero record,''
Bebitch Jeffe said. ``The perception is he's not hard-right. That
would make him somewhat attractive to moderates. But I don't think
anybody really knows what his stands on issues are.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, on the other hand, is more of a known commodity. And by
basing his campaign in Phoenix, he's making a statement that
California will be a key state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be a player because he has name recognition,'' Bebitch
Jeffe said. ``I don't think he has much in terms of organization,
and we have yet to see what he can do in terms of fund-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tim Hodson, director of the Center for California Studies at
California State University, Sacramento, dismisses Quayle's
candidacy, arguing he wasn't a strong candidate on the ticket
either in 1988 or 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Quayle's chances are about as good in California as
they are nationally, which means, in my opinion, not very good,''
Hodson said. One of the problems for Quayle, Hodson said, is the
crowded field. He has lots of competition for votes from the
conservative wing of the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of whether California Republicans look at Dan
Quayle as a formidable candidate, and I think the conclusion would
be no.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, Hodson said, ``is intriguing.'' As an Arizonan, he's
far enough away from California to be ``exotic,'' but close enough
to understand Californian and Western issues, Hodson said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that President Bush rarely set foot in the state
after winning the 1988 election, and that Californians resented him
for it. President Clinton has been attuned to that, making more
than 50 trips to the state since he was first elected. Vice
President Al Gore has also spent a lot of time in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Hodson said many California Republicans realize the party needs
to moderate its image to target the state's growing minority
population. Latinos, in particular, are a growing force in the
state politically, winning more political offices at all levels of
government.
</P>
<P>
   California Latinos have become more politically active in the
wake of initiatives on immigration and bilingual education, which
were led by conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   That has alienated Hispanics from voting Republican, despite the
fact that many Latinos agree with the party's conservative social
and economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Hodson points to the contrast between recent gubernatorial
campaign ads from Wilson and Bush: Wilson's 1994 ad featured
Hispanics flooding across the border; Bush spoke fluent Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Republican that comes into California _ a Pat Buchanan _
who starts talking about we have to have one language, one culture,
one faith, they're going to get chopped up into little pieces,''
Hodson said. &QL; 
Chris Moeser can be reached at 444-8069 or at
chris.moeser(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
