<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE CHEFS LIKE, GARDENERS LIKE, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Ore., N.M.)  (For release Sunday, Feb. 28) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERT KOURIK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seed catalogs are brimming with new and scrumptious vegetables:
the intense burgundy-red New Red Fire lettuce; Early Moonbeam
watermelon, with a lemon-yellow flesh; the curled red-purple leaves
of the Red Ursa kale, and delicate half-inch Red Currant tomatoes,
to be eaten like grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these distinctive vegetables are entering seed catalogs
in a new way _ from consumer demand driven by what creative chefs
around the country are serving to adventurous diners. Gardeners
tired of the same old flavors or types of vegetables can choose
from many new tastes and selections. A decade ago, most Americans
had never heard of the nutty-flavored arugula, red radicchios, the
mild Asian green mizuna, savory mesclun or Hopi Blue corn. All of
them have found their ways into retail seed packets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to 10 years ago,'' said Renee Shepherd, the owner of
Renee's Garden Seeds in Felton, Calif., ``many new seeds came only
from seed producers and breeders and were displayed at yearly
tours'' given for garden writers and editors and industry
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   This meant that seed companies offered mostly hybrids that they
had tested in various parts of the country and developed by
commercial breeders or the U.S. Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   In the last dozen years or so, premium vegetables, both hybrids
and heirlooms, have entered the seed business in a process starting
with small farmers' offering unusual crops, often organic, to
chefs. When the public becomes excited by the intriguing flavors,
other restaurants, specialty produce distributors and farmers'
markets pick up on the new vegetables, and some of them end up in
the retail seed trade for the entire country to savor. The process
generally takes from four to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   An example is a mesclun salad mixture developed in the mid-1980s
by several individuals, including Doug Gosling when he was the head
gardener for the Farallones Institute Rural Center, a nonprofit
environmental center in Occidental, Calif. Mesclun salad mixtures,
which can now be purchased in farmers' markets and many
supermarkets, probably originated in France and Italy and can
include such greens as arugula, special green- and red-leafed
lettuces, colorful kales, mizuna, wild greens and slightly bitter
chicories and radicchios. The greens are cut quite short, often
less than four inches tall, prewashed, mixed together and sold as a
ready-to-eat salad.
</P>
<P>
   Gosling's mix of 30 or more organically grown varieties of
greens, herbs and edible flowers (an American enhancement) was
selling at wholesale to New York chefs for $15 a pound by 1983.
Now, many seed companies offer packets of simple mesclun salad
mixes (aka cut-and-come-again salads), as well as packets of the
individual ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shepherd attributes the interest in exotic, unusual and
heirloom vegetables to many factors: ``America as a nation does not
have a single dominant food culture; the increase of ethnic groups
in America; the interest Americans have in travel; the availability
of new flavors in restaurants, and the interest Americans now have
in bringing vegetables to the center of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The farmer-to-restaurant-to-seed-packet process can be speeded
up by tastings attended by specialty growers and chefs, all of whom
have an interest in new vegetables. For example, for six years, an
event called the Sonoma County Chefs' Tasting helped to introduce
chefs from across the country to the unusual produce that farmers
were growing. At the event, growers displayed their specialty
produce, restaurants showed off trend-setting uses of little-known
crops, and chefs spotted new delights for experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   Such attempts to link farmers with chefs are sprouting up
nationwide. This year, as in the last two years, the Eastern Native
Seed Conservancy in Great Barrington, Mass., is sponsoring tastings
of nearly 200 varieties of heirloom tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners and chefs can have a direct effect on what seeds are
being offered. ``Consumers and chefs complained so much about the
poor taste of typical oregano, seed companies finally offered
Origanum vulgare heracleoticum for a true Greek oregano,'' said
Rose Marie Nichols McGee, an owner of Nichols Garden Nursery, in
Albany, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   She also gave the example of fresh leaf cilantro (Coriandrum
sativum). Mexican and Chinese restaurants started asking for the
herb, but it would bolt to seed too quickly. The growers talked
with seedsmen about the problem. Seeds were collected from various
parts of the world, and some seeds were found not to bolt so
quickly. They were made available to the growers, and the
restaurants got their cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   All of this feedback from gardeners, farmers and chefs has
generated some tasteful choices from seed companies, like
rich-flavored black Russian tomatoes; frisee, a mild, finely cut
green; flavored basils; red Russian kale; unusual Chinese
eggplants, and golden beets.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Predictions include tomatillos; Cape gooseberries,
sweeter relatives of tomatillos; tomatoes that have great flavor
when ripe but are still green, like Green Stripe and Green Grape,
and mashua, a nasturtium with edible flowers and pale-yellow,
peppery tubers.
</P>
<P>
   And garlic. In Occidental, Calif., Chester Aaron grows more than
80 garlic varieties. Seeds of Change, a mail-order company in Santa
Fe, N.M., is growing 10 of them, including Creole Red, Asian
Tempest and, from the former Soviet republic of Georgia, Purple
Glazer, all for sale starting in April for delivery in fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
