<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA BIBLE WEEK DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Gov. Jane Hull, declaring that she wants to bring
Arizona residents together, not divide them, said Friday that she
would no longer issue proclamations for Bible Week.
</P>
<P>
   It was just such a proclamation by Hull in November that sparked
an outcry from non-Christian groups and resulted in a lawsuit
against the state by the Arizona Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's decision is likely to put an end to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to issue a proclamation that says that I'm going
to acknowledge . . . Bible Week,'' Hull told ``The Republic.'' ``I
want to bring people together. I don't want to divide them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was certainly, in my mind, no desire to offend any
religious group. I think this is one of those things I'd like to
see resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull's comments surprised ACLU officials because in November,
after the lawsuit was filed in federal court on behalf of three
citizens, she vowed to fight the case vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's change of position was praised Friday by Eleanor
Eisenberg, executive director of the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' Eisenberg said. ``I'm very gratified
that the governor was concerned enough about the proclamation being
divisive that she decided against doing it in the future. It
probably means we can withdraw the lawsuit because that's the
relief we were looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue, however, probably won't go away quite yet. A similar
lawsuit by the ACLU also is pending against Gilbert Mayor Cynthia
Dunham, who also issued a Bible Week proclamation in November.
</P>
<P>
   Gary McCaleb of the American Center for Law and Justice, who is
defending Dunham, said, ``there are negotiations'' under way aimed
at settling the suit, but he wouldn't comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Dunham was out of town Friday and unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible Week proclamations caused an uproar last fall that
lasted weeks, with opponents saying they violated the
constitutional separation of church and state. Others complained
that the proclamations indicated government support of a particular
religious belief.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Roslyn Silver agreed and issued temporary
injunctions against both proclamations.
</P>
<P>
   The state argued that its proclamation recognized the Bible as
only a cultural and historical document, not primarily as a
religious book. Hull also noted at the time that she routinely
issues proclamations on a variety of topics, some of them involving
religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   But Eisenberg said the state's Bible Week proclamation differed
from others because it ``included a suggestion that people read the
Bible for spiritual guidance. It came pretty darn close to the
government suggesting to us what to read.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's proclamation called the Bible ``the foundational
document of the Judeo-Christian principles upon which our nation
was conceived,'' and ``a constant course of moral and spiritual
guidance for Americans.'' It said National Bible Week has ``helped
to strengthen spiritual understanding throughout our nation by
encouraging personal reading of the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   The wording was provided by the New York-based National Bible
Association, which every year requests every governor and every
mayor to proclaim the week. The association has declared Bible Week
every year since 1941 to garner publicity. Last year, 26 states and
more than 400 cities had proclaimed Bible Week.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said that, although she won't issue any more such
proclamations, she would have no problem ``recognizing individual
good works done by any religious group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not give up the ability to issue proclamations because
I think they are important to the groups who request them.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg said the ACLU would have to look at the types of
proclamations Hull was referring to, but would have less of a
problem with the state ``recognizing an event without promoting it,
or without making suggestions about following a certain spiritual
path.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Hal Mattern can be reached at 444-8652 or at hal.mattern &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
