<HEADER>
A1468 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     02-27 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS HOLD OFF CHICAGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ With no warning, Hurricane Tim blew into the Windy
City on Friday night, explaining tersely that he was in town to
work, and reacting defiantly when a reporter jokingly asked if a
coaching change was on his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys have a deathwatch,'' Kings president Tim Leiweke said
following the team's crucial 2-1 victory Friday night over the
Chicago Blackhawks before a United Center crowd of 18,364. ``We
don't. We're very patient. Our coaches are going to finish the
year. Our players now know their damn careers are on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Affecting his most strident us-against-the-world stance, Leiweke
also promised that those very players would lift the Kings into a
playoff run that quite possibly would extend into May. About the
only thing he didn't promise was a Stanley Cup, which would require
the Kings to play into June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will look at themselves in the mirror at the end of
the season,'' Leiweke said. ``You have a deathwatch. We don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain his appearance in Chicago, Leiweke would only
say: ``We had business.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the Kings, and they were fortunate this segment of their
business trip didn't end in disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   They were outplayed the entire night by a Blackhawks team making
its home debut under interim coach Lorne Molleken, but the Kings
survived to record their eighth straight win over Chicago (17-36-8)
and improved to 2-1-1 on their season-long six-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   The victory allowed the Kings (23-32-5) to remain three points
out of a playoff berth with 22 games remaining. The fifth game of
the trip is Sunday afternoon against the Dallas Stars, who are
9-0-6 in the last 15 meetings between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we got the win, and I'll take it,'' coach Larry Robinson
said. ``But I wouldn't like to play that way against Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   The heroes Friday for the Kings were Donald Audette and Rob
Blake, who gave the Kings a 2-0 lead through two periods, and
goalie Jamie Storr, who made 33 saves, including a stop with his
right shoulder on a Todd White penalty shot.
</P>
<P>
   White was awarded the shot when Yanic Perreault was ruled to
have closed his hand on the puck in the crease 1:58 into the third
period, a call strongly disputed by the Kings. Storr made the save
look easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to the top of the circle, and he was showing he wanted
to try a poke check,'' White said. ``He made a great move by not
biting on my fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr said: ``I wanted to challenge him.... How many times do
you see a guy take a penalty shot and the goalie stays back in the
net and they score? You've got to create something.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third penalty shot against the Kings this season, the
first against Storr _ and the first that didn't result in a goal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blackhawks scored 1:11 later, when Steve Duchesne failed
to check ex-King Ed Olczyk, who was left free to Storr's right to
poke in a short cross-ice pass from Tony Amonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a defenseman's job,'' Robinson said, referring to
Duchesne. ``He's got to get position, especially in a big game.
He's got to be a little stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings did just enough to win, and the Blackhawks did just
enough to lose. Chicago was hapless during six minutes on the power
play in the first period, and the Kings converted on two of their
few scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   Blake and Audette, who scored on a power play, have goals in
consecutive games. Wednesday, they produced the third-period goals
that created the opportunity for Luc Robitaille to score the
game-winner in overtime at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's performance by the Kings wasn't nearly as impressive.
But the result of the latest biggest game of the year was the
important part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game we play is the biggest game of the year,'' Blake
said. ``We got ourselves in this position. We can't take any days
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Leiweke: ``I'm pretty happy with these guys. They showed
some character the last two games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
