<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARKIEWICZ-COLUMN-JAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF OF PONY EXPRESS REACHES PINNACLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a year it's been for the ``other member'' of the Pony
Express.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Eric Dickerson's done all right for himself with his
selection to the Pro Football Hall of Fame, but let's talk about
his counterpart in the SMU Mustangs backfield, Craig James.
</P>
<P>
   James had a pretty nice career in the NFL, too, as a running
back for the New England Patriots. He didn't leave it all on the
field, though, rushing through his second career, the sports
broadcasting business, much as he did Southwest Conference
defensive lines in his college days.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Plano resident crossed into another end zone
recently when CBS picked him to join its ``NFL Today'' studio show
as an analyst for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what I've tried to accomplish in broadcasting, it's the
pinnacle,'' James said the other day from his home.
</P>
<P>
   When CBS gave him the good word, James recalled, ``I kind of
went like, `Wow!' It really was a sense of relief because I'd
gotten what I'd wanted. Now, it's up to me to perfect what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   James and former NFL head coach Jerry Glanville will try to
breathe some life into a show that was comatose from the get-go
last season. TV newcomers George Seifert, Brent Jones and Marcus
Allen were overwhelmed by the demands of the pregame program.
Savaged by critics, the threesome was obviously overmatched by
their competitors at Fox, led by Terry Bradshaw.
</P>
<P>
   James is sympathetic toward his ``NFL Today'' predecessors. He
remembers what it was like for him when he took over KRLD radio's
nightly sports talk show in 1991, one of his early gigs in
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first big job, two hours live, with me carrying
it,'' James recalled. ``That little light went on and I spoke for
30 seconds _ and I had no wind! I was scared to death. If I'd had
to go on \RTV\S before tens of millions of people \Rlike rookies
Seifert, Jones and Allen\S . . . I just don't know. Thank God I
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   James learned his role the old-fashioned way: He grew into it
through a succession of local sports broadcasting jobs. He worked
as a color analyst on SMU football after his NFL days, was host to]
a weekly Cowboys show and served as anchor on Channel 4 sports.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he expanded a part-time college football role at ESPN
to full-time status, giving him national exposure. He moved to CBS
two years later, setting up last year's late-season NFL studio
fill-in role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the commitment once I got into the business that I
wouldn't just do games,'' James said. ``I wanted to learn the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, working in all phases of broadcasting, including sales,
production and marketing. He learned much in these areas as
executive producer of ``The Michael Irvin Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If people say I look comfortable up there, that's why,'' he
said. ``Because I know what everybody's trying to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   James has developed a reputation as a straight-talker on the air
in a business populated by speak-no-evil types.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bold enough to speak my mind,'' he explained. ``I don't
straddle the fence. That may be good or bad, but it's an opinion. I
hope that on Monday morning people are talking about something I
said on Sunday. Not that I'm trying to stir the pot. ... I want to
beat them to the thought.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his style, James summarizes, ``I really feel like a guy
in a group of guys sitting at home watching the game. Of course, I
have the privilege of having a microphone. But I can share their
sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   James insists that his new, high profile won't alter his style
or attitude. He isn't worried about his Fox competitors, either.
Playing golf last week with Bradshaw, James told his new opponent,
``I'm coming after that Fox money.''
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, though . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect them,'' James said. ``I watched their show and I
enjoy them. But they've got their team and we've go ours. I'm not
worried. As a player, if I worried too much about the Jets or
Dolphins or whoever we were playing that week, I couldn't do my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his running-back days, James said he has only fond
thoughts of Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still very close to Eric,'' James said. ``I'm going to try
like heck to get to Canton \Rfor the Hall of Fame induction
ceremony\S. He is really a genuine, likable person. He's been
misunderstood, and I think he recognizes why.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, James jokes, ``If he were really a good guy, he'd
loan me a few thousand yards \Rto pad my NFL stats\S. I mean, when
we were 18, I carried him.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
