<SLUG> BC-BKW-WOMEN'S-BASKETBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROS AND CONS OF PREDETERMINED SITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the next week, the NCAA will gather the bids to determine
which sites to use for the first and second rounds of the women's
NCAA Tournament. This is the way it has been done since the
tournament began in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   However, the NCAA is considering going to predetermined sites
beginning next year for the first two rounds, much the same way it
does for the regionals and Final Four and in the men's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to go through the management council, the board of
directors and the economic committee before it's approved,'' said
Tricia Burke, vice president of the NCAA women's basketball
championships. ``The final vote would be in August.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the 16 schools selected to play host to a first-round
site have approximately five days to prepare for the event. If the
proposal to use predetermined sites is approved, a city and
university would have one year to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   The process would be similar to the regional bid process _
schools submit their proposals, covering facilities, hotels and
other amenities, and are awarded the games approximately one year
before the tournament begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think it's a good concept; whether it's the right time
or not it's hard to know,'' Burke said. ``With such large parties,
it would make it easier for traveling and allow for better
planning. It would also allow us to try to get into larger markets
with larger fan bases.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside is smaller, successful programs with good fan bases
such as Stephen F. Austin might find it difficult to play host to
first-round games. Nacogdoches has a population of 33,500 and has
less hotel space than an Austin or Springfield, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter whether I like it or not, it's coming,'' SFA
coach Royce Chadwick said. ``I would hate to see them not look at
fan base as a criterion. I know we can fill our place up for
tournament games; we have before. Whereas if you have tournament
games in a major metropolitan area, they might not fill it.''
</P>
<P>
   With this system, for example, Texas could be named a host, but
its team could play its first-round games at the University of
Virginia, or Duke or some other predetermined site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general thought is that it provides a better chance for
everyone in the tournament to play at a neutral site,'' Chadwick
said. ``When you are playing on a neutral floor you would like it
to be as even as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's tournament went through a similar growth in the 1980s
and perhaps this step is inevitable.
LSU HOOP DREAMS
</P>
<P>
   Katrina Hibbert steps to the foul line and tries to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana State is tied with Tennessee 70-70 with seconds left
and Hibbert is at the line for a one-and-one.
</P>
<P>
   That's a dream, though. After all, who could possibly expect the
Lady Tigers to be tied with then top-ranked Tennessee late in the
game?
</P>
<P>
   Hibbert did, and so did her teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was consuming my thoughts all the time,'' Hibbert
said. ``During practice, we would joke about being tied and being
at the line with the game on the line. But we were just kidding
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee wasn't laughing Sunday when Hibbert's three-point play
with 11.7 seconds remaining put LSU ahead for good in a 72-69
victory. The loss snapped Tennessee's 31-game conference winning
streak. The Lady Vols had not lost a regular-season conference game
since Feb. 24, 1997, when LSU defeated them, 83-78.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a confidence lift for our whole team,'' said
Hibbert, who scored a team-high 18 points and handed out eight
assists. ``We didn't even get to shake their hands after the game
because people started running all over the court.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Hibbert was besieged with media requests and
phone calls from well-wishers. It's quite a different experience
than the Australian expected when she arrived in Baton Rouge more
than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here I never really knew the whole tradition of
Tennessee,'' Hibbert said. ``I didn't realize how big they were or
how good this conference is.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if she knows now?
</P>
<P>
   PACKING THE PIT
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 9,700 tickets have been sold for New Mexico's game
tomorrow against Utah. If the Lobos (20-5, 11-2 Western Athletic
Conference) defeat the Utes, it will clinch a tie for first place
in the Pacific Division for UNM's first regular-season title.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the program lost all-time leading scorer Abby
Garchek from last season's NCAA Tournament team, this season's 20
victories are all the more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   A big crowd at UNM's ``Pit'' for a women's basketball game is
not.
</P>
<P>
   Through 13 home games this season, the Lobos women have drawn
82,419 fans, an average of 6,340, which ranks 10th among NCAA
Division I schools. With the two games this week closing out the
regular season, New Mexico also is on track to become only the
sixth women's basketball team to go over 100,000 in attendance this
season.
</P>
<P>
   This season, attendance is up by an average of 1,330 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a combination of being successful last year and
finding new fans, and then this year being successful again,''
coach Don Flanagan said. He has led UNM to three consecutive
winning seasons, including a school-record 26 victories last season
when the Lobos won the Western Athletic Conference tournament. ``We
don't want to be a one-time phenom. We want to be consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   ALL-AMERICA TIME
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if these names appear on first-team
All-America lists:
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Canty, Alabama: The best player you've never heard of
averages 20 points and 7.3 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie White-McCarty, Purdue: She will leave West Lafayette
as the program's second all-time leading scorer and maybe with a
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Chamique Holdsclaw, Tennessee: Arguably the game's most dominant
player since Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Hammon, Colorado State: The quintessential gym rat ... and
shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Dalma Ivanyi, Florida International: Because she plays for a
small program in a relatively obscure conference, she probably
won't make it on as many lists as Memphis guard Tamika Whitmore or
Tennessee's Tamika Catchings, but she leads the nation in assists.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the year: Bonnie Henrickson, Virginia Tech. Unless you
scoured the Top 25 every week you wouldn't know the No. 9 Hokies
(25-1) are having their best season ever.
MOVE OVER, MJ
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of players and coaches have been inducted into the
Basketball Hall of Fame in Springfield, Mass., but only 14 players
have had their lockers enshrined. Achieving that is a separate
honor.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's is there. And now, so is Rebecca Lobo's and
Swoopes'.
</P>
<P>
   The gold medalists and NCAA champions will both have their
lockers dedicated at the Hall of Fame today.
GAMES TO WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow
</P>
<P>
   SEC Tournament title game, 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky and Ole Miss desperately need strong finishes and an
appearance by either one of the three in this game probably pushes
them into the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Monday
</P>
<P>
   ACC tournament title game, 7 p.m. Don't be stunned if top-seed
Duke ``isn't/ here.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten tournament title game, 6:30 p.m. No. 1 Purdue has little
to gain and is primed for an upset here before the real tournament
begins.
nn
</P>
