<HEADLINE>
RECORD FIELD EXPECTED DESPITE CELEBRITY SNOW-IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Some of the celebrity luster of today's
Cowtown Marathon races was lost yesterday when four-time world
cross country champion Lynn Jennings was unable to get a flight out
of snowed-in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings was scheduled to run in the women's 10K. But officials
are still expecting a record field.
</P>
<P>
   Entries for the marathon, marathon relays, 10K and 5K had
reached 11,519 early yesterday. The marathon saw an increase over
recent years with 734 entries; the 10K has 4,989, and the 5K 5,263.
Last year, 1,300 registered on race day, which boosted the count to
a record 13,905.
</P>
<P>
   Weather usually is a factor for race-day registration, and
forecasts call for no rain and temperatures in the 50s at race
time.
</P>
<P>
   The women's 10K will still have Jody Hawkins of Blooming Grove,
last year's Avon National 10K winner and winner of the recent
Austin Half Marathon. Hawkins will be wearing bib number 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity runners in the men's 5K include former Olympian and
two-time world cross country champion Craig Virgin and former
Southwest Conference 5,000-meter indoor champion Paul Stoneham of
Fort Worth. Virgin will be wearing No. 15001, and Stoneham will
wear 2002.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
