<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' RODRIGUEZ SHOWS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Catcher Ivan Rodriguez acknowledged what
Rangers management questioned _ his leadership qualities _ after
the seven-time All-Star reported to camp eight days late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a leader,'' Rodriguez said yesterday
afternoon upon his arrival to the Rangers' Charlotte County Stadium
complex. ``I consider myself just another player who's got a job to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not share his view.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Rangers rewarded Rodriguez with a five-year
contract extension through the 2002 season worth $42 million and
place greater expectations upon a:
</P>
<P>
   27-year-old catcher with 71/2 years of major-league service;
</P>
<P>
   player earning $8 million this season;
</P>
<P>
   seven-time All-Star;
</P>
<P>
   seven-time Gold Glove Award recipient;
</P>
<P>
   four-time .300 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like for him to be a leader,'' Rangers general manager
Doug Melvin said, ``but that's his choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez expressed being ``upset'' and ``a little bit down''
after learning of comments about his tardiness attributed to
Rangers owner Tom Hicks, president Tom Schieffer and Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they've been saying those things,'' Rodriguez
said. ``They know what I've been doing. I've talked to the manager
\RJohnny Oates\S three or four times already. Now, I don't know if
Doug Melvin or Tom Hicks knows what I've been doing, but Johnny
Oates knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez remained in Puerto Rico to finish closing on a home he
purchased for his father and completing plans for his youth
baseball academy, which is scheduled to begin operations in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, I've spent eight years in this organization,''
Rodriguez said. ``Do they remember the seven years that I reported
a week early?''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also took offense to Melvin's comparison to Hall of
Fame catcher Johnny Bench. Melvin wondered how often Bench reported
to camp late.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to make the Hall of Fame by getting here two
weeks early,'' Rodriguez countered.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's response: ``Well, I guess it's just a matter of who's
upset more then: him with me for the Hall of Fame comment or me
with him for not being here on time.''
</P>
<P>
   Responsibility and accountability remain the heart of the matter
from the Rangers' view.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boss was asking me a lot of questions that I had to answer
for Pudge that I couldn't answer at times,'' Melvin said. ``I can't
change my stance that I'm disappointed that he wasn't in camp.
We've gone out and spent a lot of money for a winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez downplayed his responsibility to teammates, all of
whom reported on time except for right fielder Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't be mad because I'm one week late,'' Rodriguez said.
``They've got to do what they've got to do. I'll do what I've got
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Rodriguez ruffled some feathers, Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard whispers that some guys are upset,'' Melvin said,
``but they're not going to stand up and say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, who did not speak to Rodriguez yesterday, could not
answer whether the two would talk privately about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows where my office is,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Would Melvin initiate a discussion?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate I'll do that,'' Melvin said, ``and I know
where he is _ as of today.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
