<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PENGUINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLE PLAYERS SHINE IN HULL-LESS OUTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Who needs Brett Hull, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' role players filled the hole last night left by a
hamstring injury to Hull as the Stars outgunned a dangerous
Pittsburgh Penguins' team, 6-4, before the 25th consecutive sellout
crowd of 16,928 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   With Hull and his team-leading 26 goals expected to be out of
the lineup two to three weeks, the Stars picked it up at every
level and came at the Penguins in waves. Dave Reid stepped up to
the second line and contributed a goal and an assist. Pat Verbeek
had a goal and two assists and the third line of Tony Hrkac, Mike
Keane and Grant Marshall chipped in the game-winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, every line contributed to a hard forechecking
performance, allowing the Stars to get 35 shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who we are and that's who we've been,'' Verbeek said.
``This is no different than before. We had key guys out last year
and we did the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   This, however, is the first extended streak in the 1998-99
season in which the Stars have had to deal with injuries _ Hull,
Darryl Sydor and Brian Skrudland are out of the lineup. But Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said the bad breaks could actually turn into
golden opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, long haul, it's good for us,'' Hitchcock said. Hull
``has forced us to look in the mirror offensively, and we've got to
have contributions throughout the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars got just that from the opening puck drop as Verbeek,
fresh off an early scrum with Penguins goalie Tom Barrasso, whipped
in a slap shot from the right wing for a 1-0 lead at the 7:23 mark.
The Stars were all over the Penguins early and tallied 19 shots in
the first period alone, but the Stars trailed after 20 minutes when
the Penguins received a breakaway goal from Martin Straka and a
deflection goal off of a Stars' defenseman among their five
first-period shots.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 2-1, the Stars came out invigorated in the second
period and seized the lead. Jamie Langenbrunner blasted in a slap
shot from the right side at the 58-second mark and Sergei Zubov
played pinball with a shot from the wing off a Penguins defenseman
to make it 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then the race was on. Reid made it 4-2 when he picked up a
rebound goal off a Joe Nieuwendyk shot at the 9:50 mark, but the
Penguins again answered with goals from Straka and Kip Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars appeared to be losing momentum with the 4-4 tie, but
didn't back down. Marshall forced a turnover at his own blue line
and pushed the puck forward to Keane. Keane passed back to Marshall
and Marshall then went cross-ice to set up Hrkac for the
game-winner, the first point for Hrkac in the past 10 games. Mike
Modano then added an empty-netter after Stars goalie Ed Belfour
held off a furious flurry from the Penguins, including a Jaromir
Jagr swipe at what appeared to be a certain game-tying goal with
6:10 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the list of clutch plays stretched to Belfour,
Derian Hatcher, Guy Carbonneau, Richard Matvichuk, Shawn Chambers,
Craig Ludwig and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But most noticeable was the offensive push on a night that
Hitchcock said beforehand the Stars might have to win 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a player playing as good as Hull was, it's easy
to just let someone else do it,'' Hitchcock said of his role
players falling into an offensive lull in the past two weeks. ``But
everybody is going to have to contribute because you never know
when you're going to be the hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Stars had 19 of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
