<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-JAZZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS SNOOZE THROUGH ROAD LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ To sum up just how boring last night's game
between the Mavericks and Utah Jazz was, one fan was stretched out
asleep over three chairs behind the Dallas bench at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   It drew laughter from the Mavericks, who also were asleep at the
wheel. The Mavericks never woke up, losing, 80-65, before a sellout
crowd of 19,911 at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Mavericks' fourth game in five days, and their
second in two nights. And once it was clear the Jazz was going to
maintain its 20-something lead for the balance of the game,
Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson decided to rest most of
his regulars.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Mavericks will be playing their third game in
as many nights when they host the Sacramento Kings at 7 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game that I thought we had to be careful of,'' Nelson
said. ``I don't want to burn up all of the starters and then not
have anything left for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I used this as a game to hope that our reserves could keep
it close, and have a chance to insert the starters back in. But
when that didn't happen, I made the decision that I'm just going to
let the reserves play it out and hope that they can get a good feel
to their game.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting shooting guard Michael Finley played just 12 minutes
and was 1-of-3 from the field and finished with two points. Shawn
Bradley, who played collegiately at Brigham Young University in
nearby Provo, only played 11 minutes and collected two points,
three fouls and four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Starting point guard Steve Nash put in nine minutes of work and
finished with two points on 1-of-2 shooting. And starting power
forward A.C. Green played seven minutes and scored four points.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' starters combined to score only 15 points and
went 6-of-18 from the field. Rookie Dirk Nowitzki, starting in
place of the injured Cedric Ceballos, led the Mavericks starters
with five points and played a game-high 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was somewhat disappointed because he had about three
dozen members of his family and friends at the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people made some long drives to come up here and support
me,'' Bradley said. ``But they'll love me whether I played or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos is out six to eight weeks after fracturing his right
wrist Thursday night on a flagrant foul by Denver's Loren Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   Garbage time came very early last night. With Karl Malone (13
points, 10 rebounds) bulling his way inside, and Bryon Russell (17
points) bombing away from the outside, Utah built a 52-34 lead at
the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz lead got as high as 26 (68-42) in the third quarter.
The Mavericks (4-10) converted only 2-of-15 shots in the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are 0-18 all-time at the Delta Center, and have
lost their past 23 games in Salt Lake City. They shot 29.4 percent
from the floor and were outrebounded, 53-41.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pack led the Mavericks with a game-high 18 points, and
Samaki Walker had 11 points and eight rebounds in 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Finley called the game ``weird,'' but added that he understands
why Nelson did what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``His philosophy basically was to pretty much save the guys that
were getting major minutes for \Rtonight\S, being that we have to
compete in a back-to-back-to-back,'' Finley said. ``So I
understand.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
