<DOCNO> NYT19990227.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1502 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     02-27 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMBO IS NO JOKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The new Lakers era was ushered in with laughter
Friday. The encouraging thing was it came a solid 60 minutes
!ital!before!off! the first Dennis Rodman sighting of the night.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Mitch Kupchak walked into a room in the Forum
and solemnly introduced Kurt Rambis as Del Harris' replacement.
Nobody uttered a word in the next second so Rambis piped up. ``No
applause?'' he deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   It was a joke that asserted that his promotion was not.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, humor comes in handy when you look as unassuming as
Clark Kent and are surrounded by Supermen. The truth is, Rambis can
poke fun at himself but his egg-on-his-face guise belies a
hard-boiled center.
</P>
<P>
   In his four-plus seasons as an assistant on Harris' staff, no
one escaped Rambis' wrath, not even superstar center Shaquille
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   That's significant because opposing power forwards apparently
aren't the only ones apt to tiptoe around the 7-foot-1 manchild.
Harris handled O'Neal like a Fabrege egg and look where it got him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I do something bad,'' O'Neal said, ``I expect to be
cussed out, not talked to in a politically correct way.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of political correctness, the race card regrettably was
raised by some almost as soon as Rambis' promotion was made
official to explain why the deck was stacked against the Lakers
assistant who lost out on the job. It's true, Larry Drew is
African-American. As for the rest of it, ``race had absolutely
nothing to do with this decision,'' Kupchak asserted (Drew, for his
part, let his class show through by interrupting Rambis' press
conference to offer his congratulations).
</P>
<P>
   To be conversant in Lakers' history is to be inclined to believe
Kupchak. When head coach Mike Dunleavy left the Lakers for
Milwaukee after the 1992 season, one of his assistants, Randy
Pfund, was named to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Pfund won favor for his fealty, having spurned a head-coaching
offer from the Sacramento Kings and an assistant's job under his
old boss, Pat Riley, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Rambis, 40, recently had dismissed coaching overtures
from the Kings and the Clippers. At the first opportunity, the
Lakers front office returned his loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak even tried to give Rambis a little extra breathing room
by stating that the Lakers absolutely, positively won't enter into
conversations with any other coaching candidates.
</P>
<P>
   At least until the season's end.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that a head-coaching position in the NBA is about as
secure as an unlocked car on an L.A. street. There are a couple
other salient reasons to wonder whether the Lakers have done Rambis
a good or bad turn.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to read the fine print on the pretty
purple-and-gold package to know all the ingredients are all there
for a meltdown: sky-high expectations, a slow start, a shortened
season and an unseasoned head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the best situation to be working under,'' Rambis
readily admitted.
</P>
<P>
   But _ and on the first day of a new job, there's always one of
those _ ``I relish a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if not for his penchant for hurdling obstacles, Rambis'
NBA career would have been shorter than Rodman's attention span. He
made a star-studded Lakers team in 1981-82 as an unheralded free
agent and was a fixture there for the next six seasons, providing
hustle, defense, rebounding and toughness. To his opponents, he was
Kurt Rambo.
</P>
<P>
   ``His role was to rough people up and I hated him because he did
his role too well,'' said O'Neal, who played against Rambis as a
rookie. ``You don't know much about him, you see his long hair and
those ugly-ass glasses and you think he's one of those beach cats.
He had a lot of heart, though.''
</P>
<P>
   On the way to winning four NBA championships with the Lakers,
Rambis was learning a lot that he'll be able to draw on these next
few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always helped my teammates to play hard,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   The task before him now is to get his players to hustle on both
ends of the court. Somehow Rambis has got to find a way to convince
them that a solid defensive effort is the key to starting the
fast-break offense that trips the lights in Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to keep re-emphasizing all the things we've
been trying to accomplish for years now,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis' way of reminding his players of their shortcomings is as
subtle as the man himself. He doesn't scream at people, he shames
them into shaping up. Pity the poor guard, for example, who
persists in putting up 3-pointers down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt has a tendency, if you continually make a mistake, of
making you feel bad,'' said guard Kobe Bryant. ``He has the ability
to be a friend of yours. At the same time, he's not worried about
getting on your bad side.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's the players who should be worried about getting on
Rambis' bad side. As far as changes go, that's a good start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 0155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
