<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Mighty Ducks are No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the NHL standings, of course. But when it comes to the
power play no team is better than Anaheim, which defeated San Jose
3-1 in the third period before 17,174 at the Pond on the strength
of two more power play goals.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long and physical game that featured a Brian Marchment
cross-check on Steve Rucchin in the first three minutes of play,
after the NHL's favorite villain had run over Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Anaheim's special teams that were the difference as
they have been so many times this year.
</P>
<P>
   While Rucchin and Selanne scored on the power play to give the
Ducks 63 power play goals in 60 games, Anaheim easily killed off a
four-minute penalty in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's big chance came just six seconds after Rucchin scored
his 22nd goal of the year at 11:35, re-directing Fredrik Olausson's
pass. The Sharks, however, could manage only one harmless 60-footer
on their power play.
</P>
<P>
   A Ducks' victory would move them one game over .500 (26-25-9),
keep them in fifth place, three points ahead of St. Louis, and move
them seven points ahead of seventh-place San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks were on the verge of falling to 0-4-2 since winning
four consecutive games on their recent 10-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   A Anaheim win would be its ninth of the month -- a new club
record -- and give them 18 points in February -- tying the record
for points in a month.
</P>
<P>
   But the game certainly wasn't an easy one. Rucchin had his bell
rung when he was high-sticked by Marchment after coming to the aid
of Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin, who broke his nose on Feb. 17 against Edmonton,
finished the first period, but played only two shifts in the second
period before retiring for the night.
</P>
<P>
   The game was played at break-neck paace in the opening period
with both teams more than willing to throw their weight around as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks took a 1-0 lead when Olausson slipped down from the
right point and fired a hard pass into the slot that Rucchin
deflected past San Jose goalie Mike Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   The energy expended in the first 20 minutes seemed to take its
toll on the Ducks in the second period, especially after Vernon
stacked his pads and stopped Jeff Nielsen's shot on a two-on-break
with Paul Kariya less than two minutes into the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks took control of the game and got the got the tying on
their third excellent scoring chance. Alex Korolyuk picked up his
seventh goal of the year at 5:52 when he fought off Pavel Trnka and
converted Mike Ricci's centering pass.
</P>
<P>
   But San Jose's Magnus Ragnarsson then made the mistake of
holding Kariya's stick and giving the Ducks another power play
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim swarmed all around the Sharks net. Vernon kept the Ducks
at bay from almost two minutes, but Selanne and Kariya combined to
the give them a 2-1 lead at 10:21. Selanne, while skating
backwards, deflected Kariya's point shot into Vernon's pads, picked
up the rebound and scored his 33rd goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks appeared to have tied the game less than two minutes
later when Joe Murphy shoved a rebound past Guy Hebert, but the
goal was waved off when it was ruled that Patrick Marleau's skate
was in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding off that good break and the momentum change provided by
the power play, Anaheim took a 3-1 lead at 15:40.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne took the puck away from Ragnarsson and put a cross-ice
pass on the stick of Travis Green, who beat Vernon with a perfect
shot into the right corner of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Cullen nearly gave the Ducks a 4-1 lead 19 seconds later,
but his shot bounced off the left post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
