<DOCNO> NYT19990227.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1504 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEABORG-OBIT-SFCHRON &LR;      02-27 2163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEABORG-OBIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUSADING SCIENTIST GLENN SEABORG DIES  &HT;      
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Glenn Seaborg, the prodigiously talented
co-discoverer of plutonium, tireless advocate of nuclear arms
control, policy adviser to nine presidents, and longtime faculty
leader at the University of California at Berkeley, died Thursday
night at his home in Lafayette after a long illness. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Felled by a stroke last August in New York, where he was being
honored by the American Chemical Society, Seaborg was flown back to
the Bay Area and hospitalized in Berkeley. But when hope for his
recovery failed last Tuesday, he was brought home to Lafayette
where he lived with his wife of more than 56 years, Helen Griggs
Seaborg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Seaborg was a true giant of the 20th century, a legend in
the annals of scientific discovery,'' said Charles Shank, director
of the Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory where Seaborg had worked for
almost his entire career. ``For his service to science, to
education and to our nation, we honor Dr. Seaborg's distinguished
lifetime and will forever treasure his contributions to our
institutions and to our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Few scientists in this century have played as significant a role
in the issues of war and peace as Seaborg. With his deep, resonant
voice and towering frame _ he was 6 feet 3 inches tall _ Seaborg
was a familiar figure for decades around the globe, from Berkeley
and Washington to Moscow and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Theodore Seaborg was born on April 19, 1912, in Ishpeming,
Mich., where he learned to speak Swedish from his immigrant mother
before he spoke English. When the family moved to Southgate in
Southern California, the young, impoverished Seaborg went to high
school in Watts, worked his way through UCLA and graduated with a
degree in chemistry in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved physics foremost,'' he recalled much later with a
typical wry grin, ``but I studied chemistry because chemists could
find jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The young chemist went to Berkeley as a graduate student and
quickly found himself in competition with his fellow students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, surrounded by dazzlingly bright students,'' he recalled,
``I was uncertain I could make the grade. But taking heart in
Edison's dictum that genius is 99 percent perspiration, I
discovered a pedestrian secret of success. I could work harder than
most of them.''
</P>
<P>
   He could also form strong friendships with scientists like
Ernest O. Lawrence and J. Robert Oppenheimer, and after
successfully completing advanced research in nuclear chemistry at
the Berkeley radiation lab, he received his doctorate there in
1937.
</P>
<P>
   Seaborg's work on radioactive isotopes won him his first fame.
In 1940, he and physicist Edwin McMillan discovered plutonium,
which earned the two Berkeley researchers the Nobel Prize in
Chemistry in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   With World War II under way, Seaborg joined the secret Manhattan
Project to develop the atomic bomb. He served at the University of
Chicago's Metallurgical Laboratory, where he led the team
developing chemical processes for large-scale plutonium production.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is most famous for his role in discovering the
explosive ingredient of atomic weapons, Seaborg opposed the use of
the bomb against Japan as World War II neared its end. Joining in a
report by other Manhattan Project scientists, he urged that the
weapon first be exploded in a ``barren'' desert or on an
uninhabited island. The scientists had hoped that the demonstration
of the bomb's horrific potential for death and devastation _
witnessed by U.N. representatives _ would persuade the Japanese to
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   But the scientists' appeal was ignored and on Aug. 9, 1945, a
U.S. B-29 bomber dropped a plutonium-fueled bomb on Nagasaki,
destroying the city and killing an estimated 70,000 Japanese
civilians _ and effectively ending the war.
</P>
<P>
   Seaborg was to continue his concerns over the buildup of atomic
weapons for the rest of his life, even though he felt forced by the
Cold War to support development of the hydrogen bomb.
</P>
<P>
   In his tireless efforts to stem the nuclear arms race during the
1950s, he played a major background role in U.S. negotiations with
the Soviets that resulted in the breakthrough limited nuclear test
ban treaty of 1963. It barred nuclear weapons testing in the
atmosphere, underwater and in outer space. Seaborg was in the
delegation to Moscow for the treaty signing.
</P>
<P>
   Later he became a powerful advocate for what became the 1996
comprehensive treaty to end all nuclear weapons tests everywhere _
a treaty now signed, but not yet ratified, by the Russian
Federation and the United States, and by 150 other nations of whom
eight have already ratified it.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Seaborg returned to Berkeley to become a
professor of chemistry in 1946. An avid football fan since his
youth, he also became the Berkeley faculty representative to the
Pacific Coast Intercollegiate Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   He was named chancellor of the Berkeley campus in 1958. Besides
supervising academic activities, he reveled in his support of every
team the school could field: basketball, baseball, water polo and,
of course, football (Cal played in the 1959 Rose Bowl with Seaborg
cheering the team on).
</P>
<P>
   Those were also years of scientific breakthroughs for Seaborg
and his colleagues as they discovered a host of hitherto unknown
``transuranic'' elements heavier than uranium. Those new elements,
far beyond uranium in the periodic table of the elements, added an
entire new series of ``actinides'' to the table and revised forever
the classic table first devised in 1869 by the Russian chemist
Dmitri Mendeleev.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their radioactivity, several of the transuranic
elements are now widely used in medicine, while an isotope of
plutonium itself provides the power and heat for many
interplanetary spacecraft, including the Cassini mission now on its
way to Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 16 known transuranic elements that Seaborg identified
has been named seaborgium, while others, like berkelium,
californium, fermium and nielsborium are named for places and
people associated with nuclear discoveries. Altogether, Seaborg and
his colleagues discovered 10 of the transuranics, of which
plutonium was the first.
</P>
<P>
   But even earlier in his career, he and colleagues John J.
Livingood, Emilio Segre and Margaret Melhase discovered eight
radioactive isotopes of more common elements, including iodine-131
and cobalt-60, that are crucial in the diagnosis and treatment of
cancer and other diseases. In recollections written later, Seaborg
noted that the iodine isotope was used successfully in treating
thyroid disorders in his own mother as well as in former President
George Bush and Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of my work that has proven to be such a benefit to
society,'' he wrote of the medical applications of his discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Seaborg's energy and interests in important
causes never seemed to flag.
</P>
<P>
   He served many American presidents in many capacities. He began
by becoming a member of presidential advisory committees on atomic
energy and on science in the Truman and Eisenhower administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in January of 1961, Seaborg received a phone call from
President John F. Kennedy asking him to take the chairmanship of
the Atomic Energy Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I would think it through,'' Seaborg recalled saying,
and Kennedy replied, ``Take your time. I'll call you tomorrow
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaborg agreed to a two-year term but stayed for 101/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Berkeley in 1971 to become university professor
of chemistry, a distinguished title that made him in effect a
professor at all UC campuses. He also became associate director at
large of what is now the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, a
post he retained until his death.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had left Washington, presidents Gerald Ford, Jimmy
Carter, Ronald Reagan and Bush all frequently called on Seaborg for
advice on issues involving science, education and nuclear policy.
</P>
<P>
   But although he advised Reagan, Seaborg was outspoken in his
opposition to Reagan's ``Star Wars'' program for space-based
anti-ballistic missile weaponry. He expressed his opinions about
the ``surreal nature'' of the Reagan administration in published
letters to newspapers as well as in the Bulletin of the Atomic
Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Needless secrecy generated by exaggerated national security
policies _ especially in the Reagan years _ was another of
Seaborg's sources of outrage. During his years as chairman of the
Atomic Energy Commission _ whose functions were later assumed by
the Department of Energy and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission _
Seaborg detailed all his work in his daily journal but was
scrupulous in having every entry reviewed and cleared. When he left
the AEC in 1971 his journals were officially declassified, and he
carried them home.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, however, security agents came to Seaborg's
home in Lafayette in what he called an ``arbitrary and capricious''
effort to ``sanitize'' his personal papers. In an episode he called
``utterly ridiculous,'' the censors blotted out words, paragraphs
and entire documents that had already been declassified, Seaborg
wrote in an angry account in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of education reform was another of Seaborg's
compelling interests. In 1959, as a member of President Dwight
Eisenhower's Science Advisory Committee, he stated that ``basic
research and the education of scientists go best together as
inseparable functions of universities.''
</P>
<P>
   Much earlier, at a public ceremony in a Chattanooga, Tenn., high
school, Seaborg was talking of his scientific discoveries and the
importance of education with local students. With great pleasure he
wrote in his journal that night: ``A high school student asked me,
`When you were doing that work, did you know you were going to make
that discovery?' When I said `No,' he responded with, `Oh, you mean
you were just piddling around?' I then replied, `I guess that's
about the best definition of science yet.'''
</P>
<P>
   To encourage the best in science education, Seaborg helped found
the Lawrence Hall of Science in Berkeley 30 years ago. The hall is
located high on the hill above what is now the Lawrence Berkeley
National Laboratory but was known simply as the Radiation Lab when
he was working on plutonium there at the age of 28. The hall is at
once a science museum with varied programs for school children and
a world-renowned training facility for science teachers. Seaborg
served as the hall's director from 1982 to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Although Seaborg's relations with Reagan were strained at best,
he did serve on the President's National Commission on Excellence
in Education and helped word the widely quoted conclusion of its
final 1983 report, called ``A Nation at Risk.'' The conclusion
declared:
</P>
<P>
   ``If an unfriendly power had attempted to impose on America the
mediocre educational performance that exists today, we might well
have viewed it as an act of war. As it stands, we have allowed this
to happen to ourselves. We have even squandered the gains in
achievement made in the wake of the Sputnik challenge. Moreover, we
have dismantled essential support systems which helped make those
gains possible. We have, in effect, been committing an act of
unthinking, unilateral educational disarmament.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaborg was there when the report was presented to Reagan. Years
later, the Berkeley advocate for education reform recalled, sadly:
``We succeeded in drawing almost unprecedented attention from
educators, parents, public and press. (but) Incidentally, President
Reagan used the occasion to advocate voluntary prayer in schools,
and tuition tax credits, and abolishing the Department of Education
... ''
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, Seaborg chaired the California Department of
Education's Academic Standards Commission whose final report called
for rigorous performance standards for students through high
school. The report was approved unanimously by the state Board of
Education, although its science standards have been assailed by
many of the nation's leading scientists who claim it unduly
emphasizes rote learning rather than ``inquiry-based'' science
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the report was issued last October, however, Seaborg
was too ill to defend it.
</P>
<P>
   During his long career, Seaborg received eight honorary degrees
and served as president of both the American Association for the
Advancement of Science and the American Chemical Society.
</P>
<P>
   The Seaborgs were married in 1942 and had six children. Seaborg
is survived by his wife, by their sons David of Walnut Creek, John
Eric of Free Union, Va., and Stephen of La Mesa, Calif.; and by
their daughters, Dianne Seaborg of Lafayette and Lynn Seaborg Cobb
of Grand Junction, Colo. Their first child, Peter Glenn Seaborg,
died in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements were pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
