<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN HAS NEW ROUTINE DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ There's Pacific Standard Time. And there's Dennis
Time.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, we're all on Dennis Time.
</P>
<P>
   6:05 p.m.: New Laker Dennis Rodman shows up late for his first
day of work. Or early, depending on how you set your watch.
</P>
<P>
   Players are supposed to be in the locker room at 6 for a 7:35
game. But a team official, adopting the lenient ``Dennis is
Dennis'' tone set by Lakers owner Jerry Buss in the middle of the
contract talk, says he thought Rodman might pull an old stunt by
blowing in at 7 and throwing on his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   6:10: Rodman crosses the locker room so quickly, ducking into
the back room containing the exercise equipment, that some of the
reporters here to chronicle his debut miss this historic moment.
</P>
<P>
   A photographer who got a good look at him in the tunnel from the
street offers a description: Rodman was modestly attired in a dull
green wool hat, T-shirt, baggy pants and sensible shoes. OK, we
made up the part about the sensible shoes.
</P>
<P>
   He drove a white Corvette and was accompanied by bodyguards
named Wendell Williams and Kelly Davis.
</P>
<P>
   6:15: It's noted that Rodman has been assigned the locker-room
cubicle that belonged to recent Lakers bad boy Nick Van Exel.
Significance? It's closest to the back door.
</P>
<P>
   6:15{: It's noted that Rodman's uniform, hanging on a hook,
bears a purple No. 73.
</P>
<P>
   73? Because he's won !ital!seven straight rebounding titles and
!ital!three straight championship rings. And because if you turn it
around you get his age. Anyway, that's what he said the other day
between curses and boo-hoos.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman is believed to be the first Laker to wear a
non-traditional number since George Mikan was No. 99. End of
Rodman-Mikan comparison.
</P>
<P>
   6:20: Shaquille O'Neal, lacing up his sneakers three cubicles
down the row from Rodman's, on being teammates with a former enemy:
``He does his thing. I do my thing. I'm not going to go out with
him at night or nothin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the nightclubs might not be big enough for the both of
them.
</P>
<P>
   6:25: Reporters outnumber players 2-1 in the small locker room.
All find amusement in the efforts of Kurt Rambis, named the Lakers'
head coach earlier in the evening, to choose the right socks. Match
the shoes? Match the slacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta match the pants,'' Eddie Jones decrees. Rambis had
matched the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   So there's the first change from the Del Harris era.
Coach-player fashion banter.
</P>
<P>
   6:30: In case reporters on the Rodman beat didn't pick up on
this, those pre-game one-on-one interviews we'd all been hoping for
will not materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will never see him in the locker room,'' Lakers publicist
John Black says. ``I guarantee it.'' He means during press visiting
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Post-game interviews should not be expected either. But Rodman
has indicated he's willing to talk to reporters if they're willing
to trail him from the locker room to the tunnel. A Chicago writer
describes scenes like those from the Bulls days as ``moving
scrums.''
</P>
<P>
   7:15: Rodman, in middle of a parade of Lakers, takes the court
for final warmups. Fans, half-filling the Forum, have trouble
picking him out because his hair is a sedate purple, green and
gray.
</P>
<P>
   One of those might be his natural color. Who can remember?
</P>
<P>
   7:38: The ``Star Spangled Banner'' is performed by an unplugged
group called Dakota Moon. Rodman is the Laker who's swaying to the
beat.
</P>
<P>
   7:40: Ten photographers surround Rodman as trainer Gary Vitti
tapes his wrists.
</P>
<P>
   7:44: The game begins with Rodman on the bench between
straight-laced Derek Fisher and Sean Rooks. Rodman is the Laker
who's taking his shoes off.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a protest, as it was in his San Antonio days. He's
putting on ankle wraps.
</P>
<P>
   7:47: The scoreboard video screen shows Rodman on the bench.
Fans erupt. Rodman shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   7:54: The moment we've been waiting the whole month for: ``For
the Lakers, No. 73 ...'' Standing ovation as Rodman strips off his
warmups _ that's all this time _ and enters the game.
</P>
<P>
   7:55: Rodman's immediate impact is all positive: On the first
Lakers possession with him on the floor, he keeps alive a rebound
that O'Neal grabs and puts back; on the next, he grabs a rebound
and passes to O'Neal for a layup and an 18-11 lead.
</P>
<P>
   8:15: Rodman ends his first six-minute stint with one rebound,
one assist, one missed shot, two fouls and the Lakers lead in
energy. Of course, he's had six weeks longer than the rest of them
to store it up.
</P>
<P>
   8:16: The air goes out of the crowd and the team, which messes
up back-to-back fast breaks.
</P>
<P>
   8:17: Fans in the rafters start a ``We want Rodman'' chant.
</P>
<P>
   8:50: Halftime: Lakers 49-35.
</P>
<P>
   9:20: Rodman, having started the second half, goes out after
grabbing his sixth rebound in 16 minutes of action to tie O'Neal
and Travis Knight for the team high late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   9:21: ``We want Rodman'' again.
</P>
<P>
   Of course they do. They don't have a moving scrum in their
immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   10:02: Game: Lakers, 99-83; Rodman, 0 points, six assists (tying
for team high), 11 rebounds (leading the team) in 26 minutes. He
walks shirtless off the court trailed by minicams.
</P>
<P>
   10:18: Great, huh? ``So far,'' says Derek Harper, veteran
realist. ``Just wait, though.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
