 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ In a report on the eve of a visit to
China by Secretary Albright, the State Department criticized China
on human rights, finding ``widespread and well-documented''
examples of abuse. The Pentagon also issued a report on the
military balance between China and Taiwan, renewing fears about
China's military intentions. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLICY (San Francisco) _ With surprises abroad and
critics at home bedeviling his foreign policy, President Clinton on
Friday defended his efforts to cooperate with Mexico in fighting
drugs, to engage with China to promote political freedom and to
threaten force to bring peace to Kosovo. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HONGKONG (Hong Kong) _ Bending to intense political
pressure, Hong Kong's highest court said on Friday that it had not
meant to challenge the authority of the Chinese government in a
recent ruling on immigration. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ELECTION (Lagos, Nigeria) _ Furiously crisscrossing this
vast, unruly country on the campaign trail, Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo
showed at every stop that he was the front-runner in the
presidential election which will be held on Saturday. By Norimitsu
Onishi. With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ International monitors were
detained overnight and most of Friday by Serbian security forces at
Serbia's southern border with Macedonia, while other monitors were
blocked from entering a village where Serbian troops were massing.
By Carlotta Gall. With map.
</P>
<P>
   GUATAMALA-WAR-REPORT (Undated) _ The language was harsh, the
country's emotional, cathartic response even stronger. A
nine-volume report issued by a truth commission on Thursday that
blamed the Guatemalan military for the deaths of nearly 200,000
people in their 36-year civil war surprised nearly everyone with
the bluntness and severity of its judgments and recommendations. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOUP-KITCHENS-II (Undated) _ Second of two articles: These are
anxious times at Second Harvest, the hub of America's sprawling
system of church-basement soup kitchens and food pantries. Over
nearly two decades, that network has expanded to serve more than $1
billion worth of food each year to 20 million Americans. But now,
as changes in welfare policy push many people away from the public
dole, private charity is lagging ever further behind in its efforts
to feed the lengthening lines. Part of the problem, by the
charities' account, is rising demand on a system that was never
really able to keep up in the first place. By Andrew C. Revkin.
With photos.
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-AVIATOR (Camp LeJeune, N.C.) _ The Marine pilot involved
in the Italian cable car accident testified at his court martial.
By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-PERPWALK (New York) _ The perp walk has for much of
this century been a symbiotic New York celebration. The police got
to show off their cunning in nabbing bad guys. The press got
close-up pictures, often in time for deadlines. The public got to
put a face on fear. No one lost, unless the perpetrator turned out
to be innocent. This was the sticking point that on Thursday caused
a federal judge to single out one particularly obnoxious perp walk
as an unconstitutional invasion of privacy. By Blaine Harden. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy grew even faster in the
fourth quarter than initially estimated. The government says gross
domestic product expanded at a 6.1 percent annual rate in the final
three months of last year, above the earlier estimate of a 5.6
percent rate and the fastest pace in more than two years. Consumer
spending during the quarter was stronger than first estimated, the
increase in imports smaller and the rise in exports bigger. Despite
the fourth quarter's upward revision in growth, inflation remained
well in check. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-EXCURSION (Detroit) _ Ford unveiled its new sport utility
vehicle, the Excursion, which at 19 feet and 3{ tons is the biggest
passenger vehicle on the market. By Keith Bradsher. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE-NASDAQ (New York) _ The New York Stock Exchange is
exploring ways to trade high-profile NASDAQ stocks. By David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   BROKERS-BIAS-SUIT (Undated) _ Tuesday is the final day that
women can file a claim under a class-action settlement of a case by
female brokers that charged gender discrimination by Merrill Lynch
in wages, promotions, account distributions, maternity leaves and
other areas. About 900 women, 31 percent of the 2,900 current and
former Merrill Lynch brokers who are eligible, are expected to
file. By Ann Wozencraft. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-SUMMIT (Bonn, Germany) _ BONN, Germany _ European heads
of state, meeting here Friday, failed to agree on plans to reduce
their enormous farm subsidies. But there were nevertheless signs
that once-sacred programs soon may come in for an overhaul. By
Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft's defense against
antitrust charges entered its final day Friday, and the presiding
judge once again injected himself into the proceedings to pose
questions that suggested he was skeptical of Microsoft's case. By
Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OBITUARIES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-SEABORG (Undated) _ Glenn Seaborg, the Nobel Prize-winning
physicist who discovered 10 atomic elements including plutonium and
one that now bears his name, has died. He was 86. By Malcolm W.
Browne.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-QUINTERO (New York) _ Tony Award-winning theater director
Jose Quintero, whose landmark productions of Eugene O'Neill dramas
renewed interest in one of America's greatest playwrights, died
Friday of cancer. He was 74. By Mervyn Rothstein and Richard
Severo. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Houston) _ Cyrus Atefi, as I shall call him, was
brought to this country from Iran in 1978, when he was a few months
old. His father had been a bureaucrat in the Shah's intelligence
agency, so the family fled after the Islamic revolution. The
parents, two older children and Cyrus were given political asylum
in the United States. Last fall agents of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service went to Cyrus' place of work and took him
away. The reason was that a 1996 law, the Illegal Immigration Act,
defined his drug offense as an ``aggravated felony'' despite the
low sentence, and made him deportable. If Cyrus is deported to
Iran, he is likely to be arrested and tortured. By Anthony Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BAD-WRITERS (Undated) _ Ridiculing academic writing is becoming
commonplace these days. Yet the debate has taken a new twist
recently with a decision by Edward Said, the new president of the
Modern Language Association, to use his first official column in
the association's newsletter to denounce bad writing. In an essay
on how science is growing at the expense of the humanities, he
accused literature departments of fostering incomprehensible
writing and factionalism, resulting even more in their
``diminishment and incoherence.'' By Dinitia Smith. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ Sports of The Times
column on the troubled 2-9 Nets, including their sudden merger with
the far more powerful Yankees. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MATCH (Carlsbad, Calif.) _ CARLSBAD, Calif. _ After losing
to Tiger Woods Friday morning, Stewart Cink correctly predicted
that Woods would be beaten by Jeff Maggert. By Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
