<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S IMPACT RAISES AUTHOR'S SENSE OF DESPAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What if Michael Jordan had succeeded at baseball?
</P>
<P>
   The landscape of two sports would have changed, not to mention a
chunk of the culture.
</P>
<P>
   In hoops alone in this corner of the world, the Sonics would
have been the 1996 NBA champions, George Karl would still be coach
here, the Mariners and Seahawks would struggle in the Sonic shadow,
Nike might still be flying high, Dennis Rodman would have washed
out of the league instead of joining the Sonics' biggest nemesis,
and perhaps the NBA lockout would have been averted, or at least
shortened, without the influence of the cabal led by Jordan and
agent David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, David Halberstam would have an unfinished
manuscript on his desk, because ``Playing for Keeps: Michael Jordan
and the World He Made'' wouldn't be nearly as good a story with
Jordan shagging flies in spring training for the White Sox, talking
about how happy he was that Randy Johnson stayed in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan failed at baseball. In returning to basketball and
succeeding so preposterously with three more championships and
recognition as the world's most familiar human, he became the face
of American pop culture and the template with which to measure a
disturbing transformation of society.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan even became less predatory. A better teammate, of all
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . When he failed at baseball,'' Halberstam wrote, ``he had
for the first time realized what it was for a player struggling
against his limits _ for he had known no limits before, certainly
no limits to his individual performances.''
</P>
<P>
   But Halberstam went well beyond the limits of a sports saga,
which was expected from the nation's pre-eminent
journalist/historian. His affection for pro basketball, established
20 years ago when he wrote ``Breaks of the Game,'' about a season
with the Portland Trail Blazers, didn't keep him from conveying his
despair over what has happened to the NBA and the
entertainment-driven society that fostered the industry's tawdry
hucksterism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if the architects of the modern game did not
entirely believe that its new fans, unlike those who attended the
old Chicago Stadium, found the game adequately entertaining,'' and
so embellished events ``by music boomed out ever more loudly, more
and more idiotic games played on the Jumbotron or on the floor . .
. mini-bike races between toddlers, acrobats firing T-shirts into
the crowd . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar, Sonic fans?
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch this week during the Seattle stop of his national
book tour, Halberstam lamented the American lust for entertainment
and the celebrity adoration that drives it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A celebrity who actually achieves something is rare,'' he
said. ``Heroism now is cinematic and artificial. Fame today comes
from notoriety, not achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you say it started with O.J. Simpson, or goes all the
way back to Patty Hearst, it's a significant force. Since the
impeachment trial ended, what has been the biggest national story?
Whether Hillary Clinton will run for the Senate from New York:
Maybe she will, maybe she won't . . . but there's really nothing
there but our fascination with her celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   In spending a season around the Bulls, Halberstam found two
extremes for his point: Jordan and Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was the classic achiever whose overarching skills and
relentlessness created success and wealth, which begat more success
and wealth, which spread to many individuals and endorsers who
associated with him and the Bulls. Rodman, on the other hand, was
simply a good basketball player who came up with a shtick, in part
due to his hook-ups with the master re-inventor, Madonna, that had
no real worth or substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really doesn't know what he thinks,'' Halberstam said.
``Rodman's inability to control himself is extremely dangerous. He
thinks he's in charge, but he can't stop the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``By his final season with the Bulls, it was much harder to keep
him in sync. He was carried away by his own cult.''
</P>
<P>
   While the book is an exhaustive, entertaining chronicle of
Jordan and his impacts, it isn't the ultimate story of Jordan
because it lacks intimacy, which is a little surprising for so
comprehensive a work. The author was denied a promised one-on-one
interview, and there is only a paragraph devoted to Jordan's wife
and children.
</P>
<P>
   But Halberstam does get his arms around the changes in the NBA,
and by extension the culture that embraced the league so intensely,
by weaving wonderful portraits and anecdotes of many people and
issues that traced the arc of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   As a family snapshot, the sports world comes off more than a
little dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is an entertainment society good? Well, as someone born on the
other size of this DMZ, I don't regard it as a plus,'' said
Halberstam, 64. ``The genie is too far out of the bottle now, but
there is some possibility we're in a phase, and we will get beyond
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as the interest remains in Rodman's hair and Hillary's
daydreams, the phase richly deserves fat-guy basketball and
scorned-woman politics.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
