<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN WITH RODMAN, RAMBIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Years hence, historians will no doubt debate whose
era this was. There will be the staunch Rambis camp and the equally
stubborn Rodman camp, each clinging to its own interpretation of
events and hairstyle trends.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, as the Lakers unveiled a new coach and a new
power forward, the only debate was over how many dozen points would
comprise the Lakers' margin of rout over the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Lakers squandered a chunk of a 29-point lead, the
99-83 victory seemed like a good enough start for both head coach
Kurt Rambis and Designated Worm, Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever's era it is, the Lakers are 1-0 in it. And enjoying the
ride so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun. If you mix just playing the game, and then playing
with Dennis, and having Rambis in there as your coach, what more
can you ask for?'' said Kobe Bryant, who scored a game-high 22
points.
</P>
<P>
   In punishing their soon-to-be arena roommates for the second
straight night, the Lakers continued a steady counterturn out of
the three-game tailspin that got coach Del Harris fired two days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And the Clippers? The Chris Ford-Michael Olowokandi era is
heading for its own brand of notoriety, having lost 11 straight to
begin the season. The Clippers are six losses away from matching
Miami's 1988 record for worst start to a season.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Lakers, a week of chaos came to a merciful close.
They introduced Rodman on Wednesday, Rambis before the game Friday,
then unveiled both to a frenzied 17,505 at the Forum. The house was
nearly hoarse by the end of pregame introductions and certainly
sore in the throat after drowning out Rodman's intro late in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis' impact will take time to evaluate. Rodman's? Easy. The
Lakers won by 16 points. In Rodman's first 17 minutes of play, the
Lakers outscored the Clippers by 19.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 11 rebounds, six assists, one steal and zero
points on two loudly cheered field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy that hasn't touched a basketball in nine months,
that's pretty good,'' Rodman said. ``I felt a little shy at the
beginning because I didn't want to mess up, but when I stepped on
the court it all just came back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The hair, by the way, was a muddy mix of browns and blacks and
possibly some purple and yellow, maybe a bit of blue... well, it
was hard to tell. In transition, as Rodman put it.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he was much the same Rodman that helped the Chicago
Bulls to their last three NBA championships, looking every bit as
tenacious as he did in Game 6 of the Finals _ his most recent game
_ last June. The lockout, the reported offseason of partying, his
lack of a team to practice with the last six weeks, none of it
seemed to affect Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eveready Bunny,'' Rambis said, and the folks who make the
Energizer battery will have to forgive him. ``That's what he does.
As the game wears on he just keeps getting better and better. I
asked him how much he wanted to play. He said, `Yes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Rodman had wrapped his arms around a single loose
ball, he was earning high marks from his new team. By the time he
joined his first shootaround, Rodman was giving teammates pointers
on defending the pick-and-roll.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Bill Bertka might have given the Worm the
highest praise one can give a new Laker: a comparison to the
legends.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's another aspect he brings to the team that I like,''
Bertka said. ``I think back to when Wilt (Chamberlain) came to the
team, I think back to when Kareem came to the Lakers. They brought
a mental toughness and a professionalism to the franchise, that
professionalism and that toughness is infectious. Dennis loves to
play basketball, and I think that for our team is going to be a
very helpful aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman wasted little time showing his hustle. He entered midway
through the first quarter and promptly saved a couple possessions
and recorded his first assist and rebound.
</P>
<P>
   And helped Rambis record his first win. And the new Lakers boss
promptly responded with a coach-like reality check.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great,'' Rambis said, ``but we've got a tough schedule
coming up. I had to remind the players that this is not an
indication that everything is OK with us. ... We've still got a lot
of work to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
