r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-L     02-27 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Mighty Ducks are No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the NHL standings, of course. But when it comes to the
power play no team is better than Anaheim, which defeated San Jose
3-1 Friday night on the strength of its league-leading 62nd and
63rd power play goals.
</P>
<P>
   But Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg still thinks the best is yet
to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are still finding more confidence as the season
goes along,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The long and physical game played before 17,174 at the Pond
featured a Bryan Marchment cross-check on Steve Rucchin in the
first three minutes of play, after the NHL's favorite villain had
run over Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Anaheim's special teams that were the difference as
they have been so many times this year.
</P>
<P>
   While Rucchin and Selanne scored on the power play, Anaheim
easily killed off a four-minute penalty in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's big chance came just six seconds after Rucchin scored
his 22nd goal of the year at 11:35. The Sharks, however, could
manage only one harmless 60-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell (somebody) how important it is to have a
good power play and penalty killing at this time of year,'' said
Selanne, who extended his point-scoring streak to 12 games with a
goal and two assists. ``These games are like playoff games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' victory moved them one game over .500 (26-25-9), kept
them in fifth place -- three points ahead of St. Louis. It also
moved them seven points ahead of seventh-place San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks (20-26-4) are 0-4-2 since winning four consecutive
games on their recent 10-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's ninth win of the month was a new club record and give
the Ducks 18 points in February -- tying the record for points in a
month.
</P>
<P>
   But the victory certainly wasn't an easy one. Rucchin had his
bell rung when he was high-sticked by Marchment after coming to the
aid of Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin, who broke his nose on Feb. 17 against Edmonton,
finished the first period, but played only two shifts in the second
period before retiring for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruch is a warrior,'' said Selanne. ``He told us he doesn't
look pretty right now, but he'll do what he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg, however, insisted that Rucchin did not leave the game
because of the hit, but rather that the Anaheim center was
suffering from the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the flu,'' said Hartsburg angrily. ``He feels awful and
couldn't finish the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensity and hitting was playoff-like most of the night --
especially in the first period when neither team would back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't mind it,'' said Hartsburg. ``We have some guys who
thrive on it. The intensity was a good sign tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks took a 1-0 lead when Fredrik Olausson slipped down
from the right point and fired a hard pass into the slot that
Rucchin deflected past San Jose goalie Mike Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks took control of the game early in the second and got
the got the tying from Alex Korolyuk at 5:52 on their third
excellent scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   But San Jose's Magnus Ragnarsson then made the mistake of
holding Paul Kariya's stick, giving the Ducks another power play
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon kept the Ducks at bay for almost two minutes, but Selanne
and Kariya combined to the give Anaheim a 2-1 lead at 10:21.
Selanne, while skating backwards, deflected Kariya's point shot
into Vernon's pads, picked up the rebound and scored his 33rd goal
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks appeared to have tied the game less than two minutes
later when Joe Murphy shoved a rebound past Guy Hebert, but the
goal was waved off when it was ruled that Patrick Marleau's skate
was in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding off that good break and the momentum change provided by
the power play, Anaheim took a 3-1 lead on Travis Green's 11th goal
of the season at 15:40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
