<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS REBOUND TO DEFEAT SPURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Sonics still have a ways to go, but Friday night
the team at least made its offensive low point look like an
aberration.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after forward Vin Baker made just one basket and the
Sonics shot a season-low 34.2 percent, they rebounded with a 92-82
victory over the San Antonio Spurs at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory snapped a two-game losing streak and vindicated a
repulsive 99-81 loss Wednesday at San Antonio (6-7). It was just
the second win for the Sonics (8-4) in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back on the roller coaster in the NBA,'' Sonics coach
Paul Westphal said. ``They thumped us, and we came back and thumped
them. We're still not shooting 50 percent, which I'd like to see
one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite shooting 42 percent, the Sonics executed better
offensively and pinned down the Spurs defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors were a big part of a decisive third quarter. The
Sonics went on a 30-18 run in that period to distance themselves
from the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton was again the catalyst, scoring 14 of his game-high
23 points in the third. He made all five shots he attempted, which
included three 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's three-point play with 57 seconds left put the Sonics
ahead 74-59 and seemed to knock out the already dazed Spurs. The
Sonics also forced San Antonio to turn the ball over 10 times in
the third, which resulted in easy, fastbreak scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Four Sonics scored in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't miss everything you put up, at least I hope not,''
Sonics guard Hersey Hawkins said. ``And in that third quarter, we
got into a groove defensively and offensively. When you put the
ball in the hoop, it makes all the difference in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio committed 19 turnovers, and suffered through
35-percent shooting for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you have turnovers like that, people are playing good
`D' so I think they did a real good job defensively,'' Spurs coach
Gregg Popovich said. ``They stepped it up a notch and it showed.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was a reversal of fortune for both teams in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Sonics stifled the Spurs' Twin Towers _ David
Robinson and Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were dominated Wednesday when those two combined for
47 points and 30 rebounds in the teams' first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Duncan managed 22 points, but Robinson was held to
10 points on 2-for-9 shooting. Overall, the Sonics did a better
containing the post. They were quicker with double teams, crowding
Duncan and Robinson as soon as they touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to limit his touches and put a body on him
because he roamed around a lot in San Antonio,'' Sonics center
Olden Polynice said. ``I was intent on not letting that happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker came out determined as well. After shooting 1-for-7 in the
first meeting, Baker showed signs of slipping out of his funk and
into a groove.
</P>
<P>
   He started the game by making three of his first six shots.
Baker even made consecutive free throws for the first time this
season after missing his first two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take anything at this point,'' said Baker, who finished
with 16 points on 7-for-19 shooting. ``The one thing I was happy
about is,, once I made my two, I wanted to get back to the line. I
haven't felt like that in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that Baker's only problem at the start was his
aggressiveness. He picked up his third foul with 9:13 left in the
second quarter and went to the bench with eight points and four
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody picked it up a little bit,'' said Sonic Dale Ellis,
who started his second straight game at shooting guard. `` . . .
Gary shot the ball well. We did a better job of executing our
offense and got good shots. We really wanted to beat this team.''
</P>
<P>
   TIP-INS: Rookie Vladimir Stepania made his second straight
appearance, finishing with four points and three rebounds in six
minutes. The 6-foot-11 forward/center played in just five games
before Friday night. . . . Baker, who was poked in his left eye
during Wednesday's loss to the Spurs, did not wear protective
goggles. He wore goggles during Thursday's practice, although his
blurred vision has since subsided. . . . Forward Billy Owens has
recovered from his broken left pinky and will practice Sunday for
the first time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
