   &UR; TOP: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUDGET (Washington) _ With the prospect of huge budget
surpluses diminishing the commitment to fiscal discipline, Congress
now appears all but certain to increase the spending limits that
were a central part of efforts to balance the budget and tame
Washington's insatiable appetite for new programs. The current caps
would require deep spending cuts this year, even as both parties
are pushing for more spending on the military, education and other
programs. It is a dilemma with tremendous political and economic
ramifications, and Republicans in particular are in a bind. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `w' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Undated) _ For Microsoft's witnesses at its
antitrust trial, the simple words of introduction have become
deeply unnerving. ``My name is David Boies, and I represent the
United States.'' It is no wonder why the big software company's
witnesses have come to fear facing Boies, the Justice Department's
trial lawyer, in the government's sweeping antitrust case against
the Microsoft Corp. Time after time, he has caught Microsoft
witnesses off-guard as the words from their mouths on the stand
contradict the statements in internal Microsoft documents and often
their own e-mail. Yet as both sides have now presented their main
evidence, with the last of Microsoft's 12 witnesses having finished
last Friday, the question remains just how much the company has
been merely embarrassed or truly damaged in the courtroom. By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 2 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-VOTE (Lagos, Nigeria) _ Nigerians vote for a president;
reports of big turnout. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 2 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-PROMOTE (New York) _ Portrayed in her new book as a
troubled young woman and a pawn of Washington power struggles,
Monica Lewinsky moves now to the center of competing financial
interests _ TV networks anxious to promote exclusive interviews,
book publishers intent on protecting the mystery of their
information until publication, and a retinue of handlers concerned
with financial security and shaping an image. Thus far, her
expanding group of advisers have devised a rather schizophrenic
strategy to promote Ms. Lewinsky's interests here and in foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   1-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-LEGACY-I (Victorville, Calif.) _ Every 20 seconds, someone
in the United States is arrested for a drug violation, and every
week, on average, a new jail or prison is built to lock up more
people in what has become the world's largest penal system. It was
not always so. Ten years ago, half as many people were arrested for
drug crimes, and the nation's incarceration rate was closer to
those of other democracies. But in the 1980's the United States was
shaken by crack cocaine, and the criminal justice system has never
been the same. Crack prompted the nation to rewrite its drug laws,
lock up a record number of people, and shift money from schools to
prisons. It transformed police work, hospitals, parental rights,
courts. More than anything, crack changed the makeup of American
prisons. Nearly twice as many whites use crack as blacks, according
to national surveys, but as the war on drugs focused on poor city
neighborhoods, blacks went to prison at a rate far surpassing
whites. (First of two parts.) By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   4-column photo and graphic layout with story.
</P>
<P>
   4-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; in `a' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
