<SLUG> BC-SMALLBIZ-HEALTHCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF OF WORKERS IN SMALL CONCERNS UNINSURED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of workers in small companies who have health
insurance fell below 50 percent last year for the first time in at
least a decade, according to a study by the Henry J. Kaiser Family
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The drop, coming when the economy remained strong and jobs were
plentiful, deepened a gap in coverage that the Census Bureau had
reported in 1997 when the number of uninsured Americans rose to
43.4 million, or 16.1 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser report said many small companies had dropped health
insurance or made it more difficult for employees to obtain by
tightening eligibility requirements or extending waiting periods
before they could receive benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The number of small companies that offered health insurance
dropped to 55 percent, compared with 59 percent in 1996. The
decline translated to 1.8 million more workers in small companies
that were not offered health insurance last year, said Jon R.
Gabel, director of the survey, which was conducted by KPMG Peat
Marwick, the accounting and benefits consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In small concerns with fewer than 200 employees, 47 percent of
employees did not have insurance, the survey said, compared with 52
percent in 1996. In companies with 200 or more employees, 64
percent of employees had health coverage, down slightly from 2 of
every 3 workers in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the best of times,'' said Gabel, who has been
surveying employee benefits since 1989. ``What will happen to
insurance if the economy slows down?''
</P>
<P>
   He said employees of small companies were as willing as any
workers to participate in health insurance, even though they
typically earned less and had to pay more for less coverage than
workers in large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Benefits managers at 1,581 randomly selected companies were
surveyed last summer. The margin of error was plus or minus 2.5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   William S. Custer, a health economist at Georgia State
University, said the Kaiser survey was consistent with a census
report last year that was based on a 1997 survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the growth of the economy,'' Custer said, ``more
people are working and losing their eligibility for Medicaid,'' the
state-run health programs. Most were hired by small businesses,
which were ``less likely to offer coverage,'' said Custer, who was
not involved in the Kaiser survey.
</P>
<P>
   In a finding that surprised some health policy experts in
Washington, the small employers strongly supported a number of
proposals for more government regulation of health insurance. In
the Kaiser survey, 80 percent favored requiring health plans to pay
for emergency room visits and 88 percent favored assuring patients
an independent review of health plan decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Small employers were less enthusiastic about proposals to permit
patients to sue a health plan for medical malpractice: 47 percent
were in favor, 33 percent were opposed and 21 percent were
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Caldeira, a lobbyist for the National Federation of
Independent Business, which opposes the legislative proposals, said
the federation's members overwhelmingly were against adding to
regulations, which they believed would increase the cost of
insurance premiums.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
