<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-JC-STAR28-COX     02-27 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-JC-STAR28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lyons comes of age
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Albany ruled Georgia high school basketball in the
early 1990s. Westover won four consecutive Class AAA boys titles,
twice beating rival Albany High, and college recruiters besieged
the southwest Georgia city in pursuit of such blue-chip prospects
as Dontonio Wingfield, Melvin Drake, Michael Spruill and Pertha
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   But the player who might have had the most raw talent in Albany
at the time wasn't part of any of it.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Lyons was nothing more than a playground legend then _ a
high-school dropout with loads of basketball moves and nowhere to
display them properly.
</P>
<P>
   Now _ at age 26 _ he finally has a stage. Soon, he might have a
much larger one.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leading junior college scorers in the nation, Lyons is
averaging 27 points per game at Georgia Perimeter College. Big-time
recruiters are flocking to south DeKalb County to see Lyons and the
cat-quick Jaguars, who went into the weekend 28-1 and ranked No. 3
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can stop Derrick,'' coach Alfred Barney said. ``Major
college coaches get a look at him and can't believe it. They all
wonder where he's been.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand how they missed him. College coaches
don't spend much time at Albany's Turner Job Corps Center, where
Lyons honed his skills after dropping out of high school without
ever playing a varsity game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my state championship,'' Albany High coach Archie
Chatmon said. ``Not even Westover could have beaten us with
Derrick. It's not a question of whether he was as good as those
other players back then but if he could have been even better. He
had that much talent.''
</P>
<P>
   But to show it, Lyons had to get on the court. When his mother
was forced to move in 1989, he transferred from Dougherty to Albany
late in the ninth grade. But he never gained his eligibility for
the next season. Hopelessly behind in school and short of money,
Lyons dropped out of school in 1991 at age 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, real hard, to go to high school games then,''
Lyons said. ``Those players were getting all this attention, and I
was nothing. It hurt bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It hurt even worse when Robinson, Drake and Wingfield became
college standouts. Lyons had to watch them on television and
wonder, what if?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was wasting my basketball talent,'' Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   But to play in college, Lyons first had to get there. Encouraged
by Chatmon, Dougherty coach Charlie Givens and others, Lyons took
courses at Turner Job Corps, but he failed to get the GED he needed
in place of the high school diploma he never got. He was working
construction jobs around Albany when his life finally began to
change for the better.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about Lyons for several years, Georgia Perimeter's
Barney tracked him down in the summer of 1997 and persuaded him to
give the GED test one more try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this was my last chance,'' said Lyons, who has a
6-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting the books like he never had before, Lyons passed the GED
test at age 25 after cramming for three months and became eligible
at Georgia Perimeter (then DeKalb College) for the second semester
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons, a well-built 6-foot-4 guard, scored 21 points in his
first game _ against nationally ranked Allegany and Steve Francis _
and there has been no stopping him or the Jaguars since. They
finished No. 9 in the nation last year and this season have lost
only to Pensacola in the third game.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting better than 65 percent, Lyons scores on thunderous
dunks, unstoppable spin moves and high-arching 3-pointers. He also
swoops down on the ball like a condor in Georgia Perimeter's press
and is always willing to hit an open teammate with a pass. That's a
rarity in junior college basketball, where most players think that
they have to score to be seen by major colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is definitely one of the top players in junior college,''
said Barney, whose team is averaging 97 points per game. ``He can
take over a game. Florida State, Iowa State and other schools are
already after him, and a lot more will be if we get back to the
nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lyons probably won't be eligible to play at a major college
until the 2000-2001 season _ when he will be 28. Because he didn't
enter Georgia Perimeter until January 1998, he won't graduate this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to sit out a year if I have to,'' said Lyons,
occasionally called ``Old School'' by teammates. ``After everything
(else), I'm not going to let that stop me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons' mother and grandmother are just as proud of having him in
school as they are of his basketball success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to encourage him the best I could, but I never thought
it would happen,'' mom Rose Ellis said. ``I'm sure glad it finally
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very, very proud,'' grandmother Mary Taylor said.
``None of my kids or grandkids ever finished high school or went to
college. Derrick is the first.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
