<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-THRASERS28-COX     02-27 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heating up the hockey market in Atlanta
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They started with an $80 million expenditure, a hole
in the ground and a caricature of a bird that appeared to have used
too much feather mousse and would have Toe Blake spiking his
fedora.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, members of the sales staff, attired in team
togs, were out knocking on doors of 300 Atlanta businesses, waving
hockey sticks in one hand and ticket brochures in the other. A
half-page ad in this newspaper last week read, ``Power Play With
Pano,'' the hope that haute cuisine would lure the rich to the
luxury of a club seat.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Atlanta Thrashers' staging of clinics at ice and
roller rinks and youth centers is not considered unusual in
marketing circles, running ads in movie theaters and sending
representatives to a Kwanza festival, a Jewish synogogue and a
Catholic church men's club, comprising mostly retirees, at least
indicates a significant barrier push.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to new-time hockey. Sorry, Toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot different than it used to be,'' former Atlanta
Flames player Curt Bennett said recently, as he watched two dozen
kids at a Boys &AMP; Girls Club play street hockey. ``Are these kids
gonna go to a hockey game? Probably not. But it broadens the base
of hockey fans. Back when I was playing, I can remember (coach)
Boomer (Geoffrion) sitting in a little office downtown, on the
phone selling tickets. That was the extent of our marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Flames left for Calgary in 1980, they were averaging
10,024 fans per game. The NHL has mandated the Thrashers sell at
least 12,000 season tickets by March 15. The team will not release
a current sales figure, but Derek Schiller, the team's vice
president for sales and marketing, vows, ``It won't be a problem.
An announcement is imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fortunate. Because Schiller's father, Harvey, who happens
to be the Thrashers' president, said, ``If we don't sell 12,000
tickets, Derek's fired.'' He was joking. We think.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the unlikely, worse-case scenario, it is logical to
assume that the NHL is not going to strip Atlanta of its hockey
franchise, and in the process chuck the Time Warner/Turner empire
out of the exposure-hungry league and refund an $80 million
expansion fee. At Wharton, they would refer to that as a bad
business decision.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL has been aiming for a return to the Atlanta market since
Tom Cousins sold the team to Canadian Nelson Skalbania, who moved
the team to Calgary. The Flames' attendance dwindled over time. But
overall, they didn't suffer from lack of fan support as much as
little corporate involvement and a real-estate depression that left
Cousins strapped for cash.
</P>
<P>
   With about seven months to go before the Thrashers' first game _
214 days, according to the electronic billboard on the Downtown
Connector _ there is no indication that finances will be a problem
this time. The Omni has been replaced by one giant revenue stream,
an arena with 18,500 seats for hockey, with a title sponsor,
Philips, and 90 leased luxury suites. Club-seat sales have not been
as strong as hoped, prompting a recent corporate push and ticket
agents dressed like Wayne Gretkzy. But it is comforting to Derek
Schiller that approximately 65 percent of the team's ticket
purchases _ at an average of $45 per ticket _ have been personal,
nor corporate. The NHL average is 60 percent corporate, 40 percent
personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's a good sign that people are spending their own
money right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The message being: Atlanta is buying into a product, even though
a player hasn't been drafted, a coach hasn't been hired and general
manager Don Waddell only bought a Zamboni last week; actually, he
bought four at $55,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   There are other positive signs: Nashville, Tenn. _ with a
population of 700,000, 18 percent of the Thrashers' estimate of 3.8
million for metro Atlanta _ is averaging 15,846 fans in its first
year, has had 10 sellouts and even drew 13,507 the night Tennessee
played in the Fiesta Bowl. The population of the Atlanta area has
more than doubled since the Flames left, in large part because of
an influx of Northern transplants, and hockey's popularity has been
broadened by a roller-blading boom.
</P>
<P>
   It all bodes well for the short term. The belief is that the
Thrashers, because of the initial euphoria, have a
two-to-three-year honeymoon period to attract fans and establish
themselves. After that, Atlanta's tendency to support winners
figures to hold form.
</P>
<P>
   John Bevilaqua, the president of Creative Marketing Strategies
in Atlanta, said he suspects that the growth of street hockey will
lead a number of youths to persuade their parents ``to take them to
a game, even though the parents may not know anything about the
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Bevilaqua added, ``They've done a lot of things well. But in the
end, the quality of the product determines whether people come back
again. Think about Coke. They did all this market research and
thought it would be smart to change the formula they had used for
99 years. But consumers said, 'We don't like this.' The Thrashers
are the new kids in town. Everybody will try it. The Flames were
enormously popular for their first two, three or four years, then
their popularity tailed off. There should be enough transplanted
snowbirds now to sustain a fan base. But I'm not ready to say yet
they're going to be a success in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   The executives of the Thrashers, like the brown song birds they
represent, are willing to sidestep out on a limb. Derek Schiller
left his comfortable position as head of marketing for the champion
New York Yankees to sell hockey to Atlanta. Schiller agrees that in
the end the product will determine the Thrashers' success. He joked
that the best marketing strategy is to ``sign Pavel Bure,'' a
reference to the Florida Panthers' post-Bure attendance jump.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers' roster figures to lack marquee value for at least
a year or two. But the first step of the marketing plan, Schiller
said, was merely spreading the word that the NHL is returning. He
estimated that when the team began its one-year-out marketing
campaign in October about 10 percent of Atlantans knew who the
Thrashers were. ``Now I believe that's up to at 60 to 70 percent,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That can be attributed to both advertising and exhaustive
efforts in the community. The team has staged several clinics and
has set up booths at events all over town. It recently kicked off a
street-hockey program in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we said from the outset was we were not going to
pick out just one segment of the population to market to,'' said
Schiller, who played high-school hockey in Colorado Springs, and
still plays in an adult league. ``We wanted to reach across all
demographics.''
</P>
<P>
   If the name, ``Thrashers,'''was not immediately embraced by area
sports fans, the logo and team colors were. To Schiller, it meant
more than potential T-shirt sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a logo that has been received well in the marketplace
has done us a world of good,'' he said. ``If we had a poor logo,
people might say, 'I like the NHL but you guys are kind of boring.'
It's amazing the way a look (creates) perceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   A series of breakfasts and cocktail parties have been used to
gauge feedback from current or potential season-ticket holders. In
the process, team executives have tried to create a buildup, with
little more than the logo in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You market potential,'' Schiller said.
</P>
<P>
   You try to create new avenues, like implementing hockey into
math programs in school _ one goal plus two goals equals hat trick.
You consider hiring a syndicated radio personality, Scott Ferrall,
to do play-by-play, hoping his celebrity appeal will compensate for
a lack of game-calling experience and maybe lead to a sweeter
broadcast deal. You get the word out that a cross-section of
Atlanta sports celebrities _ Tom Glavine, Chuck Smith, Bill
Goldberg _ have purchased season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to sell out every game,'' Harvey Schiller said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like setting the bar high.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
