<HEADER>
A1607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAFEATURE28-COX     02-27 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEATURE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will Rodman help L.A. win title, or create havoc?
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Of all the accomplishments in an NBA career marked by
championships, suspensions and stupefying shenanigans, what Dennis
Rodman pulled off Wednesday eclipsed anything anyone has ever done:
He got a coach fired before playing a single game.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, that's what the Lakers' expulsion of Del Harris came
down to; if Harris could not handle the ultra-talented bunch
without Rodman, general manager Jerry West reasoned, the decent,
respectful Harris would get run over once the pierced-bodied,
robo-rebounder showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already there are problems,'' Rodman acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   And the fun has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Rodman for the rest of the season amounted to a
crapshoot for Los Angeles. If he performs on the court as he has
over the years _ that is, defend the post with fervor, rebound in
traffic and project an energy that permeates his team _ the Lakers
could become the championship team they look to be on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that Rodman was nearly as valuable as Michael Jordan
during the 1996 NBA finals against Seattle, hauling in virtually
every key rebound. And his defensive job on Karl Malone was
significant to last year's Chicago three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rodman) brings something different to the table,'' West said.
``He brings a tenacity. We've never had a player like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting Rodman alongside all-stars Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe
Bryant catapults the Lakers to the top of the league in marquee
value.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of the equation, however, is frightening. B.R. _
Before Rodman _ the Lakers have shown themselves to be a fragile
group, capable of imploding at the mere scent of turmoil. It was
convenient to bounce Harris after the team continued to
underachieve with three losses in a row, the last pair to inferior
Denver and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   West used such words as ``floundering'' and ``deterioration'' to
describe the club. The Lakers played listlessly, and Harris, an
ordained minister, did nothing to reverse their plight. Last year,
he won the battle with former Laker guard Nick Van Exel, whom he
failed to control or co-exist with much of the season. West dealt
Van Exel to Denver, hoping that Derek Fisher's team-oriented
approach would serve the club better. It hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   And so, enter Rodman. The flip side to A.R. _ After Rodman _ is
that the psychedelic-haired, tattoo-covered forward has a penchant
for creating an atmosphere of discord. Over the years, he's been a
one-man El Nino, causing havoc in devastating fashion. His antics
with the San Antonio Spurs in the 1995 playoffs _ two ejections for
flagrant fouls, two bare feet after taking his shoes off on the
bench _ preceded the team's elimination by Utah and his move to
Chicago. With the Bulls, many times they overcame Rodman's
silliness en route to three championships.
</P>
<P>
   There was Jordan to do what David Robinson did not in San
Antonio, which was impose his will and strong personality. And,
significantly, there was coach Phil Jackson, who deftly dealt with
Rodman by allowing him enough space to function in his far-out
world but remain a viable cog on the court.
</P>
<P>
   There's no telling if Kurt Rambis, the interim coach, can
command enough respect from Rodman to keep him relatively in check,
but the evidence was blatant that Harris was not that savvy or
strong-willed. If Rodman's foolishness _ and there will be some _
distracts the talent, the Lakers again will not fulfill their
promise. After all, what place embraces weirdness more than L.A.?
And there are hourly flights from there to Rodman's city of
lewdness and crudeness, Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could (not) care less what players do off the floor,'' West
said.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds good _ until Rodman starts missing practices and
planes. Until he starts offending fans and officials alike,
insulting teammates and spewing venom in the media. Yet, so
intriguing is Rodman that even the fired Harris conceded to
regretting the lost opportunity to coach him. ``I don't know what
kind of ride it would have been,'' Harris said, ``but I sure wanted
to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ride with Rodman probably will register NBA earthquakes high
on the Richter scale. He craves attention so much that he'll see to
that. So, the ultimate question: Is Rodman worth the trouble?
</P>
<P>
   Considering what he could add on the court if he acts anything
close to ``normal'' off it, the answer is yes. But with this guy,
there are no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
