<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-PRIEST28-COX     02-27 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-PRIEST28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Difficult task set before Jasper priest
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The Rev. Ron Foshage was a consoler in the
courtroom all through the dreadful trial that appalled America.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic priest was a familiar sight at the Jasper County
courthouse because he volunteered to sit with the ailing father of
the white racist on trial for dragging a black man to death.
Without the priest, the heartbroken Ronald King would have been all
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Foshage, known as Father Ron, offered to provide spiritual
comfort even though King is not Catholic and doesn't attend his
church. The priest's gesture was all the more extraordinary because
he is the pastor for District Attorney Guy James Gray, who was
seeking the death penalty for King's son. As Gray introduced one
startling piece of evidence after another, his priest sat a few
feet away, consoling a sometimes sobbing Ronald King.
</P>
<P>
   Many say Jasper could learn from Foshage as it tries to recover
from the emotional trauma of a two-week trial over one of the most
vicious racial killings in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Ron wasn't trying to send a message, but if there's a
message in it, it's that we've got to help each other and forget
any feelings of hate and anger and dislike, and those kinds of
things,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Mays, who publishes a bi-weekly African American
newspaper called East Texas Communicator, said she was proud to see
Foshage by Ronald King's side in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say there is no racism in Jasper. I am not
going to say all blacks and whites get along in a good
relationship, because they don't,'' Mays said. ``But Father Ron's
outstanding, caring position during this trial is an inspiration to
what Jasper can become.
</P>
<P>
   Foshage, the only Catholic priest in Jasper County, has received
some unkind calls from people around the country. They criticized
him for supporting the father of John William ``Bill'' King, who
was convicted and sentenced to death last week for torturing and
beheading James Byrd Jr., a disabled black man.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most people thank me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crank calls do not surprise Jasper residents who have become
accustomed to cruel remarks from outsiders who blame the whole town
for what happened to Byrd. They defend Foshage as strongly as they
defend their town.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was setting a good example of how people ought to express
themselves toward people that are in trouble or who need a helping
hand,'' said Andrea Tatum, a Jasper optician.
</P>
<P>
   Foshage, 51, is well known in Jasper County even though
Catholics are less than 1 percent of the population. A native of
St. Louis, Mo., he has lived in Jasper for 13 years and serves as
pastor for four parishes. He drives 800 miles a week to celebrate
15 Masses and attend to other needs of his parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   He has assumed a leading role in trying to improve race
relations in Jasper since Byrd's murder, and presided at the recent
ceremony to remove the 163-year-old fence that separated black and
white graves in the city cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Foshage has comforted Ronald King since last summer, but was
spurned in his attempts to counsel Bill King. The priest went to
see Bill King in jail, but had no idea what to say to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a nervous wreck. I got in the car to drive to the county
jail and I said, `Jesus please either tell me what to say or don't
let me see him,''' Foshage said.
</P>
<P>
   When he got to the jail, he was told that King was not allowed
to have any visitors. Later, Bill King refused to see the priest.
</P>
<P>
   One person who did want to visit with Foshage was Gray, the
prosecutor. He has consulted the priest over the past few months on
the meaning of Bill King's Satanic tattoos as well as the Catholic
church's position on the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he is not a strong advocate of the death penalty but
believes it is necessary for murderers who would kill again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic church's official position is that if a person
commits a serious crime and goes through a proper (legal) channel
and is judged by his peers, the church accepts the death penalty,''
Foshage said.
</P>
<P>
   He told the prosecutor, ``Guy James, this (case) meets all the
criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   In their meetings, the prosecutor showed the priest the evidence
he planned to present at trial. The priest knew the trial would be
a shock for Ronald King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mentioned to him if he needed some spiritual guidance, I
would certainly be there for him,'' Foshage said. ``I simply told
him that if no one was going to sit with him I would be proud to
because he's such a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King has three other children. Two live out of town and
did not come to Jasper for the trial. His daughter in Jasper came
to court only a few times with her father.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say Ronald King's emphysema has deteriorated severely
since his son's arrest last summer. Before, he walked without
assistance and breathed on his own. Now, the 68-year-old retired
lumber mill worker uses a wheelchair and an oxygen tube.
</P>
<P>
   Foshage helped him to and from the courtroom during the trial.
On the days that Ronald King did not feel up to attending, Foshage
sat in his place in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't until the trial that he saw how horrible (his
son's involvement) was,'' Foshage said. ``Several times he would
turn to me and say, `Father l didn't know that.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when they were talking about the tattoos. They
showed the Blessed Virgin and the Christ child with the horns,''
Foshage said. ``He turned to me and grabbed my leg and said,
`Father I'm so sorry' because he knew the Blessed Virgin was
important to us as Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most difficult moments of the trial for Foshage came
when Ronald King testified and tearfully pleaded with the jury to
give his son a life sentence. Ronald King was ashen-faced and
shaking and the priest was worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald are you OK?'' the priest asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to do this. I've got to do this,'' Ronald King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing Mr. King hurting so deeply and knowing I couldn't do
anything to take away the hurt really bothered me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Foshage did not meet Bill King until the jury was deliberating
whether to give him the death penalty. Law officers allowed Ronald
King to see his son for 20 minutes, and the priest accompanied him.
</P>
<P>
   While father and son hugged and cried, Foshage stood nearby. At
one point, Bill King shook the priest's hand and thanked him for
caring for his father.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the meeting, ``He pushed his father to me in the
wheelchair and he gave me a great big hug and said, `I can't thank
you enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wondering if Bill even loved his dad until I went back
and saw that moment,'' Foshage said. ``I said Bill we're praying
for you. I told him the Lord loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   Foshage himself was overcome with tears at one point during Bill
King's trial. When the jury convicted the younger King, his father
began sobbing and had to go home. But Foshage stayed.
</P>
<P>
   He went to the other side of the courtroom and hugged each
member of the Byrd family and told them that Ronald King wanted
them to know how sorry he was for their loss.
</P>
<P>
   When the priest returned to his seat, he was crying and so upset
he immediately got back up and retreated into a restroom. There, he
began to pray:
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, you want me to be here, and I certainly need to be here.
Give me the strength to do what you want me to do or what needs to
be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Foshage returned to his seat a few minutes later, determined to
continue the assignment he said was the most difficult task he had
ever faced as a priest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
