<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boston Ruins most surprising
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a year that could see four of the ``Original Six''
teams _ Boston, Montreal, New York Rangers, Chicago _ miss the
playoffs, along with 1998 Stanley Cup finalist Washington, no
team's collapse this season is more surprising than the Bruins. The
Capitals have suffered an inordinate number of the injuries, while
the Bruins, considered a team on the rise, are struggling at the
.500 level despite strong goaltending from Bryon Dafoe and one of
the league's best coaches in Pat Burns. And that coach is getting
fed up. ``Everyone here is worrying about things they can't
control,'' said Burns, who has never missed the playoffs in his 10
years as a head coach. ``I'm sick of all that. I'm sick of the
money, sick of people saying we're lifeless, that we don't play
with emotion. Well, one think I'm not is a quitter.'' Dafoe is
among the leaders in goals against average (2.12), saves percentage
(.924) and shutouts (six). But the Bruins are scoring only 2.58
goals per game. Dafoe said, ``It's discouraging. As happy as I do
feel about my goals-against (average) and save percentage, I'd
trade it in for where I was as far as wins last year. I'm ahead in
all categories from last year except for wins. Probably the most
frustrating thing is you can go out and feel you had a pretty good
game, but you walk away pretty disappointed because it's a loss. It
doesn't matter how well you played because, if you don't win, it's
not satisfying. That's the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   TIES THAT BIND
</P>
<P>
   If Tampa Bay owner Art Williams accepts an offer of
approximately $125 milion for the Lightning from Bill Davidson, the
league should approve the sale quickly. Commissioner Gary Bettman,
a former legal counsel for the NBA, has strong ties to Davidson.
Bettman is seeking to upgrade some ownership situations in the
league, and Davidson who owns the Detroit Piston and the Palace in
Auburn Hills, Mich. _ has had his assets valued at $1.5 billion.
``We're pushing very hard to get this thing done quickly,'' said
Tom Wilson, Davidson's point man in negotiations. ``At this point,
anything that isn't a step back is a step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   That Carolina signed goalie Trevor Kidd to a two-year, $4
million extension hardly insures his future with the team. Kidd was
scheduled to become a restricted free agent but he still might be
left unprotected during the Thrashers' expansion draft, given the
career rejuvenation of starter Arturs Irbe. He is 6-9-3 with a 2.75
GAA and two shutouts. . . . The Rangers are pushing to get a deal
done with potential unrestricted free agent Brian Leetch. One
problem: Leetch doesn't merely want to be the NHL's highest-paid
defenseman, about $6 million annually, he wants to be among the
highest paid players, $8 million or more. Leetch: ``Everyone is
pretty much in the same mode: We'd all like to stay. But come July
1, you're in a great position to decide where you want to play for
a good portion of the rest of your career.'' . . . Only one thing
prevented Buffalo from acquiring center Doug Gilmour from Chicago:
Gilmour exercised his no-trade clause. The Sabres would have
shipped Matthew Barnaby to the Blackhawks. Barnaby, a nightly
scratch for the Sabres, said, ``Sometimes it's better to move on.
I'm still part of the Buffalo Sabres, but when you haven't played,
you lose focus.'' . . . The Rangers continue to shop defenseman Ulf
Samuelsson in an attempt to trim their payroll, and Philadelphia is
interested. . . . Phoenix forward Rick Tocchet after a 7-1 loss to
Florida: ``They looked like the (Soviet) Red Army team. Geez, they
were flying. They looked like 21 (Pavel) Bures out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
