<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flames may be on move
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ It is with some irony that as Atlanta
prepares for a return to the NHL with an $80 million expansion
franchise and an expensive arena, the city's former NHL team
suddenly has all the appeal of a 63-cent Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
   And it might soon be headed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Harley Hotchkiss, a co-owner of the Calgary Flames,
said, ``Our only recourse is to leave'' if the Canadian government
does not grant the team some tax breaks. It was a microcosm of the
problems facing all six north-of-the-border franchises in the NHL.
The six Canadian teams _ Calgary, Edmonton, Montreal, Ottawa,
Toronto and Vancouver _ pay 10 times the property taxes _ $21.8
million _ of the 20 operating in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The financial situation is worsened by the fact that players are
paid in American dollars, even though revenues to the north are in
devalued Canadian dollars. Also, owners do not have the sweet arena
deals of most U.S. franchises.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ottawa is in first place in the Northeast Division
despite the NHL's third-lowest payroll and an average of 17,000
fans per game in an arena with 142 of 147 luxury suites leased. But
owner Ron Bryden estimates that he will lose $7 million _ U.S., not
Canadian _ this season, and he will not commit to keeping the
Senators in Ottawa past next season _ when, it's worth noting,
Alexei Yashin will be due a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should not come as a threat,'' Bryden said, referring to
a possible move. ``But if no one in Canada cares, why should I
care?''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is similar in Calgary, which landed the Flames
when owner Tom Cousins, needing a financial fix for the sagging
real-estate market, sold the club in 1980 to Nelson Skalbania, who
moved it out of the South. The Flames prospered, landing a new
arena and winning a Stanley Cup in 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 years later, the Flames might miss the playoffs for the
third season in a row and could be headed for financial losses
despite the league's second-lowest payroll. Attendance has dropped
more than 3,000 per game since a peak of 19,986 in 1990-91. And
with free-agency approaching, franchise centerpiece Theoren Fleury
will be gone sooner _ before the March 23 trade deadline _ or later
_ signing elsewhere after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury would have been dealt to L.A. three weeks ago, but the
deal was contingent on him approving a four-year, $25 million
extension. He declined, mostly for personal reasons: His wife is
pregnant and due in April, and he doesn't want to uproot his
family. L.A. remains a likely destination after the season, if the
Flames' can't find a trade partner. Calgary probably can't afford
to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to know Fleury may not be here when all is
said and done,'' general manager Al Coates said. ``You don't like
to lose your top players for economic reasons. ... We have to be
careful. We have to keep our salaries in line. It's not our fault.
It's our problem but not our fault.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flames' last link to Atlanta is Al MacNeil, who coached the
final year before the move and now is the team's director of
operations. MacNeil says he thinks that the Flames will survive in
Calgary, but he recognizes the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came here, it was another era,'' MacNeil said. ``The
people who brought the team here were successful businessmen,
Calgary was thriving and they weren't afraid to spend money. What's
knocking the heck out of us is the Canadian dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, Seattle and Portland are possible NHL markets.
Conservative projections have at least three Canadian teams
relocating _ Calgary, Edmonton and Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's being said by the crepe-hangers,'' MacNeil said. ``But
the situation has to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleury is resigned to the possibility of leaving a city where he
has lived and worked for 11 years. What really disturbs him are
thoughts that the Flames might not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look how much money hockey generates taxwise for the
government,'' he said. ``They should do something. If they keep
losing Canadian teams, that's a lot of taxes they won't be getting
from the players. These owners are businessmen. If you were a
businessman, would you just keep shelling it out?''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years after moving to Calgary, the Flames face an
uncertain future. The only certainty is that they won't be moving
to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
