<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Art of the (side) deal
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nobody ever projected that Marty McSorley was going to
be the key to the Thrashers' first season. But Edmonton's possible
circumvention of expansion draft rules involving the veteran
defenseman has set off alarms with NHL officials.
</P>
<P>
   For the expansion draft, each team must expose one defenseman
and one forward who have each played 40 games this season or 70 in
the last two and who is either under contract for next season or
has an option for such. Oilers general manager Glen Sather is
planning to use McSorley as the defenseman, but there's a problem:
He's not under contract for next season, and actually, Sather
doesn't want to lose him.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley makes $1 million this season, but an Edmonton newspaper
said the GM will sign the vet to a voidable option year worth $2.3
million in 1999-2000. At that price, the Thrashers surely would
pass on McSorley. The belief is that Sather, because of a side deal
with McSorley, would let the option for next season expire, making
the player an unrestricted free agent, then re-sign him for
slightly over $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The league is keenly aware of the scenario, but its power might
be limited. ``All contracts have to be approved by this office,''
NHL spokesman Frank Brown said. ``I won't comment on
hypotheticals.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell said he ``would not make a
big deal about'' the McSorley situation. ``Nobody ever said we were
going to get a great team out of the expansion draft, anyway,''
Waddell said. ``Our main objective is to get a good goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   JERSEY UNVEILING
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will unveil their home jerseys during March 27
ceremonies at Centennial Park. Further details will be made
available this week.
</P>
<P>
   STAT PACK
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa goalie Ron Tugnutt is on pace to have the lowest
goals-against average of the modern era, which is defined as when
the red line was introduced in 1943-44.
</P>
<P>
   Year _ Player _ Team _ GAA
</P>
<P>
   1998-99 _ Ron Tugnutt _ Ottawa _ 1.50
</P>
<P>
   1971-72 _ Tony Esposito _ Chicago _ 1.77
</P>
<P>
   1950-51 _ Al Rollins _ Toronto _ 1.77
</P>
<P>
   1953-54 _ Harry Lumley _ Toronto _ 1.86
</P>
<P>
   1955-56 _ Jacques Plante _ Montreal _ 1.86
</P>
<P>
   DRAFT PEEK
</P>
<P>
   It didn't make big news in Atlanta _ unless you work for the
Thrashers. Center Tim Connolly, projected to be one of the top five
players taken in the June amateur draft, suffered a broken leg last
week and is out for the season. Connolly, who had 34 goals and 34
assists in 46 games for Erie of the Ontario Hockey League,
attempted to skate around a Windsor player when the two collided
and went down. The good news for Connolly is that it was a clean
break, with no ligament damage, and some scouts say they think that
it won't affect his standing. ``That's why you scout these guys so
much early,'' Waddell said, ``because now you won't get another
chance to watch him play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
