<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dealing with defeat Robinson's main obstacle
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few question that NHL Hall of Famer Larry Robinson has
at least two of the three qualifications to be a successful coach:
1) he knows the game; 2) he commands respect from his players. But
the Los Angeles coach has yet to prove that he can deal with
defeat, as evidenced by several, woe-is-me, Hamlet-like speeches
and a tendency to blame officials after games, such as last week's
post-game explosion in Calgary. After a 2-2 to the Flames, Robinson
called the officiating, which didn't appear awful to most people,
the ``worst I've ever seen.'' If he is not fined by the NHL, it
will be a miracle. Robinson was particularly upset by Calgary's
tying goal, when 5-foot-6 Theoren Fleury appeared to grab L.A.'s
6-2 Mattias Norstrom in front of the net, stole the puck and
scored. Fleury laughed when told about Robinson's comments, alluded
to his own diminutive stature and said, ``Penalty on me? Yeah,
right. It was just a battle for the puck _ and I won.'' If the
Kings don't make the playoffs, Robinson probably will be gone, and
the decision will be made by president Tim Leiweke, not general
manager Dave Taylor. The Kings have been decimated by injuries all
season, but the team nonetheless has underachieved, and a new arena
with several unsold seats awaits next season. If available,
Robinson would draw interest from several teams, including the
Thrashers. To quote one NHL executive, however, ``There's no doubt
Larry's a great coach. But he doesn't take losing well. He might
need to be with one of the six teams that can win a Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE, DIRK
</P>
<P>
   One day after proclaiming, ``Everybody's job is in jeopardy,''
Chicago coach Dirk Graham proved prophetic _ as it related to
himself. The Blackhawks, with only 16 wins and 131 goals (2.22) in
59 games, fired Graham before he could complete his first season
and have given a mandate to replacement Lorne Molleken to open up
the offense. Graham was inspirational as a player, but his methods
didn't translate as a coach, and he certainly was no X-and-O
wizard. Even Molleken said, ``Dirk's belief was to simplify the
game. That was dumping the puck in and going in to create a
forecheck off that. Sometimes players got frustrated with it, for
whatever reason. But that was Dirk's belief, and as a coaching
staff, we backed it.'' The players didn't _ particularly Tony
Amonte, Doug Gilmour and Alex Zhamnov. A few days before the
firing, Amonte and Graham openly feuded on the ice during a
practice, then later claimed that it was all an act for the media.
No matter whether it was, Amonte's playing time had dropped
dramatically in recent weeks _ and he is the Hawks' top triggerman.
But Graham was ``set up for failure,'' to use GM Bob Murray's
words. There has been a blur of personnel blunders, and Murray
continues to suffer because of meddling from executives Bill Wirtz
and Bob Pulford.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Seen in a Calgary souvenir shop: Flyers' souvenier pucks at
$4.95 (Canadian), Blackhawks' at $3.95. . . . There is a growing
believe that Dallas might not trade backup goalie Roman Turek, even
though it surely would lose him to Atlanta in the expansion draft.
Turek, 10-1-2 with 1.80 average and .921 saves percentage through
16 games, provides the Stars with an insurance policy should
starter Ed Belfour get injured during the team's possible Stanley
Cup run. Teams have 48 hours to deal after the playoffs before
setting its protected list, but Dallas might not want to sacrifice
a position player instead of a goalie because there is goaltending
depth in the system. . . . For those keeping track, coach Marc
Crawford won only three of his first 14 games in Vancouver. . . .
San Jose survived its road trip (4-5-1), but its playoff future
will be determined by a stretch in which the Sharks play 18 of 24
against Western Conference opponents. Center Mike Ricci said,
``It's definitely not time for us to say, 'Oh, God, this trip's
over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
