<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Feb. 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rain will spread across the Northeastern states as a
strengthening storm system arrives from the Middle West. The day
will begin with some sunshine near the New England coast, but
clouds will thicken and rain will arrive during the afternoon and
evening. Farther south over the eastern Ohio Valley and Middle
Atlantic states, damp weather will prevail much of the day. A few
thunderstorms will be imbedded in the rain area over the Middle
Atlantic region later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt ahead of a cold front in the
Southeast. The thunderstorms will build from northern Florida and
southeastern Georgia early in the day into the eastern Carolinas by
afternoon. Strong, shifting winds between the ground and 15,000
feet combined with increasingly humid air will heighten the risk
for severe thunderstorms with hail and a few tornadoes during the
midday hours.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the cold front, gusty breezes from the northwest will
draw cooler air from the western Great Lakes through the Ohio
Valley to the interior Southeast. Snow showers will dust parts of
the northern Great Lakes states. Rapid clearing will follow the
cold front in the Southeast, but, farther north, clouds will linger
for much of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Wet weather will persist over much of the Pacific Northwest as
onshore flow delivers moist air from over the Pacific. Early
morning snow levels in the Cascades will be near 6,000 feet but
will lower to 4,000 feet by evening. Meanwhile, most of the
Southwest will be mild and dry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: When Winter Ends
</P>
<P>
   While the calendar indicates that winter isn't over until March
20, many meteorologists would say that the season ends Sunday. The
event commemorated on the calendar is the end of astronomical
winter, a time when the most direct rays of the sun shift from the
southern to the northern hemisphere. For the purposes of official
climate records, winter began on Dec. 1, 1998 and ends on Feb. 28,
1999. According to another unofficial measurement, winter will pass
on March 5, the end of coldest 90-day period of the year in most of
the northern United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
