<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1637 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-DELEG28-COX     02-27 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-DELEG28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia without a heavy hitter
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From Carl Vinson to Richard Russell to Sam Nunn to
Newt Gingrich, Georgia had a decades-long run of powerful members
of Congress to look out for its interests.
</P>
<P>
   Military bases, defense factories and roads were built. Federal
dollars flowed and flowed and flowed.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the federal government shut hundreds of defense
facilities around the nation, Georgia was spared.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, for the first time since the Depression, Georgia
lacks what in sports terminology might be referred to as a ``go-to
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is diminished influence. Period. End of story,'' said
Republican Rep. Charlie Norwood. ``It was pretty nice when the
speaker was from Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a congressional heavyweight could not come at a
worse time. Unlike the heyday of the Great Society in the 1960s or
the Ronald Reagan-inspired defense build-up in the 1980s, Congress
controls relatively little money for discretionary projects.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH MASKED LOSS OF NUNN
</P>
<P>
   The battles over the defense budget are more fierce. The Clinton
administration set aside no money in 2000, for example, for the
C-130J cargo plane, a mainstay of the Lockheed Martin plant in
Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another round of base closings looms.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's 13 members of Congress, while no less vigilant than
their predecessors, are scrambling to minimize the damage from
Gingrich's resignation as well as Nunn's retirement two years
earlier. Between them, the two men served in Congress 44 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's role as speaker in a sense masked the absence of
Nunn, whose expertise on defense matters and stout protection of
Georgia's bases and production facilities were unquestioned.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn himself was the successor to Russell, who also was chairman
of the Senate Armed Services Committee and, for a time, the Senate
Appropriations subcommittee on military spending. And Russell
served much of his Washington career with Vinson, whose 50-year
House tenure included leading military committees for 30 years,
beginning in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the state's longest-serving congressman is
Democratic Rep. John Lewis, who arrived in 1987 and ranks 115th out
of 435 in terms of seniority. Lewis also is a chief deputy whip for
the Democrats, assigned to help garner support for Democratic
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, beginning his seventh year of service, is a
member of the Senate leadership, but he has staked out a position
on education and as a master of internal party politics. These are
not the sorts of topics that typically translate into more federal
money on the local level.
</P>
<P>
   None of the other 11 Georgians in Congress is a committee
chairman or a ranking minority member. Rep. John Linder had been
chairman of the House Republican campaign committee, but he lost
his post in the aftermath of Gingrich's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol Hill newspaper Roll Call, which ranks delegations'
clout every two years, dropped Georgia 10 slots, from 20th to 30th,
because of Gingrich's exit.
</P>
<P>
   On his first day in Congress last week, Republican Rep. Johnny
Isakson tried to put the best face on his status as the most junior
House member, magnified because he took Gingrich's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fool,'' he said after Speaker Dennis Hastert
(R-Ill.) swore him in a second time for the benefit of
photographers. ``However, I do have the same vote as the
highest-ranking member. I'm going to do my best to leverage that
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Isakson's partners in the House insisted that the state
will fare just as well in the post-Gingrich era. Georgians sit on
key committees, including Appropriations, Commerce, National
Security and Ways and Means. Isakson will join the transportation
panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the speaker, but we didn't lose our voices,''
Republican Rep. Mac Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Bob Barr, whose district is home to the Lockheed
Martin plant, said, ``I think we have a very strong delegation. We
have members on every one of the key committees.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has placed calls on behalf of Lockheed Martin to the White
House, where he is well-regarded for his staunch defense of
President Clinton during the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Jack Kingston is on the appropriations panel.
Republican Saxby Chambliss and Democratic Sen. Max Cleland sit on
the military committees in their chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss has hired a former Gingrich defense aide, Krister
Holladay, as his deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   But as of the middle of February, the Air Force had no plans to
accelerate the purchase of the C-130Js, which threatens to shut
down the production line that employs 2,000 to 3,000 people
sometime in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Clinton asked for one of the cargo planes in his
budget. But before the year was out, Gingrich had inserted into the
budget six additional planes, at more than $50 million each.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED MARTIN AFFECTED
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin officials and members of Congress said,
ultimately, the C-130J program is not at risk. The Air Force's
long-range plans call for 150 planes to replace its aging air cargo
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   And the planes also are popular in Congress because they often
go to state National Guard units.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even a temporary shutdown of the production line would
mean layoffs for Lockheed Martin workers and probably escalate the
price of the new F-22 fighter, which shares some overhead costs
with the cargo plane program.
</P>
<P>
   A potentially bigger worry is the fate of some of the state's
military bases. Vinson, Russell and Nunn used their positions not
only to protect the facilities, but also to enhance their missions
to ward off future efforts to close them.
</P>
<P>
   State and congressional officials mounted an all-out effort to
preserve the bases in the last round of closings, which employed a
bipartisan commission in an effort to remove politics from the
issue of shuttering bases and eliminating jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, two Gingrich appointees served on the base-closure
commission and a former Nunn aide played a key role on the
commission staff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 1416EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
