<DOCNO> NYT19990227.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DATELINE-CALCUTTA28-C     02-27 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATELINE-CALCUTTA28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carrying the burden of survival
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALCUTTA, India _ Every muscle in Shankar Raj's 56-year-old body
ripples as he hoists the wooden handles of his two-wheeled rickshaw
off the dusty ground. His eyes meet mine only once as he turns
around to ask our destination, and then he begins a slow trot.
</P>
<P>
   Raj's soot-covered bare feet quickly fall in stride as he ambles
along winding back alleys with the weight of two adult passengers
in the seat behind him.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 hours a day, Raj and his rickshaw jostle for space among
taxis, cars, buses, scooters and every other mode of transport in
this congested city. After 32 years, he has perfected a rhythm to
his maddening work. On every fifth step, he chimes a brass bell
around his right wrist to signal his presence to pedestrians in his
way. He stares vacantly ahead, stopping and going at the customer's
behest, withstanding verbal - and sometimes physical - abuse for a
bumpy ride or a wrong turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a life you would wish for. But what am I going to
do? My family depends on me for food,'' he says, catching his
breath.
</P>
<P>
   Half way into the three-mile journey, I could stand no more of
watching man act as beast of burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop. We'll get down here, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds, Raj has come to a complete stop from a full
gallop.
</P>
<P>
   He slowly lowers the handles of the rickshaw, bringing his
passengers closer to the ground. He looks up in disbelief when he
is handed twice the negotiated rate of 15 cents. ``Bless you, my
child,'' he says, wiping the sweat off his brow with the end of his
tattered T-shirt. ``God will save your soul for having mercy on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   For his hard labor, Raj, like most other rickshaw wallahs, earns
an average of $1-2 a day, low even by Calcutta standards. After
paying for food and housing and the 30-cent rickshaw rental fee,
the average puller pockets 10-20 cents on a prosperous day.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is saved is usually sent to far-away homes, often in
villages in neighboring states, to care for the families they have
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The rickshaw wallahs who share a stand on central Calcutta's
Creek Row consider themselves slightly luckier than the rest _ they
sleep rent-free on the floor of a factory across the street. In
return, they perform domestic chores for the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Ali Hassan, spend nights on the garbage-strewn
sidewalk next to their bustling Colootolla Street stand in front of
the Tashkent laundering shop and Vikram scooter rentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do this because we have to do it. This is not any kind of
life,'' says Hassan, 32. ``Sometimes, when I am working, I think
about how it would be if I could get another job, a better job. It
is backbreaking for one man to pull another man. I mean, it is
inhuman, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I once had your health. Now look at me. Look at my body, my
feet,'' says Hassan pointing to the veins bubbling from his legs
and the callouses covering the bottoms of his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later, Hassan puts the shade down on his
rickshaw and takes off with the load of two burkha-clad women
firmly planted on his vinyl-covered seat.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 700,000 Calcuttans use rickshaws every day, nearly
three times the number who ride the much more costly subway. This
is a city in which these human-powered vehicles are still a vital
mode of transportation as they weave in and out of traffic-logged
streets faster than cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summer, people like to use rickshaws more than taxis
because they are so much cooler,'' says Prem Mahato, 35, who left
home in Bihar to find work in Calcutta. ``It is unbearably hot
then, but more profitable for us. Same thing in the monsoon season
_ rickshaws are more convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahato says that when he is running from one place to another,
he often dreams about doing something else. He once found escape
from this grueling line of work as a sweeper with the local Campa
Cola factory. But the respite ended when the soft-drink company
closed its doors several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Invented by the Japanese, rickshaws were introduced here in 1918
by Chinese immigrants. Calcutta is now the only major Indian city
that allows the antiquated means of transport on its streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Calcutta Municipal Corporation officially authorizes 12,000
rickshaws to operate in the city. But there are probably an equal
number of unlicensed ones. There have been attempts to remove
rickshaws altogether to help speed up the crawling pace of city
traffic _ the last effort being in 1997. Protested by the rickshaw
pullers' union, the ban was never implemented.
</P>
<P>
   That was a good thing for Dalo Sau, 33, whose wife and two
children back in Bihar depend on the $12-15 he sends them each
month.
</P>
<P>
   On this warm February day, Sau has managed to take advantage of
the mid-afternoon traffic lull to rest his weary body. But not his
mind. Almost horizontal on his parked rickshaw, he knows that at
any moment, he might once again have to give his all.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I have to eat, I will pull this rickshaw,'' says
Sau. ``There is no choice, is there?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
