<HEADER>
A1649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKS-SAFRICA-560&AMP;ADD     02-27 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-SAFRICA-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS FOREIGN BANKS LENT BILLIONS FOR APARTHEID
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Swiss and German bankers played a key role in propping
up South Africa's apartheid government, according to a report
issued last week by groups seeking billions of dollars in
reparations and debt forgiveness for the current South African
government.
</P>
<P>
   When most governments around the world were boycotting South
Africa under U.N. sanctions, major Swiss and German banks continued
to give billions of dollars in loans, the groups said.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, at least, American banks started to scale back their
involvement in South Africa from 1985 to 1986, but money continued
to flow into the country.
</P>
<P>
   This report focuses only on the Swiss and German involvement.
The researchers said they wanted to leave the in-depth work on
American and British involvement to researchers from those
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source, the money helped the white-minority
government survive and left South Africa with a substantial debt
that undermines the new government's ability to turn around the
economic and social situation it inherited, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking that the Swiss government and banks explain how
this happened,'' said Mascha Madorin, an economist with the Swiss
Action Financial Center. The demand by her group, part of a
coalition of eight nongovernmental groups, that Switzerland be held
accountable in South Africa comes on the heels of disclosures about
Swiss banks' dealings with Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Although the study does not call for a specific amount of debt
forgiveness, Gottfried Wellmer, who wrote the study, said an
appropriate amount for Switzerland, Germany, Britain and the United
States would be $11.3 billion, the amount of South Africa's public
debt in 1993, the last year of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss banks have said they were against apartheid but were free
to conduct business in South Africa. As a neutral country that is
not a member of the United Nations, Switzerland declined to impose
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   A Swiss Foreign Ministry spokeswoman, Yasmine Chatila, said
Swiss National Bank figures indicate that ``banks began to reduce
their positions in South Africa starting in 1984.''
</P>
<P>
   A Swiss parliamentary committee has rejected a proposal to set
up a panel to examine the country's ties with the apartheid
government. The issue will be taken up again in Parliament next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Nils de Dardel, the committee chairman, said he hoped the
report, titled ``Apartheid-Caused Debt: The Role of Swiss and
German Finance,'' would lead to an extensive inquiry, including
access to banks' archives.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Madorin said the watchdog group was eager for a full-scale
inquiry because she had had to rely on South African Reserve Bank
figures; comparable information was not available from the Swiss,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her data, for example, showed that Swiss banks increased their
financial presence in South Africa until 1989. They also helped
bypass sanctions by aiding South African corporations in setting up
seemingly independent companies or buying foreign companies, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the United States and Germany together
were responsible for more than 50 percent of South Africa's 1993
debt, meaning they would be asked to cancel more than $5 billion in
debt. The Swiss were responsible for nearly 21 percent, or around
$2 billion, the report said. The remaining $3 billion to $4 billion
came from the British.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   South Africa began looking to outside sources for financing in
the 1970s to update and expand military forces, arms and supplies.
Four countries _ Germany, the United States, Britain and
Switzerland _ were South Africa's most important business partners.
By 1993 South Africa got 90 percent of its long-term foreign
financing from these four nations, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The $11.3 billion is long-term public sector debt. The total
foreign debt in 1993, both private and public, was $25.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States was the biggest player in the private
sector, Germany had the largest role in the state-run area because
it financed public works like electrical power stations, railways
and telecommunications facilities, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland had a major importance to the South African economy
in three areas: as a financial center for South Africa's trade in
gold and diamonds, as a long-term lender to the apartheid
government and its public entities and as a short-term lender
during crisis periods, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
