<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson, Jordan still keeping eyes on NBA happenings
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Bulls yanked the stalls of Michael Jordan and
Scottie Pippen from their United Center locker room. They'll be
redecorated in some fashion honoring the two main reasons Chicago
won six NBA titles in eight years. There were no preparations to
acknowledge their former coach, Phil Jackson, but the Lakers opened
a can of Worms, so to speak, when they fired Del Harris last
Wednesday after signing Dennis Rodman. Speculation is rampant that
Jackson is No. 1 on owner Jerry Buss' coaching list if Kurt Rambis
slips this season. As of late last week, no one with the Lakers had
contacted Jackson or his agent, Todd Musberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot rule out (Jackson coaching again) this season,''
Musberger said. ``But we should not read too much into that,
because we are in hypothetical land and Phil is quite happy working
the speaking tour and helping his good friend Bill Bradley,'' who
is running for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, my office never does a commitment for Phil
without an escape clause. How would Phil react if (the Lakers) say,
`I got a job for you?' '' Musberger said. ``That's hard for us to
comment on until it really happens. ... But he keeps one eye
trained on the action in the NBA. He's as up on it today as he was
when he was with the Bulls. He has not closed the door on coaching
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that open the way for another Jordan return? He did say
he'd only play for Jackson. And he apparently has been keeping up
with the NBA. He's called Bulls assistant coach Frank Hamblem and
player Dickey Simpkins. When the Hawks beat Chicago 83-67, Jordan
left a message on Hamblen's voice mail saying, ``I can score 67
points in a game. Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpkins added: ``He called me one time, getting on me about
having just one rebound in a game. But I wouldn't say he's missing
this. I would say he's just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   WHOA, NELLIE
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago next month, the largest trade in NBA history went
down, a nine-player deal by Dallas' Don Nelson and New Jersey's
John Calipari. Already, it's clear that the Mavericks got the worse
of the deal. But not by much.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days on the job, Nelson sent Sam Cassell, Jim Jackson,
George McCloud, Chris Gatling and Eric Montross _ his starting five
_ to the Nets for Robert Pack, Khalid Reeves, Ed O'Bannon and Shawn
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson called the acquisition of Pack and Bradley ``our point
guard and center cornerstones of the future.'' Turns out, neither
Pack nor Bradley even starts for a Dallas team that's anemic.
Reeves and O'Bannon are out of the NBA. As for the Nets, Calipari
kept Cassell and Gatling, but Jackson and McCloud were eventually
traded. And Gatling asked to be traded on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moral of the story: Size doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   THEY SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't care anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lakers' Eddie Jones, the subject of countless trade
rumors, on why he would OK a deal to Charlotte for Glen Rice after
refusing other deals in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather get teeth pulled.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cleveland's Bob Sura on guarding mercurial 76ers point guard
Allen Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think David Stern's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Detroit's Grant Hill who was unable to change his July wedding
plans with singer Tamia Washington to participate in the 2000
Olympic Trials
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, this is a dog year. A lot of guys are going out on the
floor with a lot of hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   _ New York's Larry Johnson on the rash of injuries around the
league
</P>
<P>
   ``He just needs to meet me outside in the parking lot, and we'll
settle it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Houston's Scottie Pippen on referee Hue Hollins, a nemesis
over the last five years
</P>
<P>
   ``They're manhandling him. Rik's not playing with force, and
they're just throwing him around.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Indiana coach Larry Bird on passive center Rik Smits
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To the NBA. The league has done a credible job acknowledging
Black History Month. It has sponsored weekly symposiums at New
York's NBA Store featuring such former league stars as Tiny
Archibald, Isiah Thomas and Buck Williams, to discuss the history
of the league and the influence of blacks and its future.
Transcripts are on NBA.com.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To the Los Angeles Lakers. Del Harris led the Lakers to 61 wins
last year and, after a 6-6 start this season, he gets the pink
slip? True, L.A. should be better than its record, and the coach
takes some responsibility. But he's a decent man who got caught up
in the selfishness and uninspired acrimony of a group of players.
He deserved better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
