<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1678 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYONS-VERDICT-455&AMP;ADD     02-27 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYONS-VERDICT-455&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTIST LEADER FOUND GUILTY OF SWINDLING AND THEFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARGO, Fla. _ The head of the United States' largest black
religious organization was found guilty on Saturday of swindling
millions of dollars from companies trying to do business with its
members and of stealing donations intended to rebuild churches in
the South destroyed by arson.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Henry J. Lyons, the powerful president of the National
Baptist Convention USA, was convicted of racketeering and grand
theft in Pinellas County Circuit Court on Saturday afternoon after
a monthlong trial that mixed law and religion and, his lawyers
said, was an attack on the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The same jury refused to convict his aide and co-defendant,
Bernice Edwards, on a single racketeering charge, causing Ms.
Edwards to break down in tears when the verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been so long,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors argued that she and Lyons had used nonexistent
membership lists and the good name of the Baptist convention to
steer more than $4 million from corporations eager to do business
with black communities, and that they had used the money to finance
their lavish lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons seemed emotionless as the verdict was read. His conviction
on the single racketeering charge and two counts of grand theft
could carry a sentence of up to 30 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, which deliberated one full day and part of two others,
had its verdict ready by midmorning, but the decision was not read
until Saturday afternoon because of a mysterious e-mail message
sent to two Tampa Bay television stations that seemed to point to
jury misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edwards' lawyer had moved for a mistrial, minutes before the
verdict was read, asking Judge Susan Schaeffer to throw the unknown
verdict out because of the e-mail, which claimed that a juror had
openly discussed deliberations with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail included details identifying the juror, including her
first name and the fact that she had once appeared on the Ricki
Lake show. When the judge questioned the juror under oath, she
denied having discussed the case but did concede that she had been
on the Ricki Lake show.
</P>
<P>
   As the judge tried to decide what to do, a second e-mail
message, apparently from the same person, arrived saying only that
the information about the juror had been secondhand.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to help the judge make up her mind. She said she
could not delay the reading of the verdict for such a flimsy
reason.
</P>
<P>
   At least two members of the all-white jury had tears in their
eyes as the verdict was read. Later, a member of a small group of
supporters who sat behind Lyons throughout the trial, stood up and
told the judge, ``We remain people of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge replied, ``So do I.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both defendants were charged with one count of racketeering,
involving several instances of promising to sell nonexistent lists
and access to what they said were the convention's 8.5 million
members. Prosecutors said that figure was grossly inflated and
might be more like a million.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also said that Lyons had stolen most of the $240,000
donated to his organization by the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith, money that was supposed to be passed along to the black
churches that had been burned down.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trial in which the name of God was evoked again and
again, mostly by lawyers for Lyons and Ms. Edwards, whom they
described as his servants.
</P>
<P>
   But as Lyons and his aide tried to cloak themselves in religion,
and as their lawyers tried to convince jurors that when money was
floated into his personal account, it was just the way that black
churches ``do business,'' prosecutors hammered again and again at
their credibility, with bank statements, letters and other
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 28-day trial, prosecutors documented specific
instances of what they say was theft, claiming that the minister
used the good name of his organization to steal millions.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution produced two letters from the convention to the
Anti-Defamation League, which, prosecutors said, falsely claimed
that the money the league had donated to the burned black churches
had been distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also produced a document in which the convention had
estimated its membership, state by state. The list, which Lyons and
Ms. Edwards used in their scheme, the prosecutors said, claimed
more black members for some states than there were black residents.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, Lyons and his lawyers predicted that God
would deliver him and Ms. Edwards from what they called the
persecution of the state.
</P>
<P>
   As the all-white jury of five women and one man began
deliberations on Thursday afternoon, Lyons, Ms. Edwards and a group
of about 25 associates joined hands in the courthouse hallway and
sang ``What a Friend We Have in Jesus.'' Then a supporter and
convention member, the Rev. Charles Emery of Gary, Ind., led the
group in a rousing prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our father, we need your intervention,'' said Emery, who asked
God to help the jury reach the ``right'' verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need you to work on their hearts,'' he said, as the people
in the circle shouted ``Yes, Jesus,'' and a man stomped his feet.
``We need you to work on their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as tears filled the eyes of some in the circle, Emery made
a prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We claim the victory right here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he had finished, Lyons' wife, Deborah Lyons, hugged a
weeping Ms. Edwards. It was the actions of Mrs. Lyons that led to
the investigation of her husband's business dealings and lifestyle.
In July 1997, Mrs. Lyons set fire to a $700,000 waterfront home
that her husband had bought with Ms. Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lyons was sentenced to five months' probation in the
incident, but afterward she said she did not suspect her husband of
having an affair with Ms. Edwards _ he had several other affairs,
prosecutors claimed _ and stood by her husband throughout the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Others stood by him, as well. His church, Bethel Community
Baptist Church in St. Petersburg, retained him as pastor, and
leaders in the National Baptist Convention voted to keep him as
president, even as some members worried that he would drag the
100-year-old organization's reputation down with him.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons' lead lawyer, Grady Irvin, told the jury that it was the
cemetery and life insurance corporations that were greedy, that
they took advantage of ``the little preacher'' who was just trying
to represent his membership.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted a closing argument from prosecutors that dripped
with sarcasm and scorn. One of the items the defendants bought was
a diamond as big as a marble, they said.
</P>
<P>
   What Lyons and Ms. Edwards did, in the name of their church and
their religious organization, is ``beyond hypocrisy,'' said Bill
Loughery, the assistant state attorney. ``Somewhere along the line,
he traded the Good Book for the bank book. That's what this case is
all about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
