<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Personalities battle on the court
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kenny Anderson and Antoine Walker are battling. While
the Celtics were being blown away in Washington, Walker screamed at
Anderson, turned to the bench and said loudly, ``I can't play with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson told Walker to get in position if he wants the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Furious, coach Rick Pitino screamed, ``The next guy who opens
his mouth is getting suspended for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the players went at it again in practice, they denied
there is a problem, and Pitino said, ``It's not a problem. It won't
happen again. I'm very disappointed that it happened as a coach
because it's unprofessionalism at the highest level.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE BATTLES
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Alonzo Mourning and Washington's Terry Davis were in a
verbal battle before the Heat blew out the Wizards. Davis called
Mourning a ``sissy'' and said he always complains about foul calls.
``Zo'' then complained about receiving an unnecessary beating from
Davis and other centers around the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was in the World Wrestling Federation,''
Mourning said. ``Someone is going to have to take notice. I can't
retaliate like I did last year. All I can do is grin and bear it
and toe the line. It's every game this is happening. You can see a
team's game plan is to try and foul me.'' Mourning punished Davis
with 29 points, 12 rebounds and six blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Miami, Mark Strickland is back in Pat Riley's doghouse.
He's the most athletic big man Miami has, but he doesn't defend and
has lapses in concentration. ... Meanwhile, after being blown out
by the Heat, Washington coach Bernie Bickerstaff questioned his
team's toughness. Forward Juwan Howard then questioned
Bickerstaff's tactics. He refused to double team Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ITCHING TO RETURN
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are winning and Latrell Sprewell is itching to get
back for their Friday trip to Milwaukee, where his family lives.
He'll have an MRI done on his right heel this week. ... All is not
well with the Knicks, however. Larry Johnson is in great pain from
tendinitis in his left knee. Johnson was told he must play in pain
the rest of the season. Coach Jeff Van Gundy said it's Johnson's
daily decision to practices and play. ``If I could get 25
productive minutes, that would be good,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   NETS IN TANGLES
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the perils of Calipari. Nets coach John Calipari met with
reserve forward Chris Gatling, who's insisting he be traded. He
wants to deal Kendall Gill for the Warriors' John Starks, but Gill
says he will quit before he plays for P.J. Carlesimo. Then there
was a recent the on-court dispute with Scott Burrell, who was sent
to the table to report in with Eric Murdock, then recalled.
Calipari said he was sending a message to the players on the floor.
Burrell said, ``You're embarrassing us.'' The two players met with
Calipari before the Portland game. ``I'm not going to say it's not
a problem,'' Murdock said.
</P>
<P>
   BULLS COACH OPTIMISTIC
</P>
<P>
   Tim Floyd on whether the Bulls can compete this season: ``I'd
prefer not to talk about our talent. In terms of it, it's the best
I've ever coached.'' Guess that means the Bulls definitely get to
the Sweet 16. ... Indiana's Mark Jackson has been doing that goofy
dance again and coach Larry Bird isn't pleased. ``He is back to
doing his shake. I don't like that. We talked about it. And I
didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
