<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-WESTNOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Years of solid production garner respect, says Malone
 &HT;    By Jeff Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Antonio McDyess got two technicals and was ejected
during Denver's loss at Utah. That made the young forward wonder
when he will get the respect shown Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the message the ``Mailman'' sent: ``Ten years. And you've
got to produce for 10 years. And there's still people that are
going to test you. I've done it now for 14 years. Like anything
else, a lot of guys come in and say a lot of things, and the only
thing you can say to them is: years and production. That's what
gets it. You've got play a lot of years, and you've got to produce
all those years.''
</P>
<P>
   McDyess may do it in nine years. When the Nuggets stunned the
Jazz Wednesday, he went 10-for-15 with 24 points. Malone, who was
5-for-13, had 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   `ADMIRAL' TAKES CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan of the David Robinson, this should lead your
personal newscast: Robinson dunks. Robinson pumps his fist.
Robinson dives for a loose ball? Yes, it's all true. Give teammate
Mario Elie the MVP. Robinson played like the David of young,
totaling 29 points, 17 rebounds, three steals and two blocks
against Olden Polynice and the Sonics. In the second half he didn't
miss a shot and had 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising play? He crashed to the floor early in the
fourth quarter to wrestle for a loose ball, getting a jump ball.
``That's a perfect expression of how badly someone wants to win the
game,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said. ``You couldn't make
something like that up. I hope somebody got a picture of that
because it will be hanging in my office.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie, who had been riding Robinson for his laid back ways,
``told him I want to see that every night. When your main player is
playing well, it fires you up.''
</P>
<P>
   A GRIZZLY DISPLAY
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver coach Brian Hill was livid with counterpart Butch
Carter in the wake of the Grizzlies' loss in Toronto. In the
closing seconds of the game, Hill, fuming, glared toward the
Raptors bench and touched a finger to his temple, as if to say,
``What are you thinking?''
</P>
<P>
   What infuriated Hill was Carter's decision to make substitutions
for Charles Oakley, Doug Christie, Kevin Willis and Vince Carter so
they could be acknowledged by the sellout Air Canada Centre crowd
of 19,800. Hill felt his team was being shown up. Asked about his
finger-to-temple display, Hill said, ``I'll remember this for a
long time.'' ...Grizzlies' general manager Stu Jackson says Bryant
``Too Big Country'' Reeves is ``getting there (in shape). He had
lost about 17 pounds by the time a lot of the stories came out
(about his weight) but he still has a ways to go. He has to be more
consistent and he has to work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLES AND TRIPLES
</P>
<P>
   As Jason Kidd goes, so go the Suns. When Kidd has a
double-double (three times) or a triple-double (four times),
Phoenix is 7-0 this season. When he doesn't, the Suns are 0-4. Kidd
has four of the five triple-doubles in the NBA this season and now
has 23 for his career, sixth all-time since the league began
keeping the stat in 1979. He passed Michael Ray Richardson (21).
Next is Michael Jordan (28). ...Suns center and former Chicago Bull
Luc Longley got a visit from Bulls owner and Arizona resident Jerry
Reinsdorf last week. Reinsdorf stopped by Longley's house to
present him with his 1998 championship ring. ``He thanked me for a
great job and wished me luck in my future endeavors with the
Suns,'' Longley said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
