<SLUG> BC-BKC-RUTGERS-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE RISES FOR MIAMI BUT DIMS FOR RUTGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Rutgers Scarlet Knights played one of their most
resilient games of the season on Saturday, although at the end they
had nothing to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   They fought back from a 17-point second-half deficit to come
within 3 points of the University of Miami on two occasions before
the Hurricanes held on, 68-63, in front of 10,494 people at Miami
Arena, the fourth-largest crowd in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Billet's basket in the last five seconds brought Rutgers
within 66-68, but Miami forward Tim James ended it with two free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Billet had a 3-point attempt blocked by James with 15 seconds
left that could have tied it for Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they'd be tough,'' James said. ``They are a quality
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Greer led the Scarlet Knights in scoring with 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers, 17-11 over all and 9-9 in the Big East, needed a
victory to feel better about securing a bid to the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament. Now the Scarlet Knights
must hope to be impressive in the Big East tournament, which begins
Wednesday at Madison Square Garden in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For Miami (21-5, 15-3), this was its eighth straight Big East
victory. If Connecticut is upset in Sunday's game with Syracuse,
Miami will win the No. 1 seeding in the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in with a three-game losing streak, Rutgers coach Kevin
Bannon chose to pull his two freshman regulars _ center Rashod Kent
and guard Dahntay Jones. Replacing them were the 6-foot-11-inch
Alvydas Tenys and another freshman, Billy Collins, making his first
start. Never mind that Kent, with .662 field goal accuracy, is on
target to break the school record for field goal percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The moves worked, as the Scarlet Knights got off to a good
start. Greer and Rob Hodgson clicked on 3-pointers to open the
game's scoring, and their defense forced Miami into missing its
first half-dozen shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes didn't score until 4 minutes 10 seconds had
elapsed, on a James jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team could muster much offense. With 8:18 gone in the
game, Rutgers clung to a 13-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Miami stayed close in part because of Rutgers' off-target
shooting, and the Hurricanes took their first lead of the game _ at
16-15 _ with 6:37 left in the half on Kevin Houston's free throw.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights promptly retook the lead on Greer's
turnaround jumper, but it was short-lived. Kent entered the game in
the half's last four minutes, but missed three of four free throws
as Miami built a 24-21 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Kent's dunk helped, but the Hurricanes scored 8 of the last 12
points to take a 32-27 lead into halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously for Rutgers, Billet, who came into the game having
made 38.7 percent of 610 career 3-point attempts, missed both of
his chances from beyond the arc in the half. And Rutgers made just
one free throw, against six for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes, meanwhile, had control at halftime without much
of a contribution from their two top scorers. James, a senior
likely to be chosen in the National Basketball Association draft,
had 6 points. Johnny Hemsley, who has been a consistent long-range
threat, was scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   That changed dramatically in the second half, as Miami began to
assert itself on the scoring of the James-Hemsley tandem. Hemsley
quickly had a pair of 3-pointers, while James contributed an
alley-oop dunk, a tip-in and a jumper.
</P>
<P>
   When the Scarlet Knights looked up, they were behind, 54-37.
</P>
<P>
   A 9-point run by Miami put the visitors in a major hole, but
they didn't roll over. With Miami up by 56-41, Greer sank a pair of
3-point shots to pull Rutgers within 9 points with 8:19 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights kept the pressure on, easing within 6 points
of their hosts before a pair of free throws by Miami center Mario
Bland and a James driving layup restored the comfortable lead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hodgson made four straight free throws and Collins sank
one of two to bring the visitors within 61-55.
</P>
<P>
   Kent fouled out shortly thereafter, with 7 points and 2
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a Hemsley's 3-pointer, the Scarlet Knights showed
great resilience. Billet's free throw with 3:27 left made it a
6-point game again. Then a free throw by Hodgson and Greer's drive
brought Rutgers within 3. The Knights could not get any closer.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Miami retired James' jersey, No. 40. The only
other Miami player to have his number retired is Rick Barry, who is
in the Basketball Hall of Fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
