<SLUG> BC-NY-FOREIGN-STUDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN STUDENTS DISCUSS CHALLENGES OF LIFE IN NEW YORK CITY AT
CONFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Expressing concerns ranging from finding jobs to
finding dates, foreign students from nine countries who attend 13
colleges and universities in the New York region met Saturday for a
conference at Hunter College on the opportunities and challenges
international students face in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was sponsored by Metro International, a nonprofit
group founded in 1977 to help build a bridge between foreign
students and New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to get them out of the classroom, and into the
city, so they have more than just an academic experience when
they're here,'' Margaret Shiba, the program's executive director,
said of the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The students, from Europe, Asia and South America, said they had
come to New York only to discover problems similar to those they
faced at home. Moreover, they said, few New Yorkers seemed excited
about meeting foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Sascha Jerrentrup, a student from Dusseldorf, Germany, led off a
discussion about racism in New York City. Here to study engineering
at the Stevens Institute of Technology in Hoboken, Jerrentrup, who
is white, said he was dismayed by the relationship between black
New Yorkers and the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised when I was in the subway,'' he said,
recalling an incident he had seen. ``There was this black guy just
taking a nap. Two white policemen were saying, `Is everything OK,
sir,' but you know the way it was meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerrentrup said the stereotype abroad is that racism in America
is confined to paramilitary groups hiding out in the Idaho hills.
But in his view, the recent shooting of an unarmed immigrant by the
police in the Bronx suggested far broader problems with race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image is of a melting pot where people from all
backgrounds can live together comfortably,'' he said, adding,
``It's a nice picture, but it's not the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants in another session, on language and culture, said
the fast pace of American life, and of speech, posed problems.
Several students said they found it hard to get involved in
conversations because people spoke so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   And several said that the internationalism of New York had an
unexpected downside. ``In New York, you could spend your whole life
never speaking English,'' said Elkin Urrea, from Colombia, who is
studying English at Hunter College.
</P>
<P>
   A student from Russia, Boris Baranov, who had traveled to the
Midwest, said he got less attention in New York. ``They treat us
more like immigrants'' than like visitors, he said of New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The students also spoke of the aggressive socializing in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Acton, an international student organizer at Teachers
College at Columbia University, described typical New York behavior
as going to a party and ``seeing how many people can I meet in a
night, whereas in other countries fun might be sitting down with
coffee and having a long talk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
