<DOCNO> NYT19990227.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1722 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURWITZ-LUMBER-HNS &LR;      02-27 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURWITZ-LUMBER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURWITZ REJECTS $450 MILLION REDWOODS DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn.: Calif.)  
(Eds.: Filed in ``a'' and ``f'' categories) 
 
By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pacific Lumber Co., the California logging
operation owned by Houston-based Maxxam, on Friday rejected a $450
million deal to preserve the largest stand of ancient redwood trees
left in private hands.
</P>
<P>
   The decision could well end an arduous, 2 1/2-year effort by
federal and California regulators to consummate an agreement with
Pacific Lumber and protect groves of redwood giants, some dating
back to the time of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made a last-ditch effort to salvage the
negotiations, calling Maxxam Chief Executive Charles Hurwitz from
Air Force One on Thursday to discuss the deal, White House
spokeswoman Amy Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president believes this deal would be the best thing for
the company, the American people and the environment,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Houston financier could not be swayed. Pacific Lumber
President John Campbell said late Friday the proposals as
structured would have forced the company to drastically reduce the
amount of lumber it produces annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company was willing to make substantial concessions had an
overall agreement been reached that left the company economically
viable,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell did not reject out of hand the notion of negotiating
further this weekend, although the likelihood of a turnaround at
this juncture seems remote.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, in a prepared statement
released late Friday, said: ``I am sorry that the Pacific Lumber
Co. has decided to walk away from the Headwaters transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this transaction would have been in the best
interests of both Pacific Lumber and the American public,'' Babbitt
added. ``I would have provided economic security for Pacific Lumber
by providing them with a road map for future harvests.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt vowed to vigorously enforce regulations to protect
endangered species that live in Pacific Lumber's woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., who had been instrumental in
getting the parties this close to an agreement, said, ``I am deeply
disappointed that an environmentally sound agreement to preserve an
incredible natural resource and help retain thousands of jobs in
the region has been rejected by the company.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the fate of Pacific Lumber's damp and misty
Headwaters Forest, acres of towering redwood trees that, if left
unprotected, could someday become backyard decks and hot tubs.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said the company had no immediate plans to begin
logging in the old-growth redwood areas. Pacific Lumber officials
plan to meet Monday to figure out where to go from here. The
company could resurrect litigation against the government, accusing
it of using regulations to unfairly take control of private
property.
</P>
<P>
   The state and federal proposals would have created a 7,500-acre
preserve in exchange for $380 million in federal and state funds.
Congress has authorized nearly $250 million for the federal share,
but that funding will expire Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The California Legislature also had agreed to provide $112
million more to purchase an additional 2,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Of that money, $450 million would have gone to Pacific Lumber,
with the remainder going to another company and to the local
community.
</P>
<P>
   But as part of an agreement to purchase the property, state and
federal regulators wanted to impose a series of restrictions that
would have regulated Pacific Lumber's timber operations on its
remaining 211,700 acres for the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   One key restriction would have barred the company from logging
within 100 feet of fish-bearing streams and within 30 feet of other
waterways on the property.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions also would have banned logging operations in 12
areas set aside as conservation zones for the marbled murrelet, a
rare seabird protected under the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   If Pacific Lumber were to violate these provisions, the company
would have been forced to pay 150 percent of the timber value for
trees cut down in the stream buffer zones and 250 percent of the
timber value for chopping down trees that serve as nesting areas
for the murrelet.
</P>
<P>
   Both California's Wildlife Conservation Board and Interior
Department officials approved the final sale proposals Thursday.
But the Maxxam and Pacific Lumber boards rejected them Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, which have battled with Hurwitz and
Pacific Lumber for years over the Headwaters Forest, expressed
disappointment at the company's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hurwitz would be very foolish to walk away from the table
at this point,'' said Jill Ratner, president of the Oakland,
Calif.-based Rose Foundation. ``The company is not going to get a
better deal. The areas that are off limits are not going to be open
to substantial logging, with or without this agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they'll keep talking, and I hope Mr. Hurwitz will come
to his senses,'' Ratner said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber has been cited numerous times in recent years for
violating California's rules governing logging. In November, the
company lost its logging license, forcing it to rely on contractors
to harvest timber.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental activists contend the company's record required
regulators to take a firm stance.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the California Department of Forestry and Fire
Prevention issued Pacific Lumber a conditional operator's license.
And Campbell, in a prepared statement, said the company is
determined to win back the confidence of regulators and the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not tolerate violations of forest practice rules,''
Campbell said. ``Every member of our compliance team has the power
to halt operations if there is a question or concern about
compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
