<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
A number of things topsy-turvy in this NBA season
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Dale Robertson
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The coach was as straight-laced and upstanding as a man can be.
The only thing shocking about him was the natural silver color of
his hair. He had dedicated his life to his profession, that of
teaching basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The player, on the other hand, is covered in tattoos, has his
body pierced in myriad places, maintains a lifestyle that would
make Bacchus, or the Marquis de Sade, blush and says his only
remaining goal is to play an NBA game stark-naked.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, given the times, the team eagerly hired the
player and immediately fired the coach.
</P>
<P>
   I love this game.
</P>
<P>
   We sort of knew Del Harris and Dennis Rodman weren't going to be
Phil Jackson and Michael Jordan, didn't we? Bill Clinton would have
been a better fit on Ken Starr's team than the Worm was going to be
on Harris' Lakers. So Harris became the NBA's first post-lockout
coaching fatality a dozen games into the league's weirdest season
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder what color Del's distinguished 'do would have turned as
he tried to rein in Rodman? Alas, we'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the Rockets will get their first up-close viewing of the
new-look Lakers on Sunday after a short detour through British
Columbia. They're returning to the Great Western Forum three weeks
and two days after unsuccessfully launching their long-delayed
season there. Amazingly, the abbreviated campaign will be
one-fourth gone.
</P>
<P>
   And we won't know a heck of a lot more about what they've got
than we did Feb. 5. The Rockets were one of the most turned-over
teams in the NBA at the outset, with seven fresh faces _ three of
them rookie guards. And their growth process has been uneven to say
the least, particularly since Charles Barkley lasted only five
starts before hobbling off with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   So if they can't be sure who or what they are, how can we
possibly expect to?
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley is potential star material. That we've seen.
Michael Dickerson might be, too. The Cat and the Doctor (M.D. _ get
it?) could be franchise anchors well into the future, although
they've both shown the consistency of a Rodman news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Bryce Drew, the other new kid, is as lost as he can be,
although, oddly, he's no more fogged in than third-year pro Matt
Maloney, who has played himself into oblivion as though he were
allergic to his fat new contract. See, money can't always buy
happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Rudy Tomjanovich's denials, it's obvious the point will
have much to say about where the Rockets are ultimately pointed.
One concerned veteran has mused: ``If we don't get that position
straightened out, we're wasting our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a number of the league's other would-be lords have
behaved more like laggards as well. With the aforementioned Lakers
and San Antonio scuffling along in .500 land, the reconstructed
Rockets aren't being trampled by a runaway pack. Tomjanovich can _
and does, readily _ contend that, because of all the changes, his
lads should still be stutter-stepping.
</P>
<P>
   Which, nonetheless, doesn't explain the disinterested effort of
Thursday night against the Hawks. That wasn't the result of a
chemistry problem. It was purely biological. The Rockets' heart
took the evening off.
</P>
<P>
   There's no surprise the early Finals favorites appear to be Utah
and Indiana. Had the Jazz started the season in June, it would have
been hitting all the right notes. Karl Malone and John Stockton
could come off life support and execute the pick-and-roll perfectly
straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   As for the similarly intact Pacers, they held the most organized
lockout workouts of anybody and were thus way ahead of the
competition on opening night. That they started a hesitant 4-3 was
a huge surprise, but a recent five-game winning streak indicates
they're beginning to build momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The goofiness seems to have given small boosts to dregs
Vancouver, Dallas, Denver _ all, unfortunately, Midwest rivals of
the Rockets _ plus Milwaukee, Philly and Toronto. The grandest
irony, of course, has been the first two teams to hit double digits
in defeats were the Clippers and the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Business as usual in the Clip joint; tragi-comedy in the
no-longer-United Center, where Chicago hasn't managed a victory in
six tries. The Sixers deep-sixed the Bulls by 18 in the ruined
temple Thursday night. Were this to be a full season, these poor
unlova-Bulls would be a serious threat to lose 72 games.
</P>
<P>
   With that dynasty in ruins, the '99 NBA race is a total
crapshoot, a phrase that also addresses the number of balls
clanking off rims from coast to coast. The pro game's offensive
elements never have been in a deeper funk, and it's not just
defensive dedication causing the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   But surely the Worm's return will make everything right again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
