u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     02-27 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Ward looks bound for minors again
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Fran Blinebury
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ For two years now, Daryle Ward has been the
Bigfoot of the Astros organization, an out-of-focus figure in a
grainy photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Man or beast or myth?
</P>
<P>
   Large footprints have been left at the Class AA and AAA levels
in Jackson (Miss.) and New Orleans the past two seasons, with Ward
hitting a combined .317 with 42 home runs and 186 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet so few outside those minor-league outposts ever have had so
much as a glimpse of Ward, who was acquired by the Astros in
December 1996 as part of the package that also brought Brad Ausmus,
Jose Lima, Trever Miller and C.J. Nitkowski from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks with the big club a year ago when Jeff Bagwell was
sidelined with a laceration in his right knee and only four plate
appearances as a pinch hitter. Then Ward disappeared back into the
woods, where the gossip mill at times turns him into a legendary
figure among radio talk-show callers.
</P>
<P>
   Big stick, big power, big future. Or big bust?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably just not a fit on our ballclub,'' Astros general
manager Gerry Hunsicker said candidly.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is Ward _ at 6-2 and kindly listed at only 230
pounds on the roster _ is big, too big, to be considered much of an
athlete anywhere but at first base or in the batter's box. And the
Astros, of course, are well-situated with Bagwell on the right
corner of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   There have been experiments with Ward in left field, and the
conclusion is as an outfielder he makes a decent first baseman.
Good hands. He'll usually catch what's thrown at him. But little
mobility to either direction.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Ward, 23, is an American League player trapped
in a National League organization, a prospect whose only future to
make a real impact in the game is likely as a designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question at all in my mind or in most of the
people in our organization that this kid can hit at the
major-league level,'' Hunsicker said. ``In truth, I like this kid's
bat better than I like (Mitch) Meluskey's. And you know what we
think of Meluskey, since we traded away our starting catcher from
the last two years and are giving him a chance to win the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's problem is actually twofold. Bagwell, of course, is going
no place, except likely on to another season of hitting .300 and
driving in 100 runs for the Astros. And Ward has failed to make
progress with his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daryle is a lot like Meluskey was in that his mindset is that
he's a good-enough hitter for his bat to carry him to the
major-league level,'' Hunsicker said. ``We've talked to him and
told him that wasn't going to be the case. Meluskey, it seems, got
the message. He worked hard to improve his defense last year, and
now it looks like he's ready to make a place for himself in
Houston. With Daryle, there hasn't been any indication of that kind
of development.''
</P>
<P>
   Which would seem to make Ward a candidate to be traded to an
American League team. Except each time Hunsicker might be tempted
to do that, he is reined in by his own philosophy, which has been
to make sure the front-line players for the two-time NL Central
champ Astros are backed up by sufficient depth.
</P>
<P>
   That point has been hammered home in the early part of this camp
with the loss of Moises Alou for the majority, if not all, of the
season with a torn ACL. What if Hunsicker had given in to the
temptation to ship young Richard Hidalgo to Toronto in order to
reel in Roger Clemens? Rather than a solid outfield lineup of
Hidalgo, Carl Everett and Derek Bell and the confidence they can
maintain, the Astros would be scrambling to patch a huge hole.
</P>
<P>
   It might be tempting to try to trade for a prospect who looks
like a better fit right now, but a significant part of a general
manager's job is to prepare for the worst. So Ward waits,
impatiently, maybe less than fairly. He is like infielder Russ
Johnson, capable of playing for somebody in the majors but needed
as insurance for a team that wants to contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one significant injury (to Bagwell) away from him being
a factor on our team,'' Hunsicker said. ``It's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A year from now, the Astros will move into the Ballpark at Union
Station. With a cozy (315 feet) left field and grass, the balls
down the line that would now go by Ward on the turf at the
Astrodome for triples might well be playable.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, top 1997 draft pick Lance Berkman will probably be
ready to take a spot in the outfield next season.
</P>
<P>
   Which would leave Ward's future with the Astros right back in
the same spot, like Bigfoot, out of place, out of focus, out of
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
