<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 AILING KNICKS HAVE NO TIME TO REST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Mich. _ Of all the New York Knicks, Patrick Ewing
looked as fresh as a blossom next to his withering teammates Friday
night in Boston. This aging center with knees as worn as bald tires
was still standing after logging 82 minutes of playing time in a
48-hour stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He was the lucky one. Charlie Ward was gathering his things in
one corner of the locker room, holding a chunk of ice over the
blood-shot, swollen right eye he received from a finger poke in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Larry Johnson was grimacing from tendinitis as
he slipped on his left shoe. Behind a door, Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy was alternating sweats with chills while being treated for a
stomach flu after the Knicks' 94-80 loss to the Celtics in Boston,
a defeat that came 24 hours after the Knicks' overtime victory
against visiting Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there is no rest for what ails them.
</P>
<P>
   The fire drill continues with an afternoon game against the
Detroit Pistons on Sunday. Instead of sleeping in Saturday, the
Knicks taped themselves up and practiced for a game that will mark
the beginning of their first three-games-in-three-days stretch of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way the NBA is today,'' Ewing said. ``You have to
suck it up to win. You can't worry about being tired. If you have
to play, you have to play.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks (8-4) have to use rubber bands and paper clips to
hold themselves together for this next exhausting push, that's what
they'll do to keep pace with the rest of the Eastern Conference.
Other teams have already begun to experience the grind of the
unrelenting schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Knicks have had it easy. In their first 12 games,
only five were on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Once away from home, the Knicks have struggled. Three of their
losses have been away from the cozy comfort of Madison Square
Garden. And in those three defeats, the opposition has made a
mockery of the Knicks' league-best defense. Orlando, Cleveland and
Boston all walked away with 90-point games and double-digit
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find a way to change that pattern,'' Marcus Camby
said. ``We've been playing excellent at home, but we haven't been
able to do it on the road. Sunday, it's like a must-win game for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   To start their dreaded three-games-in-three-nights tour with a
victory, the Knicks have to cut the common threads of their three
road losses.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, they have been out-rebounded and have averaged 19
turnovers per loss. Second-chance points and mistakes have been
their undoing. In a season as fatigue-inducing as this one, a
talented Knicks team that relies on outworking opponents to win is
particularly vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said it the other night, we get away with things out there
because of our talent,'' said Chris Childs, referring to how the
Knicks beat Minnesota even though they were badly out-rebounded.
``But if you just have talent against a team that outworks you,
you're not going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons have been suspect in their work habits, a fact that
has irritated Grant Hill. After a week of bickering,
finger-pointing and a five-game slide _ which included a dreadful,
78-69 loss at the Garden on Feb. 15 _ the Pistons have soothed
their dysfunction with four victories in their last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the ball better and leaning on Joe Dumars more, the
Pistons are just waiting to make amends for their sloppy effort
against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Only Hill, who scored 31 points, hit double figures for Detroit.
Back then, the Knicks had a healthy glow about them. Now, that has
faded. One look at Johnson will tell you.
</P>
<P>
   After a 22-point effort against Minnesota on Thursday, Johnson's
tendinitis flared up in Boston and left him nearly frozen on the
court. He scored only three points and revealed how this tug-of-war
with his knee could last all year. He has been healthy one day,
hampered the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope not, but it was a problem this time,'' said Johnson,
who shot 1 of 5 against Boston. ``It was more when I sat down after
the initial start of the game. I was loose to start out with, but
once I sat down, I couldn't move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially frustrating when you lose like we did to
Boston. If you win, it's all right to have a tough night. When
you're losing, you really want to help your team. I've got to do
what I've got to do. I've got to fight through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his teammates will start that fight Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
