<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO FIGURE OUT THE BOND MARKETS IS GIVING EXPERTS FITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the strange things happening in the financial markets,
the recent behavior of interest rates is perhaps the weirdest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After January's Consumer Price Index reading last week showed
the 12-month inflation rate at only 1.7 percent, the 30-year
Treasury bond yield spent most of this week heading for heights not
seen since last summer. Although inflation is nil, those seeking
haven in the safest security known to humankind have begun
demanding an inflation premium way out of line with what current
reality would seem to require. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you accept the textbook theory that the natural rate of
interest is 3 percent, which is the return investors would require
in the absence of any inflation, the purchasing-power protection
being demanded lately by long Treasury investors is remarkable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What makes it all the more remarkable is how the prospect of
deflation is starting to seriously focus the minds of increasing
numbers of economists, financial analysts and pundits. After an
entire generation has come of age conditioned to fear inflation,
the world suddenly finds itself increasingly anxious over the
possibility of declining prices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those with vivid memories of deflation's destructive power are
those old enough to have experienced its consequences during the
Great Depression of the '30s. More than six decades later, most
still shudder when they ponder those bad old days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While deflation remains a question mark for the long term, the
short-term consequences of a slumping bond market mean trouble for
the stock market because bond prices and rates move in opposite
directions. As bond prices fall, the rising yield makes them more
competitive with stocks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a veteran money manager told The Wall Street Journal this
week, either bond prices have to go back up, which will bring
yields back down, or stock prices will go down. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since inflation shouldn't be a cause for concern, what is
driving the bond market? Conventional wisdom apparently holds that
stronger-than-expected U.S. economic growth late last year is
responsible. With the economy so hot, analysts say, it's unlikely
the Federal Reserve will act to further reduce interest rates even
though most of the rest of the world is struggling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Friday's revelation of a fourth-quarter growth pace for
the U.S. economy stronger than earlier estimated ignited rumors
that the Fed might even raise interest rates. This, of course, is
possible, but doesn't seem probable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given the fragile state of the global economy, such a move would
be psychologically devastating to world markets. The reason? It
would intensify fears of deflation because America is the only
engine of growth for many of the world's most depressed economies.
Any Fed policy move that would diminish U.S. demand for foreign
goods would be seen as a threat to global economic stability and a
contributor to further risk in countries already on the
deflationary brink. Adding to such worries is a rising trade
deficit, which raises political barriers to sound economic
policy-making. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other words, all the economic variables have converged at one
of those confounding junctures guaranteed to give market experts
fits. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
