<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNEY-PRISONER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA COURT WON'T LET PRISONER DISCONTINUE DIALYSIS TREATMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerrell Brown's kidneys are shot. So is, by a psychiatrist's
estimation, his tolerance for life-saving dialysis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as an inmate in a Des Moines jail, Iowa's high court ruled
Friday, he can't just quit. At least not yet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jailers can now require Brown _ by force, if necessary _ to
submit to the dialysis treatments that filter toxins from his
blood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Brown refused to be taken from the Polk County
Jail to Iowa Lutheran Hospital. His keepers challenged that refusal
in court, but a district judge Thursday ruled he could not be
forced to take the treatment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday the Iowa Supreme Court agreed with the jailers, issuing a
temporary order allowing forced dialysis at least until a hearing
that is scheduled March 16. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old Brown, meantime, has remained short of precise
in explaining why he wants to stop dialysis. Without it, his
doctors say, he'd likely be dead within a week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is not at all concerned about death,'' said Des
Moines psychiatrist Michael Taylor, who spoke with Brown at length
before testifying that the inmate understood the choice he was
making. ``And he's not trying to kill himself....He is tired of the
situation he's in.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been in jail since his arrest on a felony crack
cocaine charge since Dec. 16. His trial has been scheduled April 12
and his bond placed at $36,000. If convicted, he could be sentenced
to eight to 25 years in prison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If he lives that long. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chronic high blood pressure ruined Brown's kidneys. He had been
undergoing dialysis treatments for a little over a year before his
arrest. He needs three to four hours of dialysis three times a week
to stay alive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As usual on Monday, deputies transported him from the jail to
the hospital on Monday in handcuffs and leg shackles wearing a
prison-issue green jumpsuit. But when guards came for him on
Wednesday, he refused to go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a culmination of things,'' said Tom Berg, the attorney
assigned to represent Brown in his dialysis fight. ``It's a
multitude of factors.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside jail, about 200,000 Americans rely on dialysis. And
sometimes, especially when their overall health deteriorates, they
quit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Association of Kidney Patients, 7
percent of patients 65 or older voluntarily end their dialysis each
year. But in Brown's age group, only 0.7 percent of those between
20 and 44 years old choose to stop their treatments each year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said Brown had only missed an occasional treatment before
being locked up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue with him was that he was not trusted to go to
dialysis on his own,'' Taylor said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In jail, of course, that responsibility was not his, but that of
his jailers. ``He understood that,'' Brown said. ``He just didn't
like it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also said Brown felt humiliated by going to the hospital
under guard. The psychiatrist said Brown understands the great
danger of passing up treatment _ electrolytes build up in the body,
fluids aren't flushed, serum potassium causes irregular heart
beats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Polk County Attorney Michael O'Meara argued the state
has an interest in stopping inmates from killing themselves, in
part so they can try defendants on criminal charges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility to do everything we can to preserve
this person's life,'' O'Meara said. After the court order Friday,
Brown went to the hospital for dialysis without resistance. ``We're
still holding out hope that Mr. Brown, when he realizes the concern
people have for his welfare, will have a change of heart.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taylor thinks that is unlikely. He said Brown seemed unworried
what his death would mean to his wife or two pre-teen daughters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``His father passed away when Jerrell was in his early 20s and,
in his words, Jerrell `got over it.' He felt his daughters would
`get over it' as well,'' the psychiatrist said. ``The most notable
thing about talking to him is his amazing lack of concern about the
whole situation.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
