r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AARP-IMAGE-KAN &LR;      02-27 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AARP-IMAGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSING AN IMAGE PROBLEM, AARP DITCHES FULL NAME IN FAVOR OF
ACRONYM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Steve Rivkin turned 50 two years ago, an irksome little
letter landed in his mailbox. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He'd had an inkling it would show up. When it did, he looked at
it with contempt and then tossed it unread, unopened, into the
trash. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It read: ``Dear friend, forget everything you've heard about
AARP being just for retired people. That couldn't be further from
the truth. As a matter of fact, life is just beginning at age
50.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rivkin, the president of a marketing firm in New Jersey, agrees
with the life-at-50 statement. But to him and three out of four
other baby boomers who have turned 50 since Jan. 1, 1996, AARP
might as well mean RIP. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though almost half of all Americans over 50 belong to AARP, only
one-quarter of eligible baby boomers do, 50 being the age of
eligibility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AARP officials, distraught and discouraged at being shunned by
the boomers, a few months ago changed its name from American
Association of Retired Persons to just AARP. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning behind the shortening? To lose the word
``retired,'' because people hardly ever retire at 50. In fact, many
boomers expect to work well past ``retirement'' age of 65. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've listened to people say that AARP is rocking chairs and
old retired people,'' said Carola Wilson of AARP. ``People in their
50s think, `AARP isn't for me, it's for my parents.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But changing its name to AARP instead of something that embraces
boomers and still appeals to existing members might go down as one
of the biggest marketing bungles ever, some experts say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Their solution to the problem made it worse,'' says marketing
expert James R. Rosenfield, a member of AARP. ``There's only one
good explanation for creating a solution that makes the problem
worse _ being stupid and myopic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he continued, ``AARP is the world's worst acronym _ it
sounds like a dog barking, like aarp, aarp!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For AARP, there's a lot at stake. Since Jan. 1, 1996, almost 7
million boomers have turned 50. By the end of 2014, all 78 million
boomers will have hit the big five-oh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But just because they're 50-plus doesn't mean they'll act like
it. Many boomers seem to have developed a sort of
Peter-Pan-into-perpetuity complex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Face it. Have Americans ever seen so many retain-your-youth
products and procedures proliferating over the airwaves, in
magazines and in newspapers? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plastic surgery procedures are more popular than ever. Sales of
skin creams, cosmetics, suntan lotions, hair-coloring products and
vitamins are exploding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of these attitudes, Hallmark has developed birthday
cards like the one that reads: ``It's your 50th birthday. Party
like two 25-year-olds.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of the I-don't-want-to-grow-old attitudes
abound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One recent survey found that the typical boomer believes old age
begins at 79. And as an article in /{American Demographics/} notes,
boomers will ``push the threshold of the traditional `mature'
market into older and older age groups.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some boomers in the 30-plus crowd already reject the term
middle-aged _ they're not middle-aged, they insist, they're just
mid-youth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AARP-alternative organizations are popping up, many on the
Internet. One, the National Association of Baby Boomers, or NABB,
touts itself as the antithesis of AARP. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To quote: ``In many respects, we stand in direct opposition to
the points of view espoused by the American Association of Retired
Persons. NABB intends to become an advocate for members of our
generation. We wish to preserve the caliber of our lives.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson of AARP insists its organization is relevant to
boomers and many others over 50. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we're looking to expand our benefits and have the
most up-to-date offerings, the kinds of services that boomers will
be interested in,'' Wilson said. ``Already, we have a lot that we
think can be helpful to boomers like discounts, tips on healthy
living and caregiving.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But even its own marketing puts the negative before the
positive. For instance, one AARP mailing reads: ``Experience tells
us this may not be the most welcome piece of mail you ever
received. Just one of the most useful.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then there's that pesky acronym, says Rivkin, who
specializes in analyzing and creating corporate names. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rivkin says AARP chose the same dubious route that Kentucky
Fried Chicken did when it rechristened itself KFC to get away from
the fear-of-fat word, fried. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they're going to camouflage themselves and get away
from an inappropriate name,'' Rivkin said. ``But in our language
all of us grow up understanding that initials stand for something,
so we begin translating backwards.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rivkin points out that GE, AT&AMP;T and IBM successfully made the
transition from a full name to a set of initials, ``but it took
literally years and billions of impressions.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And while Tom Otwell of AARP insists people refer to the
organization by its individual initials, Rivkin doubts that
assertion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A. A. R. P. has four syllables, AARP one,'' Rivkin said. ``And
not a very pleasant one _ it's very guttural, not at all soft.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The solution, Rivkin said, should have been something entirely
new. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been a new name with a new identity,'' he said.
``That's the real answer, not a masquerade of initials.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Scott Aylward, president of advertising agency
Barkley Evergreen &AMP; Partners in Kansas City, isn't surprised by
boomers' aversion to AARP. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're selling a product that people want to be in denial
about,'' Aylward said. ``Probably nothing that happens to you when
you turn 50 makes you feel older than when you receive that
letter.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 1728EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
