r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVENTOR-CELEBRITY-KA     02-27 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVENTOR-CELEBRITY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTOR BECOMES CELEBRITY BY BUILDING SMALL TRACTORS FROM
SCRATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Kan. _ The road to glory is pocked with unexpected
terrors that strain both wisdom and resolve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Dennis Franz, a lifelong resident of this one-time cattle
town north of Wichita, faced such an ordeal in 1988 when the pilot
light in his steam-powered car burned out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The danged thing just wouldn't relight,'' said Franz, 55, a
very large and powerful-looking man known in Newton for building
all manner of odd and wonderful things, particularly very small
tractors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pilot-light disaster happened on Independence Day that year,
as Franz neared 12,000 feet on the side of Pikes Peak in Colorado. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was driving a perfect reproduction of a Stanley Steamer, an
old-time automobile. He had built the car from scratch, working 40
hours a week in his spare time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now he was testing his creation in the famous Pikes Peak auto
climb. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But everything went wrong,'' he told his hometown newspaper,
/{The Newton Kansan/}. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``An absolute and perfect fiasco,'' he added last week. ``The
car boiled over, the battery went dead, and then the pilot light
quit on me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all depressed,'' said Franz's middle daughter, Robin
Gay. But at that dark moment she struck a match to her father's
heart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let the mountain beat us,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Franz, who has spent his life solving mechanical problems, was
so moved by her words that he hauled it home, rebuilt it and headed
west again toward triumph. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back in August, and what a sight it was,'' Gay said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There was Dad, chugging up that mountain all alone, steam
billowing out of his car in the cold air. At the top, a crowd
gathered around clapping and cheering.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That applause ratified Gay's sense that her father was a most
unusual man, a link, no less, in the great chain of grease-covered
wizards who have long made rural America a breeding ground for
mechanical innovation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the idea for his steamer was born at a county fair in
1985, when Franz, who owns a heating and cooling business in
Newton, first saw an original Stanley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to make one of those,'' he told his wife, Rita, to
whom he has been married 35 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She was not surprised. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny's been building things ever since I met him,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When they met _ ` ``American Graffiti' time,'' Franz said _ he
was a high school dropout, a hot-rodding street racer with a
reputation as a brilliant backyard mechanic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the guy everybody went to when they had a mechanical
problem,'' said Rita Franz. ``People knew he made cars run good and
run fast.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By 1982, settled into family life, fast gaining respect as a
businessman, Franz redirected his excess energy and imagination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That year, using only his own design and scrap materials, he
built a 7 1/2-foot-tall grandfather clock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He sat down with a hand calculator and figured out all the
gear ratios,'' said Rita Franz. ``He taught himself the workings of
a clock train and made every part.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The clock now stands in foyer of the Franz's rambling red-brick
home. Every hour on the hour it plays ``The Star-Spangled
Banner.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose that melody because it has a lot of notes,'' said
Franz, who made and tuned the clock's numerous tone rods. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``And then he built other clocks,'' said Gay. ``Lots of clocks.
We had clocks ticking all over the house.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such things seemed normal to Franz's three daughters, for when
they were children, he talked to them every night at supper about
his mechanical projects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see how excited he was by them,'' said Gay. ``He told
me once that he actually saw new ideas in his dreams.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On many evenings, Franz sat for hours reading the family
encyclopedia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem to matter which volume,'' Gay said. ``He's
interested in everything.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some 10 years ago, after completing a second Stanley-type car,
Franz, temporarily at a loss for what to do next, turned to his
wife. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to build /{something/},'' he said. ``Maybe I'll build
a scale-model tractor.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so in a moment of whimsy, Franz took the first step toward
an acclaim he neither wished for nor imagined. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' he said, ``I didn't know much about classic
tractors. I didn't grow up on a farm.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So he visited a nearby farmer who had a 1925 John Deere Model D
tractor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked it over, and knew I was seeing a year's work,'' Franz
said. ``It was hard to make that commitment.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he did. And 2,500 hours later, after hand-fabricating
thousands of parts, he finished a perfectly detailed,
radio-controlled, three-eighths-scale model of a rural icon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'll never do this again,'' he thought when he
finished. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then he began building his second tractor, a
three-eighths-scale model of a classic Case. His third was a
one-fourth-scale Deere that weighs just 65 pounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Miniaturization confuses people, because it's done in three
dimensions,'' he explained. ``A one-fourth-scale model is actually
64 times smaller than the real thing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His tractors are about knee-high to an adult, and in 1991, on a
lark, he took his first tractor to the Kansas State Fair. And there
he became a true farmland celebrity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite their toylike size, Franz's tractors are fully geared,
working machines with astonishing power. They can pull pickup
trucks around like twigs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the state fair, his tiny tractor won a tug-of-war with a
large group of children, hauling them, squealing and laughing,
through a field of grass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That story was told and retold across Kansas and elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soon, to his delight and dismay, Franz discovered that he had
tapped into a thriving rural subculture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out that there are hundreds of antique farm-machine
shows every year,'' he said. ``I didn't know a thing about them,
and suddenly they all wanted me to come with my little tractors.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every year now, Franz receives scores of such invitations. He
accepts only a few. But when he does appear, he steals the day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the star of our show in 1997,'' said Winona Smith, who
helps run the annual threshing bee in the north-central Oklahoma
town of Fairview. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought us the biggest attendance we've ever had.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the fair's opening parade, Franz stood behind the bleachers
driving his tractors by remote control. Each machine had a doll in
the driver's seat, and the dolls seemed to be steering the tractors
and even changing gears. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 15,000 people there, and they were all stunned,'' Smith
said. ``When Dennis did his tug-of-war challenge with the kids, the
crowd was so thick you couldn't see him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But children are not his only fans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Old farmers, real machine experts, stood around his models in
total awe,'' said Oma Gay Nichols, another Fairview fair planner.
``Dennis does amazing work, perfect down to the finest detail. He's
a kind of genius. It's hard to fully appreciate what he does.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's something Robin Gay has heard all her life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's mind is like a wheel constantly spinning to create
things,'' she said. ``He never gives up. He just seeks new
answers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask why he does it, all I can say is, why does an
artist paint?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
