<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOCMEETING28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC scandal: 10 more accused members get chance to respond
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The second batch of International Olympic Committee
members implicated in the Salt Lake City bidding scandal will have
a chance Sunday to defend themselves against charges that they
improperly accepted extravagant gifts and perks during the city's
campaign to win the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's six-man inquiry commission began meeting Saturday
behind closed doors at IOC headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland,
to review allegations involving 10 members implicated in a report
issued Feb. 8 by an ethics commission in Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The report identified 24 members, but 14 already were named by
the IOC commission in late January. Four of those have resigned,
five have been recommended for expulsion, and one was issued a
warning. One died before the investigation began.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is expected to make its ruling on the other
three, whose cases were not closed in January because the IOC said
further investigation was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the meetings will come Sunday when accused members
will be allowed to appear before the commission, which recommends
what action to take.
</P>
<P>
   Theo Chapman, an IOC spokesman, said Saturday it was unclear how
many members would appear in person. Some have responded to the
allegations in writing.
</P>
<P>
   They sometimes have a tendency to just show up at these things,
Chapman said as the commission convened at the IOC's Chateau de
Vidy complex on the banks of Lake Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, led by Canadian IOC member Dick Pound, also
intends to begin reviewing reports by former bidding committees
that may contain further instances of improper conduct by members
dating back to the campaign for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said it has received responses from nearly all the
28 letters it sent to national Olympic committees and former
bidding groups. IOC officials expect to receive its report on the
Atlanta bid from the U.S. Olympic Committee on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Former officials from four of the six cities _ Atlanta, Athens,
Toronto and Manchester _ that bid for the Centennial Games have
indicated that their reports would contain no new allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Salt Lake ethics panel reported that the IOC
members or their families benefited from more than $1.2 million in
cash, travel, medical care and other improper inducements. There
were 115 IOC members in 1995 when Salt Lake was selected to host
the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 new members implicated last month have been asked to
respond to the allegations before the commissioners recommend what
action to take.
</P>
<P>
   Members are being given the opportunity to appear before the
commission or to send their information in writing to defend
themselves, Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only one member _ Australian Phil Coles _ has indicated
that he intends to appear in person. Coles was named in the Salt
Lake report as making excessive visits to Salt Lake during the
city's campaign for the 2002 Games, Chapman said. Coles, who
arrived in Lausanne Friday, has denied he did anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that even more names will surface when the
commission reviews the responses from the former bidding cities.
</P>
<P>
   Since the IOC has vowed to clean house definitively at its
special session in two weeks, the Pound commission intends to
finish its work Sunday and report immediately to the IOC executive
board, which is expected to take action as early as Monday. The
board can vote to expel, warn or exonerate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
