<SLUG> BC-VETERAN-MEDAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN OF WORLD WAR I RECEIVES FRENCH HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Born 103 years ago in the Missouri Ozarks and reared without a
formal education, Lee Otis Owens didn't grow up thinking he'd see
France from the seat of a horse-drawn wagon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he know that France, the country he helped liberate in
World War I, would one day bestow on him its Legion of Honor
medal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happened Friday at American Legion Post 199 at
7942 Leavenworth Road, Kansas City, Kan. Octave Merveille, an
honorary French consul, pinned the medal on Owens' maroon suit
jacket. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed that I could be this important,'' Owens said
before the ceremony as television camera crews set up their
equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Owens is one of several veterans in Kansas and Missouri whom
Merveille, of Mission Hills, has been honoring on behalf of French
President Jacques Chirac. Chirac recently began a campaign to honor
surviving members of the U.S. Armed Forces who fought in France in
World War I. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Merveille also traveled to St. Joseph to honor
103-year-old veteran Arthur Cook. Last weekend, Merveille pinned
the honor on three veterans in southeast Kansas. Today, he plans to
go to southwest Kansas for three more ceremonies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And last Veterans Day, the deputy consul of France, Jean-Pierre
Tutin, presented the honor to McKinley Wooden, 103, of Lee's
Summit, in a ceremony at the Liberty Memorial. Wooden died in
December. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like personally to thank Mr. Owens,'' Merveille said
in a brief speech at the American Legion post. ``I probably
wouldn't be here today if he hadn't (made his sacrifice).'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who was drafted, served in the Army's 89th Infantry
Division from Feb. 25, 1918, until June 5, 1919, seven months after
the war. In the war, which ended Nov. 11, 1918, he endured heavy
and frequent artillery fire in the Argonne Forest as he carted guns
and ammunition to the front line on a horse-drawn cart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After his discharge, Owens returned home to Alton, Mo., to work
as a carpenter. Nearly three decades later, his son, Eugene, died
fighting in World War II on the same soil Owens had helped
protect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't talk much about the war when I was growing up,'' Pat
Trower, Owens' daughter, said Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But when Owens moved to Trower's Kansas City, Kan., home 14
years ago, he began telling stories. They included one about the
Battle of the Argonne Forest, which reached its peak in the last
weeks of the war, resulting in 117,000 French and American
casualties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like an earthquake,'' Owens recently told his
daughter about Argonne. ``The whole ground shook. Bullets made a
sound like thunder over my head. I never thought I'd get out
alive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
