<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 DEPRESSING SEASON NOT WHAT GATLING HAD IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It started out so nicely. Chris Gatling,
the hometown hero who grew up only miles from the Meadowlands, came
into the season in great shape and great spirits. He talked of
winning the league's sixth-man-of-the-year award, of helping the
Nets challenge for the Eastern Conference title, of displacing the
Knicks as the metropolitan area's top basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   But after only 10 games of this depressing Nets season,
Gatling's tune changed dramatically. Gatling, no longer set on
trying to help New Jersey win the Atlantic Division title, wanted
out. He asked coach John Calipari for a trade a few hours before
the Nets (2-9) were defeated by Portland on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gatling, from Elizabeth, N.J., refused to comment on his trade
requests on Thursday and Friday, and he gave no indication before
the Portland game that he was disgruntled. Cordial with the news
media and jovial with his teammates in the locker room, he was
accepting of his decreased playing time, saying he would simply
have to wait his turn.
</P>
<P>
   While John Nash, the Nets' general manager, has said the club
will try to accommodate Gatling's wishes, Calipari brushed aside
the incident on Friday, almost implying that it was a non-issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gat and I have been on the same page,'' Calipari said. ``Guys
get disappointed when they're not playing, and I want guys to be
upset when they're not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatling has been playing, but only sparingly. After averaging
11.5 points and 5.9 rebounds in 23.8 minutes a game last season,
the 6-foot-10-inch forward's production and court time have dropped
considerably. He entered Saturday night's home game against Boston
averaging only five points and 3.9 rebounds in 16.4 minutes. Not
since he was a rookie in Golden State, during the 1991-92 season,
has he played so little. And even then, he averaged 5.7 points a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Every Nets player besides Keith Van Horn has suffered
statistically this season, but Gatling's numbers have been
unusually low. Gatling, a 55 percent shooter for his career, is
making only 36 percent of his shots this year. And with a season
high of 14 points, he has scored in double figures only twice.
During the five-game losing streak the Nets took into their meeting
with Boston, Gatling has averaged 4.6 points in 12 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   While Gatling, a 19-point scorer as an all-star for Dallas in
1997, is apparently disturbed by his lack of playing time, he is
largely to blame for it. In Tuesday's loss to the Knicks at Madison
Square Garden, Gatling played only eight minutes. But that was more
because of his five fouls than because of Calipari's refusal to use
him. With Rony Seikaly ailing from ligament damage in his right
foot, and the Nets' offense struggling badly without a low-post
presence, Calipari needed Gatling on the floor. But he picked up
three fouls in just four minutes of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Calipari, who brought Gatling to the Nets two years ago in a
nine-player trade with Dallas, said Gatling's trade requests would
not make him wary of playing him in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a professional,'' Calipari said. ``He understands it's in
his best interest to play well. I've known Gat for a long time and
I asked for him to be in the trade when we did the trade. And every
time he steps in the game, where's the ball go? To him. I know and
have great confidence in his game.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the hours following Gatling's trade request, Calipari
used him only 11 minutes against Portland. And foul trouble was not
the problem, as Gatling had only two. Gatling has asked for trades
before and not always during times of struggle. After the Nets
played well in losing to Chicago during last season's playoffs,
Gatling said he wanted to go to a new team.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of his mood swings and seemingly changing heart, Gatling's
teammates have viewed the request as an emotional response to a
troubling situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
