<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFEREES-PEACEMAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHEERING FOR THE MAN WITH THE WHISTLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RALPH KEYES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some kids collect stamps. Mine collects whistles. David's
friends buy Tommy Hilfiger's latest. He gets the newest style of
referee jersey. His younger brother writes fan letters to Steve
Young. David corresponds with Esse Baharmast.
</P>
<P>
   Like Baharmast, my son is a soccer referee. He has wanted to be
a referee since he was 5 and he and his friend Billy would blow toy
whistles and ``make calls'' on each other. At 19, David has a real
whistle in his mouth: a Fox 40. He's refereeing professional soccer
games, and couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no word I can find that adequately describes the
pleasure I get from being a referee,'' David once wrote. I
appreciate that sentiment but don't get it. It also complicates my
life.
</P>
<P>
   There's no model for relating to a son as referee. I knew how to
root for David when he was a pitcher, a place-kicker, a point guard
or a soccer midfielder. But how do you cheer for a guy in the
middle of the field with a whistle in his mouth?
</P>
<P>
   At 14, David took a 10-hour course to become certified as an
entry-level soccer referee. He already had begun working kids'
games in our local parks program. David nearly was lost to the
ranks of officiating when a coach cursed him as he worked his first
game. David has since come to realize that even as a
seventh-grader, he knew the rules better than this coach did.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually his skin thickened. Mine didn't. I don't enjoy
watching my son officiate soccer games. I can't bear the taunts of
``Come on, ref,'' ``Ref, you're blind'' and ``Call it both ways,
ref.'' I want to grab these cretins by the scruffs of their
ignorant necks and shake some sense into them. David just laughs
hecklers off. He says that one day when told to ``Call it both
ways!'' he's going to say OK and hold his arms out in both
directions.
</P>
<P>
   He is bothered only when he feels he has not reffed his best. To
get better he goes to referee clinics, is assessed by older
referees and seeks their counsel. David relishes the camaraderie of
the reffing community _ a beleaguered, misunderstood group _ and
idolizes its most prominent members.
</P>
<P>
   When the American referee Esse Baharmast was vilified unjustly
for a call he made during the World Cup, David wrote him an e-mail
of support. He already had written fan letters to other referees,
including one who invited him to be his guest at a Major League
Soccer game. There David got to engage in shop talk and banter in
the referees' locker room, then carry a clipboard onto the field as
if he was part of their crew. He was in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   David watches soccer on television as much in terms of
officiating as play. He knows the names of most of those blowing
whistles. If my son misses a game, his first question is not ``Who
won?'' but ``Who reffed?''
</P>
<P>
   Watching soccer with your referee son can be disconcerting. With
him at my side, it's hard to criticize the officiating. I always
figured that second-guessing referees was half the fun of being a
fan. Not when David's around. For one thing, he thinks my knowledge
of the rules doesn't match theirs. Even on judgment calls he won't
let me off the hook. ``How can you say that wasn't offside?'' he'll
ask if I protest a call. ``Were you in position? Don't criticize if
you don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   During his junior year of high school David spent a semester in
Costa Rica. Within weeks of arriving he had scouted up a couple of
games to referee. One erupted in a bench-clearing brawl. ``Don't
worry,'' he wrote us. ``I was perfectly safe. There was a security
guard at the park and as soon as it all began he wasn't trying to
break up the fight, he was right at my side. My friend Cuto also
told me later that he heard some players from the home team vowing
to protect me as well.''
</P>
<P>
   David's an athlete as well as a referee _ he was the captain of
his high school's soccer team and the place-kicker on its football
team _ but one who always has hated pickup games. ``Dad,'' he would
tell me as a child, ``they don't obey the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he is playing soccer for Earlham College in Richmond, Ind.
This is partly because he still loves to play, partly because he
thinks that playing will improve his perspective as a referee.
David recently began officiating games in the A-League,
professional soccer's highest minor league. I took him to one game,
in Cincinnati, then made myself scarce, watching my teen-age son
march onto the field lined up straight beside the center referee
and two linesmen. With their mottled green shirts, multicolored
flags and sober demeanor, the referees looked like medieval
jousters.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks earlier he had been the ``fourth official'' in an
A-League game between Cincinnati and Atlanta: handling
substitutions, calming the benches and standing ready to conduct a
shootout if two overtime periods did not break a tie. This was
almost necessary. When Atlanta scored with two minutes to go in the
second overtime, my son said he was the happiest man in the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   David's referee organization in Dayton, Ohio, has helped him
climb the professional ladder. It selected him as the male youth
soccer referee of the year for southern Ohio and has assigned him
increasingly difficult games to work, some involving players many
years his senior. This would make me a nervous wreck. My son the
ref thrives on that kind of challenge.
</P>
<P>
   In a way his perspective has changed very little since he was 5.
As far as David is concerned, he is on a mission. He is helping the
world become a better place by making it safe for soccer. ``All my
friends ask me,'' he once wrote in an essay for a soccer award, ``
`How can you like going out there and getting yelled at all the
time?' Until recently I didn't know what to reply. Now I think I
understand why it is that I love trying to keep 22 players from
killing each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always wanted there to be peace in the world. However,
when justice isn't done, there can be no peace. This is where I
fall in. As a referee I am the person responsible for making sure
that one group doesn't oppress another. We all want to leave a
legacy behind when we die. I'd like to be remembered as a
peacemaker. I won't do that in any negotiating room after a war. I
won't sit at my desk and speak through written words. I won't be in
a classroom lecturing on human brotherhood. I will teach peace and
brotherhood in the place I love to be most: on the soccer field.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
