A1752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES28-COX     02-27 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battles over 49ers, Redskins heat up
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last week proved again that, in the NFL, the
ruthlessness in the board room is often as nasty as the violence on
the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Denise DeBartolo York reminded her employees
in a lengthy memo that brother Eddie DeBartolo is to have no
involvement in the activities of the franchise. While he waits to
testify in the racketeering trial of former Louisiana Gov. Edwin
Edwards, the 49ers owner-in-exile is in limbo. He isn't likely to
be reinstated by commissioner Paul Tagliabue until NFL owners weigh
the ramifications of his testimony. York gave husband John York and
aide Keith Lenhart oversight responsibilities for the team.
</P>
<P>
   The events in the Bay area, however, pale in comparison to what
is transpiring in the increasingly contentious battle for the
Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Very quietly, potential owners Howard Milstein, Edward Milstein
and Daniel Snyder _ whose $800 million bid for the franchise was
accepted by trustees for the estate of the late owner Jack Kent
Cooke _ hired former 49ers director of personnel Vinny Cerrato as a
consultant. Imagine how awkward it must be for Redskins general
manager Charley Casserly and coach Norv Turner to have Cerrato
looking over their shoulders and evaluating player moves. The
hiring of Cerrato reinforces the notion Casserly, and possibly
Turner even at this late date, still will be fired if the new
owners are approved.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, league vice president of public relations Greg Aiello
confirmed last week the NFL has hired investigator Terry Lenzner to
check out the Milstein group. Lenzner is no stranger to
inside-the-Beltway intrigue. Lenzner was hired by President
Clinton's attorneys to aid in the Paula Jones and Monica Lewinsky
cases and was subpoenaed by special prosecutor Kenneth Starr to
explain his activities.
</P>
<P>
   There remains a core of owners, notably Jerry Richardson of
Carolina, who desperately want Cooke's son John Kent Cooke to
retain the 'Skins. Ironically, the Milstein brothers passed league
muster when they were bidding for the expansion Cleveland Browns.
Now there are questions about their ability to finance the Redskins
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Trifecta
</P>
<P>
   Not since Jim Plunkett (New England), Archie Manning (New
Orleans) and Dan Pastorini (Houston) went off the board at the top
of the 1971 draft have three quarterbacks been selected to start
the lottery. The trifecta is a longshot this year, but it could
happen. Cleveland figures to start the draft by taking Tim Couch of
Kentucky. Philadelphia has talked about Texas tailback Ricky
Williams with the second pick, but when Jim Haslett interviewed for
the head coach job, he told Jeff Lurie the team needs to groom a
young passer, and the Eagles owner now seems to be in agreement.
With quarterbacks mentor Andy Reid as the head coach now, Philly
might opt for Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida or Oregon's Akili
Smith. In Cincinnati, owner Mike Brown likes Georgia cornerback
Champ Bailey, but some Bengals favor taking Smith or Donovan McNabb
of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons officials will meet Monday with former New York Giants
quarterback Danny Kanell, but Gary Wichard, the agent for San
Francisco backup Jim Druckenmiller spoke last week with GM Harold
Richardson to gauge the club's interest in his client. It will not
be surprising if Kanell, who would welcome a chance to play for Dan
Reeves and learn from Chris Chandler, is signed by week's end. ...
Georgia Tech defensive end Nate Stimson, who wasn't invited to the
combine, is turning scouts' heads in personal workouts. Stimson
will play linebacker in the NFL. ... Look for new 49ers president
Bill Walsh to sign free agent quarterback Steve Stenstrom, who
played for him at Stanford, as a backup to Steve Young. The Niners
recently signed Jeff Garcia, who led Calgary to the Grey Cup in
1998, and he is being counted on to win the No. 3 job. ... In the
wake of the free agent defections of tackle Orlando Brown and guard
Wally Williams, Ravens left tackle Jonathan Ogden, a guy in a class
with Jacksonville's Tony Boselli, told agent Marvin Demoff to seek
a trade out of Baltimore. Contractually the Ravens can only keep
Ogden two more seasons. His deal stipulates the team cannot use a
``franchise'' label on him. ... Cincinnati will pay quarterback
Jeff Blake a roster bonus of $500,000 on Monday, meaning Neil
O'Donnell is history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
