<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTON-FARKAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE'S FARKAS FOCUSED ON NCAA CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Farkas readily admits that his ultimate goal is helping the
Boston College hockey program win its first national championship
since 1949. Advancing to the 1998 NCAA title game only to lose,
4-2, to Michigan, Farkas says, has only made him and the Eagles
more determined to take care of last season's unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a national championship before I graduate is my
biggest goal,'' said Farkas, a junior who leads the Eagles with 26
goals. ``We are really tight at this point in the season and I
think we are gaining momentum as a team right now. We have been to
the national championship game before so we know what it takes to
win. It is a special thing to be a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently third among Division I scorers in goals, Farkas is in
touch with his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to score 50 goals if my team is not going to win
and be successful,'' Farkas said. ``It's great to put the puck
through the net, but if the goals aren't coming, then a player has
to be disciplined enough not to let the rest of his game suffer and
hurt the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rated as the nation's top &UR;  &LR; high school recruit by The Hockey
News coming out of the Nicholls School in Buffalo in 1996, Farkas
chose Boston College over Boston University and Michigan State.
Since then, he has never put himself ahead of Boston College's best
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the Toronto Maple Leafs drafted the forward 57th
overall in the 1997 NHL draft, Farkas put that enticing possibility
on the back burner to concentrate on the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought of playing in the NHL is exciting, but I don't
think about it too often,'' he said. ``I prefer to concentrate on
playing well for B.C. There are a lot of great players here who are
helping me immensely and are making me look good and perform well.
I'm thrilled to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Maple Leaf officials, however, are paying close
attention to Farkas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a player getting better from year to year,'' said
Anders Hedberg, Toronto's assistant general manager. ``Jeff stands
out because of his speed and quickness and the dimensions of his
game. We had him rated a lot higher on our draft board and were
thrilled when he lasted to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps other teams were concerned about his size. When he first
arrived at Boston College, the 6-foot-1-inch Farkas weighed a
modest 160 pounds and was concerned whether his body could take the
daily pounding at the college level, competing against bigger,
stronger players.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer he stayed in Boston to work out and add more muscle
while maintaining his stamina. He now weighs a solid 185 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``His strength is a lot better because he put on a lot of weight
which has helped him immeasurably,'' said the Boston College coach,
Jerry York.
</P>
<P>
   Also, participating in the World Junior Championships for the
third consecutive year last December and January, has helped him
develop as a player. Farkas said that having to adjust to the speed
and wide-open offenses in international competition against the top
amateur players in the world has made him a more complete player on
the ice. York agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff has learned how to involve his teammates in the game,''
York said, ``and utilize the players around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the focus has shifted again to the NCAA tournament. Boston
College (19-11-4) is currently ranked No. 6 nationally. The first
round of the tournament begins March 26-27 in Worcester, Mass., and
Farkas, is pointing toward the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone gets what they deserve,'' he said. ``I feel some
pressure to perform at a high level because I want to come out and
be the best all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that puts more pressure on me, than that's OK'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
