<SLUG> BC-NY-SEIZED-CARS-510(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUNKEN DRIVERS MAY FIND COST OF RETRIEVING CARS PROHIBITIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Drivers whose cars are seized under the Giuliani
administration's new crackdown on drunken driving face such a long
and costly series of court battles to get their vehicles back that
many may simply decide to give up their cars without a fight,
defense lawyers said last week.
</P>
<P>
   They predicted that a driver who was arrested for the first time
on drunken driving charges, and whose blood alcohol level is barely
over the legal limit could expect to lose the car and pay up to
$1,000 in legal fees. But, judging by the way the authorities have
dealt with car seizures in the past, defense lawyers predicted that
the police may allow these drivers to buy their cars back, at their
trade-in value.
</P>
<P>
   The selling back of seized cars _ frequently done in drug and
prostitution cases _ is not official policy in cases of drunken
driving, but court officials speaking on the condition of anonymity
said it was likely to be an option quietly offered to first-time
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   But drivers who test far above the legal limit or who are
second-time offenders can expect to be mired in criminal and civil
court battles for more than a year, pay up to $10,000 in legal
fees, and lose the cars anyway. The lawyers said these drivers may
find it easier just to plead guilty and surrender their cars.
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure how the new system will evolve if it
withstands court challenges on its constitutionality. Some predict
that nearly all drivers will simply give up on getting their cars
back. Others predict an explosion in the number of drivers who
demand trials, a move that would cripple the city's already
overburdened court system and make the crackdown enormously
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But the most likely scenario, according to defense lawyers,
prosecutors and court officials, is that a two-tiered system will
develop. Wealthy first-time offenders who are willing to fight will
be able to buy their cars back from the police. But repeat
offenders and the poor will face such a drawn-out battle that they
will in essence be forced to give up.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell C. Ellman, a lawyer who specializes in drunken driving
cases, said the city faces enormous court costs if the crackdown is
carried out as strictly as Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has outlined.
Ellman and court officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity
predicted that the city would allow defendants to settle their
civil cases, in essence, by buying their cars back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is going to have to plea bargain on the civil side,''
he said. ``If even 20 percent of drunk drivers went to trial you're
talking about 1,000 cases. The city does not have the capability to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But city officials say they have the resources to carry out the
crackdown, cars will be taken away from first-time offenders and
they are not bluffing. ``The harm a first-time offender can do on
the road is the same as a second-time offender,'' said Daniel
Connolly, a special counsel in the city law department. ``If it
saves one life, anything that discourages people to drive drunk is
worthwhile.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For those accused of driving drunk, the problems begin with a
stark choice after being pulled over. If the driver refuses to take
a breath test, the driver's license is automatically suspended for
six months. And even drivers who do not take a breath test can be
charged with driving drunk and lose their cars based on how a
police officer assesses their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   If the driver takes the breath test, a blood-alcohol reading of
0.10 or higher will trigger his or her arrest and the automatic
seizure of the car. A lower score can lead to an arrest for driving
while impaired, a traffic infraction, but not the seizure of the
car.
</P>
<P>
   After a night in jail, the driver must appear before a judge, be
arraigned and most likely be told to return to court in a month.
Under the crackdown, the driver now has to resolve two issues
before regaining his or her car _ a criminal drunken driving charge
and the civil action the city has begun to seize the vehicle
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers said they would counsel clients to first resolve
their criminal cases. In one of the few pieces of relatively good
news for offenders, officials in district attorney's offices in all
five boroughs this week said that prosecutors were, in essence,
taking no position on the crackdown and would continue to offer
plea bargains in drunken driving cases.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Brooklyn and the Bronx currently allow first-time
offenders who are not involved in accidents and test at .15 or
lower to plead to the lesser charge of driving while impaired, a
traffic infraction.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan and Staten Island, drivers are allowed to plead to
the lesser charge if they test below .12 or .13. Queens prosecutors
said they evaluate each defendant on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, roughly half of the 4,970 people charged with drunken
driving in the city were allowed to plead guilty to the lesser
charge of driving while impaired, according to court records. But
Giuliani administration officials said they would still move to
seize the cars of people who plead to the lower charge.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers were split over whether they would advise their
clients to take the plea or demand a trial. Some said any guilty
plea would bolster the city's case in civil court that the car
should be seized. But others said it was more practical to take the
guilty plea and hope the city quietly allows first time offenders
to buy their cars back.
</P>
<P>
   A police official who spoke on condition of anonymity said that
the ``majority'' of the 1,800 cars seized last year in drug,
prostitution and cases of driving without a license ended in
``settlements'' where the defendants bought their cars back from
the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, the city lawyer, said the city will evaluate whether a
first time offender's car should be seized on a ``case-by-case''
basis. But he and the police official confirmed that the Police
Department has never had a car seizure case go to trial in the
past. Either the defendant gave up the car or the police agreed to
a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials who spoke on condition of anonymity and defense
lawyers said the city could adopt a zero tolerance policy, but the
cost would be enormous. Under a zero tolerance crackdown on drunken
driving, the number of civil actions involving cars filed by the
city could triple from 1,800 last year to nearly 7,000 cases.
</P>
<P>
   For now, most of the 22 drivers who have had their cars seized
appear to be waiting to see if the practice is declared
unconstitutional. As of Friday, only one driver, Pavel Grinberg, a
Polish immigrant from Staten Island, had filed a letter to the
Police Department demanding the return of his car.
</P>
<P>
   Grinberg, a first-time offender who tested just over the legal
limit during the first night of the crackdown, is the test case the
New York Civil Liberties Union hopes to use get the crackdown
declared illegal. Grinberg's lawyers are expected to go to court
next week to demand a court order barring further seizures and the
immediate return of Grinberg's brown 1988 Acura, his family's only
car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
