<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACKLEDE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hartwig no longer an afterthought on pole vaulting scene
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes you just know it's going to be your day.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeff Hartwig, it dawned on him when he clipped the pole
vault bar at 19-feet, 1/4 inch and it popped into the air, only to
drop neatly back into place. Hartwig took advantage of his good
fortune and never looked back, taking down his own American record
with a clearance of 19-5 Saturday afternoon at the USA Indoor Track
and Field Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was a weird deal,'' said Hartwig, smiling. ``That's
the first time I've ever hit the bar that hard, where I didn't put
my hand on it, and it popped right back down.''
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't all about luck.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Atlanta Olympics, former University of Tennessee
vaulter Lawrence ``LoJo'' Johnson was the talk of the event.
Hartwig was an afterthought, even though he made the Olympic team.
But ever since, Hartwig has been the preeminent American vaulter
and a factor on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   He was a model of consistency last outdoor season, enjoying 22
clearances of 19 feet or better _ including 15 straight at one
juncture. This indoor season he's cleared 19 feet in all six
outings, and needed to be at his best Saturday against a field that
saw four vaulters clear 19 feet and an impressive nine over 18-4.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwig has worked himself into a groove that likes of which
Tony Gwynn enjoys most baseball seasons. ``I feel like I really
have to screw something up not to jump 19 feet,'' Hartwig said.
</P>
<P>
   His season debuted smartly with an American record clearance of
19-4 3/4 at a vaulters-only competition in Reno, Nev. Next up is a
chance to raise the record again at the world indoor championships.
But before leaving the Georgia Dome, Hartwig made three attempts
Saturday at 19-8 1/4 _ the first of which was strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to make it,'' said Hartwig. ``Just a
little timing difference and I go over that bar.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his emergence the last two seasons, Hartwig credits the
arrival on the scene of Johnson _ a black vaulter who broke the
American record while a senior at Tennessee before the Atlanta
Games _ along with his frustration about not getting invited to
major meets in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you see a guy like Lawrence, who obviously has lot of
physical potential, guys are going to step back and say, 'Wow, who
is this guy?'' Hartwig said of Johnson, who finished third. ``He
pushes you. Then, I didn't make the world championship team (in
1997) and I couldn't get into the major meets. I was jumping well,
but in small meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to beg and plead to get into meets. Now, people are
looking at me as the guy to beat. I enjoy that, cause my confidence
is real high.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
