<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1766 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEGALA-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      02-27 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEGALA-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS-BRED BEGALA COUNTS WHITE HOUSE TENURE AS `EXTRAORDINARY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Come Monday, Paul Begala's toughest problem will be
figuring out how to pack the nine-point buck whose stuffed head
looms disconcertingly out of place in his cramped office in the
White House basement.
</P>
<P>
   Into a box it will go along with his photograph of Barbara
Jordan, his autographed picture of Mickey Mantle, the portrait of
his wife and three sons and the photograph of him holding a trout
he caught last year on vacation just after he learned his boss, the
president of the United States, had been lying to him and the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   Begala, 37, a boyish but scrappy Texan who grew up in Missouri
City, will be leaving his high-powered post as counselor to, and a
top spinmeister for the president to take a teaching position at
Georgetown University and write a monthly column for George
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to make a difference. I believe I've
contributed to a remarkably successful administration,'' said
Begala, citing accomplishments such as a balanced budget and more
teachers in the classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   His departure closes a political circle, bent more like a roller
coaster rail, and leaves the president without one of his most
ardent and earliest supporters. His tenure also is a meditation on
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Begala joined Clinton's presidential campaign in 1991 as a
political strategist with his then-partner James Carville, and
served as an unofficial adviser until 1995. He left for Texas after
a brief falling out with White House officials but returned with an
official appointment in 1997 just in time to help save Clinton from
the biggest scandal of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``To his credit, the president has apologized for the things he
did that set all this in motion,'' Begala said. ``That's all I can
ask. It's up to each individual to decide whether he or she can
find it in their hearts to forgive him. I have and for me it's
easier than most because of this debt of loyalty that I owe him.''
</P>
<P>
   A debt of loyalty?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Lord, look at me,'' he exclaims, arms wide. ``There's a
lot of able, talented, bright people in their early 30s who don't
get to go to work in the White House, who don't get to go to the
state dinner for the prime minister of Great Britain, or meet
Nelson Mandela or Vaclav Havel or Jacques Chirac or the pope
himself. The opportunities he (Clinton) has given me just have been
extraordinary. I can't ever repay him.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from others, such sentiments might seem disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   But Begala, who wears kangaroo-hide cowboy boots with his suits
and drives a decade-old Ford Bronco, displays such an earnestness
and enthusiasm, whether talking about the Texas Longhorns or the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is very old school, a very traditional sense of loyalty.
He's from a very traditional form of Catholicism. He has a very
kind of traditional view of the world,'' Carville said of his
former partner.
</P>
<P>
   Carville and Begala first met during the failed 1984 campaign of
Texas Democrat Lloyd Doggett for the Senate. Their informal
partnership lasted through Clinton's election when the eccentric
Carville emerged as a media star.
</P>
<P>
   David Begala, the oldest of five siblings who owns a
construction company in Houston and takes him hunting, calls his
brother a crusader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of Paul's nature is to be a champion of the underdog,''
David Begala said, referring often to his pride in his brother's
public service.
</P>
<P>
   The Begalas attended high school in Sugar Land, home of Clinton
nemesis Tom DeLay, the House majority whip. His mother and
stepfather now live outside of Dallas, and his father is moving to
a new home in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Begala should feel some kinship to the whitetail hanging
over his desk.
</P>
<P>
   From January through August 1998, Begala emerged as Clinton's
most public and most combative defender against charges of a sexual
affair with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   He jumped from talk show to talk show and absorbed shots from
the media as the most public face among the White House defenders.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated the president's denials of a sexual relationship
with Monica Lewinsky. He attacked independent counsel Kenneth Starr
as corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   But, Begala also joined the camp of advisers calling on the
president to apologize to the nation Aug. 17, the day Clinton
admitted to the affair and defiantly lashed out at Starr without
apologies to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But he stakes no claim to victimhood. ``I refuse to whine,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he does speak of the ``dark moments'' during the scandal.
Begala often could be seen around the White House at the height of
the scandal with his eyes puffy and red from lack of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   After the president's August confession, Begala took his wife
and sons on a two-week vacation in Wyoming. He shaved his beard at
wife Diane's suggestion. He withdrew from television appearances on
Clinton's behalf and pondered his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go through a period to arrive at a place where I
could forgive. But I know I made the right decision,'' Begala said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what the president did was manifestly wrong but what
others tried to do in response to that wrong was even more
outrageous because what they tried to do was attack the
Constitution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the White House and resumed his defense of the
president as Republicans attempted to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personal integrity is the essence of Paul,'' said Doug Sosnik,
also a senior adviser to Clinton, echoing the ``old school'' traits
voiced by Carville.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a boyish sweetness to him and a strong belief in right
and wrong,'' Sosnik said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Martin, chairman of Austin-based Public Strategies where
Begala worked from 1995 until 1997, recalled his ``almost childlike
excitement'' at the prospect of returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is one of the best shapers of a message of anyone I've
ever met, and the ability to do that in a campaign and under fire
is a rare talent,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   But, the high point of his career was not helping Clinton win
the presidency in 1992 but twice meeting Pope John Paul II, for
whom his eldest son is named.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States introduced me to the pope.
I'm a Catholic, and I try to live my faith. I certainly practice
it. There's just nothing professionally that can compare to that.
It speaks to why I have this abiding loyalty for the president. He
didn't need to do that. He didn't need to introduce me and say nice
things to the Holy Father. But he did,'' Begala said.
</P>
<P>
   He's leaving, not because of the scandal but because it's time
to move. He likely will be joined soon by other top Clinton aides
as the exodus that had been frozen by the impeachment trial thaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been unbelievably challenging,'' Begala said of the past
13 months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
