<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auburn's Ellis best coach; Arizona's Terry best player
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ March Madness is finally here but before we proceed,
let's hand out some regular-season awards.
</P>
<P>
   COACH OF THE YEAR: Despite last Wednesday's loss to Arkansas,
Auburn's Cliff Ellis gets the nod for winning the SEC championship
and getting the Tigers into the NCAA Tournament for the first time
since 1988. Honorable mention: Rick Barnes, Texas; Jim O'Brien,
Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER OF THE YEAR: 1. Jason Terry, Arizona: The Wildcat point
guard leads the Pac-10 in scoring (22 points a game), assists (5.6)
and free throw percentage (.865). He is a reason a team with five
freshmen in its rotation is ranked in the top 10. Honorable
mention: Elton Brand, Duke; Andre Miller, Utah; Mateen Cleeves,
Michigan State; Chris Porter, Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   TOP CONFERENCE: Big Ten, with seven legitimate NCAA teams
(Michigan State, Wisconsin, Purdue, Ohio State, Iowa, Minnesota,
Indiana).
</P>
<P>
   FRESHMAN OF THE YEAR: Corey Magette, Duke. Averaged 10.6 points
in only 17.3 minutes per game as a reserve on the nation's No. 1
team. DePaul's Quentin Richardson is a close second.
</P>
<P>
   TOP NEWCOMER: A tie between JUCO transfers Chris Porter of
Auburn and Steve Francis of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   MOST DISAPPOINTING TEAMS: Rhode Island, Kansas, Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   GAME OF THE YEAR: Princeton 50, Penn 49 on Feb. 9. Princeton
rallied from a 33-9 halftime deficit to win. Honorable mention:
Duke 92, St. John's 88 in overtime on Jan. 24 at Madison Square
Garden. It had the feel of a regional championship final.
</P>
<P>
   BEST COMEBACK: Texas, which went from 14-17 a year ago to Big 12
champions under first-year coach Rick Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   THE GRAPEVINE
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian State coach Buzz Peterson and Duke assistant Quinn
Snyder are the early favorites to replace Vanderbilt basketball
coach Jan van Breda Kolff, who is resigning after the season.
Peterson is a former North Carolina player and Vandy athletics
director Todd Turner is a Carolina grad.
</P>
<P>
   One hitch if the 'Dores want to hire Peterson, who led the Apps
to a 19-7 record this season. Peterson is tight with former Vandy
coach and Dean Smith assistant Eddie Fogler, now at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   While at Vanderbilt, Fogler's relationship with chancellor Joe
Wyatt was strained at best. Fogler may advise against a trip to
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Duke sophomore guard William Avery of Augusta says he would turn
pro if he is assured of being a lottery pick. Avery has had a great
season in his first as a starter but he is no lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC athletics directors have no plans to boycott Auburn
after that school's decision to buy its way out of a Sept. 2
football game with Florida State. But there is a very good chance
that a Florida State-Auburn basketball game scheduled for next
season will not be played.
</P>
<P>
   New Duke football coach Carl Franks, the former Florida
assistant, showed up at the right time. The athletics department
recently received a $5 million gift that will go toward a football
office complex and training facility.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL NEWS
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes from the football rules committee this week
was the elimination of all bandanas worn under the helmet. It may
seem trivial, but it became such a problem several years ago that
some of conferences on the West Coast passed a rule to ban them.
Turned out that some of the players were in gangs and using the
bandanas to show their colors. In a survey of coaches, 85 percent
said they wanted the bandanas eliminated, according to Georgia
athletics director Vince Dooley, chairman of the rules committee.
</P>
<P>
   The bandana decision is just part of an NCAA trend toward
consistency in the uniforms. This season, for instance, players
will have to wear jerseys tucked in their pants. No more cut-offs.
Next season, any hand pads or gloves must be gray.
</P>
<P>
   Former Alabama great Kenny Stabler has signed a three-year
extension
</P>
<P>
   on his contract as the analyst on the school's radio network.
</P>
<P>
   Ole Miss coach David Cutcliffe went back to work this week after
having his gall bladder removed.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State football signee Darnell Dockett, a defensive
lineman, will be eligible in the fall after making the necessary
standardized test score. The Seminoles are still waiting on three
others.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
