<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1768 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-NEXT-TRIAL-HNS     02-27 1573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-NEXT-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JASPER, WELCOME LULL WILL NOT LAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ When the fog lifted in the Piney Woods on Friday
morning, local churches were preparing for the weekend's
activities: a black history month celebration at Greater New Bethel
Baptist, where James Byrd Jr.'s family worships; a spaghetti supper
at St. Michael's Catholic, which has reached out to his killer's
ailing father.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden was relaxing after a chicken
soup dinner brought in by friends the night before, defense lawyers
C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. and Brack Jones were sleeping for the
first time in days, and Dan Rather was flying back to the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take a little time off,'' said Jasper County
District Attorney Guy James Gray, ``take my wife somewhere, hit a
few golf balls and drink a little whiskey.''
</P>
<P>
   He can because John William ``Bill'' King, convicted last week
of capital murder for dragging Byrd to death behind a pickup, is
headed to death row.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the television satellite trucks have abandoned
their spaces outside the Jasper County Courthouse and city workers
have pulled up the one-hour parking signs around the square, this
timber town of 8,000 knows the quiet won't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Byrd, 20, summed it up when a predominantly white jury
announced the fate of the 24-year-old racist who tortured and
killed his disabled father.
</P>
<P>
   ``One down,'' he said, ``two to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Still to go are King's high school buddy, Shawn Allen Berry, and
his former prison mate, Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., who will be
tried separately in the coming months for Byrd's kidnapping and
murder. Prosecutors are seeking the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, as word of King's sentence filtered down to
the courthouse lawn, Cribbs and Jones were asked what advice they
could give to the lawyers representing King's co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a job pumping gasoline,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back and go to med school,'' added an exhausted Cribbs.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday morning, Jasper's most famous lawyer, Joe Tonahill,
had some words of his own. Tonahill, who made his name defending
Jack Ruby, is retired now, but even if he hadn't already left the
courtroom behind, he said, ``I would have run away from these cases
as fast as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   And if appointed to represent one of Byrd's killers in the face
of the evidence stacked against them? ``I would have taken him up
to the top of the courthouse,'' he said, ``and told him just to
take a dive straight down, head first.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jasper woke up June 7 to find James Byrd Jr.'s dismembered
remains in the middle of Huff Creek Road, outside the gates to a
rural black cemetery, everyone started talking. Steven Scott
recalled seeing the 49-year-old black man the night before,
climbing into the bed of a gray pickup on Martin Luther King
Boulevard. Three white men, he said, were in the cab.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Berry, then a 23-year-old manager at the local
movie theater, was in custody, pointing the finger at King and
fellow white supremacist Brewer. Berry later led police to the
murder weapon, a 24 1/2-foot logging chain that had been cleaned at
a Jasper carwash and thrown into a shallow pit outside a friend's
trailer home.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Berry had his best opportunity to strike a
bargain and save his life. If he would testify against his
co-defendants, painting a picture that minimized his own
participation in the heinous killing, prosecutors said they would
recommend he be spared from the death penalty. Berry declined.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as the jury of 11 whites and one black convicted
King, Gray said his offer was permanently withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a chance, but that was before the DNA results came
back,'' the prosecutor said. ``No sir. A jury is going to decide
all three of these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry's defense attorney, Joseph C. ``Lum'' Hawthorn and
Brewer's court-appointed lawyer, Douglas Barlow, both of Beaumont,
had spent several days in the gallery, watching Gray and assistant
prosecutor Pat Hardy play their hand against King, and by
extension, against their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always to a lawyer's advantage to see a preview of the
evidence and to see the prosecutors before a jury,'' Barlow said.
</P>
<P>
   What they saw could be devastating to their cases: DNA evidence
linking all three suspects to the crime scene, Byrd's blood on
clothing and shoes found at their apartment, and numerous writings
by King, implicating his friends.
</P>
<P>
   King's genetic blueprint was found on a cigarette butt at the
crime scene and a drop of Byrd's blood was recovered from his
sandal, but the physical evidence against Berry and Brewer may be
even more solid.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Baechtel, a DNA expert with the FBI in Washington,
testified at King's trial that the victim's blood was found on
Berry's jeans, shirt and one boot from the apartment where the
suspects were staying, and Byrd's flesh and blood stained the
undercarriage of Berry's 1982 Ford pickup. Berry's DNA was on a
cigarette at the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   That evidence, along with Berry's statement to police, tools
engraved with his name discovered at the crime scene and extensive
tire track prints lifted from Huff Creek Road, doesn't bode well
for Berry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always conceded that he was there,'' Hawthorn said.
``He led police to the chain. It was his cooperation that led them
to King and Brewer. He was there, but he didn't participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot judge Shawn Berry by the evidence presented against
Bill King. Shawn Berry is nothing like Bill King, and anybody in
Jasper who knows Shawn or has heard of Shawn will tell you that.
His case should stand or fall on its own merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick DeGuerin, a veteran criminal defense lawyer from Houston
who is not involved in the Byrd case, agreed that the key to
defending Berry and Brewer will be in separating them from King.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can do that,'' he said, ``I don't think they have a
ghost of a chance of escaping conviction, but they might have a
chance to save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blame it all on King,'' DeGuerin advised. ``Berry came forward
first, and he's just a kid. He has a good chance of saying he was
afraid of King and was intimidated into this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, King was the ringleader. You've got to put it all
on him and say, `It's easy to see how Berry could have been
influenced.'''
</P>
<P>
   If that is the defense, Berry could have an easier time in his
hometown than King had, DeGuerin said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn agrees and has not sought a change of venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Jasper know him. They know his family, and they know
his reputation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At King's trial, prosecutors revealed some of the physical
evidence against Brewer as well. Baechtel, the DNA expert,
testified that Brewer smoked a cigarette and drank a Bud Light at
the crime scene. Byrd's blood was found on Brewer's tennis shoe.
</P>
<P>
   King's writings, including a note he passed to Brewer in jail,
also could be introduced against Brewer, 31. In the note, which
jailers intercepted and photocopied for prosecutors, King assured
Brewer that even though Berry had ratted on them, they would escape
the death penalty or die proud, as martyrs for the white
supremacist cause.
</P>
<P>
   DeGuerin said Barlow's challenge will be to distance his client
from King as much as possible, even though the two ex-cons belonged
to the same racist prison gang. ``Try to show that Brewer was
horrified by what King did that night, and shocked when King,
through his writings, tried to implicate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, that could backfire if Brewer responded to the
notes and incriminated himself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer is from Sulphur Springs and was unknown in Jasper before
the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be good for him if his case ends up in Jasper,''
DeGuerin said. ``He basically has a clean slate. You can re-create
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But DeGuerin said moving the case out of Jasper County, as
Barlow has requested, would be his first choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere in that town is, `We've got to redeem the name
of our town and prove we're not racists. The whole world is
watching,''' DeGuerin said. ``All three of these cases should have
been moved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gray is determined to keep the trials right here if he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a bombshell that dropped on our community. It could
have happened anywhere in the country, but it fell in our laps,''
he said last week. ``A horrible thing happened here, and we didn't
want to run from it. It's our responsibility to deal with it. We'll
take care of our own mess.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Byrd family will see that they do. ``We'll be here every
day,'' said Byrd's sister, Mylinda Washington. ``We'll do whatever
it takes to do this for our brother. He would do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington said it was extremely difficult to listen to the
testimony at King's trial, which was often so chilling and
disgusting that it drove some family members from the courtroom in
tears and made others physically ill. But she said her family's
religious beliefs and love for each other held them together during
the first trial and will see them through two more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm having a hard time, I just tell myself anything we've
been through is mild in comparison to the torture that my brother
suffered,'' she said. ``We can do this. We'll be here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 1859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
