voluntarily to a civilian government. That elected government,
which began in 1979 and ended with a military coup in 1983, was the
last time Nigeria had nonmilitary leaders. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LAGOS, Nigeria -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- NIGERIA-ELECTIONS-3,
2-27 -- Workers at a polling place in Lagos, Nigeria, examining
voter registration cards. Election officials in Nigeria have taken
strict precautions to prevent voter fraud during the country's
presidential election. Tens of millions of Nigerians cast ballots
Saturday to choose their next president, hoping to end a long era
of military dictatorship and to fulfill the promise of democracy
for Africa's most populous country. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) IKEJA, Nigeria -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- NIGERIA-ELECTIONS-2,
2-27 -- A supporter of Nigerian presidential hopeful Olu Falae of
the All Peoples Party (APP). Tens of millions of Nigerians cast
ballots Saturday to choose their next president, hoping to end a
long era of military dictatorship and to fulfill the promise of
democracy for Africa's most populous country. They will choose
between General Olusegun Obasanjo, a former military ruler trying
to regain power 20 years after relinquishing it, and Falae, a
former finance minister, his rival. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LAGOS, Nigeria -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- NIGERIA-ELECTIONS-1,
2-27 -- A 100-year-old nanny, Amina Umar, is one of tens of
millions of Nigerians who voted in Saturday's presidential
election, which many hope will end a long military dictatorship.
Voters will choose between General Olusegun Obasanjo, a former
military ruler trying to regain power 20 years after relinquishing
it, and Falae, a former finance minister, his rival. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HILLMAN, Mich. -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- SICK-DEER-2, 2-27 --
Galen H. Schalk says he has found three deer infected with bovine
tuberculosis on his farm in Hillman, Mich. Michigan's dairy and
beef cattle farmers are terrified that their herds may be infected
by the recent spread of bovine tuberculosis among the wild deer in
the area, the first such sustained outbreak ever documented in
North America and a potentially serious threat to the Midwestern
livestock industry. (John Robert Williams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HILLMAN, Mich. -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- SICK-DEER-1, 2-27
--The Turtle Lake Club, whose clubhouse and cabins sit on 26,000
acres in northern Michigan, is being sued by the state for erecting
30 miles of fence around club property. State officials fear that
the fence will disrupt deer migration and allow bovine tuberculosis
in wild deer to spread to livestock on nearby farms. Officials
first became aware of a bovine tuberculosis problem in upstate
Michigan in late 1994, when an emaciated buck was shot on the
Turtle Lake Club's property and was found to have the disease.
(John Robert Williams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-I-4, 2-27 --
Monica Boguille, a 20-year-old mother of two and a part-time
secretary with no prior convictions, was sentenced to 10 years for
conspiracy to distribute crack cocaine. She occasionally counted
money for her boyfriend, a crack dealer, L.C. Godfrey. Godfrey, a
wholesale supplier of cocaine for a drug ring, who was deemed
helpful to prosecutors, received only nine years. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TOPEKA, Kan. -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-I-3, 2-27
-- Gloria Van Winkle, 39, is in the sixth year of a life term in
the maximum-security unit at the state prison for women in Topeka,
Kan., for possessing $40 worth of cocaine. A mother of two and a
drug addict, she had two convictions for cocaine possession when a
convicted thief told undercover agents she was smoking crack and
they set up a sting. Ms. Van Winkle was sentenced under the Kansas
three-strike law. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DUBLIN, Calif. -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-I-2, 2-27
-- Tonya Drake, 35, a mother of four, had no criminal record or
history of drug use when she was sentenced to 10 years in prison at
the Dublin Federal Penitentiary in Northern California, for mailing
a package that contained 232 grams of crack cocaine. She says a
friend paid her $44 to mail the package, which she did not know
contained drugs. Since the 1980s, when crack cocaine scared the
country and prompted the nation to rewrite its drug laws, the
criminal justice system has never been the same. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) VICTORVILLE, Calif. -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- CRACK-LEGACY-I-1,
2-27 -- The newest federal prison in the United States, being built
in the Mojave Desert near Victorville, Calif., will be filled
nearly to capacity when it opens this spring. Since the 1980s, when
crack cocaine scared the country and prompted the nation to rewrite
its drug laws, the criminal justice system has never been the same.
Since 1985 the nation's jail and prison population has grown 130
percent, and it will soon pass 2 million, even as crime rates
continue a six-year decline. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Feb. 27, 1999 -- SKYSCRAPER-CRANES, 2-27 --
Tom Emerson climbs up a small derrick crane on Friday which will be
used to bring down the crane used to build the Conde Nast building.
The crane, which was the eighth highest point in Manhattan, will be
removed on Sunday, weather permitting. Since last summer, when the
crane finished climbing up the 51-story tower it helped build, the
boom tip has been been poised nearly 900 feet over Times Square; a
point on the skyline almost rivaling the Citicorp Center. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
