<HEADLINE>
CEO GRAZIANO CONTINUES TO SEE UPSIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ One of the most important decisions about the
1999 Dodgers took place before the 1998 Dodgers finished playing.
</P>
<P>
   It's when Dodgers President and CEO Bob Graziano decided to hire
Kevin Malone on Sept. 11 rather than wait until the end of the
season. It gave Malone the opportunity to assess the on-field
talent first-hand and gave him an understanding of what was
missing.
</P>
<P>
   It's also why there are very few questions _ the bullpen, the
infield defense, a fifth outfielder _ in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painful in 1998, but I think because we were able to
accept the pain in 1998 we'll see the benefits in 1999,'' said
Graziano, who arrived in Dodgertown on Saturday. ``The downside to
making (change) after the season was too great to do it then.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two weeks between his hiring and the end of the season,
two necessities were evident: the Dodgers needed a center fielder
and a No.1 starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Voila. Once the free-agent market opened, the Dodgers signed
Devon White and Kevin Brown to fill those voids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely put me in a position where I felt like I had a
head start,'' Malone said of his starting date. ``I'm way ahead of
the game. I probably wouldn't be as confident in what we have on
this team if I didn't start then.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear things and you read stats, but when you can
personally evaluate a player, your convictions are stronger.
Because of that, it helped me be prepared when players started to
be available as free agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrying 11: After discussing the matter with his coaches and
general manager Malone, manager Davey Johnson said it's ``80
percent'' he'll go with 11 pitchers on staff instead of 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on a lot of things, but you have more specialty
people now,'' Johnson said. ``You could get by with less. The way
we're set up, I'm thinking we're probably going with 11.''
</P>
<P>
   Side work for Rojas: Johnson said he wants a secondary set-up
man in case closer Jeff Shaw is overworked _ ``that's when I know
we're rockin' and rollin','' Johnson said _ and that could be
right-hander Mel Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rojas needs to work out a few mechanical problems on
the side, which he'll try to do in the next few days with pitching
coach Charlie Hough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it is getting his arm in position a little quicker,''
Johnson said. ``Occasionally, he's not getting on top of his
fastball. Occasionally, he's not getting on top of his slider and
sometimes he throws a whirly-bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting and waiting: Baseball's collective bargaining agreement
states players don't have to report to training camp until March 1,
but don't expect Shaw to be at Dodgertown before Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the team is upset.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger officials have told Shaw to remain at his Ohio home until
his wife, Julie, gives birth to the couple's third child.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek was sporting
a cut above his lip after a bad hop caught him flush on the
face.... The evaluation process should accelerate this week with
intrasquad games Tuesday and Wednesday. The most notable pitcher
scheduled to be used is left-hander Greg Cadaret. Right-handers
Chan Ho Park and Brown are slated to pitch simulated games those
days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
