<HEADLINE>
16 IS SWEET ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The joke used to be that making it to the Stanley Cup playoffs
was akin to having your name in the phone book. Everyone made it.
Not to be there every spring was somewhat like having an unlisted
number: You had to request to be left out.
</P>
<P>
   Jokes aside, Edmonton boss Glen Sather suggested recently that
the NHL expand the playoff format to include 20 teams, adding four
to the tournament. The six Canadian squads especially, he said,
could use the potential income boost _ a reality emphasized by the
declining value of the Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
   When the league consisted of 21 teams, after the NHL-WHA merger,
a 16-team tournament included nearly 80 percent of the clubs. By
the fall of 2000, the league will have expanded to 30 clubs, which
means a 16-team tournament in 2001 will represent just over half
the league.
</P>
<P>
   In those terms, Sather's plot makes sense. The boost to 20 teams
would mean two-thirds of the clubs qualify. It's still a drop from
those Ma Bell sign-up-for-service days of the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But think about it: 20 teams. Stop the insanity. A fifth round
would be added, a best-of-five preliminary series for which some
teams (conference winners, maybe division winners) would receive a
bye. In such a scheme, it's conceivable the Cup winner would have
to win 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   A little perspective on that, here in the Hub of Hockey: The
Bruins have won only 18 postseason games in their nine playoff
series dating back to 1992. Imagine trying to win 19 games within
eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Leave the postseason formula alone. There's a much better
argument to be made against expanding the league to 30 teams. But
it's much too late for that now.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs and Islanders met Thursday for the first time since
the Bryan Berard-Felix Potvin swap, and the Leafs walked off with a
4-1 victory. Equally chilling for the Islanders had to be the
crowd, announced at 8,355, that media reports estimated to be under
5,000. Coach Bill Stewart: ``I don't like it when we don't put a
product on the ice that's conducive to people paying good,
hard-earned money.'' Stewart is a realist, which is to say he isn't
long for the league. Honesty is the shortest path to unemployment .
. . The Flames presented Theo Fleury with a silver stick last week,
once he became the franchise's all-time leading scorer. The memento
is valued at around $10,000. Upper management in Calgary says it
isn't a fait accompli that they'll lose Fleury as a free agent this
summer. They're willing to offer him big money, probably upwards of
$7 million a year. But if other bidders drive the bidding into the
Pavel Bure range ($9 million-plus per year), their speedy, gritty
winger will be gone. One factor in the Flames' negotiating favor:
Fleury is extremely close to his 13-year-old son, Josh, who also
lives in Calgary, and he doesn't want to be based too far from
southern Alberta . . . Detroit Pistons owner William Davidson _ his
fortune built in the glass (windshield) business _ is poised to buy
the Lightning from Art Williams, who, only weeks after taking
control of the Bolts last spring, proclaimed No. 1 draft pick
Vincent Lecavalier to be the NHL's Michael Jordan (gee, wasn't
Jordan the NBA's Wayne Gretzky?). Davidson was ready to buy the
Lightning last year, but got blindsided by Williams, who swooped in
and signed on the dotted line without knowing the full depth of the
club's debt or ongoing operating expenses. Williams became a quick
study in disaster and now will have to sell to Davidson at a loss _
but at least it will be a hard-number loss (estimated $20 million)
rather than a more devastating drain. The deal could be done as
early as Monday. Rick Dudley, hired last summer as general manager
in Ottawa, was rumored to be hired as Tampa GM when Davidson was
ready to make the deal last year. With Dudley firmly in place in
Ottawa, Davidson is expected to retain GM/coach Jacques Demers and
the rest of the management team, including Jay Feaster and Cliff
Fletcher . . . Actor Tom Hanks and ``Wheel of Fortune's'' Pat Sajak
have signed on for luxury boxes at the Kings/Lakers new arena in
Los Angeles, where one-year leases range from $197,000 to $300,000.
The suites include the usual amenities, including TVs connected to
satellite feeds of any other sports event playing in the country .
. . While on the celebrity beat, singer Celine Dion and actor
Michael Keaton (he of the Batmobile) are just two of the names
linked with Mario Lemieux's possible bid to buy the Penguins. If
nothing else, that would save the Penguins an anthem singer and a
Zamboni driver. But how wise would it be to have a co-owner whose
voice is synonymous with a sinking ship? . . . Edmonton last week
tried another netminder, Steve Passmore, and he played well in a
2-1 loss to the Ducks. ``Years from now,'' he said, ``I can say the
first two goals I allowed were by Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne.''
In depression some three years ago, and tending a bar in Kamloops
(British Columbia), Passmore said he contemplated killing himself,
following the death of his father, a chronic health problem, and
rejection by his girlfriend. He hung in, and after four-plus years
in the minors, finally got his chance. ``I talk to my dad during
every anthem,'' he said. ``Before the game (with the Oilers), I
kind of welcomed him to The Show _ hope he got here on short
notice.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   He isn't saying this year is the end, but Gretzky has made a
habit this season of presenting friends with autographed sticks as
he's made his way around the league. The Great One handed one to
Sather when the Rangers recently stopped in Edmonton. ``He thanked
me for what I'd done for him,'' said Sather. ``It was pretty
nostalgic. I hope it wasn't his way of saying, `I'm quitting.' ''
Sather suggested that Gretzky should move to Edmonton, put his kids
in school, get his boys in a great hockey program _ and play for
the Oilers. ``But I told him he'd have to play for free, just for
old time's sake,'' said Sather. ``I told it to (Mark Messier) once,
too. I told him he'd be only getting a friend for life.'' . . . The
Canucks finally got Kevin Weekes, their goaltender of the future
acquired in the Bure swap, under contract last week. The pact is
valued around $1.9 million over three years, with the first year a
pro-rated $550,000. There is a chance he'll get his first start
Sunday night against the Sabres, but Garth Snow's revival in net
last week was making it difficult for coach Marc Crawford to make
the switch. Meanwhile, look for Corey Hirsch to be left exposed in
the June expansion draft . . . Mark Tinordi (sprained ankle) isn't
expected back in the Capitals' lineup unless they make the
playoffs, and by that time he may be someone else's property. Many
contenders are looking for help along the back line, prompting
rumors that the Rangers' Ulf Samuelsson and the Oilers' Bo Mironov
will see new environs on or before the March 23 trade deadline.
Dallas and Detroit are especially in need along the Thin Blue Line
. . . A series of injuries behind the Vancouver blue line _ most
notably a Mattias Ohlund shoulder sprain _ prompted the Canucks to
dress ex-Bruin Steve Staios Wednesday night against the Sharks.
Staios promptly wrenched his left knee and won't play for at least
a couple of weeks . . . An Edmonton Sun report Friday had the
Oilers eyeing Boston's Steve Heinze and Don Sweeney for a possible
swap, along with Jim Carey. The only Oiler name brought up in the
report was Mironov, the hard-hitting blue liner who will be an
unrestricted free agent July 1 . . . Word around St. Louis is that
the Blues won't haggle much on contract with Pierre Turgeon, making
$4.6 million this year after winning big in arbitration last
summer, and could just let him walk rather than get slammed again
in arbitration. If so, the slick-but-soft Turgeon, who will be 30
in August, would be free to sign with whomever he pleases. Headed
into the weekend, Turgeon had 43 points in 43 games, leaving him 25
short of 1,000 career points. Let's see, age 30, 1,000 points.
Sounds like a $6 million salary base from here.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks, who will miss the playoffs for a second year in
a row, finally embraced the inevitable and whacked rookie coach
Dirk Graham only hours after his club lost to the Bruins last
Sunday. Lorne Molleken, former minor league coach for the Oilers,
moved in for relief duty, but the Hawks need a respected, seasoned
coach. They put a feeler out on Terry Murray last year, but club
owner Bill Wirtz swatted that idea away when he heard Murray wanted
real money (upwards of $700,000 a year). It's time to stop the
good-ol'-boy chain and bring in someone like Ted Nolan . . . A
couple of coaching candidates to keep in mind over the next 24
months: Peter Laviolette and Bruce Crowder. Laviolette has worked
wonders with the Baby B's in Providence. Crowder, an ex-Bruin, has
had ample seasoning now with UMass-Lowell and Northeastern. He
doesn't have to go anywhere, and he's never expressed an urge to
return to the pros, but his teams play a professional, smart game.
If he wants it, he should get a shot to return to The Show . . . No
decision yet on whether NHLers will be involved in the 2002 Olympic
mix at Salt Lake City. The subject will be on the top of the agenda
when the International Ice Hockey Federation holds its annual
spring meeting in Norway in mid-May, following the World
Championships. At the same meeting, the IIHF is expected to
finalize plans to slot the World Championship for February in
upcoming years. It would prevent the conflict with soccer in Europe
and not compete for the same sponsorship/TV dollars . . . With
defenseman Darryl Sydor down with a sprained knee, the Stars have
inquired about signing free agent Doug Lidster, the 38-year-old
backliner who finished up last season with the Rangers. How thin is
the market? Lidster, staying in shape with the Canadian national
team, has at least one other club making an offer . . . Anaheim
defenseman Pascal Trepanier, whose uncle is ex-Montreal winger and
coach Mario Tremblay, was headed toward a career as a veterinarian
before turning pro, first with the Colorado organization. ``He's
making more money than fixing sick cats and horses,'' said
Tremblay. With his uncle so much a part of the Habs, Trepanier grew
up with his share of bleu-blanc-et-rouge paraphernalia. ``I'm
embarrassed to say,'' he said, ``I played street hockey with a Guy
Lafleur stick _ I didn't know any better.'' He also wore a pair of
Chris Chelios shoulder pads . . . Ex-Boston University Terrier
Chris Drury has taken to wearing a visor (college redux) after
getting clipped around the eyes three times with sticks. Dave Reid
got him for six stitches. Bryan McCabe cut him for eight. Steve
Washburn carved him for nine. ``He's got more stitches than a
baseball,'' said Avalanche coach Bob Hartley. When Drury was cut by
Reid, referee Kerry Fraser didn't whistle a penalty, contending
that Drury ducked into Reid's shot. ``I'm only 5 feet 7,'' said
Drury, ``I didn't have to duck.'' . . . Hingham's Tony Amonte,
perhaps the Blackhawks' only hope to rebuild the franchise, finally
had his long locks cut last week. He told the hairstylist he wanted
more of the George Clooney look. A few snips later he was Clooned
and groomed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
