<HEADLINE>
POWER PLAY TAKES ADVANTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing at even strength, the Bruins were a futile lot for much
of Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   When they were on the power play, however, it was a different
story.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins took great advantage of their man-up opportunities,
scoring on three of five chances, and that was enough to propel
them to a 4-3 victory over Washington at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The power-play snipers were Anson Carter, who tied the game at
1-1 in the second period, and Dmitri Khristich, who scored a pair.
Khristich's first, at 13:10 of the second period, put the Bruins
ahead, 2-1. His second, at 24 seconds of the third period, gave the
Bruins a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Allison got the winner, at even strength, with 4:22
remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The power-play surge couldn't have come at a better time
because, even though the Bruins won, their performance left a lot
to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't very nice, but sometimes it's better to win ugly
than lose pretty,'' said Burns. ``It's an ugly win, but we'll
definitely take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Khristich's pair extended his point streak to four games, which
coincides with the current Bruins' roll of 3-0-1. The two goals he
potted Saturday were his 25th and 26th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Khristich said the power-play success, which had been lacking of
late, was the result of keeping it simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play hasn't done well lately, I think maybe we got a
couple from Joe Thornton's line, but we haven't scored any lately
until today,'' said Khristich. ``It's a real breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did really keep it simple. Just little shots to the net. We
did that and nice things happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bourque echoed those sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're trying to get it to the net and trying to keep
it simple,'' said Bourque. ``Those goals weren't pretty goals. It
just goes to show you that you have to put the puck on net and
things will happen. When you don't, nothing happens. I mean, a shot
on net is never a bad play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see so many weird goals. They're not all highlights or
pretty ones, but getting the puck to the net and crashing the net,
you're going to get opportunities and rebounds. You've got one
extra guy out there so you should outman people in front. Simplest
is always the best way.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the way Burns wants the Bruins to do things when
they're on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand that the power play is only a chance,
it's not a definite goal,'' said Burns. ``Everybody thinks you get
a power play and bang, bang it's in the net. If it was that easy,
we'd have power plays being scored at 50 or 60 percent. Why do we
have power plays _ in the 18 and 19 percent across the board in the
NHL?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's difficult. It's a little bit tougher. You can
have all the patterns you want, but sometimes the simple way is the
better way.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Bruins did it that way and the results were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little bit down and now we're back, we hope,'' said
Khristich. ``The power-play goals were really good for us and
hopefully we'll keep scoring them when we have the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns has been preaching all year that the simple way is the
winning way. Nobody could argue that point Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
