</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATRIOTSQB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MAY REARM WITH MOBIL QUARTERBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Patriots found out the hard way last season how fragile NFL
quarterbacks are. It hadn't been an issue for them because they had
one of the most durable quarterbacks in the league, Drew Bledsoe,
and a loyal veteran backup, Scott Zolak, who could play in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``pinch'' turned into a serious matter when Bledsoe
broke his right index finger late in the season. He won dramatic
games against Buffalo and Miami with the finger heavily bandaged
but wasn't able to play in the last three games of the regular
season or the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   At the most crucial time, the Patriots had to go with Zolak, who
hadn't started a regular-season game for three years. In the end,
the Patriots never really had a chance, and their season ended with
a 25-10 loss to Jacksonville in the wild-card round of the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Now the team's thinking on the quarterback position is changing.
Don't be astonished if the Patriots use one of their two
first-round picks on a quarterback, if the man they want is
available.
</P>
<P>
   That man appears to be Donovan McNabb of Syracuse, a mobile,
strong-armed, athletic quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Would he be available at No. 20 or 28?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question. The other question is, would the Patriots,
who have other needs, use a first-round pick on what essentially
would be a backup player?
</P>
<P>
   Vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier said last week
that the Patriots would draft a quarterback, and he said it may be
early.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Cade McNown is certainly another quarterback catching
everyone's eye. While originally thought of as an early
second-round pick, McNown has improved his stock with strong
performances at the Senior Bowl and the scouting combine.
</P>
<P>
   He's lefthanded, mobile (4.75 in the 40), escapes pressure, and
can throw. What he doesn't have is great size (though he was
measured at a shade under 6 feet 1 inch). But former Patriots
offensive coordinator Larry Kennan, who is running McNown's
workouts, said, ``He's built a lot like Steve Young. He's a tough
kid with the type of attitude you love to see in a quarterback. He
has a strong arm. I've got to believe people are thinking of him as
a first-rounder now.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier thinks as many as five quarterbacks could go in the first
round, possibly Tim Couch, Akili Smith, Daunte Culpepper, McNabb,
and McNown. Also enticing is Washington's Brock Huard. The Patriots
love Syracuse players and would love to see McNabb fall to them,
but if McNown were there, how could they pass on him?
</P>
<P>
   Grier said he would look for a quarterback who was the opposite
of Bledsoe, which means mobility is important.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget, the Patriots may address their running back
situation with a trade, a free agent, or even a later-round pick
(as they did the year they got Curtis Martin in the third round).
They would love to draft an offensive lineman, a defensive lineman,
a linebacker, and a receiver or tight end fairly high. They have
five picks in the first three rounds, and if they do it right, they
have a chance to fill in most of their needs there.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also are after a veteran quarterback, someone in
his 30s, who can back up Bledsoe and perhaps help during games.
They will see what becomes available after June 1, when teams begin
to cut veterans with big cap numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent Steve Bono would be considered, as would Jeff
Hostetler, who is currenly trying to get work in his hometown of
Pittsburgh behind Kordell Stewart. The Patriots also are intrigued
by Warren Moon, but he would like to go someplace where he can
contend for a starting job. If the Steelers go with Hostetler, then
Mike Tomczak would be available.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Punter/quarterback Tom Tupa, who signed with the New York Jets
as a free agent, never wanted to leave the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best environment I've ever played in,'' he said.
``I've never been around a group of players that liked each other
so much and did things together off the field. That's why it was so
disappointing to me that they didn't make more of an effort to get
a contract done with me. I thought I put up good numbers in my
three years there and I felt comfortable there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa said he felt comfortable going to the Jets because of his
relationship with Bill Parcells, his former coach in New England;
Bill Belichick, his coach in Cleveland and a former assistant in
New England; and the many ex-Patriots and ex-Browns who have made
their way onto the New York roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to New England, I didn't know anyone except Coach
Belichick, but it turned out to be a great experience,'' said Tupa.
``I'll miss all of the guys and all of the people my family met and
got to know there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa will now get a look at the Jets-Patriots rivalry from the
other side; he never felt the Patriots were ``psyched out'' by the
Jets after Parcells took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think so,'' said Tupa. ``When we played the
Jets, the players in our locker room were always sky-high before
the game. I thought we played good games against them except for
the last one when we had so many injuries. I don't know why we
didn't beat them more because we had so much talent here.''
</P>
<P>
   His assessment of Pete Carroll: ``Pete's a good football coach.
He's always compared to Bill, and that's not fair. Bill is one of
the greatest coaches of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa said Parcells has told him he will be the backup to Vinny
Testaverde, which justifies the four-year, $6.1 million contract,
with a $1.8 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa thought he might go to Cleveland, his hometown, because of
his relationship with new coach Chris Palmer. But the Jets' deal
was too good to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   He'll miss Bledsoe, his closest friend and a frequent victim of
Tupa's on the golf course and the pool table. Tupa even offered to
buy Bledsoe's new multimillion-dollar home in Medfield, which
Bledsoe may have to sell with the team moving to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offered him a million for it,'' quipped Tupa. ``He didn't
like that too much.''
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, the Patriots probably made out well with
the change of punters. For half the money, they signed Lee Johnson,
who is close to Tupa's peer as a punter and also an excellent
kickoff man. The only thing he isn't is a quarterback, but Tupa
threw only two passes for the Patriots in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa's average salary over the length of his deal will be $1.526
million, while Johnson's will be $666,667. Johnson's cap number
will be $633,333 next season and rise to $683,334 by 2001. Tupa's
cap hit is $850,000 in '99 but jumps to $1.6 million in 2000, $1.8
million in 2001, and $1.85 million in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, Johnson has punted 377 times, has placed
101 balls inside the 20-yard line (27 percent), has forced 46
touchbacks (12 percent), and has averages of 43.8 yards gross and
35.9 yards net. In addition, he has kicked off 242 times, with 33
touchbacks (14 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Tupa punted 360 times in the same period, placing 97 inside the
20 (27 percent), with 47 touchbacks (13 percent), a 43.5-yard gross
average, and a 35.8-yard net average.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Johnson had a 44.7-yard gross average and 35.6
yards net, while Tupa was 44.5 gross and 35.4 net.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   From Woolf to Wolf is the best way to describe Andrew Brandt's
journey the past month. A few weeks ago he was Ricky Williams's
agent, working for Woolf Associates in Boston. As Williams moved
away from Woolf and toward rapper Master P, Brandt parted company
with Woolf, and almost immediately was hired by Green Bay Packers
vice president Ron Wolf as director of finance and football
operations. ``It's certainly different being on the other side
having to deal with agents and trying to structure deals based on
the salary cap from this end,'' said Brandt, who has already closed
some big deals and is beginning work on franchise player Antonio
Freeman. Wolf needed a money man and found Brandt impressive in
their past dealings. Maybe this will start a trend of agents being
hired on the other side . . . Chip Myers was a friend to many in
the NFL. The Vikings' new offensive coordinator died at 53 of a
heart attack at his suburban Minneapolis home last week, leaving a
wife, five children, and many grandchildren. As an assistant coach,
Myers had no benefits except a $250,000 life insurance policy
provided by the NFL. Kennan, who is executive director of the NFL
Coaches Association, will fight for more benefits for assistants in
the future. He also said that coaches around the league will likely
put together a fund for Myers's family. ``We'll do whatever it
takes,'' said Kennan. ``This is a tragedy. Chip was loved by all. A
great man and a great football coach.'' The Vikings will likely
replace Myers by promoting Ray Sherman, who was hired to be
quarterbacks coach after being fired as Pittsburgh's offensive
coordinator . . . The NFL almost has to do something to help the
Patriots in the Robert Edwards situation. The team has sent a
letter to the league formally requesting compensation and
salary-cap relief for the loss of Edwards, who may never play
again. The Edwards case almost certainly will kill the ``Beach
Bowl'' game and may have some impact on the future of the Pro Bowl
if the league doesn't do something about the liability issue.
Edwards, meanwhile, has returned to Georgia. It will be five weeks
before he's able to walk again, and then he starts a very long and
probably painful journey back . . . The Patriots quietly
restructured Chris Slade's contract to free up more cap room. By
guaranteeing his 1999 salary at $2 million, they were able to
spread that over a four-year period. That left them about $800,000
under the salary cap, ample room to be able to get Adam Vinatieri's
deal done.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots appear to be serious about Heath Irwin as the
starting center. Enticing, however, is 10-year veteran Mark
Stepnoski, a five-time Pro Bowler who may not return to Tennessee.
Stepnoski started his career in Dallas and said he'd be willing to
return to the Cowboys at a hometown discount. The Patriots have had
preliminary discussions with Stepnoski but they probably wouldn't
pay big money for him . . . Another Syracuse player who might be on
the Patriots' radar screen is fullback/tight end Ron Konrad. He's
the top-rated fullback on most lists, but at the end of his combine
workouts, he gave a private workout for teams as a tight end.
Konrad is 6-4, 251 pounds, and would seem to fit nicely in the
``H-back'' set-up the Patriots use at times. If they lose Lovett
Purnell as a restricted free agent (Baltimore?), the Patriots would
need another pass-catcher type behind Ben Coates. Konrad could be
their man . . . Todd Collins will be in St. Louis Monday for his
second visit with the Rams. It appears the Rams will sign Collins
if they lose linebacker Roman Phifer to the Browns. Losing Collins
would be a bigger blow to the Patriots than they think. ``It would
have been nice to finish my career there,'' said Collins. ``I don't
think they want me back. They haven't even talked to us about
anything. I loved it there, I really did. I thought we had a good
group of linebackers and we'd played together for a long time. It's
a shame to break that up. But the Rams have made me feel like they
want me. I know people think it's all about the money, but for me
it's knowing an organization really wants me. I always felt that in
New England until now.'' Collins wanted to get one more thing off
his chest: He said the reason he took the 1995 season off wasn't
that he wanted to get away from Parcells. ``Bill had nothing to do
with it,'' said Collins. ``It's one of those stories everybody just
ran with and sometimes it's not worth trying to set people
straight. I enjoyed Bill very much. I really enjoyed playing for
Pete as well.'' . . . Patriots linebacker Tedy Bruschi, who is
representing himself in negotiations, has been offered a four-year,
$7.4 million deal with a $2 million signing bonus . . . Los Angeles
is expected to be awarded the next expansion franchise, even though
there's been no agreement on the stadium site. Houston will have
some support (that stadium deal is even better than Hartford), and
it eventually will get a franchise, either through relocation or
expansion. After Al Davis is told he doesn't own the LA market, he
may wind up in Houston. He's also been talking to people in
Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
