<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1786 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-MINORS-BOS     02-27 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MINORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX PROSPECTING IN THE MINORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ He is the type of baseball lifer who might
greet the day with the words, ``I love the smell of pine tar in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   With wide-brimmed straw hat, hard-set eyes on a sun-spackled
face, Kentucky whiskey drawl, and the dust of countless diamonds on
the soles of his shoes, Eddie Haas is a guy who once played with
Hank Aaron and Ernie Banks and managed Dale Murphy, but the better
part of his days are now spent evaluating talent for Red Sox
general manager Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   During the season, he scouts big leaguers, but it is here,
standing behind a batting cage watching what the Red Sox hope is
their future generation of players, that Haas flashes a rare and
triumphant smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``See the ball come off his bat?'' he said, voice thick with
excitement as line drives as true as summer fly from Mark Fischer's
bat. ``That's the way big leaguers hit the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fischer, like Nomar Garciaparra and Jason Varitek before
him, came to the Red Sox via Georgia Tech, a first-round
``sandwich'' draft pick in 1997 whose progress through the system
was slowed last season by a knee injury that required surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But he worked hard last fall in the team's instructional league,
with Haas taking a special interest. And here, in this
by-invitation-only minicamp of the team's top minor league
prospects, the soon-to-be 23-year-old outfielder has laced a
cloudless morning with sweet promises of the days to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the ticket to a whole lot of money, buddy,'' said Welby
Sheldon ``Buddy'' Bailey, the 42-year-old Virginian and new Sox
minor league field coordinator, as Fischer launched yet another
drive into the left-field screen on a back diamond of the City of
Palms Park complex.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Gardner Jr., the 32-year-old son of the former Sox
infielder and Twins manager whose own managing career is on the
fast track after he was named Midwest League Manager of the Year
last season, had the righthanded-hitting Fischer in Michigan in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn, Fischer, you really hurt that ball,'' he said as
Fischer, whose face is distinguished by eyebrows that belong in the
Politburo, stepped out of the cage.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that Duquette, his throat still raw from a flu
that he can't shake, is here this morning, visiting with Kent
Qualls, his new director of player development, instead of a couple
miles up Edison Avenue, where the big leaguers are working out.
Duquette's first job in pro baseball after leaving Amherst College
in 1980 was as an assistant in the Milwaukee Brewers' scouting and
minor league department, and player development remains his first
love.
</P>
<P>
   For Duquette, this is a moveable feast, and not only because of
Fischer. In the infield, the slender shortstop taking ground balls
from Gardner is Adam Everett, the All-American from South Carolina
who was scouting director Wayne Britton's top draft pick last
season. Everett is from Kennesaw, Ga. _ the heart of Newt Gingrich
country _ and was rated the top defensive player in the draft by
Baseball America, the respected trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox gave Everett a $1.75 million bonus to sign, and last
August he played 21 games for short-season Lowell in the New
York-Penn League.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got real smooth action,'' Gardner said of the 22-year-old
who some in the organization believe may be an even better fielder
than Garciaparra. ``The ball jumps into his glove. His feet move
well with the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Garciaparra figures to be the Boston shortstop
for at least a decade, the Sox seem to have an embarrassment of
riches at the position. There also is Julio Guerrero, the brother
of Vladimir Guerrero, the Expos outfielder who Montreal manager
Felipe Alou has said has a chance to be the best player ever to
come out of the Dominican Republic, Sammy Sosa notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Guerrero is just 18, and he is already 6 feet 3 inches
with coltish legs and a torso that hasn't begun to fill out. At
this rate, Guerrero not only will be too big to be a shortstop, he
might be best suited to play small forward. The Red Sox already
anticipate moving him one day to third base or the outfield, just
as they ponder making a third baseman out of Aaron Capista, the
switch-hitting shortstop from Joliet, the Illinois town where Pete
Rose did his prison time.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero may be the rawest of the players here, and as you'd
expect from a Dominican teenager, it's not just his game that needs
work. ``Hello, Julio, how was your winter?'' Duquette said as
Guerrero jogged past. One look at his apologetic smile and a shake
of his head, and it was clear that Guerrero had no idea what his
employer had just said.
</P>
<P>
   It is upon another Georgian, outfielder Dernell Stenson, that
the fondest Red Sox hopes are pinned. Stenson, who was a defensive
lineman in high school in LaGrange, the heart of Georgia football
country, does not turn 21 until June 17, and has just three seasons
of pro ball on his resume since being signed by scouting
cross-checker Kevin Burrell as a third-round pick in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But last season, while playing for the Double A Trenton Thunder,
Stenson hit 24 home runs, which is more than Mo Vaughn ever hit in
the minors. The analogy is not accidental. At 6-1, 230 pounds, with
thighs that resemble redwoods and skin the color of deep mahogany,
Stenson may be the lefthanded power hitter that will most remind
fans of Vaughn while perhaps helping them forget him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Stenson, who figures to play left field for Triple A Pawtucket,
does not hang over the plate the way Vaughn does. Nor is he a
bundle of nervous movement in the batter's box, like Garciaparra.
There is a noticeable trigger mechanism to his swing. Just a
shifting of weight to his powerful back leg, a short stride, and
wrists flashing through the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``His swing is very calm,'' Haas said. ``Very quiet. That's
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The most fragile of all prospects, of course, are the pitchers.
The Sox once thought they had a future Roger Clemens-type in Texas
high schooler Andy Yount, but he shattered a glass in his hand,
cutting tendons in his middle finger, and after numerous
operations, the Sox elected to let him go. Chris Reitsma, the
Canadian kid and second-round pick in 1996, has twice fractured his
elbow; the first time, it snapped like a sapling while he was
delivering a pitch for Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Even 1997's No. 1 draft pick, lefthander John Curtice, already
has undergone shoulder surgery for a frayed labrum, though he is
expected to fully recover. Curtice is the Virginia high schooler
who once dyed his hair green at the suggestion of his mother. Back
then, the Sox knew they were getting a free spirit in the David
Wells mode. What they didn't count on was for Curtice to pack on so
many pounds, his body becoming Wellsian, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been addressed,'' Bailey said, sternness creeping into
his voice. ``He's a gifted guy, and we're not going to send him out
of here, even if his arm is healthy, if he's not in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Peek at the future
</P>
<P>
   Herm Starrette, another Appalachian-bred member of the Sox
instructional staff, was the team's bullpen coach until being
reassigned last season. Now, Starrette, a native of North Carolina,
oversees the in-season rehabilitation of pitchers in Fort Myers. On
this day, he is talking in rapturous tones about Jerome Gamble, a
fourth-round pick last season who turns 19 on April 5.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble is Deep South _ Alexander City, Ala. _ a strapping, 6-2,
200-pounder built like a young Bob Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot,'' said Starrette, ``this kid is better than sex. He's
got everything _ fastball, nasty curveball, changeup. All he's got
to do is pitch. The best thing to do with him is leave him alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pitchers here are the kids who will start in the
lower minor classifications, and Starrette says there are plenty of
good ones. He mentions a couple of college lefthanders, Andy
Hazlett and Mike Maroth, as well as an undrafted sleeper, Mike
Mowel, a 19-year-old Connecticut kid (East Hartford) who showed
some promise at Lowell last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sonofagun is going to be good,'' Starrette said of Mowel.
</P>
<P>
   The hope, of course, is that enough of these kids will indeed be
good enough to make it one day on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot to look forward to,'' the 60-year-old Starrette
said. ``Barring injury, we should have some good players in
Boston.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
