<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-NASCAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR ABOUT TO JOIN BIG LEAGUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the heels of the most-watched Daytona 500 in history _ CBS
drew a 9.5 rating and 25 share on Feb. 14 _ NASCAR officials are
taking a bold step to capitalize on the popularity of their Winston
Cup series by consolidating their broadcast rights.
</P>
<P>
   The move, announced Wednesday, will enable NASCAR, the only
sport to see its TV ratings rise each year this decade, to command
a hefty rights fee, more in line with the NFL, NBA, NHL, and Major
League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``By retaining and negotiating the rights, we will be able to
develop new strategic values and new media products that would not
have been possible under our old approach,'' said Mike Helton,
NASCAR's chief operating officer. ``(This) decision will continue
to propel the growth of the sport well into the next century, and
we believe it will significantly benefit the entire industry, and
particularly our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   News of NASCAR's decision was greeted enthusiastically on Wall
Street, as several racing-related stocks traded at near 52-week
highs Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Under NASCAR's old approach, track owners were allowed to
negotiate their own television deals, which now generate $100
million in fees for 34 races.
</P>
<P>
   While NASCAR will not approach the NFL's $17.9 billion TV deal,
it could, given its soaring ratings and popularity, land a network
package worth $500 million-$750 million, about as much as ABC paid
for the NHL rights.
</P>
<P>
   But those are conservative estimates.
</P>
<P>
   If a bidding war were to ensue among CBS, which now televises
the Daytona 500; ABC/ESPN, whose network/cable tandem could provide
programming on two fronts; NBC, which would be looking to add a new
sports vehicle after losing the NFL; and Fox Sports, which has
emerged as a significant player, then rights fees could soar.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even as high as $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, by contrast, NASCAR received just $3 million for the
rights to 28 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hell of a deal, and it could be higher,'' said Bob
Bahre, the 72-year-old owner of New Hampshire International
Speedway. ``I thought it was a heck of a good move. Bill France
talked to us about it. NASCAR talked to every track owner about it,
and we all felt the same way. It was a good move.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahre said he negotiated a five-race, $33 million deal for Las
Vegas Motor Speedway ``that was a record at the time, except for
Daytona, but you'll see purses go right to the moon. When this deal
goes into effect, Daytona will probably pay a $15 million purse.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Helton, the changes go into effect in 2000, but
NASCAR will retain the same revenue-sharing formula _ track owners
receiving 65 percent, competitors 25 percent, and NASCAR 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bahre said TV revenue at his track would likely triple from $7
million to more than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked making my own deals,'' Bahre said. ``But I'm all for
this, because it's good for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After plummeting from first to 11th in the Winston Cup standings
following a 39th-place finish that was the result of a a blown
engine in last week's Dura-Lube 400 at Rockingham, N.C., Jeff
Gordon took to the track at Las Vegas for a test session in a Busch
Series car co-owned by his wife, Brooke, and crew chief Ray
Evernham. ``This is truly a test for us,'' said Gordon, who plans
to campaign the No. 24 Pepsi-Frito Lay Chevrolet Monte Carlo for
five Busch races this season. ``This car has never been to a
racetrack. We've really got a lot of things to try and we've got to
try and get a lot of laps on the Busch car. A lot has changed since
I sat in one of them.'' For one, when he starts in the Sam's Town
300 Saturday at Las Vegas, Gordon will likely encounter stiff
opposition from young guns such as Dale Earnhardt Jr. and
18-year-old phenoms Casey Atwood and Adam Petty. ``Ray and I have
talked about getting more involved in NASCAR racing and the Busch
Series is pretty much where we started together,'' said Gordon.
``When I met Ray, it was in a Busch car and we've had a lot of good
times in them. But I really want to stick with five Busch races and
run some other younger driver, but we need to get more
sponsorship.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Although Mark Martin won last week's Winston Cup race, Mike
Skinner also benefitted from Gordon's engine woes by vaulting to
the top of the standings, with 315 points, after finishing sixth .
. . Championship Auto Racing Teams announced an addition to its
1999 schedule, the Hawaiian Super Prix Nov. 13, a $10 million,
pay-per-view, non-points race between the series's top 16 drivers.
It will be staged on a 1.8-mile layout on the tarmac of Barbers
Point Airport near Honolulu. The winner will take home $5 million,
making it the largest single-day payout for any motorsports event.
``A $5 million prize for the winner is awesome,'' said Michael
Andretti. ``There will be a lot on the line and that will be
reflected in the racing. I commend CART for being so progressive
and putting this event together. The race will definitely cap off
the season and give us a nice, happy finish _ especially for the
guy that wins.'' . . . Evidently, two-time CART champion Alex
Zanardi took a hefty pay cut to return to Formula One. In an
interview with Autosport magazine, Zanardi's former team manager
says the Italian star was offered $13 million to remain with Chip
Ganassi's Target team but opted to take a $5 million deal to drive
for Team Williams . . . Racearama '99 will take place at the
Eastern States Exposition in West Springfield Friday through
Sunday. For more information, call Stafford Motor Speedway at
860-684-2783 . . . Officials at Stafford, in Stafford Springs,
Conn., were recently recognized by NASCAR for having the Best 50th
Anniversary Campaign Presentation at the NASCAR Winston Racing
Series promoters meetings at Daytona Beach. ``This is the only
award of its kind ever issued by NASCAR,'' said Stafford track
owner Jack Arute Sr., who credited Cory Posocco, director of
marketing and promotions, for hatching the idea. ``It's something
to cherish throughout NASCAR's next 50 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
