<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1788 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-CAPITALS-B     02-27 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CAPITALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE, BRUINS KEEP CAPITALS AT BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruins4Capitals3
</P>
<P>
   They were trailing by one goal after the first period. Not a big
gap to make up, but what rankled coach Pat Burns wasn't that the
Bruins were down. In a stretch run where every point counts, his
team didn't come out with the energy, passion, or focus he was
expecting against an opponent _ the Washington Capitals _ who also
were fighting for their lives in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   So Burns let his players know of his displeasure during the
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The troops responded to the wakeup call with a pair of goals in
the second and two more in the third _ including the winner with
4:22 remaining _ to edge the Capitals, 4-3, Saturday at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we have to get a kick in the butt to get us going,''
said goalie Byron Dafoe, who stopped 33 shots and was a big reason
the Bruins won. ``Pat came in between periods after the first and
kind of lambasted us a little bit. We weren't hitting, we weren't
skating that hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for people to understand. You have to get up for
every game, but when you're playing 82 games and playing every
second night, sometimes it takes a few minutes or a period to get
into a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a situation where we have to be ready at the drop of
the puck. We can't take shifts off or periods off. That was the
situation in the first and we responded in the second.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's power play, which has been up and down this season,
converted on three of five opportunities. Dmitri Khristich had a
pair of goals, both with the man advantage, and an assist and Jason
Allison had two power-play assists and the winning goal at even
strength. Anson Carter, who has been playing on the top line with
Allison and Khristich, had a power-play goal and an assist.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Ken Klee gave Washington the lead at 9:12 of the
opening period. Carter tied it at 9:04 of the second and Boston
earned its first lead at 13:10 on Khristich's first. Klee tied it
at 18:41 with his second. Khristich, who extended his point streak
to four games (five goals and 10 points) then gave the Bruins the
lead, 3-2, with his 26th of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington wasn't done. During a two-man advantage of 1
minute 28 seconds _ after Don Sweeney was whistled for high
sticking at 2:03 and Tim Taylor was assessed a five-minute major
and game misconduct for boarding Sergei Gonchar at 2:35 _
Washington pulled even again on a goal by Jaroslav Svejkovsky at
3:50, 13 seconds before the two-man advantage expired.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins killed off the remaining 3:33 of the major, the final
minute of which was taken over by Ray Bourque, who skated the puck
around his own zone and the neutral zone, dodging Capitals right
and left.
</P>
<P>
   Allison put the finishing touch on the victory at 15:38 when he
took a backhand pass from Steve Heinze and beat Olaf Kolzig from
the slot. Kolzig was so upset he smashed his stick to smithereens
against the right post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't very nice,'' said Burns of the aesthetics, or lack
thereof, in the win.. ``But sometimes it's better to win ugly than
lose pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first period, we weren't very good. We were emotionless.
For some reason or another, I don't know why. You've got to be up
for every one of these games and I think that has something to do
with experience, when you're not ready to be able to battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we found a way to get around it and get the points and
they're valuable points. It's Dafoe's win, there's no two ways
about that. He really kept us in there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
