<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMMATES GIVE SHORTSTOP AN ASSIST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ When it comes to talking about himself, the
shortstop is notoriously indifferent. It's part of his charm.
</P>
<P>
   He just doesn't get this whole media thing. He frames it, as he
frames just about everything else, very simply. What, he asks
himself, does this have to do with winning baseball games? Or with
making me a better ballplayer? The answer, of course, is nothing,
and he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Other guys might at least reason that making nice with the print
and electronic media will put their names before the public and
perhaps lead to endorsements. Garciaparra is not other guys. He
does not care about endorsements or any of the trappings of
celebrity. He is what he is, a baseball player, and what a baseball
player.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nomar is little help when it comes to explaining Nomar,
why not turn to his contemporaries in the clubhouse? I say
``contemporaries,'' because, with the exception of Pedro Martinez,
it would be inaccurate to refer to any of them as his ``peers.'' I
wanted to know what impressed them or fascinated them or intrigued
about their amazing shortstop. So here are the thoughts of five
teammates with the combined wisdom of 43-plus years and 3,168 games
of major league experience.
</P>
<P>
   BRET SABERHAGEN (15 years): ``I don't know if this is an
overused reference, but to me he's a throwback. Old school. A lot
of players come up today and think they are owed, but, if anything,
you owe the game. That's the way Nomar sees it. He's not cocky or
arrogant. He plays the game with intensity and he prepares with
extreme intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anyone in this clubhouse who is ready to go to
battle every day, it is Nomar Garciaparra. There is talk about him
having to become more of a `leader' now, but, personally, I don't
want him to do anything different. He doesn't have to start
speaking up in the locker room. His leadership is the way he gets
ready for a game and the way he plays. If anyone in this clubhouse
can't see that as leadership, he's wearing a blindfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of like George (Brett). Interesting, he wears the
same number, too (5). George never went around calling team
meetings, but he would speak up when he wanted to. What he did was
lead by everyday example, and I see Nomar very much the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   SCOTT HATTEBERG (two-plus years): ``He has an incredible work
ethic. You watch him every day, and you're amazed. I know he goes
to a facility and works out hard for six weeks before he even comes
here and then he works his butt off once he gets to spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he will ever be satisfied with what he does.
That's what drives him to be a great player, and he will be a great
player because of it. When he didn't make the All-Star team last
year, you'd never know whether or not he was upset. I'm pretty good
friends with him, and he never said a word. That tells you what
kind of guy he is.''
</P>
<P>
   JIM CORSI (eight-plus years): ``When I think of Nomar, I think
of his athleticism in the field, his work ethic, and his
consistency. I'm also fascinated with his rituals. They are what
help keep him strong mentally. We all have our rhythms and our
superstitions, but no one has as many as Nomar.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more thing: He's truly humble. That's why he doesn't want
to talk about himself.''
</P>
<P>
   MIKE STANLEY (11-plus years): ``Nomar is someone who is bound
and determined to be great. Look at the year he had. (.323, 35,
122, as AL MVP runner-up.) Pretty solid numbers, right? So what
does he do? He comes back here with 10 more pounds of muscle,
because he's not satisfied with himself. Other guys would be
basking in the glory, but Nomar is mature and he is someone who
always wants to be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he a throwback? Well, he's not flashy. He's just a guy who
works hard. He gets in his work and then he gets in his extra work.
He never takes anything for granted. Stars and superstars today
often get in some sort of cruise control, but Nomar always kicks it
into another gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of his continued intensity, he reminds me of a guy I
played with _ Paul O'Neill. Paul's the kind of guy who will hit a
ball off the top of the wall for a double and be cursing because
the ball didn't go out. Nomar has that in him. His will to succeed
is so strong that he is never satisfied. He never gives away any
at-bats. There are guys who will say, `I'd like two hits today,'
and if they get two hits the first two times up they settle for 2
for 5. Nomar would never, ever limit himself in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   DARREN LEWIS (seven-plus years): ``First of all, he is a gifted
athlete. More important to me is the way he goes about his daily
work. He works hard and he is never satisfied. He is very humble,
but he's confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``About not making the All-Star team last year, you'd never know
how he felt from looking at his face because of the type of person
he is, but once the game starts, he's gonna let you know. I think
his play proved how he felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``His conditioning is amazing. I know how hard it is to keep in
shape all year round. I get up every day in the offseason at 6:30
and run with Barry Bonds. I lift. I do what it takes. But I don't
look like Nomar. You can't outwork him. He's out there stretching
and working hard every single day. He truly wants to be a great
ballplayer and he truly loves the game. I've been around a while
now and I don't know that I can compare him to anyone else. He has
his own style. He is unique. He is a true original.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Nomar his teammates see. I'd say that we are lucky to
have him, but I suspect I'd be telling you something you already
know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
