<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVENTION IS THE PRIORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No bombshells are anticipated when the US Olympic Committee's
report on the Salt Lake City scandal is released Monday in New
York. The special investigative commission chaired by Sen. George
Mitchell is expected to focus on what the USOC and future bid
cities can do to prevent a recurrence. The answer, in a word, is
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC has already drawn up tough new guidelines for the
cities vying for the 2012 Summer Games, strictly limiting gifts and
banning early contact with IOC members. But there also must be much
closer (and earlier) supervision of the bidders. The USOC was
profoundly embarrassed when its international relations director
(Alfredo LaMont, since resigned) was revealed to have sold his
services to Salt Lake as a consultant and to have funneled payoff
cash to the IOC member from Barbados.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the first nine members (all but Steve Smith) named to
the US men's basketball team for this summer's Olympic qualifier in
San Juan were on the original (i.e. pre-NBA lockout) roster for
last year's World Championships. Not coming back are Christian
Laettner, Glen Rice, Chris Webber, and Terrell Brandon.
Conspicuously uninvited were Shaquille O'Neal, Allen Iverson, and
Jason Kidd. So the squad includes Grant Hill, Tim Duncan, Vin
Baker, Kevin Garnett, Tom Gugliotta, Tim Hardaway, Allan Houston,
Gary Payton, and Smith. The rest of the roster will come either
from the CBA or college. If the Yanks qualify for Sydney, though,
it'll be an all-NBA team. Which means that the final three guys
will sweat for a dozen days in San Juan in July to earn Olympic
medals for somebody else . . . Looks like Jean-Claude Ganga, the
disgraced IOC member from the Republic of Congo, will be a one-man
protest march when he contests his expulsion before the full body
in Switzerland next month. Ganga had hoped to get his African
colleagues to fall in behind him, but most refused. Ganga, who got
more than $250,000 in cash, medical care, travel, and gifts for
himself and his family from the Salt Lake bidders, is by far the
worst culprit among the two dozen IOC members implicated . . . The
US women's figure skating champion kept out of the World
Championships? It could happen next year. If Naomi Nari Nam, the
current 13-year-old runner-up, were to win the title (which she
could if Michelle Kwan decides to go to college full-time), she
also would have to win a world junior medal to be eligible. That's
why Nam can't go this year and 13-year-old Sarah Hughes can, even
though Hughes placed two spots below her at nationals. The reason
for the loophole in the 15-year-old age limit ``is because the ISU
didn't want really young skaters competing against ladies,'' says
John A.W. Nicks, Nam's coach. ``Some countries were sending 10- and
11-year-olds. The problem here is, you've got a young lady of 13
performing and interpreting music like a 16- or 17-year-old
skater.'' . . . Even though this isn't an Olympic year, attendance
at the recent US Figure Skating Championships in Salt Lake was
absurdly low. The Delta Center, reduced to 10,000 seats, was less
than half-full for every session but the women's final. Reasons
abounded: not a skating town, just one marquee name (Kwan), poor
promotion, and a touring event coming up . . . If the ISU wants a
better field for next year's Four Continents figure skating
championships, it won't sandwich it between the US nationals and
the Grand Prix final. Last week's event, essentially the World
Championships minus the Europeans, was missing both Kwan and
Michael Weiss. A better time would be mid-December . . . Newest
members of the US Figure Skating Hall of Fame include Burlington
brother-sister pair Kitty and Peter Carruthers, who won Olympic
silver in 1984, and two-time Olympian (and Harvard grad) John Misha
Petkevich.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Should be a bump-free ride to the semis next week for the US
women's ice hockey team at the World Championships in Finland. The
Americans, who'll suit up 11 Olympic gold medalists, face
last-seeded Russia, then meet Sweden and China (7-1 and 5-0 victims
at Nagano). Odds are they'll face Olympic podium mates Finland and
Canada in the medal round . . . The Austrian men and women have a
chance at grabbing all but one of the titles when the World Cup
Alpine circuit winds up next week in Spain. Besides dominating the
Nations Cup team standings, they've all but clinched the individual
women's title (Alexandra Meissnitzer), have a chance at the men's
(Hermann Maier is a close third behind Norway's Lasse Kjus and
Kjetil Andre Aamodt), are leading six of the eight disciplines, and
have a chance at grabbing the men's giant slalom. The only bauble
out of reach is the men's downhill, which Kjus has in hand . . . No
overall medals (no surprise) for the US long-track speedskaters at
the recent World Championships. KC Boutiette and Jennifer
Rodriguez, both fifth in the all-around last year, were ninth
despite setting American point records. Boutiette did lower his US
mark in the 5,000, though, (to 6:39.34) and Rodriguez placed second
in the 500. Christine Witty (fifth) and Casey FitzRandolph (10th)
were the top Yanks in the sprint event, but both decidedly
underachieved. The Netherlands's Rintje Ritsma and Germany's Gunda
Niemann-Stirnemann (her record eighth) won the all-around titles,
Canada's Jeremy Wotherspoon and Germany's Monique Garbrecht the
sprints . . . Brookline's Dan Weinstein and Natick's Caroline
Hallisey, as expected, made the US team for the world short-track
speedskating championships next month. The men's squad includes
Apolo Anton Ohno, Rusty Smith, Tommy O'Hare, and Ron Biondo; the
women's includes six-time US champ Amy Peterson, Erin Porter, Julie
Goskowicz, and Sarah Williams. The US women are seeded third
(behind China and South Korea) and the men sixth in next weekend's
team event in St. Louis . . . Excellent World Cup luge season for
the US squad. Mark Grimmette and Brian Martin retained their
doubles title, Chris Thorpe-Gordy Sheer and Chris Niccum-Matt
McClain ended up fourth and fifth overall, and 21-year-old Adam
Heidt placed fourth in singles. The rebuilding American women,
though, never managed a medal (and didn't compete in the final two
events).
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Shocking upset in the recent world four-man bobsledding
championships in Italy, where France (piloted by Bruno Mingeon) won
its first title. It was the first time in 30 years that a country
other than Germany or Switzerland had prevailed; Germany's
Christoph Langen, the heavy favorite, placed sixth. The Italians
(with Guenther Huber) had taken the two-man title earlier.
Creditable showing by the Americans: Brian Shimer was fifth in both
events, with Winchester's Jim Herberich 11th in the two-man and
12th in the four-man. Meanwhile, the US women ended up second (Jean
Racine) and fifth (Jill Bakken) in their World Cup standings . . .
Stunning performance by 21-year-old biathlete Jay Hakkinen, whose
fifth place in last week's World Cup sprint at Lake Placid was the
best showing by an American since Josh Thompson's silver medal at
the 1987 World Championships . . . Russia's financial implosion has
whacked its Olympic medalists in the wallet. The bonuses they were
promised for last year's Winter Games (up to $50,000 for a gold)
haven't come through. ``I'm confident our money was stolen,'' says
ski federation president Anatoly Akentev . . . After picking up
Olympic slots in the Europe and women's 470 classes at the World
Championships in Melbourne, the US sailors have qualified for seven
of the 11 events in the 2000 Games. Still to be earned are Finn,
Star, Tornado, and men's Mistral, but the Yanks are expected to run
the table . . . That restraining order keeping her father at bay
for a year apparently isn't enough for Dominique Moceanu. The
17-year-old gymnast, now training in Colorado Springs, has moved
from Houston to Orlando, where she's asking for another restraining
order. Meanwhile, with Moceanu absent, the gym her father built
with money from her trust fund has gone belly-up and is closing . .
. This summer's women's soccer World Cup will double as the
qualifier for next year's Olympics. The eight quarterfinalists will
make it, unless the host Australians aren't among them. Then, it'll
be the semifinalists and the three losing quarterfinalists with the
best records . . . Look for ice hockey and figure skating to switch
venues for the 2002 Games in Salt Lake. The E Center doesn't have
enough seats for the hockey federation's tastes and the Delta
Center, with its sunken ice surface, has lousy sightlines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 2005EST &QL; 
