</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-RYDERCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COUNTRY CLUB WILL BE THE PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The snow was falling in Brookline Thursday, while the world's
best golfers were competing in the World Golf Championships in
Carlsbad, Calif. The game is offering record purses, and match play
has returned to the picture.
</P>
<P>
   So it was appropriate that John Cornish was talking Ryder Cup in
the grill room at The Country Club as the snow fell. The 33d
biennial competition will be contested at the Brookline course some
six months down the road (Sept. 22-24), and it is turning into one
of Boston's grandest and most lucrative sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Brookline will reap benefits, up to $3 million alone
from the rental fees for tables at the adjacent Putterham Meadows.
The 30,000 tickets were gone by last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were working on master planning this morning,'' said
Cornish. ``We were just trying to figure where everything was going
to be located on the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to have seating for about 18,000
spectators in grandstand seats. We're going to have six Jumbotrons.
They had one at Oak Hill. They had two at Valderrama. We're going
to have a big one on our practice range. It's a difficult spectator
event, and it's hard to follow everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornish, who grew up a few paces from the front entrance at The
Country Club and attended Milton Academy, Harvard, and Georgetown
Law School, is a partner in the Boston firm of Choate Hall &AMP;
Stewart. He has good company in major-event organization. Ken
Burnes, who was general chairman of the US Open at The Country Club
in 1988, was with the firm then. Frank Porter, a current partner,
is president of the Boston Athletic Association and oversees the
organization of the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still moving things around, trying to site all of the
trailers,'' said Cornish. ``It's unbelievable what's going to be
going on here. We're going to have 250,000 square feet of tents.
We're going to have between 60 and 70 trailers. It's amazing the
media interest. This is the biggest event in international golf.
It's the end of the 20th century, and the first was in
Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   The involvement with the Ryder Cup gradually and perhaps
inevitably grew out of Cornish's role as secretary and legal
counsel of The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the PGA of America offered us the Ryder Cup, I was asked
to negotiate the contract,'' said Cornish. ``Once the agreement was
signed, I was asked by the president of the club if I'd be general
chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Cornish was chairman of administration and finance of the
1988 US Open, he fit into the grand scheme of things. He has Burnes
as one of his vice chairmen, plus Peter Barber, who was a fellow
member of the Owl Club at Harvard. Ed White, a member of the Fox
Club at Harvard, is the third vice chairman. You might say the
Ryder Cup has a little of the town (Brookline) and gown (Harvard)
mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a natural thing,'' said Cornish. ``The US Open was a
big success. The USGA came back to us and asked if we wanted to
host the tournament in 1994 or 1995. Even though we wanted to do
it, we decided it was too soon. We decided to get out of the public
eye, and our history has not been to have major tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the 1913, 1953, and 1988 US Opens. The majors we were
doing were major amateur events. We always viewed ourselves as a
club that wanted to host the amateurs. To do something on a large
scale like this was unprecedented. We hosted the US Women's Amateur
in 1902. The only professional events were the three US Opens, so
it was a major step for us to move out of the USGA and MGA arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ultimately decided we should. The principal reason was it
was so much fun doing the 1988 US Open. It wasn't a financial
thing. We felt the US Open really brought this club together.''
</P>
<P>
   Though being general chairman of the Ryder Cup takes
considerable time, Cornish relishes the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is extremely time-consuming, and I find myself
working nights and weekends,'' he said. ``But I don't have any
regrets. Managing a $50 million-$60 million operation is not
something your normal Boston lawyer has a chance to do in a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people here who are working so hard. It's by
no means one person. It's an executive committee of 20 people plus
another 30 chairmen. I think when we first started thinking Ryder
Cup we thought it would be pretty easy to do. What we found is the
Ryder Cup is the 1988 US Open times 10. We had 33 corporate tents.
This year we will have 59 corporate tents and 300 corporate tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of 33 corporate customers we have 250 corporate
customers. The corporate tables are tables of 10. There's 100 at
Putterham Meadows. They're all sold out. We've donated 300 tickets
to the city of Boston. It's going to be packaged up in corporate
sponsorship at Franklin Park. The net proceeds will go to support
youth programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited about creating a fund that will be a
lasting legacy of the Ryder Cup for the Greater Boston community.
The Ryder Cup is going to be a celebration about the game of golf.
We really wanted to do something that will last a long time. We
entered into a community partnership with Brookline, and we're
anticipating it's going to generate $3 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget the residual benefits, forget baseball's All-Star Game at
Fenway Park in July. The Ryder Cup is going to generate huge sums
of money for the town of Brookline, even though some continue to
criticize the membership policies at The Country Club. After all,
how many Irish are members of Belmont CC or Pine Brook?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unprecedented what we're doing,'' said Cornish.
``To run a professional golf tournament, you have to be a
contributor. We view that not only as our obligation, but it's
something we really want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A two-hour documentary called ``The Story of Golf'' will air
March 7 at 4:30 p.m. on WGBH-TV (Channel 2). It is a sensitive,
delightful look at the game's history. As Jim McKay says in the
narration, ``Some say it's only a game, and an odd one at that
involving a stick, a ball, and a hole in the ground. Where it began
no one knows. Its origin is lost in the midst of time. This is a
game shared by fathers and sons, on fields touched with beauty by
the hands of God. Its lure is difficult to define, impossible to
define, an obsession that can last a lifetime.'' The documentary
was produced in part by Cramer Productions, whose founder and
president, Tom ``Red'' Martin, captained the 1960-61 Boston College
hockey team and is one of the region's top senior amateur players,
out of Woodland GC . . . The forthcoming issue of Golf Digest has
an article by Dean Knuth, who created the course rating/slope
rating system for the US Golf Association. For the magazine, he did
a statistical examination of the World Golf Rankings that now
determine who plays in three of the majors and two of the rich
World Golf Championships events. Some feel that many players are
ranked higher than they should be, but when it all comes out in the
wash, he still has Tiger Woods No. 1, David Duval No. 2, and Mark
O'Meara No. 3 . . . The Massachusetts Golf Association has
announced its final tournament schedule, with the State Amateur at
The Kittansett Club July 12-16 and the State Open at Wellesley CC
June 21-23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
