A1793 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PENNYHAR     02-27 1675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PENNYHARDAWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDAWAY DOING THINGS THE HARD WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those anticipating an available and eager-to-relocate Penny
Hardaway this summer, be advised the Magic's magna cum guard is not
eager to leave Orlando, even though there appear to be many reasons
why he could be.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who stopped by last week and submitted his first
scoreless game in memory, made it clear he is expecting to be an
Orlando lifer. That proclamation came even as he talked about
having minimal communication with head coach Chuck Daly and
nonrefundable disenchantment with the team's front office over the
way it handled his injured status a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a charming work environment, right?
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway said he has little if any rapport with Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know me to this day, as a person or a player,''
Hardaway said. ``He doesn't communicate with me, and I don't
communicate with him. He doesn't really talk to anybody. You can go
around this room and ask anybody if they've talked with Chuck one
on one, where he says what he really wants from you. They'll say
no. He just doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Hardaway's comments, Daly shrugged and said, ``I
talk to him on the floor. I talk to him about things necessary to
talk about. He's different about his approach to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway knew Daly was disappointed that he was unable to play
last season and said that upper management even questioned whether
he was hurt, which prompted him to have his situation, and
rehabilitation, handled in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't change my outlook on wanting to be here for the rest
of my career,'' Hardaway said. ``It just changed some relationships
with the general manager and the president, some of those guys.
Once you've been put out on an island by yourself, and no one comes
to your rescue, not even the head coach . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The head coach is supposed to be a guy that comes through for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway mentioned Kenny Anderson's injury of last year and Rick
Pitino's decision not to play Anderson until Anderson got healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever said that for me,'' Hardaway said. ``And I had
definitely been there a lot longer than Kenny had been here. Your
head coach has to stick up for you. With (Daly's) frustrations at
me for not playing, it was like, `You're getting what you deserve.'
''
</P>
<P>
   So he doesn't have a relationship with the coach and he's angry
with the suits for trashing him and for questioning his grit. Why
on earth wouldn't he put a ``For Sale'' sign on his house and get
out this summer under his opt-out clause?
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the things, you'd figure as soon as my contract was
up, I'd be bailing out of there,'' he said. ``But I made
commitments to guys like Bo Outlaw, Ike Austin, Nick Anderson,
Darrell Armstrong, guys that just re-signed their contracts, that I
was going to be here for the rest of my career. So I can't be
selfish and think about myself. I have other guys to think about. I
brought those guys here and I can't just leave them. That's the
reason why I'll be in Orlando. It's not about the money. It's about
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway and the Magic got off to a great start, so, for now,
all is harmonious. Daly, of course, is not the least bit content,
par for the course for the Prince of Pessimism. He quoted a line
from ``Tender Mercies'': ``I don't trust happiness; I never have,
and I never will.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago that Hardaway was getting gold in
Atlanta and was first-team All-Pro for consecutive seasons. Then
came the injuries, which happened to coincide with Shaquille
O'Neal's decision to leave Hooterville and play for the Lakers.
Hardaway played 59 games in 1996-97 and only 19 last season. He had
a couple ill-fated comebacks last season, and Daly was pretty blunt
about his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't know me, and he was going around saying negative
things about me,'' Hardaway said. ``With my injury, I couldn't run
and I couldn't jump. He thought I was out there dogging. All he
wants me to do is go out there and perform, and all I want to do is
go out there and win games. We both have the same thing in common,
and winning cures everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you win, you have great chemistry; when things slip
a little, that's when the test comes,'' said the coach. ``I've
found over the years that as teams get better and improve, they
kind of take on their own direction, internally. I also found when
you have good teams, they start believing how good they are and
they have to come back to you a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the mediocrity in the East, Orlando could just as
easily slide as stay where it is. The Magic have been one of the
surprise teams of this young, down-is-up season. They've got a good
mix, they've got two promising rookies and draft picks down the
road. And, if we believe him, they've also got Hardaway, even if it
sometimes pains him to say so.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to look at the Lakers from afar with anything
other than morbid fascination. Maybe the coaching change to Kurt
Rambis will calm things; it worked the last two times they switched
early in the season. In fact, the last team to make an in-season
coaching change and win the title was the 1982 Lakers, who fired
Paul Westhead (who had won five straight games at that point) and
replaced him with Pat Riley. Since the beginning of the 1981-82
season, there have been 63 in-season coaching changes; only two
teams, the Hawks and Celtics, have not made one. Seven of the
changes, two of them featuring Larry Brown (San Antonio and New
Jersey), removed a head coach with a winning record. But the
Lakers' situation appears to be more than the coaching, and more
than the addition of Dennis Rodman, whom Hardaway lobbied for in
Orlando. ``I really wanted him,'' Hardaway said. ``We have a
veteran team and we could really handle what he had to offer. I
don't know how the Lakers are going to handle it because they have
no control. Rodman isn't going to respect that assistant or whoever
comes in. He needs a veteran coach. You have Kobe (Bryant) and Shaq
(O'Neal), but Shaq is the man on the team. Eddie Jones? If you're
hearing trade rumors three years in a row, and your teammates start
talking about how they can't wait for the trade deadline to get him
out of here, how would you feel? He's one of the best players in
the league and he's out there among some guys that just care about
their numbers.'' . . . Former University of Rhode Island star
Cuttino Mobley has emerged from the flotsam in the Houston
backcourt, relegating onetime starter Matt Maloney to the pine. The
Rockets signed Maloney to a seven-year deal after the lockout, so,
as agent Keith Glass put it, ``That certainly soothes the pain a
little. Eventually, though, Matt is going to start getting a little
antsy. They told him it was a temporary thing and maybe he'll be
back when (Charles) Barkley comes back because with that front
line, the last thing they need is another scorer. They're going to
need a real point guard.'' . . . You're Not in Kansas Anymore
Dept.: The since-injured Raef LaFrentz had a Jayhawk Moment against
the Lakers Monday that could have been a monumental boo-boo. The
Nuggets, leading by 3 in the closing seconds of overtime, had the
ball at halfcourt. LaFrentz went into the backcourt to get free for
a pass from Eric Williams, but Williams was smart enough to know
that that is a violation in the NBA. Williams called time.
LaFrentz's season-ending injury is a killer for the Nuggets, and
given the normal time frame for recovery from a torn anterior
cruciate ligament, he may miss a lot of next season, too. Williams
went through this last year and has recovered. But he's been
bothered by a hamstring problem and didn't play against the Jazz or
Mavericks. ``He tried to play through it,'' said his agent, Mark
Bartlestein. ``He thought it better to take some time out and let
it heal.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Red Auerbach says he won't be visiting the FleetCenter soon, but
he offers this thought on the Celtics: ``We're just actually two
players away from being a highly competitive team. We need a tough
guy, a big banger.'' Someone like Jim Loscutoff? ``Nah, someone
like (Bob) Brannum. He was tougher than Loscutoff.'' . . . Chris
Webber returned with a vengeance to MCI Center Thursday,
registering a triple-double in Sacramento's victory over
Washington. Webber has eight triple-doubles in his career and four
have come against teams that traded him. The other three were
against the Warriors, who, of course, traded him to Washington. And
considering that Golden State and Washington play only twice a
season, Webber didn't have all that many chances to wreak havoc
against his former team. He won't see the Wizards again until next
season. The game, incidentally, did not sell out . . . Separated at
birth: Paul Gaston and Michael Doleac . . . The Clippers' home game
against the Lakers Thursday was played at the Pond in Anaheim and
drew a sellout crowd. Speaking of the Clippers, their winless start
is still not near the NBA record, which is 0-17 by the Miami Heat
in their first year, 1988-89. However, the Clippers did start 0-16
under Bill Fitch in 1994-95 . . . Going into Saturday night, the
Bulls were winless at home, where, against all logic and wisdom,
they continue to draw huge crowds. They also lost their final game
in the United Center last season, Game 5 of the NBA Finals . . .
Chicago coach Tim Floyd was tossed for the first time Thursday,
which also happened to be his 45th birthday. Watching from the
sidelines was Bulls assistant Tex Winter, who was celebrating his
77th, from somewhere, we presume, was Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf,
who celebrated his 63d Friday and, perhaps, on the dish, was
Rambis, who was celebrating his 41st . . . The Suns are averaging
97 points a game, which, if maintained, would be the lowest in
franchise history. Right now, however, that's good for third in the
league.
</P>
</TEXT>
