<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1799 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX     02-27 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER BREATHES A SIGH OF RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The relief was palpable for Jasper's 8,000
residents, who had weathered almost nine months of intense media
scrutiny since the dismembered body of James Byrd Jr. was
discovered and three white men were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   TV crews had packed their gear and rolled out of town as a
light, cleansing rain fell on this weary East Texas community the
day after a jury sentenced a young white man to die for the torture
slaying of a middle-aged black man.
</P>
<P>
   Also gone are the unmarked Suburbans with heavily armed officers
that patrolled the courthouse square during the trial, and the
helicopters that noisily circled the city while students struggled
with their TAAS tests below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is emotionally drained,'' said City Councilwoman
Nancy Nicholson. ``We're just grateful to God for bringing us
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt ending of the closely followed trial of John William
King, the first of three defendants to be tried in Byrd's death,
prompted King's 67-year-old father to call the town's main radio
station, KJAS-FM, to urge Jasperites to ``fill the void made by
this mess with love and tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the respite might be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, and Shawn Berry, 24, are yet to be
tried. One of them might face a jury as early as the first week of
May.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's attorney said he'd prefer to keep the trial in Jasper
where his client was born and, before Byrd's dragging death, was
generally well-liked by blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's attorney said he'd continue to push for a change of
venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reasons are more compelling following (King's) trial, with
the community bombarded by publicity and the local media saying
it's experienced a sense of being purged by the trial,'' said
attorney Douglas Barlow of Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the divisive issue of a 14-year-old middle school
student suspended five times for wearing a Confederate belt buckle
to class. Principal Gwen Gilford said it was insensitive, if not
disruptive, for the boy to wear such a symbol during the King
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The youth's parents say they will protest the suspensions at a
March 8 school board meeting. The Knights of the White Kamellia, a
Vidor-based Ku Klux Klan group, warned that they would demonstrate
in Jasper on March 12 if the buckle matter isn't resolved by then.
</P>
<P>
   But the community has handled both the Klan and the New Black
Panthers before without allowing their public posturing to foment
racial discord.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a unity here,'' said Clyde Williams, 49, a City
Councilman who is African-American. ``It's sort of like a secret
code. We can bicker, we can fight, but don't let any stranger come
in and mess with either one of us because then we'll join forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Byrd's slaying, even the town's oldest residents could not
recall a major racial incident in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Still, white civic leaders who considered themselves racially
sensitive were taken aback by comments raised in a series of town
hall meetings called by Jasper's black mayor to examine community
relations. Some black residents spoke of whites being oblivious to
words and actions that wound African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this murder has heightened the awareness of cultural
differences,'' said Gilford, the middle school principal, who is
black.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with outsiders is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to where people wouldn't say they were from Jasper,''
said H.B. ``Little Boy'' Neal, the 6-foot-4, 84-year-old owner of a
jukebox and billiard table business. ``I'm glad it's over. Of
course, we have two more (trials) to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Even children weren't spared the stigma that the community
carries from its association with Byrd's dragging death.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our cheerleaders went to camp last summer, other girls
said, `Oh, you're from Jasper,' '' said Gilford. ``They were
treated like lepers, in effect saying, `You're white, and that's
where a white man did this to a black man, so you must be mean.'
But once they got to know them, everyone became friends.''
</P>
<P>
   John H. Matthews, 56, spent his earliest years in Jasper, then
came back each summer to stay with grandparents during his youth
and finally returned to live after 26 years as a science teacher in
Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described yellow dog Democrat of the liberal persuasion,
Matthews said that, in one sense, it was almost providence that
such a heinous crime was carried out here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, it's a good thing this tragedy occurred in
Jasper because we're better able than other small towns in East
Texas to cope with it,'' he said. ``And that's mainly because we
have been racially integrated at various levels of government.''
</P>
<P>
   In a town that is 45 percent African-American, its mayor is
black, two of its five council members are black, as are the
director of the Deep East Texas Council of Governments and the
administrator of the largest hospital. A black retired Army
lieutenant colonel, Herman Wright, served 17 years as the school
board president and remains one of the county's most admired
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a small, atypically redneck town can find a white man
guilty of killing a black man, then the message should go out that
racism will not be tolerated,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews readily concedes that Jasper is not perfect. Before
Byrd's June 7 slaying and the subsequent flurry of biracial,
interfaith prayer vigils, he was the sole conspicuous white
marching in the Martin Luther King Jr. Day parade after moving back
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jasperites known to be unapologetic racists have kept a low
profile since June, ]But even they were outraged by the dragging
and dismemberment of Byrd, many residents said.
</P>
<P>
   The only sympathetic note sounded on the killer's behalf was the
grudging respect one man paid John King for standing by his beliefs
_ white supremacist and Norse pagan _ and not feigning a sudden
religious conversion just to save his own neck.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the community has emerged from the ordeal with new
pride and a new, street-level friendliness. Before, he was more
guarded, he said. ``I wouldn't say hello to whites I didn't
personally know. Now I greet everyone, and I am greeted in
return.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole situation arising from the murder could have played
out differently if not for two men, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The black city councilman credited the white sheriff, Billy
Rowles, for ``making the right calls.''
</P>
<P>
   After arresting the suspects within 24 hours, Rowles immediately
requested expert forensic help from the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black community saw there was no hidden agenda _ like
other cases before Rowles came to office,'' Williams said.
``Everything was out in the open.''
</P>
<P>
   The other key personality was Mike Lout, he said. The station
manager and main reporter for the 6,000-watt KJAS, Lout kept the
community indoors and informed during the Klan and Black Panther
rallies, then during all of the developments before and during the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   From the tiny station housed in his small ranch home in a mixed
neighborhood, the 43-year-old Lout filled a vacuum that otherwise
would have been filled by rumor and insecurity, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The town got through without an angry backlash because of the
city's even-handed policies and Lout's reporting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to Mike's news reports was almost a religious act
for Jasper,'' he said. ``Everyone would say, `Did you hear what
Mike Lout said?' The whole community relied on him.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
