<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1809 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      02-27 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKY ROAD LEADS TO COP'S HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ They met at a crack house near Eighth Street and
Hatcher one cold night in February 1998. &QL; 
Police had been watching dealers and users and hookers come and go
for weeks, and now were hoping to shut down the operation, at least
for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Once on the property, they noticed a one-room addition tacked
onto the main building, little more than an storage room with a bed
in it, and decided to check it out. Sgt. Bob Cahill remembers
knocking on the door. A man and woman answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't say much. Then this little guy comes out from
behind them,'' Cahill says. ``He was 3, then, and looked like he
hadn't had a bath in . . . forever. And all he had on was a pair of
shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy said his name was Rocky. The woman, whom police knew
from other busts, was his mother. The man with her wasn't the
father. The boy's father, they were told, was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill has been on the job since 1977. He's a solid brick of a
man who looks like he could play pulling guard for the football
team in his home state, Nebraska. He got a blanket and wrapped it
around Rocky, asking him when he'd eaten last. When Rocky said he
was hungry, Cahill went to McDonald's and bought him a Happy Meal.
</P>
<P>
   That night after work, Cahill told his wife, Tanya, about the
boy. The next day, she bought clothes in Rocky's size and had her
husband drive her, on his day off, to the crack house.
</P>
<P>
   Officers busted the same residence only a week later. The day
after that, Rocky's mother was picked up during a prostitution
roundup on Cave Creek Road. Child Protective Services was notified,
but the boy wasn't removed from the home.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in April, officers stopped a suspicious car leaving the
crack house. Two men were inside, each of them wanted by police. In
the back seat, by himself, was Rocky. &QL; 
`BROUGHT TOGETHER'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you're a religious person or not,'' Cahill
said, ``but I believe sometimes we are brought together with people
for a reason. I felt like that about this little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cahills have two children, one hers from a previous
marriage, one of their own. On the job, the sergeant often sees
kids in crisis. The rule is: Block it out.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, he couldn't. He found out that Rocky had been
removed from the crack house by CPS and was living in a group
foster home. He and Tanya visited him, finding a friendly,
intelligent boy who knew too much about drug use and women who
entertain men in motels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided this kid needs a chance,'' Cahill said. They
applied to be Rocky's foster parents.
</P>
<P>
   There were background checks and classes and paperwork,
paperwork, paperwork. But in time, the boy who once slept on a
crate with a rug on top came to live in a real house and to have
his own bed. &QL; 
`PART OF OUR FAMILY'
</P>
<P>
   At first, Rocky's peculiar brand of English was suited more to
the precinct than to preschool, but, Cahill said, ``we've worked on
that and he's doing fine, now.''
</P>
<P>
   He's moved up to kindergarten, and, at age 5, is thriving. He's
celebrated birthdays and holidays just like they do in real
families. And the Cahills want to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him as part of our family,'' Cahill said. ``He is part
of it. We just want to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing official yet. And the couple have no illusions.
They expect Rocky to have trouble later in life, given what he's
already been through. They're willing to risk it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get more than you give,'' Cahill said. ``And if, by
talking to you, I could get other officers to do what we're doing,
that would make it all worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officers are taught to leave the job at the precinct. To
file it, lock it up, forget about it. Or it'll overwhelm you.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that job, though _ the most important part _ is saving
lives. Luckily for a kid named Rocky, and for all of us, there's
one cop in town who decided to bring his work home with him. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990227.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-HUMMER-COLUMN28-C     02-27 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-HUMMER-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tired Devers finds homecoming sweet
 &HT;    By Steven Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gwen Torrence has faded from the competitive scene,
but it seems that Atlanta is not out of the women's sprint business
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   In a pinch, Gail Devers will do. A two-time Olympic gold
medalist in the 100 meters makes a passable substitute. This isn't
exactly some near beer or imitation soy patty kind of deal.
</P>
<P>
   Having moved into some new suburban Atlanta digs less than four
months ago, Devers established residency just in time to add to the
local domination of the 60-meter dash in the USA Indoor Track and
Field Championships. She and Torrence have titles in five of the
six championships held at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's race was not the most convenient Devers ever ran,
even if it did mean coming home. Competing in Europe this winter,
she only arrived back in Atlanta from Sweden late Friday afternoon.
Her internal clock all gummed up, she got only a little more than
an hours sleep before reporting to the Dome the next morning. She
came with a pillow and a blanket, but never found time for a good
lie-down.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted to get through this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the reports of her strong showings in Europe were not
exaggerated. So strong, Devers could return and win a major U.S.
championship in her sleep. Her time of 7.04 seconds was off a 6.98
she ran last week in France but good enough to hold off Inger
Miller (second at 7.15).
</P>
<P>
   Devers chose Atlanta because it seemed so many of her friends
already were here, including Brian Jordan, the former Falcon and
current Brave. The two knew each other from St. Louis, where Jordan
played with the Cardinals and Devers trained with coach Bob Kersee.
''So, I've still got my training partner,'' Deevers said.
</P>
<P>
   She shopped for a new hometown by feel. ''I've lived in
California and St. Louis. Anywhere I go, I look around and see if
it's somewhere I'd like to be. I just liked it here. The people are
great, very kind. Southern hospitality and all that. It feels like
home,'' Devers said.
</P>
<P>
   And a new civic motto is born: Atlanta _ A Great Place to Hang
your Spikes.
</P>
<P>
   Devers already has a feel for what sells in this area. Her
theory for growing track? ''Bobby (Kersee) is always saying, 'Why
can't track and field be more like NASCAR?' And why not?'' She
means the whole production, from the marketing of personalities to
the courtship of all things corporate.
</P>
<P>
   Could track and field really go for STP decals on the rear
quarterpanel? ''Decals, yeah, everything. It would be cool,'' she
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   As she looked around a Georgia Dome sparsely populated by an
announced audience of 9,810, Devers was struck by a wild fantasy.
''I want to fill up this stadium one day,'' she said. The field
Saturday was excellent, and still the draw was modest. She'll learn
in time that Atlanta is like many other American cities with a long
tradition of resisting track during non-Olympic years.
</P>
<P>
   After sitting out 1998, Devers has stridently announced her
return. There will be no simple handing over of the sprint title to
young Marion Jones. Devers even looks forward to resuming her
career in the 100-meter hurdles saying, ''It's ironic that I had
thought of myself more as a hurdler than a sprinter, and yet all my
medals are in the sprints.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens from here, Atlanta will be happy to hang onto a
piece of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
