<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE RODMAN MIGHT BE FINED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The new power forward with the flaky
reputation became an instant issue for the new coach setting a
no-nonsense tone in their first day of practice together.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman was 20 minutes late to practice Saturday _ his
first full, off-day practice with the Los Angeles Lakers _ and
coach Kurt Rambis said he might dole out a fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily cool. I told the players he's going to be
fined accordingly,'' Rambis said. ``I will find out what's going on
and if it's legitimate, then no harm. And if he was just late, then
he's fined. And I'm fine with the fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's ``Dennis is Dennis'' mantra notwithstanding. But
Rambis said that while the rules apply to Rodman, he will ``have
leeway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a free thinker, and if he wants to do things differently,
I do not have a problem with that, as long as it's within the
structure and the guidelines and the rules that we have set for the
team,'' said Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   Co-captain Shaquille O'Neal had little comment on Rodman's
tardiness, other than to say it was Rambis' problem and that Rodman
``worked hard in practice'' once he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodman's been relatively normal so far. His wackiest move
has been to ask for a stationary bike that he can ride during games
to stay loose when he's not on the floor. He did the same in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're gonna try to get a place for him to put a stationary
bike and ride, which doesn't bother me at all,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach is still mulling whether to start Rodman immediately
or continue using him off the bench and is struggling to find
playing time for everyone now that there are five power forwards on
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry might start sharing small forward duty with Rick
Fox and Kobe Bryant, while Elden Campbell will probably become
exclusively a backup center.
</P>
<P>
   Rambo rules: Rambis used Saturday's brief practice to establish
his coaching style immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like things are different,'' O'Neal said. ``We had a
no-nonsense practice today. Running, running, running. Wasn't much
conversation. Do I like it? Yeah. Great practice. Looks like Kurt
is gonna be a great one. As long as I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis said he wants an environment of ``intense competition and
work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We went at it today,'' he said. ``As a player I wanted to come
in and get my job done. I wanted to work hard and get out. And
that's how I'm gonna approach it as a coach. I want to keep them as
short as possible, still accomplishing all the goals we want to as
a coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting: Rambis found out he was the head coach about 2 p.m.
Friday and had difficulty with some of the subtler changes come
game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I wanted to sit down there was no place to sit,''
he said in mock complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Del Harris never sat down.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Assistant coach) Bill Bertka was complaining he was looking
at my (butt) the whole time. After a while he just said, `Look,
Kurt, when you come back here just stop right here, don't keep
walking in front of me.' I'm gonna have to get some tape or
something ... so I won't cross that line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's a coach's box, too. The referees were telling
me that. I gotta figure out wherever the hell that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Campbell became the fourth Laker to catch the flu
in the past two weeks and missed Saturday's practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
