<P>
   &QL; 
GOP (Sacramento) _ Former Vice President Dan Quayle urged
California Republicans Saturday to stick to their core values on
both economic and social issues, saying calls by other candidates
to soften those ideas is ``a recipe for disaster.'' Quayle had
harsh words for those who have suggested that the GOP moderate its
message, particularly on social issues, to give the party broader
appeal withvoters. By CHRIS MOESER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
JUDGE _ He had it all. At 26, he was the youngest municipal judge
in the country. He had a nice family, a comfortable home in south
Tempe, many close friends, a brilliant mind and an engaging
personality.
</P>
<P>
   He coached his son's soccer team, ran to keep fit and waited
tables for a Leukemia Society fund-raiser. Stephen P. Mirretti Jr.
appeared set for life. But Mirretti had a dark side, too. A
gambling addiction drove him to squander his $104,000 salary as
Tempe's presiding city judge and to steal nearly $2 million from
his employer and from several elderly people on fixed incomes. By
JANIE MAGRUDER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ANTHEM (New River, Ariz.) _ Dozens of towering saguaros dot the
hillsides along Carefree Highway near Interstate 17, and they
always catch the eye of Edward Cramer. For two years now, his drive
to and from home has included sweeping views of mountains, raw
desert land and these saguaros. In another two years, much of what
he sees from his car window will be homes, businesses, a community
center, school and park _ a virtual city within a city. By SUSIE
STECKNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ANTHEM-SIDE _ You've probably seen the child's smiling face on the
billboards as you drive on the freeway. Maybe you've seen the
baseball game and water sports on the television ads in your living
room. Or glimpsed the paintings in the newspaper ads, of a bicycle
and golf tee, schoolbook and baseball gloves. Anthem is coming. BY
CATHERINE REAGOR. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GUNSHOW (Phoenix) _ It doesn't matter to Josie Garcia if President
Clinton wants to require background checks on everyone buying
firearms at gun shows. After all, the Glendale legal secretary
browsing a weekend gun show already owns a revolver. It's the
purses, holsters and other accessories that drew her to one of the
state's biggest gun shows of the year at the Arizona State Fair
Park and Exposition. B Y LAURA TRUJILLO. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
