<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1998 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYONS28-COX     02-27 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYONS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptist leader is convicted
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARGO, Fla. _ Forgiveness for embattled Baptist leader Henry
Lyons will have to come from somewhere other than a jury of his
peers.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, an all-white jury convicted the leader of one of
the nation's largest African-American denominations of racketeering
and grand theft, saying he financed a lifestyle of luxury with more
than $4 million stolen from corporations that wanted to do business
with members of the National Baptist Convention. He also was found
guilty of stealing a $250,000 donation intended to help black
churches burned out by arsonists.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons' co-defendant, Bernice Edwards, was acquitted of
racketeering, the sole charge she faced. Edwards broke down in
tears at the verdict, while Lyons sat stoically at the defense
table, hands clasped.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons, 57, will remain free on bond pending a presentence
investigation, which should take several weeks. He faces up to
seven years in prison, although under Florida guidelines he is more
likely to receive three to five years. Both Lyons and Edwards face
a federal trial later this spring on charges of tax evasion,
extortion and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons' attorneys said they believe he will remain president of
the convention until his term ends in September. But a rival within
the group called for Lyons to resign immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The day of drama began with a bizarre wrinkle. A Tampa-area news
station reported receiving an electronic message from a viewer who
stated that one of the jurors had been overheard discussing the
case outside the courtroom _ a violation of the judge's orders.
Pinellas Circuit Judge Susan Schaeffer questioned the juror, who
denied any such conversation. Schaeffer then denied the defense's
request to declare a mistrial. Lyons came under scrutiny in July
1997 when his wife set several small fires in a $700,000 waterfront
home Lyons purchased with Edwards in an upscale St. Petersburg
neighborhood. Deborah Lyons first told police she suspected her
husband was having an affair, but quickly changed her story and has
since stood by him.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident triggered state and federal investigations that
found Lyons had negotiated several lucrative deals with
corporations that wanted to market credit cards, insurance and
funeral services to the convention's membership. Although most of
the money went into convention accounts, Lyons spent it on luxury
items for himself, Edwards and a California woman who told
convention colleagues she was having an affair with Lyons. The
grand theft allegations were related to money Lyons took as a
donation for his church group.
</P>
<P>
   When a string of black churches across the South were set ablaze
by arsonists in the early 1990s, the Anti-Defamation League of
B'nai B'rith, a Jewish group, stepped forward with nearly $250,000
in donations.
</P>
<P>
   While telling the ADL that all of the money went to the
churches, Lyons put at least $60,000 into his personal accounts,
prosecutors said. He eventually repaid the $250,000, but not until
the criminal investigations were under way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
