<DOCNO> NYT19990227.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHEM-AZR &LR;      02-27 2072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHEM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 NEW COMMUNITIES HOPE TO LURE 100,000 TO EDGE OF VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dozens of towering saguaros dot the hillsides along Carefree
Highway near Interstate 17, and they always catch the eye of Edward
Cramer.
</P>
<P>
   For two years now, his drive to and from home has included sweep
ing views of mountains, raw desert land and these saguaros. In
another two years, much of what he sees from his car window will be
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it all the time when I drive by,'' Cramer said.
``It's like our own little Saguaro National Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Developer Mark Voigt thinks about the saguaros, too.
</P>
<P>
   The desert land where they sit, he said, is ideal for homes,
businesses, a community center, school and park _ a virtual city
within a city that blends with the area's natural features, and a
concept that is being pushed by Phoenix planners to manage growth
that is exploding along I-17 in the north Valley.
</P>
<P>
   As for the saguaros, some will be saved and moved, but others
will remain where they have been for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique piece of property. You need to preserve open
space to create the value,'' said Voigt, president of Communities
Southwest. ``That's where Mr. Cra mer and I really see eye to
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The far north Valley is headed for phenomenal growth, starting
with the new, Flagstaff-size, master-planned community of Anthem
that opens Saturday near New River. The scale of the developments
in the region is massive, even in a metro area that's used to homes
popping up by the thousands virtually over night. In a decade,
100,000 more people could be living in one of the fastest growing
areas in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Just what impact will it have on the area? It depends on whom
you ask.
</P>
<P>
   It's a golden opportunity to shape a mostly untouched area. A
chance to bring jobs and houses to an area at the same time. A
threat to vulnerable desert wildlife and plant life. A traffic and
pollution head ache waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the answer, city offi cials, developers and residents
agree that growth is inevitable and brings with it enormous
challenges. That has city officials vowing to plan every step of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do it now, there is going to be no opportunity to
do it in the future,'' Mayor Skip Rimsza said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The North Black Canyon Corri dor _ which straddles I-17 and
runs from about Happy Valley Road to the city's northern limits _
is one of six areas in the city that is expected to see phenomenal
growth, according to city planners.
</P>
<P>
   By 2020, at a 2 percent growth rate, an estimated 600,000 more
people will call Phoenix home. Of those, as many as 150,000 could
settle in the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 50,000 could live just outside the city's northern
boundary even sooner in Anthem, a master-planned community by Del
Webb Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Anthem project, and three others in development now, com
prise about 9,000 acres _ more than half the size of the
16,000-acre South Mountain Park.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem, which spreads out over 5,800 acres, sits on Maricopa
County land on the east side of the freeway. Eventu ally it could
have as many as 10,000 homes. Other projects are on the drawing
boards in the corridor. A handful are being talked about, but
three, all east of the freeway, are taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   They are Tramonto near Carefree Highway; Dynamite Mountain Ranch
near the Central Arizona Project canal; and an unnamed Sunbelt
Holdings community in between.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the projects comprise more than 3,000 acres. Plans
vary, but they include homes and apart ments, community centers,
parks and some commercial development.
</P>
<P>
   Home buyers could begin moving into the corridor by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   All of the projects wind through land being eyed by Phoenix for
a 15,000-acre desert preserve _ with scenic hillsides and washes, a
mix of plant life and wildlife, and trails for hikers and others.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the area is largely untouched desert, there are many
hands hoping to shape all or part of it. As one person works to
preserve an old unpaved path for horses another maps out a new
six-lane roadway for cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   For almost every supporter of a plan, there is a critic; for
every optimist with a vision, there is a doubter.
</P>
<P>
   All of which, planners say, leaves them with opportunities and
chal lenges. Among them are:
</P>
<P>
   Balancing housing with employ ment to avoid creating a bedroom
community that has people commut ing across the city and Valley to
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Blending houses, businesses and desert.
</P>
<P>
   Adding infrastructure _ water, sewer and roads _ in an area that
has none. That includes accommo dating added traffic on I-17, al
though there are no immediate plans by the state to widen the
freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Providing schools in the already crowded and financially
strapped Deer Valley Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the issues are being addressed in a proposed North Black
Canyon Corridor Plan developed by the city. It calls for changes to
the city's general plan, which would require approval from both the
Plan ning Commission and City Council. A third public hearing
before the commission is scheduled next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area is prime, so prime,'' said Clancy Jayne, a north
Valley resident and chair of the North Gateway Village Planning
Commit tee. ``We've got a blank sheet of paper but we've got to
stay on track.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some who are critical of developing the area.
</P>
<P>
   Some fume about more traffic in the area, and the tax dollars
needed to eventually widen I-17 because of it.
</P>
<P>
   Others are skeptical about pairing master-planned communities
with desert landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really not compatible,'' said Ray Griswold, who lives
just north of Happy Valley Road. ``It's just not economical to put
in something without bulldozing the desert off.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as Chris Gehlker of the Sierra Club suggests, why not
promote more in-fill in the Deer Valley area before opening the
door to development to the north?
</P>
<P>
   ``My immediate reaction is, `Didn't your mother teach you to
clean up one mess before you start another?,' '' said Gehlker, who
works and lives in the north Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's willing to give the development a chance, saying the
city's proposals to manage growth are ``frankly pretty
attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, city officials want growth in the north Valley
to take shape much differently than it has in other parts of the
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see the air quality, the (traffic) congestion and
there's just been such dynamic growth that they say, `How can we do
this better?' '' said Planning Director David Rich ert. ``It is one
of those situations where you have the ability to get ahead of it
or wait and have a crisis situation.''
</P>
<P>
   One key to managing the area, Rimsza notes, is the high impact
fees in the area, which could be up to $10,000 per home. Businesses
also pay impact fees. Such fees are used to offset the cost of
adding infrastruc ture _ which will be a major undertaking in the
north Valley.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the city plans to have a new water treatment plant
near Lake Pleasant, with the first phase open by 2004. The cost of
the first phase, excluding water lines, is more than $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   A water reclamation plant near I-17 and the CAP is planned for
2004. The price tag: $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The city also wants to add Parkway A, a six-lane, north-south
street at about 27th Avenue, from roughly the CAP to Carefree High
way.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arizona Public Serv ice Co. is counting on new substa
tions and power lines, and will be picking future sites with the
help of residents and others.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix officials, as part of the corridor plan, ultimately want
to limit how far they extend infrastruc ture.
</P>
<P>
   A line could be drawn around 8,600 acres from I-17 to Seventh
Avenue and the CAP to the northern city boundary. Infrastructure
wouldn't go past that line for 10 years, or until 65 percent of the
area is developed to discourage hop-scotch growth.
</P>
<P>
   And city planners say they won't allow unlimited rooftops
either. They are pushing for a regional job and housing center that
would keep residents from clogging the freeway and adding to air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't build a bedroom community,'' said Jayne, who lives
near 19th and Beardsley avenues. ``That can't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   To get a balance, the number of jobs in the area would
ultimately be equal to 75 percent of the residen tial population.
</P>
<P>
   Richert said access to the freeway and Deer Valley airport is
key to attracting employers, as is establish ing a housing base
with the three projects in the works now.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he said, the city can help market the area, as well
as work with local universities and schools to provide a labor
force. By tying housing growth to employ ment, developers may even
be prompted to help bring in jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether employers will come is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   One business may look for a remote location _ high-tech firms in
the past have chosen such sites, said Tom Rex, a research manager
for ASU's Center for Business Research.
</P>
<P>
   Another business will need to be closer to a large population
base and a big airport like Sky Harbor International. Yet another,
such as a call center with lower-paid employ ees, could be
interested but find that housing is too expensive for the staff.
</P>
<P>
   While planners tackle growth, some land owners are taking issue
with certain recommendations by the city to manage it.
</P>
<P>
   One sticking point is a proposal in the corridor plan to
restrict development in the floodplain and leave washes natural.
</P>
<P>
   When Lynn Johnson bought his 14-acre parcel 10 years ago, the
city's stance was to restrict develop ment in the floodway rather
than the entire floodplain. Now, Johnson fears losing about 80
percent of his property.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my retirement,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Another land owner, Plateau Ven ture, with about 120 acres, has
about half its land in the floodplain.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Quay, the city's assistant planning director, said the
proposal to restrict development in certain areas is needed for
flood control.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're saying is, we don't want to allow you to encroach
on the floodplain knowing that we would have to do some structural
solution downstream to solve flood ing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the city's corridor plan, officials say it's critical
to blend development with the area's natural features.
</P>
<P>
   The city's ideas?
</P>
<P>
   Build homes facing the preserve, instead of having them back up
to it. Wind roads along the preserve. Keep washes natural. Build
tradi tional parks near the preserve, giving easy access to the
desert while creating a buffer zone be tween development and the
desert.
</P>
<P>
   Such guidelines are critical for the area, Robin Mofford said.
</P>
<P>
   Mofford holds titles like planning commissioner and Deer Valley
Vil lage Planning Committee chair woman, but she's also a longtime
resident who remembers taking her kids on rides through the desert
on all-terrain vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could go to the end of the street, go across the desert
into Cave Creek Wash and just take off,'' she said. ``Now we have
to hitch everything up and find out where we're allowed to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But she's not anti-growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all of us hate to lose our desert or our natural
areas,'' Mof ford said. ``We're saying, `If you're going to develop
your land, we would like to see it fit into the picture.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And that's possible, according to Bruce Swanson, the city's
Sonoran Preserve manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a way that you can meet in the middle on this
and really do a nice development that is sensitive to the land
around it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Griswold isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-year-old Arizona native was raised on a 25-acre spread
north of the CAP canal. He now lives on 2.5 acres north of Happy
Valley Road, and frets about losing the desert land and its
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a deer herd, lots of javelina and bobcats,'' Griswold
said. In his own backyard, he's spotted ``all three foxes that live
in Arizona . . . they're just beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Pam Letner has called home a one-acre lot in the
county near Jomax Road. She's also seeing the world around her
change from rural to what-the-heck-is-coming-now?
</P>
<P>
   Letner wonders how planners will balance it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The land is part of us. We want someone to make sure it's done
right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
