<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2043 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHEM-SIDE-AZR &LR;      02-27 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHEM-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN INTERSTATE 17 SUPPORT MAJOR DEVELOPMENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the predictions come true, tens of thousands more people
could be moving into new homes in the far north Valley _ bringing
with them cars and the need to get up and go.
</P>
<P>
   Just how far, and how often, is the question for traffic
planners.
</P>
<P>
   City officials vow to balance the homes with jobs, while
developers hope to create minicommunities complete with schools,
parks and businesses. All of which, they say, will help keep people
from making long commutes, and avoid traffic snarls and added air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that happens remains to be seen. But even if it does,
some are looking for major improvements in an area they say is
already burdened without the added rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   The city has dubbed the area the North Black Canyon Corridor,
which straddles I-17 and runs from about Happy Valley Road to the
city's northern limits.
</P>
<P>
   At least three master-planned communities are being developed in
that area; Del Webb's 5,800-acre Anthem project sits to the north,
just outside the city's limits.
</P>
<P>
   The focal point of traffic worries is Interstate 17. The Arizona
Department of Transportation is currently widening a portion
between Thomas and Peoria roads from six to eight lanes, which
includes two HOV lanes. Between Peoria and Deer Valley road, it's
six lanes plus HOV lanes, then four lanes north to the city's
limits.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 200,000 vehicles travel on I-17 daily, with more in
some spots, according to 1997 ADOT figures, the most current
available.
</P>
<P>
   Some want I-17 widened in the north Valley, but that's not
likely before 2020, according to ADOT plans. And that has some who
live and work in the area asking, ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic on I-17 is bumper-to-bumper now and on the weekends,''
said Clancy Jayne, a north Valley resident and chair of the North
Gateway Village Planning Committee. ``This is not rocket science.
2020? Give me a break.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is funding, ADOT spokesman Bill Rawson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is certainly aware that I-17 is going to be at
capacity in the future, particularly as development starts to pick
up there,'' he said. But ``we can't do it if we don't have the
funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about significant, significant expenditures.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a current ADOT study, state planners would like to
see I-17 widened from Loop 101 as far north as New River.
</P>
<P>
   They envision eight to 10 lanes, including HOV or toll express
lanes. Two new interchanges would be needed between Happy Valley
Road and Carefree Highway, and a third between Carefree Highway and
Desert Hills Road, recently renamed Anthem Way.
</P>
<P>
   Park-and-ride lots could be added along the way, with direct
ramps to and from the freeway's HOV or express lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Rawson called the number of projects planned along the freeway
``staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city is planning for three major roadways as
development begins to fill in the corridor in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Parkway A would run to the east of I-17 and Skunk Creek Wash. It
would begin at Happy Valley Road, at about 19th Avenue and then
curve slightly to follow the 27th Avenue alignment up north almost
a mile past Carefree Highway. Eventually, it could go farther
north.
</P>
<P>
   City planners envision a six-lane parkway, with a landscaped
median. Only four lanes may be built initially.
</P>
<P>
   The parkway is key, planners say, to help develop the central
part of the corridor, alleviate traffic on I-17 and provide another
north-south route in case of accidents or other problems on the
freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city sees that as an employment and retail core,'' said
John Siefert, a city traffic engineer. ``We don't want people
living up near Carefree Highway having to commute to Phoenix and
get caught up in that ornery I-17 traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other six-lane streets would run east-west, with one along
Dove Valley Road and the other at Lone Mountain Road.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, planners could consider building the streets as
far east as Cave Creek Road, Siefert said. But as the streets
entered a proposed desert preserve area, they would be joined so
that only one goes through the preserve. The streets could then be
split at the eastern edge of the preserve and continue on. &QL; 
Susie Steckner can be reached at 444-7129 or at
susie.steckner(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
