<HEADLINE>
WILL BUYERS SALUTE FOR NEW TOWN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've probably seen the child's smiling face on the billboards
as you drive on the freeway. Maybe you've seen the baseball game
and water sports on the television ads in your living room. Or
glimpsed the paintings in the newspaper ads, of a bicycle and golf
tee, schoolbook and baseball gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Far in the northwest Valley, emerging in the midst of a desert,
on the northern fringe of the Valley, a new community is emerging.
</P>
<P>
   And Del Webb, the developer that built its reputation on the
foundation of the Sun Cities retirement communities, is hoping that
residents will flock to what it billing as its first fully equipped
master-planned community for families.
</P>
<P>
   Ken and Mary Miller are on a waiting list that's 1,000 names
long with people from around the country who are willing to give up
time, gas money, and wear and tear on their cars in exchange for
living in development they hope will offer a city-full of places to
work, shop and play. Ken Miller says he wants to live there, even
though it means driving 46 miles a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to have everything. It will be like living in a
brand new town, and that's worth a longer drive,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Within a decade, Anthem is expected to have 50,000 residents,
making it a community the size of Flagstaff. The first buyers may
come Saturday, at an opening to tour the development.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem will have the basic offerings of a small city, including
a school, fire station, large central park and community center,
grocery store and health center, all done before the first resident
moves in late this summer. That's a rarity for most developments,
which usually build homes first and bring in the amenities later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthem is the antithesis of sprawl. It's the best researched
and planned community in the Southwest,'' analyst R.L. Brown said.
``Del Webb is building a new town, and it's paying for all the
infrastructure and creating all the amenities it takes to make it a
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is as ecstatic. A few year ago, when the
development was proposed, critics crowded planning hearings to say
it would destroy the desert, drain water resources, strain already
overcrowded schools and further clog traffic-jammed roads.
</P>
<P>
   Del Webb has tried to counter some of that criticism by
shouldering some of the financial burden.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lucas, general manager of Del Webb, said the company will
spend $180 million on construction and communities before the first
resident moves in.
</P>
<P>
   Del Webb is spending $66 million on the project's
infrastructure. It is building a water-treatment plant for the
project, funding the $12 million construction of a freeway
interchange off I-17 and donating the land and $9 million to build
Anthem's first K-8 school.
</P>
<P>
   The developer also is donating 50 acres for a high school and
will provide land for two elementary school sites at 50 percent of
the appraised value to the Deer Valley district. Developers' paying
for school construction is highly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Valley school officials are thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthem has truly raised the level of what developer commitment
to the community is all about,'' said Gerald Cuendet,
superintendent of the Deer Valley district.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry Disimone of the Save New River Coalition said he's
``horrified'' by the small number of schools planned for the
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``A community the size of Anthem should have nine schools,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   New River is the nearest neighbor to the project. It's a town
known for attracting rugged individualists and quirky characters
and an area where the biggest business is a nudist colony and
plumbing is usually a septic tank.
</P>
<P>
   Monty Gregory doesn't care that Del Webb will bring groceries or
doctors closer to his home in New River, which he built himself
over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I built a home out here to get away from that kind of stuff,
and now they are destroying the desert and bringing it all to my
front door,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't give a hoot about how nice the houses are supposed to
be or how much stuff it will have,'' said the self-employed plumber
who came here from New York to live in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   But others in New River welcome Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up here, and when I first heard about Del Webb's plans
I was a little apprehensive,'' said Mary Beth Baker, outgoing
president of the Desert Hills Improvement Association and vice
president of Desert Hills Water Co.
</P>
<P>
   But it's obvious that growth is heading north, she said, and a
master-planned community is one of the best ways for the land to be
developed.
</P>
<P>
   However its neighbors feel about it, Del Webb is intent on
attracting potential buyers by trying to provide them with
everything they may ever need.
</P>
<P>
   It has lots of competition for home buyers' dollars: Of the
36,000 new homes to sell across metro Phoenix last year, more than
40 percent were in master-planned communities.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem comes at a time when Valley home buyers are choosier.
Home building analysts say buyers want a lot more than what they
got from a new master-planned community five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Golf courses used to be the top amenity, but now those have
taken a backseat to open space, hiking trails, workout rooms and
schools.
</P>
<P>
   In Anthem, there also will be swimming pools and water slides, a
rock climbing wall, a mini railroad, a catch-and-release fish pond
and an intricate trail system reaching out to every home.
</P>
<P>
   For jobs that residents may fill, about 30 companies have
contacted the developer about moving operations to Anthem, said
Anne Mariucci, senior vice president of Del Webb. The first ones
are expected to be announced within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Del Webb also is partnering with Samaritan Health to provide
health-care services.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Samaritan will set up a temporary site, but as the
community grows, a free-standing health center offering a range of
medical and urgent-care services will be built.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem also will offer a range of home styles so that a glance
down a street reveals something more than a row of pink stucco.
Homes will range from $100,000 to more than $500,000 gated homes,
complete with wine rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem near New River is the second of the company's
``multigenerational'' projects, but the first to be designed from
the ground up. An Anthem community opened outside Las Vegas last
year, but it originally was designed as a retirement community and
doesn't include all of the family-oriented draws designed for
Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem is downplaying the traffic concerns, billing it as only a
20-minute drive from central Phoenix. But it usually takes twice
that long in non-rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   There are plans to widen I-17 as the community grows over ten to
20 years, but road and freeway improvements are expected to lag
behind the residential buildup.
</P>
<P>
   The longer drive or potential traffic jams don't deter Miller.
He counts it almost as another amenity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be that far out. It'll be like being a modern-day
pioneer in an area that some day will be huge,'' he said. &QL; 
 &UR; Catherine Reagor can be reached at 444-8040 or at
catherine.reagor &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
