<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAND FIRM' TO CORE VALUES, QUAYLE URGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Former Vice President Dan Quayle urged California
Republicans on Saturday to stick to their core values on economic
and social issues, saying calls by other candidates to soften those
ideas is ``a recipe for disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle had harsh words for those who have suggested that the GOP
moderate its message, particularly on social issues, to give the
party broader appeal with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the delegates at the California GOP convention are
despondent over the drubbing the party took at the hands of
Democrats in November, and some have suggested the party's
positions on abortion, gay rights and immigration contributed
greatly to the losses.
</P>
<P>
   But where fellow Arizona presidential candidate John McCain on
Friday evening invoked the names of Republican Presidents Abraham
Lincoln and Theodore Roosevelt, Quayle called on his party to
revitalize the coalition of economic and social conservatives that
elected Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should stand firm for what we believe in. We are the ones
that want to cut taxes and promote freedom,'' Quayle said in an
interview before his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not back down. Now is not the time to be timid. Now is
not the time not to have a backbone. Now is not the time to run
away from our core principles that have done rather well over the
years, especially for Ronald Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited tax cuts, smaller government, education reform, and
``sanctity of life'' as issues Republicans should support.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle singled out GOP congressional leaders for criticism,
blasting their decision to backtrack on tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed from what I read and hear coming out of
our Washington leadership. They appear to be walking away from the
10 percent, across-the-board tax cut, and that's a mistake,'' said
Quayle, who is pushing a 30 percent across-the-board tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look like they are going to increase federal spending,
which is a mistake. If in fact the Republican leadership runs away
from a tax cut and increases spending, they're going to create a
trust deficit with the American people _ I'm saying, `Don't back
down. Get a backbone. Hang in there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bill Clinton vetoes these bills, so what? That's what it's
all about in divided government. Try to override his veto.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle dived headlong into the issue of abortion, which has
ripped apart the California GOP in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated calls for a ban on so-called ``partial-birth''
abortions, which he said is supported by 85 percent of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's start with that. There should be consensus on that
issue, and it should not be a divisive issue in the Republican
party. Let's get on with it. It's an important issue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's speech was a sharp contrast to Friday's address by
McCain, who avoided thorny issues like abortion but emphasized the
need for the party to be inclusive, particularly in welcoming
Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech drew a generally tepid response from the
predominantly conservative delegates at the California Republican
Convention. His strongest applause lines came when he called on
Republicans to refrain from attacking each other in the primaries
and when he blasted President Clinton's plans for Social Security
reform.
</P>
<P>
   But he raised eyebrows by declining to talk about abortion,
which is dominating the convention as moderates and conservatives
battle for control of the party.
</P>
<P>
   His pledge to campaign for the Latino vote also received a cool
response, especially when he suggested that the ``politics of
division'' had cost the California party Hispanic voters in recent
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a well-crafted speech, but not for this audience,''
said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a senior associate at the School of
Politics and Economics at Claremont Graduate School. She added that
McCain may have erred by not talking about abortion and other
favorite conservative issues, such as gun rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a response of polite acceptance to the speech,''
Bebitch Jeffe said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fact that McCain may not have helped himself with the
party's conservative base became more evident Saturday when
delegates staged a rally urging Texas Gov. George W. Bush to enter
the race. If Bush decides to run, McCain will likely have to wrest
control of the political center away from Bush to win the race.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pacheco, who became the first Hispanic to win a
California Assembly seat in the 60th District in November, remains
convinced that Bush is the candidate that best understands Latino
issues, despite McCain's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco is one of four Latino Republicans in the California
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   McCain vowed to fight for the Latino vote in California,
pointing out that he received 55 percent of the Hispanic vote in
Arizona in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their support is my honor. They believe in me, and I believe
in them. I want their help to build a better country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pacheco says it's Bush who has the better record on Latino
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have met Senator McCain. . . . I admire the man. He is a
very fine gentleman. He has a lot of great qualities,'' said
Pacheco, who signed a letter with 25 other Assembly members last
month urging Bush to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we have a contest for president that is going to
require the very best candidate, and I think Governor Bush is the
guy. The reason for that is, he's established a record already.
It's more than just saying, `I'm going to reach out.' That's what
the Republican party has been saying for years. Governor Bush now
has a track record in doing it. That's different.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Sanchez of Alameda, Calif., said he liked McCain's message.
But he still prefers Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mind seeing McCain on the ticket,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't know if he's the man to lead it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to McCain's speech seemed to break along the battle
lines of the fight for control for the party. Moderates gushed,
while conservatives were more reserved.
</P>
<P>
   Selevendra Thurairajah, a conservative delegate from Los
Angeles, called McCain ``out of touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurairajah is a strong supporter of California's Proposition
187, an anti-immigration measure, and he was critical of McCain's
comments on Latino issues.
</P>
<P>
   Another delegate, Bob Strawn of Pleasanton, Calif., said McCain
should have talked more about social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Gillette, a self-described moderate from San Diego, said he
was thrilled to hear McCain's inclusive message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been disenfranchised for the last 10 years, so I am
delighted to see a rational voice emerge,'' Gillette said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
