<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI QUIETS PUNCHLESS TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Missouri and the coach who most likes to rag on
the Lone Star State's additions to the Big 12 wiped the
championship smile off the face of the Texas Longhorns yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers (20-7, 11-5) took advantage of Texas' punchless
offensive performance to hand the regular-season champs a 54-47
loss before an announced Erwin Center-sellout crowd of 16,175.
</P>
<P>
   The loss proves little more than an irritant as far as next
week's Big 12 tournament is concerned, but made for a somewhat
hollow postgame trophy presentation for the No. 22 Longhorns
(18-11, 13-3), who retain the No. 1 seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing to lose this game, but the Big 12
championship makes up for that,'' said forward Kris Clack, who
scored seven points and had four turnovers. ``It does let us know
we can't let up; that we've got to continue to play the way we have
all year. Let down a little bit and someone can take it from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri did just that from the outset, when all-conference
forward Albert White poured in 13 of his game-high 23 points in the
first eight minutes. The Tigers also clogged the middle with
6-foot-11, 335-pound center Monte Hardge and forced Texas to
generate offense from outside. The Longhorns couldn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud of our defense all day long. That was the
difference in the ballgame,'' said Missouri coach Norm Stewart,
whose team enhanced its NCAA at-large attraction and assured itself
of a first-round bye in the Big 12 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to congratulate Texas on winning the championship. I'm
sure today was a disappointment for them, but . . . they'll get
ready for the tournament. They're an NCAA ballclub and will be a
great representative as will other teams in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas committed 21 turnovers and reached the foul line only nine
times, robbing the Longhorns of their characteristic free-throw
advantage. Gabe Muoneke led with only 11 points. Center Chris Mihm
scored 10 and had 16 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team these are the kind of basketball games you see
this time of year when teams are equally matched,'' UT coachRick
Barnes said. ``You'll see games slowed down like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play excellent defense and don't give up easy baskets in
transition. But you've got to execute and have guys making shots
when the defense is on them. And you absolutely cannot make 21
turnovers. We did turn it over a couple of times trying to force it
in, but you can't go away from what you need to do. But we do need
to knock down our shots from the perimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas was only 10-for-26 in the second half and led only twice,
the last at 45-44. But Missouri's John Woods knocked down a
deciding 3-pointer with 1:53 to play and the Tigers went up 50-45
before Texas scored again.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes did not express undue concern about the
less-than-championship performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll fix it,'' he said. ``They'll do what they've done all
year _ learn from their mistakes. I told them, better today than
later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
