<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-N.C.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE MAKES THINGS CLEAR IN THE ACC 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARRY JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Duke, bidding to become the first Atlantic Coast
Conference team in a dozen years to go through the league without a
loss, took little more than a half to seize control during a visit
to North Carolina's Dean E. Smith Student Activities Center Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a crushing 81-61 victory, the first by the Blue
Devils at Chapel Hill in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Duke pushed its record to 29-1 and became the first team to go
16-0 during the ACC regular season. The league expanded to nine
teams in 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember a team that has been such an odds-on favorite
to win the national championship as they are,'' said Bill
Guthridge, the North Carolina coach. ``They're just really, really
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the 24th in a row for the Blue Devils since they
lost to Cincinnati in late November in the finals of the Great
Alaska Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   No. 14 North Carolina, the ACC's third-place team, dropped to
22-8 and 10-6 in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina started the second half as it had the first,
getting the ball inside to center Brendon Haywood, whose basket
tied the score at 35-35 after just 43 seconds had elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   But that proved to be the closest the Tar Heels would come.
</P>
<P>
   Duke immediately responded with a lay-in by its center, Elton
Brand. The Tar Heels scored a single basket over the next
six-and-a-half minutes as the Blue Devils pushed their lead to
46-37 with 13 minutes 41 seconds to go on a layup by guard William
Avery off an inbound pass.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina responded with two baskets, cutting the margin to
5 points barely a minute later on a tap-in by guard Ed Cota.
</P>
<P>
   Unruffled, the Blue Devils went on a 22-6 run, controlling the
boards at both ends as they pushed the lead to 68-47 with 5:25
remaining. Duke cruised the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Duke used its superior quickness to dissect the Tar Heel defense
and to win a decisive edge in rebounds. The bigger North Carolina
team increasingly resorted to jumpshots, with diminishing returns.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils, who inflicted the most decisive home defeat on
the Tar Heels since they opened the Smith Center in 1986, won
without Shane Battier, one of their top rebounders and defenders.
The sophomore starting forward sprained his ankle in Duke's
previous game, a victory over DePaul. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither team led by more than one basket through the first 12
minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, breaking the fourth tie of the game, 19-19 at 9:42 of the
first half, Duke mounted a 10-1 run. Most of the damage was done
inside by Brand and the freshman wing Corey Maggette, each of whom
had had 4 points during the spurt.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 29-20 with 5:30 left in the half, North Carolina
Coach Bill Guthridge called a 20-second timeout, which seemed to
settle his squad.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels scored 7 unanswered points in the next two
minutes, capped by a jumper in the lane by Cota that cut the Duke
lead to 29-27. Cota led the Tar Heels with 10 points in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Maggette immediately responded with a long 3-pointer, and the
Blue Devils pushed the lead back to 35-29 on a Maggette follow-up
shot with 1:21 remaining in the half. He had 9 points in the
period.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina closed with a rush, and nearly took the lead
before halftime. But Cota's 3-pointer with 0.6 seconds left was
ruled to have come after he stepped out of bounds, and Duke
retained its 35-33 edge.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils had the advantage in rebounds, 24-19, and led at
the half despite only 7 points combined from Brand and Trajan
Langdon, their leading scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, North Carolina got most of its scoring from Haywood,
the Tar Heels' 7-foot, 263-pound center who dwarfed Duke's
defenders. The Blue Devils relied instead on their 3-point shooting
and the interior scoring of Chris Carrawell, the 6-6 forward.
</P>
<P>
   Duke entered the game on a 23-game winning streak, matching the
longest undefeated run in school history. The Blue Devils beat
North Carolina in their previous meeting this season, 89-77.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils are among the most dominant Atlantic Coast
Conference squads ever. Bidding to become just the eighth team to
go through the league undefeated, they've won conference contests
by an average margin of 24.6 points. Duke is fueled by the nation's
most potent offense _ it leads Division I in scoring (93.7) and
scoring margin (25.7), and is second in field goal percentage
(.517).
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, in contrast, has been erratic this season,
relying heavily on young players and enduring a series of injuries
that disrupted the lineup. The Tar Heels survived overtime to win
their two previous games, against Virginia and Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   But an ankle injury that sidelined the 6-8 forward Shane
Battier, Duke's best off-the-ball defender, significantly reduced
the Blue Devils' edge. Post defense is perhaps Duke's only
consistent weakness, and interior scoring is North Carolina's
greatest strength. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
