<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ON-HOLD-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OR ELSE': WEST CRIES WOLF; SERBS OUTFOX BOMBERS _ FOR NOW  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 725-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 27 February 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Or else. That is what the West told the Serbs and ethnic
Albanians gathered in the French chateau of Rambouillet for an
extended fortnight of negotiations this month: agree to the West's
plan for NATO-policed autonomy for Serbia's southern province of
Kosovo, or else.
</P>
<P>
   Or else what? Well, if the Serbs say no, we'll bomb them. And if
the Kosovars say no? Er, well, they won't. And if both say no? Er,
well, awkward that. Then we'll all have to meet again in three
weeks' time. And so they will.
</P>
<P>
   This episode, so embarrassing to the West after all its
ultimatums, should be a reminder that no diplomat has ever lost
face by underestimating the conciliatory nature of the Balkan
politician.
</P>
<P>
   Not, it should be said, that on this occasion it was the Serbs
who took the prize; their dilemma _ whether to yield to western
pressure just before or just after NATO started bombing _ was
miraculously solved for them by the Kosovars' refusal to put their
signature to the western plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the outside world should by now know that, however
appallingly the Serbs behave, the political leadership of those
they oppress is seldom wise, and almost never admirable.
</P>
<P>
   If a three-week delay results in a few more Serb atrocities in
Kosovo, whether provoked or unprovoked, that may suit some
ethnic-Albanian politicians: they will calculate that another
massacre or two can only strengthen their claim to outright
independence for the province.
</P>
<P>
   But such a reckoning can hardly suit the slaughtered Kosovars,
or those who are trying to bring peace to this wretched region.
</P>
<P>
   For the West, the loss of face must be counted an unfortunate
cost of trying to reach a settlement, but that does not mean the
effort should never have been made.
</P>
<P>
   No peace will be won without risks, and the risks _ and
embarrassments _ involved in doing nothing outweigh those of trying
to find a solution and, in the process, suffering rebuffs.
</P>
<P>
   To let the Serbs continue their brutal treatment of the ethnic
Albanians would be to declare that the western democracies, for all
their talk of human rights, would do nothing to end an egregious
example of oppression on their doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   What hope then for those farther afield? And what of the dangers
to neighboring countries should the fighting spread?
</P>
<P>
   So, if good is to come of this setback, it may be in the opening
of western eyes and the stiffening of western spines. Bringing the
two sides to an agreement may not, in the end, involve air strikes,
but it will certainly involve a large deployment of troops on the
ground, probably for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   Those troops may be attacked, and some may lose their lives:
better to say it now, and be prepared for it, than to exclaim at
some later date that such an eventuality was never part of the
commitment, and the troops must come home.
</P>
<P>
   Western Europe's interest in this is clear. America's may be
less so. Yet America has a powerful interest, not just in peace in
Europe, the home of its traditional and still strongest allies, but
also in seeing democratic values upheld.
</P>
<P>
   In places like the Balkans, that means not only conventional
diplomacy but also the threat of force, and therefore, if that
threat is to be credible, a readiness to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, even in an age of technological wizardry, force
cannot be assured of success without the possibility of suffering
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   How much better, however, if the threat of attack is not put to
the test. When the parties reassemble on March 15, the best outcome
would be a swift agreement all around that made air strikes
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   To get the Serbs to accept that may mean persuading the Russians
to cajole them to agree to a NATO-led force in Kosovo with a big
Russian contingent. To get the Kosovars to accept may mean
explaining that they will get no western help if they do not take
what is on offer now: that is the ``or else'' for them.
</P>
<P>
   For the West, however, the ``or else'' will be an even bigger
loss of face. With NATO approaching its 50th-anniversary party in
April, that would be serious. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
