<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-TULSA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROGS FALL TO TULSA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU coach Billy Tubbs bristled, his patience
finally stretched too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to know how I feel right now, about me or my
basketball team or anything else,'' Tubbs said. ``I'm not a real
happy fella.''
</P>
<P>
   Two numbers _ 82 and 73 _ brought about his less-than-chipper
mood.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa defeated the Horned Frogs by that score yesterday at
Daniel-Meyer Coliseum, bumping them from a No. 3 to a No. 4 seed in
the Western Athletic Conference Tournament and leaving their hopes
for an at-large berth in the NCAA Tournament very much up in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely played a team that is very capable of going and
winning the WAC Tournament or at least winning two games,'' Golden
Hurricane coach Bill Self said. ``But I think TCU has probably got
to win a couple of games out in the WAC Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU (19-9, 7-7 WAC) begins by playing Pacific Division No. 5
seed BYU or San Jose State at 4:30 p.m. Tuesday, pending the
results of last night's games. If TCU wins, No. 12 Utah will be
waiting in the second round Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two victories in the WAC Tournament coupled with its Ratings
Percentage Index of 28 will likely get the Horned Frogs an NCAA
Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   RPI is a computer-generated rankings system that factors in
Division I winning percentage, schedule strength and opponents'
schedule strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a strange year. I'm going to quit trying to
figure things out,'' Tubbs said. ``The \RNCAA Tournament selection
committee\S has a very tough job this year because there are too
many teams like TCU.''
</P>
<P>
   And TCU has had too many games like yesterday's.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs started slowly, trailed by as many as 16 points
in the first half and were behind 43-33 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Tulsa's lead was only 76-73 with 43 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa's Greg Harrington let loose a wild attempt that bounced
high off the iron. Hurricane forward Eric Coley, despite giving
four inches to Marquise Gainous, came down with the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of 39 Golden Hurricane rebounds. The Frogs had 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good boxing-out team,'' Coley said. ``We just went
out and wanted it a little bit more, I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley led Tulsa with 20 points and 11 rebounds while Michael
Ruffin contributed 17 points, nine on free throws. Tulsa (21-8, 9-5
WAC) was 19-of-21 from the free-throw line. The Frogs attempted
only 16.
</P>
<P>
   It was a difference that didn't go over too well on the Frogs'
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to let us play physical, let us play
physical,'' Frogs guard Prince Fowler said. ``It should go both
ways, not one way.''
</P>
<P>
   WAC supervisor of officials Bobby Dibbler was at the game, and
afterward, TCU assistant coach Brian Fish approached him and said:
``Coach wants to see you.''
</P>
<P>
   Dibbler and Tubbs had a postgame chat in Tubbs' office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be in El Paso this summer, and we were wanting to
play some golf,'' Tubbs deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   TCU coaches had been screaming at Dibbler all game, upset that
play had become too physical, and that the referees were letting it
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't one of the more physical games that we played
in,'' Self said. ``The way I'm sure Billy sees it differently is
you have to guard Nailon by laying on him because he's great at
laying on you. ... Whoever is guarding Lee is going to have
contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said: ``Knock the hell out of him is the way they guard
him. That's exactly what they did. But hey, what's new?''
</P>
<P>
   Nailon finished with 20 points to lead TCU.
</P>
<P>
   He rested his head on his hand during postgame interviews. His
voice was low and unemotional. He looked very much like a player
resigned to the fact that the Frogs can't seem to catch a break
this season.
</P>
<P>
   He assured that wasn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost some games and turned around and won some games. A
loss doesn't stop us from making our run,'' Nailon said. ``As long
as we take care of business, it shouldn't matter about this game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
