<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ON-TRACK?-ECO     02-27 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ON-TRACK?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON YOUR MARK, NIGERIA: IF NEW START ISN'T GOOD, YOU'RE FINISHED  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...Note this weekend's election)   (This excellent 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 27 February 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Nigeria were a sprinter, it would long since have been out of
the race. Its four decades of independent existence have been
punctuated by false start followed by false start.
</P>
<P>
   When its voters go to the polls this weekend to choose a
civilian president, they will be starting once again. This time,
they had better make a success of it. One more failure would
probably put Nigeria out of the race for good.
</P>
<P>
   Would that matter? Maybe not in the long run. But in the short
run it would cause an upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   With 115 million people, Nigeria is much the most populous
country in sub-Saharan Africa. If Nigeria is ill governed, then
almost a quarter of non-Arab Africa is ill governed. If it were to
break up, then one African in four would become a citizen of a new
state.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if Nigeria were well governed, then a force for good
could become influential throughout a region still cursed, much of
it, with poverty, instability and outright warfare.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the omens are good. The two candidates for
the presidency, Olusegun Obasanjo and Olu Falae, are both decent
men.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the winner, unlike the winner of Nigeria's last free
presidential election, will probably be allowed to take office: the
signs are that the military men _ who have ruled the country for
all but ten of its 39 years of independence, and who locked up
Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner of the 1993 vote _ really do
intend to hand over this time.
</P>
<P>
   And Nigeria is not all dust and desert. It is potentially rich.
Oil gurgles beneath it, and Royal Dutch/Shell, which already pumps
about half the country's production of 2 million barrels a day, has
recently said it will invest $8.5 billion to get more out.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad vote of confidence for a poor country in a continent
habitually short of investment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, other signs are less favorable. Nigeria is not an
easy place to govern.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since it was cobbled together by the British at the
beginning of the century, it has been a country divided: divided
between north and south (the north indirectly governed through
feudal rulers, the south directly by the British colonists),
between religions (Muslim northerners and westerners, Christian
easterners), between language groups (250 or so, according to some
counts), between rich and poor and, more recently, between civilian
and military.
</P>
<P>
   So profound were these divisions in the 1960s that the country
fought a long civil war in which the eastern region, under the name
of Biafra, tried to secede. More than 1 million people died.
</P>
<P>
   Successive governments' response to so many divisions has been
to offer the illusion of greater local autonomy by creating, within
a federal framework, more and more states: the original three have
grown to 36.
</P>
<P>
   The large administrative cost might have been worth paying had
the stratagem bought contentment. It has not.
</P>
<P>
   True, the country is more mixed than ever before, and many of
the old animosities have diminished. But the peoples of the
oil-producing Niger delta feel perpetually exploited; and the
Yorubas of the west are smarting at what they consider to be years
of exclusion from power.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nigeria may not be in imminent danger of breaking up, its
new rulers will have to deal with these discontents. They will also
have to watch their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers foresee not just a loss of power but also a loss of
income. They, especially the younger ones, may yet attempt another
coup if they come to feel their prospects for enrichment have
disappeared. Before that, however, they will surely try to
manipulate the civilian politicians without formally taking over.
</P>
<P>
   The new government will anyway have to live with the awful
economic legacy of the generals. Over the years, and despite huge
oil earnings, Nigeria's infrastructure has collapsed and decayed.
Manufacturing industry and agriculture have likewise degenerated.
</P>
<P>
   And, because its refineries have been so poorly maintained, the
world's 11th-biggest oil exporter has had to import petrol to meet
the needs of its own people.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more serious is Nigeria's other curse, the culture
of corruption. Successive military governments have kept themselves
in power through a system of institutionalized theft that has
inculcated the habit into soldiers, civil servants and ordinary
people alike. Even under the purest of governments, it will take
years to eradicate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the effort has to be made. If matters do not improve, the
place will either sink, Zaire-like, into chaos, or break up, as
individual parts decide to go their own way.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do not want to see a grand Nigerian breakup, or
total collapse, this latest start had better turn out to be a good
one. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
