<HEADLINE>
RICE'S SECOND-HALF SALVO FRUSTRATES SMU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Rice's second-half salvo frustrates SMU
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Reviewing a 66-57 loss to Rice at Moody Coliseum
yesterday, SMU's Chad Elsey identified a rather obvious point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't keep coming out and giving people 15-point leads
and expect to come back and pull it out in every game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a postscript, he added, ``This team should just feel
humiliated and upset that we gave that kind of effort and they
kicked our butts.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no argument from coach Mike Dement, who watched the
Mustangs (13-14, 7-7) lose for the second time at home in three
days and settle comfortably into a fifth-seed position in this
week's Western Athletic Conference tournament in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two games ... we didn't play well until late in the Tulsa
game,'' he said, ``and we didn't play well until too late in this
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice coach Willis Wilson, however, was positively effusive after
the Owls (17-9, 8-6) nailed down the third seed in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever believed we would end up being the third seed,''
he said. ``Nobody ever believed we would even be in the tournament.
We proved a lot of people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Owls' most significant labor in this one came at the outset
of the second half, which they opened with a 14-0 run, wiping out a
three-point deficit. With 11:58 left it had grown to 20-2, and SMU
was down by 15 points (50-35).
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out flat in the second half, with no defense,'' said
Jeryl Sasser, who had 18 points and 10 rebounds in a losing effort.
``It seemed like we were satisfied just being in the tournament and
figured all we had to do to beat Rice was show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have been hungry, because getting the three-seed was
our goal, but it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For SMU, a 38-28 edge on the boards was almost useless because
of poor shooting. In the second half, the Mustangs shot 26 per cent
from the floor and 43 per cent from the free-throw line. For the
game, they were 34.5 percent from the floor and made barely half
their free throws.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:20 remaining, Elsey hit back-to-back 3-point shots that
cut a 56-44 Rice lead in half, but SMU could not sustain the
momentum. Elsey cut it to six again with another 3-pointer with
1:12 left, but it was the last gasp for the Mustangs.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls shot a blistering 59 percent in the second half and 52
percent overall, prompting Dement's assessment that ``they just
pretty much scored on us at will.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on a disappointing week that began with the Mustangs
entertaining hopes as high as a Mountain Division championship,
Sasser noted that only one option remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win the tournament,'' he said. ``With our record,
we're sure not going to any NCAA or NIT as an at-large team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
