<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-SUBURBIA-CA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT AIN'T JUST JASPER, FOLKS: MARIN COUNTY'S HATE-CRIME WAVE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...and California)   (This timely 700-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current
(week beginning 27 February 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILL VALLEY, CALIF. _ National attention may be fixed on Jasper,
Texas, where on Feb. 23 a white supremacist, John King, was
convicted of dragging a black man to death behind his truck; but to
residents of Marin County, Calif., what has been happening in their
part of the world seems almost as disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the parents of four black students from Tamalpais High
School, in Mill Valley in the southern part of the county, filed
suit against officials of the Novato school district in the
county's northern half.
</P>
<P>
   The suit followed an incident last winter in which white
students from Novato's San Marin High School wore afro wigs and
taunted black players from Tamalpais while the players warmed up
for a basketball game at San Marin.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Price, a civil-rights lawyer representing the parents,
said that Novato district officials are not doing enough to change
an atmosphere of intolerance at San Marin High.
</P>
<P>
   A few days earlier an openly gay San Marin student, Adam Colton,
was admitted to hospital unconscious. He had been beaten up, and
the letters FAG had been scratched into the skin of his stomach and
arms with a ballpoint pen.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second such ambush Colton has suffered in a single
school year at San Marin High; he was beaten up last September just
after he had set up a Gay-Straight Alliance at his school. Although
no one has come forward and confessed, most suspect that San Marin
students were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Marin is a small, diamond-shaped county just north of San
Francisco; its southern tip touches the north tower of the Golden
Gate Bridge. Nearly half of Marin's rolling, sea-edged landscape is
held in public trust within the Golden Gate National Recreation
Area.
</P>
<P>
   The urban problems of San Francisco, where a gang of white
youths recently beat up a black teenager after a basketball game,
seem quite distant.
</P>
<P>
   The county's 275,000 inhabitants, who are overwhelmingly white,
pride themselves on their wealth (Marin is among the three
wealthiest counties in the country), their tolerance, and a quirky
but sincere dedication to New Age world views.
</P>
<P>
   It is a laid-back place; hence the tag ``Mellow Marin.'' This is
where George Lucas, director of ``Star Wars,'' lives and where
Robin Williams, the actor, grew up; but it is also where Tupac
Shakur, a murdered rap-artist, attended Tamalpais High School.
</P>
<P>
   The city manager of Novato, Rod Wood, says that the continuing
attacks at San Marin High are caused by a small group of ``socially
maladjusted'' students who call themselves white supremacists. Like
others, he has no idea where such notions have come from.
</P>
<P>
   The county's economy, increasingly service-based, is thriving,
and there is little displacement of workers of one culture by
workers of another. A great deal of the personal wealth in the
county is in the form of hyper-costly property.
</P>
<P>
   One Marin County supervisor, Cynthia Murray, who represents
Novato on the county's governing board, points out that Novato
dutifully reports every hate incident when other communities don't,
and that this may inflate the figures.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Marin's easygoing veneer hides a history of
confrontations over difference, especially racial difference.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969 Tamalpais High School, which has the second-largest
number of black students of any high school in Marin, was
vandalized with spray-painted racial slurs, and was also briefly
closed by racial violence.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago a fourth-generation Asian-American boy at San
Marin High was beaten up. Shortly after the basketball game
incident last year, spray-painted swastikas appeared on walls at
San Marin High School.
</P>
<P>
   After Colton's second beating, San Marin's principal was
``reassigned'' elsewhere in the county. After the basketball
incident, the team was put on probation and its games against
Tamalpais have been cancelled for a year to allow a cooling-off
period.
</P>
<P>
   In any other country, this would have been enough. But because
no other disciplinary action was taken against the basketball team
or its chanting fans, Price has filed suit on behalf of the parents
of the taunted players. It is hard to see what good such overkill
can possibly do. &QL; 
