<SLUG> BC-GUNSHOW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCESSORIES ARE HOT AT LOCAL GUN SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It doesn't matter to Josie Garcia if President Clinton
wants to require background checks on everyone buying firearms at
gun shows. After all, the Glendale legal secretary browsing a
weekend gun show already owns a revolver.
</P>
<P>
   She was more interested in the purses, holsters and everything
else at one of the state's biggest gun shows of the year, the
Crossroads of the West Gun Show at the Arizona State Fair Park and
Exposition Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, look how cute it is,'' she squealed, sounding as if helium
leaked from her mouth, as she tried out a black leather purse.
``It's got a hidden compartment for your gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia peered across the rows of tables, with 1,200 vendors
selling everything from a standard .22-caliber Ruger to
night-vision goggles to beef jerky.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 6,000 people simply came to ogle the accessories.
Two-thirds of the exhibitors displayed something other than guns.
Rows of videos filled a table _ ``A Family Guide to Handgun
Safety,'' or ``Handguns and Home Survival,'' even ``Sexy Girls,
Sexy Guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone peddled the ubiquitous pink underwear from Sheriff Joe
Arpaio's jails. Then there was a lady selling golden Buddhas and
another with Beanie Babies and fancy candles.
</P>
<P>
   They paid $7 to browse; kids under 14 got in free with adult.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters looked for polar fleece beds and foldaway chairs.
History lovers combed the tables for ammunition for antique guns,
and those with permits to conceal weapons searched for special
pouches in which to hide their handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Many mentioned the Y2K bug, fearing some kind of chaos, as they
plunked down cash for handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They worry about some kind of trouble,'' says Jacque Harrison,
owner of Guns-R-Us. ``They think they need protection. I don't
know. I personally don't buy it. But if it makes them feel better .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Her voice trailed off as she showed a man a .38-caliber Taurus
for $269.99.
</P>
<P>
   And those buying guns didn't seem to mind the background checks,
taking about 15 minutes by cellular phone, at the roughly 320
federally licensed dealers at the show. Licensed dealers are
required to conduct such checks on all gun buyers.
</P>
<P>
   At private tables, where background checks are not required, it
took only as long as it did to negotiate the cost of an 1876
Winchester or a 9mm Ruger.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this new Clinton thing stinks,'' said Bob Brown, 54, who
tried to unload a hunting rifle for $150. ``There's already enough
guns laws. We don't need this, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown voiced a concern of many at the gun show, who worry about
government clamping down on gun owners ever more. Clinton said last
month that he plans to ask Congress to require background checks on
people who buy guns at shows and flea markets, even if the sellers
are private citizens. He called the shows ``arms bazaars.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 1993 Brady Act only requires firearms dealers licensed
by the federal government to check the backgrounds of potential
buyers to make sure they aren't felons, fugitives or illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Templeton, who sponsored the weekend show, pointed to a
government statistic that showed that only 2 percent of firearms
used by criminals came directly from gun shows. Phoenix police say
gun shows aren't a big concern, that most of the guns bought there
are purchased legally, as they are at local stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to take away the rights of our hobbyists,'' said
Templeton, wearing a pin that read, ``If guns are outlawed, who
will shoot the liberals?'' on his pink button-up shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd didn't look much different than those attending a high
school cheerleading competition at the nearby coliseum. But the
bumper stickers on their cars generally told which direction they
headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come for your guns, give 'em the bullets first'' was
on an old Chevy truck with a gun rack in the back. ``You can have
my gun when you pry it from my cold, dead hands'' graced a Ford
Explorer. ``Register voters, not guns'' read a Honda Accord.
</P>
<P>
   Across the parking lot: ``I'm a proud parent of an honor student
at Cortez High School,'' proclaimed a white minivan.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Bobby Luna slung a newly bought AR-15 rifle over his
shoulder and carried a box of ammo in his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good place to find what you need,'' said the
25-year-old from Glendale. He owns six guns now, mostly to take out
on the range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a collector yet,'' he said, ``but someday I hope to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, people browsing the show bundled rifles in
their arms and attached multiple pistols to belts along with their
digital phones.
</P>
<P>
   Carly Miller pushed a stroller overflowing with four rifles and
boxes of ammunition, her 2-year-old son, Tyler, resting on her hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier than carrying the guns,'' she said. ``My husband's
around here somewhere.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
