<SLUG> BC-RUN-FORT-WORTH-MARATHON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH MARATHON WINNER VOWS NOT TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Agustin Hernandez beat the wind, shrugged
off the warm temperatures and easily outdistanced the field in
yesterday morning's Cowtown Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he might have been the least happy men's Cowtown Marathon
winner in the race's 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who was runner-up last year, said goodbye to Cowtown
after winning in 2 hours, 34 minutes, 8 seconds. Even though he
beat second-place Chuck Weidner of Arlington by more than 14
minutes, Hernandez was unhappy that officials didn't waive his $35
entry fee. He did win an expense-paid trip to either the Boston or
New York marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and his coach, Carmelo Pena of Dallas, said they had
talked to ``someone'' about a complimentary entry but were refused.
Then, even though Cowtown never has been a money race, they had
hoped to have some of Hernandez's expenses to Fort Worth from
Apaseo El Grande, Mexico, defrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Race director Jim Gilliland said it's the first he had heard of
Hernandez trying to have his entry waived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on who he asked,'' Gilliland said. ``I would have
given him permission. What they have to realize is they should ask
in plenty of time, not the day of the race. And not everyone can
give them permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez won his second marathon in eight tries, though his
winning time was far off his best of 2:16.
</P>
<P>
   Pena said this would be the last time for any of the runners
sponsored by El Conejo, a bus company, to come to Cowtown. They
also didn't run at White Rock in December for the first time in
several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good to mile 23,'' Hernandez said. When the
construction worker hit the Trinity Park trails and bucked a
20-plus mph headwind, he tired, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his coach expected to win because last year's winner,
teammate and countryman Remedios Ramirez, didn't return, opting to
run in Guadalajara last week, where he won $3,000 for a
fourth-place finish, Pena said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't in shape to run that,'' said Hernandez, who used
Cowtown as a training run. He plans to run in New York in November.
</P>
<P>
   He had no company after the first 10 miles, which he ran with
James Newsom, a Fort Worth runner on the first leg of his
three-person relay team.
</P>
<P>
   When he reached 10 miles in 54:08, Hernandez was almost a mile
ahead of his nearest challenger. He reached the 20-mile marker in
1:49:08, meaning he ran a pedestrian 45 minutes in the final 10K.
The warm temperatures, hitting the mid-60s during the race,
hampered times.
</P>
<P>
   Weidner, 35, ran his fourth Cowtown and has improved his
position each year; he was 22nd, seventh and fourth previously. His
time this year, 2:47.47, though, was almost seven minutes slower
than last year. He already was 25 seconds behind Hernandez when he
reached the first mile in 5:47.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was terrible,'' he said. ``We had it with us about
mile 18 to 19, and then ran against it coming in. I had to bend
over, duck my head and pump my arms on the trails'' from mile 23 to
25.
</P>
<P>
   Weidner, a 171/2-year Navy veteran, said he had trained hard for
Cowtown ``because it's a tough marathon. It's maybe the toughest
course I've run.''
</P>
<P>
   Weidner, who has run 17 of the 26.2-mile races, was third until
a runner identified as Neal Johnson dropped out at 20 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised I finished second,'' Weidner said. ``I didn't
see him drop out. He looked strong when I saw him at a
turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   The masters division (40-and-over) winner was Adam Cohen of
Norman, Okla., who finished in 2:49:39.45, third overall.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
