<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO CLOSES IN ON MILESTONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
DALLAS _ Ray Ferraro said this week that he never forgets for a
moment that he is a relative Lilliputian skating in a landscape
increasingly populated by giants.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Every step of the way,'' the Los Angeles Kings' 5-foot-8
center said. ``And every time someone mentions it, I want to prove
them wrong. I'd like to be 6-3 some days, too. I don't think it's
going to happen. I think I'm out of my growth years.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's still proving people wrong. And when he steps on the
Reunion Arena ice this afternoon for the Kings' game against the
Dallas Stars, he will become only the 136th player in NHL history
to appear in 1,000 games in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, 34, also will become the fourth King this season to
reach the 1,000-game mark, joining defensemen Doug Bodger and Garry
Galley, and winger Russ Courtnall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not very many have done it,'' said Ferraro, whose role with
the Kings has increased from minimal to significant as the season
has progressed. ``The fact that I've been consistent enough to be
in the league 15 years is something I'm pretty proud of. Ever since
I was a little kid, I was told I was too small.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, who has 10 goals and 20 points in 44 games this season,
has not decided whether this will be his final season. When he
retires, a career in broadcasting may await him, and there's always
the family concrete business in his native Trail, British Columbia.
But any role in that enterprise will not include heavy lifting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pile 3,200 blocks a day when you're 16 years old, you
get a sense what you don't want to do,'' said Ferraro, who is in
the final year of a contract that will pay him $1.75 million this
season. ``It's a long eight hours at the end of a chain. I was just
trying to get money to put gas in my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, who made $7 an hour back in those days, is scheduled to
wear a microphone during today's telecast, with his comments to be
heard during the regional telecast on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't going to go on live,'' said Ferraro, who has scored
343 NHL goals. ``I wouldn't wear it if it did. I'm not going to
think about it, either. I'm not going to say something just so
they'll play it. I talk a lot anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Nice Guy: Ferraro takes no offense at his nickname: Little
Ball of Hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came from the guys in New York,'' said Ferraro, who played
for the Rangers before joining the Kings three years ago. ``The
guys in New York gave the name to Pat Verbeek (now with Dallas) and
myself, two little guys who were aggressive and seemed combative to
everything going on, so before long, it came along that we were
these two little balls of hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, Luc (Robitaille) came here (from the Rangers) and it
didn't take long to get picked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it's like being a little ball of hate, Ferraro said,
``I like it. It means I'm feisty. I don't know if my wife likes
that I'm a little ball of hate, though. I try to be better than
that at home.''
</P>
<P>
   What, me worry?: Friday night, Kings president Tim Leiweke
guaranteed that Coach Larry Robinson and his staff will finish the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Saturday for his reaction, Robinson said, ``It doesn't
affect me at all. Whether my job is on the line or not, I'll still
do my job until they tell me I don't have a job anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is in the final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Bad ice: Stars players are blaming ice conditions at Reunion
Arena for the hamstring injury Wednesday that is expected to
sideline right wing Brett Hull for at least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a surprise, getting a skate caught in a rut in this ice
surface,'' said Hull's linemate, Mike Modano. ``The weather is only
going to get warmer, the ice stickier and the puck bouncier. I
think one of the reasons why we skate much better on the road is
because we play on superior ice surfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars - whose 37-11-9 record is the best in the NHL - are
20-6-4 at home, 17-5-5 on the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 2335EST &QL; 
