<P>
   NEW YORK _ The extraordinary bull market in shares has diverted
attention from the traditional indicator of irrational exuberance,
a booming housing market. But sales of both new and existing homes
are up over 10 percent on a year ago, at levels last seen in the
1970s, and average house prices are well above what they were in
1989, the previous peak in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually, the housing market _ especially at the high end,
$200,000 and up _ is strong all over the country, not concentrated
in a few ``hot'' areas. New building is also at record levels, much
of it financed by bank lending _ which may be ominous, given how
fast consumer sentiment can turn in the housing market.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for housing has been fuelled, as usual, by the strong
economy. But as well as rising incomes, three unfamiliar forces
have been at work.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring share prices have made consumers feel much wealthier.
Mortgage rates have fallen sharply: indeed, taking into account
America's generous mortgage-interest tax breaks, real mortgage
rates may be negative.
</P>
<P>
   New financing techniques have made it easier for homeowners to
refinance mortgages and borrow against any equity locked up in
their property, and have made it possible for people who would
previously have been denied financing to get a mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Is there now a housing bubble? If there is, its bursting could
have a nasty impact on consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Property remains a huge part of the assets of most families, and
past falls in house prices have had a much greater ``wealth
effect'' than comparable falls in share prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Craig Thomas, an economist at RFA, a research firm, reckons
that there is no bubble. The 1980s housing bubble was reflected in
prices rising much further than was justified by changes in what
the land would be worth if it was put to some other use, such as
business.
</P>
<P>
   Now, rapid growth in business productivity has pushed up the
alternative value of land in tandem with house prices, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dudley, an economist at Goldman Sachs, sees no evidence
that the high price of shares has fed through to inflation in the
price of other assets, such as houses.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers seem to have learned from the last property crash, and
are not too carried away this time. How long before they have to
learn a similar lesson about shares? &QL; 
