<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WOMAN-MARATHON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN LAWYER WINS WOMEN'S MARATHON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CALAWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Her self-deprecating humor and aw-shucks
nature fit perfectly with the laid-back mentality at Fort Worth's
Stockyards, where the 21st running of the Cowtown Marathon started
and ended yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why Lori Stich, who won the Cowtown women's
division for the second consecutive time and third in five years,
loves the city so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spectators here are great,'' Stich said. ``I will always
have a special place in my heart for Fort Worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Stich took a commanding lead early and won easily in 2 hours, 56
minutes and 38 seconds on a warm day. Kelli Lusk of Denver was
second in 3:01.11.
</P>
<P>
   Stich said the unseasonably mild day led to tough running.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the humidity more than anything else,'' the Michigan
native said. ``I'm a northern wimp. Early on, I was glad when the
wind came, so it would cool things off. I run better when it is
about 20 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Stich, a 28-year old lawyer from Stanwood, Mich., won her first
Cowtown Marathon in 1995. She was in Houston, working as a clerk
for a federal judge, and decided to run the race at the urging of a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   But with one catch.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing she would not do well at the race, Stich registered as
Gloria Slight. To her surprise, ended up winning.
</P>
<P>
   For Slight, uh Stich, running has become more than a hobby. She
recently qualified for the Olympic trials by running a personal
best of 2:48.41 at the California Invitational in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   But her achievements have not taken away from her love of
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any delusions about myself that I will make the
Olympic team or anything like that,'' Stich said. ``It would be
nice to run my PR (personal record) at the Olympic trials and not
embarrass myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Stich said the only drawback to competing in the
Olympic trials, scheduled for Feb. 26, 2000, in Columbia, S.C., is
that she will miss the Cowtown Marathon next year.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Stich automatically qualifies for either the
New York or Boston Marathon. She said she expects to compete in
both races this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at marathons as a great excuse for a weekend trip,''
Stich said.
</P>
<P>
   Lusk, despite having her slowest time in a marathon since 1996,
managed to place second. She had to stop after 20 miles and walk
around a bit.
</P>
<P>
   But Lusk had reason to not be in tip-top shape. She learned
three weeks ago that she is expecting her first child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been fatigued the past few weeks, and I knew I would be
tired coming into today,'' Lusk said. ``I thought the temperature
was great. The humidity didn't bother me at all. But once we got
into the race, there were quite a few head winds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Denver native said that she was prepared to drop out at any
time but that after the 20-mile mark she felt much better than she
expected and decided to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The expectant mother flew back to Denver last night. Stich
stayed. She likes to make a habit of seeing the sights of the
different cities where she competes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Bob's, I'm going there tonight,'' Stich said.
</P>
<P>
   One more reason for the Michigan native to love Fort Worth.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
