<SLUG> BC-BALLOON-TO-MARS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RACE TO MARS: FLIGHTS OF FANCY, OR JUST PLANE CRAZY?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note March 8th launch, 14th graf)   (This intriguing 1,125-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 27 February 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general/technology news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The current scientific assault on Mars is an unashamed
celebration of modern technology. The first of an armada of
spacecraft is already on its way to map the planet's surface,
analyze its weather and shoot probes into its soil.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years a dozen or so others will follow,
carrying all manner of sensors, scanners and increasingly clever
robotic rovers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to make it easier to send the results back to Earth,
NASA, America's space agency, has started planning the first
permanent interplanetary data-link _ Mars Network. This will
require a communications satellite to be put into orbit around the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   Orbiting satellites are good at providing information about the
planet as a whole, and crawling rovers can yield extreme close-ups
of individual rocks. But there is a gap in the middle, covering
such activities as looking for groundwater, charting magnetic
anomalies and scouting out future landing sites.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the high-tech paraphernalia, therefore, one group of
researchers wants to revive a distinctly old-fashioned form of
travel.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 years after a cockerel, a duck and a sheep were
first sent aloft in France by the Montgolfier brothers, there are
plans to dispatch a balloon to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The modern-day Montgolfiers are Jim Cutts and his team at NASA's
Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) in Pasadena, Calif. Admittedly,
their proposed Mars balloon bears little resemblance to the huge
paper bag that floated over Versailles in 1783.
</P>
<P>
   For a start, instead of being a hot-air balloon, it will be
filled with helium _ a light gas that will enable it to float in
Mars's mainly carbon-dioxide atmosphere. And rather than being
constructed of paper, the JPL balloon will be made of such
space-age fabrics as mylar and kevlar.
</P>
<P>
   These strong materials are required by the balloon's
``super-pressure'' design. This means that its volume (and thus its
density) is fixed, no matter what the temperature of the gas
inside. That will ensure that it maintains a constant altitude at
the point where its density equals that of the air outside,
irrespective of the amount of sunlight falling on it.
</P>
<P>
   Most terrestrial balloons, by contrast, expand (and thus rise)
during the day in response to solar heating, and shrink and sink at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Super-pressure balloons have already been used to explore Venus,
where two short-lived versions were set adrift by the
Franco-Russian Vega missions in 1985. But the Mars balloon would be
a much more serious affair.
</P>
<P>
   As it drifted over the planet's surface during the course of
several weeks, it would be able to determine its position by
observing the sun and the stars, and to decide, as a result of
those observations, whether or not to take photographs or
atmospheric readings.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this combination of clever technology with an aerial
platform, the JPL researchers prefer to talk of their balloon as an
``aerobot.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, Dr. Cutts and his team will drop a prototype out of
a conventional balloon at an altitude of 35 km (22 miles) _ the
point at which conditions most closely resemble those high up in
the Martian atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to test the novel rapid-inflation technology that is
needed to ensure that the aerobot will inflate and attain a stable
altitude within 60 seconds or so of its arrival in the Martian
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from that uncertainty, according to Dr. Cutts, the
balloon's technology is relatively mature. He hopes that the first
aerobot will reach Mars in 5-7 years.
</P>
<P>
   But another flying machine looks likely to beat it there. Just
as Dr. Cutts and his team have been inspired by the Montgolfiers,
the promoters of this second school take their lead from the Wright
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   If the thin atmosphere of Mars can support a balloon, why not an
airplane?
</P>
<P>
   The idea of sending an unmanned airplane to Mars has been around
for a number of years, but it is taking off, as it were, as the
100th anniversary of the Wright brothers' first powered flight
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   With its characteristic flair for publicity, NASA proposes to
mark the occasion (Dec. 17, 2003) with the first powered flight on
Mars. The agency's budget for 2000, published on Feb. 1, includes a
request for $50 million to finance a Mars airplane.
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture of international solidarity, however, the
spacecraft carrying the plane would actually be sent up by the
French space agency, CNES, as a secondary payload on a
commercial-satellite launch by an Ariane 5 rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial satellite would go into an Earth orbit, while the
smaller scientific payload would continue on to Mars. If
successful, this project would pave the way for NASA and CNES to
collaborate on a number of other small, cheap ``micromissions'' to
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The Martian airplane proposal has been criticized, with some
justification, for lacking scientific rationale. Tellingly, the
money for the project has been requested even though the plane's
design and scientific mission have still to be defined. (The design
will be put out to competitive tender in a few weeks' time.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet in many ways planes would be just as good as balloons for
exploring Mars; they, too, could take atmospheric readings and
conduct medium-range ground surveys. And in one respect they would
be far better. Unlike free-floating balloons, they could be
dispatched to investigate particular places without being at the
mercy of the winds.
</P>
<P>
   According to Scott Hubbard of NASA's Ames Research Center, also
in California, the anniversary flight would mainly be a
demonstration of technology.
</P>
<P>
   The plane would be dropped into the Martian atmosphere, deploy a
parachute, unfold its wings and, driven by an electric motor, a
hydrazine-fuelled engine or a rocket thruster (depending on who
wins the competition), would fly a few hundred meters above the
surface for up to four hours.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of things it could do in that time. Dr.
Hubbard suggests that it might, for example, investigate the region
around a landing site to put a rover's findings into a broader
context.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility would be a flight along Valles Marineris, an
enormous Martian canyon, to look at the cliff faces for evidence of
long-vanished Martian oceans _ something only a plane could do
relatively easily.
</P>
<P>
   Balloons still have the advantage that they could stay aloft for
weeks at a time, compared with at most a few hours for a plane. But
since they are less able to compete on the public-relations front _
unfortunately, there is no suitable ballooning anniversary in the
near future _ they might have to wait their turn.
</P>
<P>
   On Earth, the first flying machines were balloons, followed by
planes and then spacecraft. On Mars, they will probably arrive in
reverse order. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this intriguing 1,125-word article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
