<HEADER>
A2116 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     02-27 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 7)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BRIGHT ANGEL TIME &LR;  By Martha McPhee. Harvest/Harcourt Brace,
$13. Set in the 1970s, this first novel is narrated by a thoughtful
8-year-old girl who struggles to make sense of her family's chaotic
life on the road after her abandoned mother is lured to Big Sur by
an itinerant therapist to the well-to-do. The result is ``a hard
and shining artifact of personal and social upheaval,'' Walter Kirn
wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFEDERATES IN THE ATTIC: DISPATCHES FROM THE UNFINISHED CIVIL
WAR &LR;  By Tony Horwitz. Vintage Departures, $14. A former Wall Street
Journal reporter and Civil War buff takes up with a troop of
hard-core battle re-enactors, toughing it out in the field and
tracking down secession-related controversies and die-hard keepers
of the faith throughout the South. Last year the reviewer Roy
Blount Jr. found this to be a ``splendid commemoration of the war
and its legacy'' as well as ``an eyes-open, humorously no-nonsense
survey of complicated Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONCEIVED IN LIBERTY: JOSHUA CHAMBERLAIN, WILLIAM OATES, AND
THE AMERICAN CIVIL WAR &LR;  By Mark Perry. Penguin, $15.95. This
focuses on the eventful careers of two rival commanders at
Gettysburg _ one from Maine, the other from Alabama _ who started
as poor farm boys and wound up in politics. The result is ``an
ambitious ... history of the North and South from before the war to
the end of Reconstruction,'' Frederick Allen wrote in 1998. ``The
author reaches far beyond their own lives to capture the complex
spirit of the times.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AN INSTANCE OF THE FINGERPOST &LR;  By Iain Pears. Berkley, $7.99.
This intricate literary thriller about the murder of an Oxford don
in Restoration England _ and the far greater crime to which it is
linked _ unfolds through the voices of four very different
narrators. ``Pears, with a painstaking, almost forensic attention
to detail, constructs his world like a master painter of trompe
l'oeil,'' Andrew Miller wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EDGE OF THE SEA &LR;  By Rachel Carson. Mariner/Houghton
Mifflin, $14. Seven years before the classic ``Silent Spring,'' the
author turned her formidable gaze on the narrow strip of sea bottom
that ebbs and flows with the tides, and the rich web of life
thriving along the Atlantic coastline. ``Carson's book is
beautifully written,'' Jonathan N. Leonard wrote in 1955. ``People
who get bored by too much lolling on beaches should read it as a
guidebook.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RACHEL CARSON: THE WRITER AT WORK &LR;  By Paul Brooks. Sierra Club,
$18. This book uses hefty selections from Carson's published and
unpublished writings to track her career as both a pioneering
environmentalist and a dedicated writer. In 1972 the reviewer
Josephine Johnson called this a ``rich and readable work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PATCHWORK PLANET &LR;  By Anne Tyler. Fawcett/Ballantine, $12.95.
Barnaby Gaitlin is a chronic underachiever who is estranged from
his family and driven by a hunger to peer into other people's
lives. Yet his inner turmoil is accompanied by sudden attacks of
clarity. Last year the reviewer Carol Shields called this a
``wonderful novel ... that repays our always delighted attention.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TENDER AT THE BONE: GROWING UP AT THE TABLE &LR;  By Ruth Reichl.
Broadway, $13. In recalling how a life of eating, waitressing and
cooking led her to become a food writer, the departing restaurant
critic for The New York Times (soon to be editor in chief of
Gourmet) focuses on the characters of those she loves: mainly her
flamboyant mother and her mild-mannered father. Praising this
``effortlessly entertaining'' memoir last year, Paul Levy wrote
that ``Reichl is ... witty, fair-minded, brave and a wonderful
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIGHT LETTERS &LR;  By Robert Dessaix. Picador USA, $13. In a hotel
room in Venice, a middle-aged Australian with a terminal illness
writes to a friend about his meandering journey through Europe and
his search for meaning. Last year the reviewer Patrick Farrell
admired ``the wry, chatty, surprisingly cheerful voice in which he
discourses on heaven and hell, seduction and sex.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DAY OF CREATION &LR;  By J.G. Ballard. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$13. In a parched central African nation, an obsessed British
doctor fulfills his dream of creating a ``third Nile.'' ``Ballard
constructs a moody and well-modeled landscape with as fine a
writerly intelligence as we might hope for,'' Samuel R. Delany
wrote in these pages in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WAR FEVER &LR;  $10. In this collection of Ballard's short fiction
reissued by the same publisher, Beirut becomes a laboratory for the
study of warfare and Ronald Reagan is recalled to the White House,
only to have news reports about his health overshadow World War
III. ``Far more rigorous and fastidious than Jorge Luis Borges or
Italo Calvino, Ballard keeps impeccably cool,'' Ursula K. Le Guin
wrote in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BONOBO: THE FORGOTTEN APE &LR;  By Frans de Waal. Photographs by
Frans Lanting. University of California, $24.95. A primatologist
explores the striking differences between these so-called pygmy
chimpanzees, who freely use sex to resolve tension, and their more
familiar cousins. In 1997 David Papineau called this an ``elegant
photo-essay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990227.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NO-KIDS-NO-RIGHTS-REV     02-27 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NO-KIDS-NO-RIGHTS-REVOLT-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOTHER OF ALL BATTLES: CHILDLESS WORKERS VS. WORKING MOMS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (EDITORS: RESENDING from Feb. 23 for those needing)  
  
 (This controversial ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS
PROVOCATIVE ARTICLE OFFERS A 125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 375. TOTAL
UNCUT VERSION IS 1,075 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle
news files.)  
  
 By URSULA KENNY  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is just as well that American author Elinor Burkett is
neither fainthearted nor afraid of flak (``I thrive on it
actually'') because it seems that she has started a civil war in
the U.S. workplace with a book she hasn't even finished writing
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Procreation Privilege'' _ a working title _ will give a voice
to what she sees as the last minority group in America: the
childless working woman.
</P>
<P>
   According to Burkett, women who choose not to have children are
increasingly furious about tax and time concessions being given to
those who do.
</P>
<P>
   Childless workers, she says, feel discriminated against like
never before: punished for their lack of parental status in terms
of both policy and perception.
</P>
<P>
   Her theories began during the Clinton/Dole campaign of 1996.
Both political parties were pitching at the so-called ``mythic
soccer mom'' and pushing family-friendly policies to win votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they said the word `family,' at first I thought they
meant me. I'm a member of a family,'' she says. ``But `family'
turned out to be a euphemism for `parent,' which I'm not because I
don't want to be. Then I started to wonder about stuff like why
parents get tax breaks that aren't income-sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, my brother-in-law earns $145,000 a year and yet
he still gets $3,000 in tax breaks because he's a parent. Even he
admits he doesn't need it.''
</P>
<P>
   The more research she did, the more convinced she was that she
had a case. American couples with children, she discovered, are
allowed up to 12 days of extra holiday a year, as well as parents'
evenings and sports days.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't want to offend the people they worked with, but
single people were starting to feel like second-class citizens in
much the same way that working mothers felt relegated by their male
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But when Burkett wrote a piece about the subject for the New
York Times, there was outrage. ``They freaked when they read it and
wouldn't print it,'' she says. ```Atlantic Monthly' magazine didn't
believe my findings and just about every other publication I write
for _ except `Mirabella' magazine _ got hostile. That's when I knew
there was a book in it.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 375) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the book proposal was strong too. ``I received a fax
from one publisher saying it was the most selfish thing he had ever
read. I asked the assistant to my literary agent what she thought
of it. She said that I came across as a Nazi bitch. Me. I've been a
feminist all my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Betty Friedan for a comment and she screamed at me,
at the top of her lungs, that she didn't believe this sort of bad
feeling existed in the workplace. I told her that my job was merely
to report what was going on and she hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that I'm not causing women to turn against each
other; it's policy that's doing that.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During research, Burkett interviewed many childless women in the
workplace. She wasn't short of anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   There was the copy editor at the New York Times who was forced
to work every Christmas because she had no family ties.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the female construction worker in Baltimore who
did all the early-morning and late-evening shifts because the men
she worked with were fathers.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the shift worker who, when she requested to work
days, was told it would never happen because ``we give first choice
to parents.''
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't just women. ``A guy I interviewed in New York is
thinking of suing his company because, out of a team of three, he
always does all the foreign travel and extra hours because the
other two are mothers,'' she says. ``Flexitime isn't available to
the childless in the way that it is to parents.''
</P>
<P>
   All this, Burkett points out, is at a time when more women than
ever before are choosing to be childless.
</P>
<P>
   While she knows that parents have to be able to work she ``wants
to frame things in a different way; from the point of view of the
childless worker.'' In her view, people are being punished for
their lifestyle choice while others are given ``every break going''
for theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction in Britain to Burkett's arguments has been as outraged
as in America. Marcelle D'Argy Smith, editor of ``Woman's
Journal,'' actively chose not to have children but says she is
``absolutely furious'' with Burkett's suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last thing we need, and I think that the childless
women who say that they are unhappy about working mothers are the
ones that really want children themselves _ they're bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know mothers work very hard indeed and yes, it is unfair,
but you have to cover for them sometimes _ I've covered maternity
leave three times for pregnant women. They're continuing the human
race, for God's sake, so you have to do it. I'm thrilled not to
have children but I know someone's got to and we have to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Natasha Walter agrees: ``Children are not just the
responsibility of the individual, they are a collective
responsibility for society as a whole. And anyway, this support
doesn't go on forever; children are only young for a very few
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a work colleague being frowned upon when he took
two weeks' paternity leave. I find that pathetic, as if it's
``bunking off.''
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S., the argument has begun to move on. Democrats are
suggesting that companies exchange maternity and paternity leave
for ``benefits accounts,'' so all employees can take time off.
</P>
<P>
   Those who start a family can spend time with the new baby, while
the childless have the opportunity to fulfil some other kind of
ambition, like going travelling. It's an idea with which Natasha
Walter agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very unhappy about the idea of a fight between
childless women and working mothers,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That said, I think our aim should be for more flexibility in
the workplace for everyone, including the childless who may want
the opportunity to go off and be educated or do voluntary work. But
at the moment we're right to prioritize the needs of parents.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this provocative 950-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to
reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-99 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990227.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-27 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2119 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NO-KIDS-NO-RIGHTS-REV     02-27 1301
</HEADER>
